<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Unfunded Mandates</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Unfunded Mandates</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Congress should scale-back existing unfunded mandates and refrain from
enacting more in the future.  Imposing unfunded mandates is a fundamentally
unfair and undemocratic means of enacting environmental policy that
short-circuits accountability and hamstrings the ability to set rational
environmental priorities.<p>
	Congress creates unfunded mandates when it passes laws requiring state and/or
local governments to meet particular goals or enact particular regulatory
programs and then fails to allocate resources to assist in the implementation
of these programs.  Environmental laws are responsible for a substantial
portion of unfunded mandates.  <p>
	Unfunded mandates proliferated dramatically over the past decade.  Prior to
1988, there were only 40 unfunded federal mandates, environmental and
otherwise.  Between 1988 and 1991, that number nearly tripled.  Nearly 12
percent of municipal revenues must now go to meeting  unfunded mandates imposed
by Congress.  In 1995, Congress passed a law to require explicit Congressional
authorization of any new unfunded mandate greater than $50 million.  Efforts to
scale-back existing unfunded mandates have been unsuccessful.  <p>
	Environmental mandates are among the most expensive.  There are unfunded
mandates in the <A HREF="/ebb/cleanair.html">Clean Air Act</A>, <A HREF="/ebb/cleanh2o.html">Clean Water Act</A>, <A HREF="/ebb/sdwa.html">Safe Drinking Water Act</A>, and
many other major environmental laws. County governments expect to spend over
$16.1 billion on environmental mandates between 1994 and 1998. The expense of
unfunded mandates is having a significant impact on many communities.  For
instance:<p>
<UL>
<LI>	Columbus, Ohio, will need to spend $1 billion to comply with only those
environmental mandates imposed as of January 1991.  This will cost Columbus
households an estimated  $856 annually by the year 2000.<p>
<LI>	Hastings, Nebraska, population 22,867, has estimated its mandate compliance
costs at $74.6 million, or $1,865 per household.<p>
<LI>	Lewiston, Maine, is looking at mandate costs of over $80 million.  For a city
population of only 40,000, this amounts to over $2,000 per person.<p>
</UL>
	<P>Unfunded mandates are undemocratic and they destroy accountability.  They
enable politicians to enact policies without voting for the taxes or offsetting
spending cuts to pay for them.  Members of Congress have used unfunded mandates
to demonstrate their support for popular public goals while disguising the
costs of their programs.  Unfunded mandates often mean that higher local
priorities must be pushed aside to meet Washington, D.C.&#146;s dictates.<p>
	Unfunded mandates should come to an end.  A simple &#147;no money, no
mandate&#148; policy would do the trick.  Federal lawmakers must recognize that
not every environmental concern requires a federal program or initiative.
State and local governments are just as concerned with the health and
well-being of their residents, and are more than capable addressing local
environmental concerns.  In many instances, Congress could best foster more
rational environmental policy-making by simply getting out of the way.  The
states were intended to be &#147;laboratories of democracy,&#148; developing
innovative and experimental approaches to vexing public policy concerns.
Imposing unfunded mandates prevents states from playing that vital role, and
can even inhibit the development of forward-looking and effective environmental
policies.<p>
<i>Q:  Why shouldn&#146;t the federal government impose stringent environmental
standards on states and localities?</i><p>
<p>
A:  This question assumes that state and local governments are unable to
determine environmental priorities for their own communities.  State officials
are no less concerned about clean water problems or clean air problems than are
federal officials.  If anything, state and local governments are closer to the
environmental concerns of local communities and better able to develop the
proper remedies.  It is one thing for the federal government to provide
guidance to local communities on environmental matters.  It is another thing
for the federal government to require particular programs, and leave state and
local taxpayers footing the bill.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:   Won&#146;t a &#147;no money, no mandate&#148; policy prevent the
government from providing the environmental protection that Americans
want?</i><p>
<p>
A:  A &#147;no money, no mandate&#148; policy will restore accountability to
environmental policy.  Protecting the environment is important, but so are
health care, education, crime prevention, and the whole range of concerns that
state and local governments are forced to address.  State and local governments
need the flexibility to be able to respond to the needs of their constituents.
Piling on environmental requirements without providing the resources to meet
those requirements destroys that flexibility.  Environmental protection is
necessary, but it always has costs.  Controlling unfunded mandates ensures that
when environmental policies are enacted, it is clear how they will be paid
for.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Didn&#146;t Congress enact a law to control unfunded mandates in the
104<sup>th</sup> Congress?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  The new unfunded mandates law only requires Congress to explicitly
authorize any <i>new</i> unfunded mandate of $50 million or more with a
separate procedural vote.  This law is intended to prevent unfunded mandates
from being hidden in larger bills before Congress.  This law in no way prevents
Congress from enacting new unfunded mandates, it merely requires a separate
vote.  Moreover, this law does nothing to eliminate or reduce those unfunded
mandates that are already in place.  The Executive Order signed by President
Bill Clinton in 1993 is similarly ineffectual.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
