<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Ozone Depletion</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Ozone Depletion</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Scientific evidence suggests that certain manmade chemicals may deplete the
stratospheric ozone layer.  Due to these concerns, the United States banned the
production of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs).  This phaseout will be tremendously
expensive, costing as much as $100 billion by the year 2004 in the United
States alone.  Under international agreements and U.S. law, several other
putative ozone-depleting chemicals are scheduled to be banned in the future.
Increasing the cost of the existing phaseout is not justified.<p>
	Scientists believe that CFCs find their way into the upper atmosphere and
cause a thinning of the Earth&#146;s ozone layer.  This layer acts as a shield
that filters ultraviolet light from the sun.  While ozone depletion is a
legitimate environmental concern, scientific evidence suggests that it is not
the environmental catastrophe that was once feared.  The worst-case scenario
for ozone depletion projected only a modest increase in solar radiation in
North America.  Because solar radiation increases as one moves closer to the
equator, the projected increase would be no more than moving 100 miles South
&#151; such as from Washington D.C. to Richmond, VA.  Many of the harms that
environmentalists claimed ozone depletion would cause, including skin cancer
and cataract epidemics, crop damage and increased incidence of animal
blindness, have been disproven or qualified.<p>
	As of January 1, 1996, it is illegal to produce CFCs (also known as Freon).
CFCs are used in many existing air-conditioning and refrigeration systems
nationwide, as well as in other specialty products.  The abrupt phaseout has
added several billion dollars annually to the costs of keeping this equipment
operational and imposed undo hardship on car owners nationwide.  In fact, the
extremely rapid nature of the CFC phaseout in the United States needlessly
elevated the costs of eliminating CFCs.  As a result, a black market in
illegally produced CFCs has blossomed in the past few years, particularly
because not all countries are eliminating the use of CFCs as quickly as is the
U.S.<p>
	In parts of the Third World, the phaseout of CFCs may be particularly severe.
The reduced availability of refrigeration for food and medical supplies is a
far greater health concern than ozone depletion in many countries.  Yet such
concerns received minimal consideration when the phaseout was enacted.<p>
	Due to the international phaseout of CFCs, any valid environmental concerns
about ozone depletion have been adequately addressed. However, additional, yet
unnecessary, measures have been implemented or proposed by environmental groups
and government officials.  <p>
	Methyl bromide, an important crop fumigant, is scheduled to be phased out by
the year 2001, despite weak evidence linking it to ozone depletion. The cost to
farmers of eliminating methyl bromide is estimated to be as much as $1.5
billion dollars per year.  Florida and California will be especially hard hit.
<p>
	Hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFCs), a class of refrigerants used in home
air-conditioning and as a substitute for CFCs in some applications, are also
under attack.   Federal law currently allows production of HCFCs at least until
2010.  However, some wish to accelerate this deadline.<p>
	The costs of such additional measures would outweigh any purported
environmental benefits. There is no reason for additional national or
international measures to address concerns about ozone depletion at this
time.<p>
<i>Q:  If CFCs, methyl bromide, and other compounds are also being phased out
under an international treaty,  why is the U.S. in a different position than
other countries?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  There is an international treaty, the Montreal Protocol on Substances that
Deplete the Ozone Layer, that requires the phaseout of CFC production in the
U.S. and other developed countries by January 1, 1996.  However, developing
nations have been given a ten year extension beyond this deadline, and many
developed countries are not in full compliance.  In addition, the Environmental
Protection Agency has imposed regulations on the handling of CFCs that have no
international counterparts.  <p>
	The situation with methyl bromide is similar.  American production is
scheduled to cease in 2001, while other developed nations can continue
producing methyl bromide until 2010.  Methyl bromide will not be phased out in
developing countries.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Isn&#146;t the phaseout of ozone depleting compounds necessary to avert
an environmental crisis?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Although there is scientific evidence that CFCs and other compounds affect
the ozone layer, the problem is far from a crisis.  Actual ground-level
ultraviolet radiation measurements do not show a long-term increase.  Moreover,
virtually everything the public has been told about the terrifying consequences
of ozone depletion (skin cancer epidemics, animals being struck blind by the
sun, collapse of the ocean food chain, and so forth) has been overstated, if
not completely false.  Ozone depletion, while a legitimate concern, is not an
environmental crisis.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Aren&#146;t there substitutes for the banned chemicals that make the
phaseout nearly cost free?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Although there are CFC substitutes, they cost considerably more and in some
cases do not work as well.  In addition, many people are stuck with equipment
specifically designed to use CFCs, such as the owners of air-conditioned cars
and trucks built before 1994, and small businessmen such as restaurant and
convenience store owners.  For these people, the costs of operating and
repairing their equipment has increased substantially.  Overall, the phaseout
will almost certainly cost tens of billions of dollars, and could reach $100
billion.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/pests.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
<P>
