<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Superfund</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Superfund</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The federal Superfund program to cleanup hazardous waste sites is an utter
failure.  &#147;It is hard to think of a government program with a wider gulf
between ambitions and results,&#148; according to the <i>New York Times</i>.
The existing program should either be radically reformed or repealed.<p>
	Created by the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and
Liability Act of 1980, Superfund has cleaned up less than 20 percent of the
more than 1,200 hazardous waste sites in the program.  Those sites that are
cleaned, are cleaned at an average cost of over $25 million per site, with a
large percentage of these costs going to pay lawyers and file paperwork.
Originally touted as a &#147;polluter pays&#148; policy, under Superfund,
polluter and non-polluter alike overpay.<p>
	One of the greatest problems with Superfund is that millions of dollars are
spent on cleanups which produce no environmental or public health benefits.
Current Superfund risk assessments greatly overstate potential risks to human
health.  Less stringent cleanup standards could achieve the same real-world
risk reduction at lower cost.  At some sites, containment of wastes is
preferable to attempting a costly cleanup.  Moreover, many communities with
Superfund sites would benefit more from the diversion of resources away from
Superfund toward more pressing and directly beneficial expenditures.<p>
	Another problem is the liability standards that Superfund has created.  Under
Superfund, liability for the costs of cleanup is strict, retroactive, and
joint-and-several.  This means that even those who had a tangential
relationship to a Superfund site can be held completely liable for the costs of
cleanup.  For example, private waste hauling firms and previous owners of
materials that end up at a Superfund site have been held liable for
multi-million dollar cleanup bills at Superfund sites.  This liability scheme
has created a blight of abandoned industrial sites, many of which are located
in poor communities that desperately need economic development.<p>
	Tinkering with Superfund and reallocating costs at the margins will not rescue
this failed program.  At a bare minimum, real Superfund reform must include the
following elements:<p>
<UL>
<LI>	The elimination of retroactive liability for those activities that have not
directly harmed people or their property, and the elimination of all liability
for parties not <i>directly</i> responsible for the creation or maintenance of
sites;<p>
<LI>	The elimination of all Superfund taxes, including those on chemicals,
petroleum products and corporations;<p>
<LI>	Greater local control over the cleanup process, including the determination
of cleanup standards and greater local responsibility for the allocation of
cleanup resources;<p>
<LI>	The ability of communities and site owners to opt out of the Superfund
process.<p>
<LI>	The privatization of orphan and federally-owned Superfund sites.<p>
</UL>
	One possibility for Superfund reform is the creation of a revolving state loan
fund to assist local communities with the costs of cleaning up abandoned sites
and the phasing out of federal involvement in non-federal waste site cleanup.
This would increase local authority over and responsibility for the clean up of
waste sites and encourage a more rational determination of clean up priorities.
In the long run, the federal role in Superfund should be eliminated
altogether.<p>
<i>Q:  Should there be a uniform, national cleanup standard for all Superfund
sites? Or should the required level of cleanup be flexible?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Each site is unique, and that is not accounted for in the current Superfund
program.  Instead, the federal government has imposed a one-size fits nobody
approach.  A site that is going to house a school or family homes has different
requirements than a site where industrial development, such as a factory or
waste processing plant, will occur.  This should be a factor in the
determination of cleanup standards.<p>
	This question &#151; &#147;How clean is clean?&#148; &#151; is one of the
central issues in Superfund reform. Equally important should be the question of
who makes that determination: Landowners and affected communities or the
federal government.  Fairness and accountability suggest that landowners and
local communities, which have more at stake, should control this decisionmaking
process. <p>
<i></i><p>
<i>Q:  Sites that are placed on the Superfund cleanup list are contaminated
with hazardous wastes. Don&#146;t health concerns justify mandating that all
Superfund sites be cleaned to the highest possible standards.</i><p>
<p>
A:  Although Superfund sites typically contain wastes that are defined as
hazardous, most public health experts do not believe that Superfund sites pose
a significant health risk, particularly when such sites are fenced off or
isolated.  At sites where health risks are present, it is often possible to
mitigate the risks at far less expense.  For example, it is often possible to
contain contaminated portions of a site for far less money than would be
required to make the soil clean enough to eat.  The last ten percent of cleanup
is often as expensive as the first ninety percent; yet the last stages of
cleanup add minimal risk protection.  Superfund regulations should not be based
on the assumption that cleanup to pristine standards is the proper policy for
every site.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Does the Clinton Administration Superfund proposal adequately address
the needs of local communities?</i><p>
<p>
A:  The Clinton proposal devotes considerable space to the inclusion of local
communities in the Superfund decisionmaking process.  However, the Clinton
proposal stops far short of what is necessary.  Rather than simply including
community representatives in the federal decisionmaking process, the process
itself should be decentralized as much as possible.  This would truly give
local communities the authority and responsibility that they need to adequately
address Superfund concerns.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
