</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Insurance for Beginners</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<BR>


<CENTER>
<H1>Insurance for Beginners</H1>
by Catherine England

<BR>
</CENTER>

<P>When we buy insurance, we buy increased peace of mind.  If insured-against
events occur, they will not be as much of a financial burden.  With insurance,
we exchange the chance of a large, unexpected payment, whose timing we cannot
control, for a series of smaller, known payments over the life of the insurance
contract.  Finally, buying insurance buys us private risk analysis.  The
insurance company must determine how many 30-year-old houses will catch fire
this year and what steps can be taken to reduce that probability.<p>
	Insurance companies share this information with consumers through differences
in premiums.  We can learn something about what actions or changes reduce risk
by finding out what earns a discount or leads to lower insurance premiums.<p>
	Insurance allows us to protect our wealth more efficiently, and wealthier
societies typically demand more insurance.  Funds can be invested in other
activities rather than being set aside for unforeseeable contingencies.
Insurance thus allows both insured individuals and society to operate with
longer time horizons.<p>
	To realize these broader benefits of insurance, private insurance markets must
exhibit three fundamental elements.  First, premiums must be risk-based.
Second, insurance markets should remain competitive.  Third, insurance
companies must be allowed to earn (but they should not be promised) profits.<p>
	True insurance does not &#147;spread&#148; risk.  Insurance is more accurately
described as a contract that transfers from the policyholder to the insurance
company part of the risk of financial losses associated with insured-against
events.  To better manage their exposure, insurance companies tend to pool the
risks they accept.  But the pools created by private insurance companies are
pools of similar risks.  Most important, premiums paid by an individual
policyholder reflect the probability that he or she will make a claim, not the
probability that someone somewhere will make a claim.<p>
	In insurance markets, consumers&#146; interests are best protected by
competition.  Competition (and potential competition) forces insurance
companies to remain efficient, to control administrative and claims costs.
Competition forces insurance companies to base premiums on expected future
losses.  It prevents them from passing along past losses to new policyholders.
Competition leads insurance companies to pay claims promptly and serve
policyholders well.  Finally, competition encourages innovation and leads
insurers to attempt to extend insurance markets into currently underserved
areas.  In a competitive market, insurers only grow and thrive to the extent
they meet customers&#146; needs.<p>
	As a rule, governments best foster a competitive environment by staying out of
the way.  Government-imposed rules and regulations are far more likely to
inhibit competition than to promote it.  Regulation of rates, artificial caps
on profits, unnecessarily high entry restrictions, and limits on the variations
in contracts may serve some purpose, but they also discourage vigorous
competition.  <p>
	Possible profits provide insurance company owners and managers with an
incentive to provide insurance services to consumers and to find better ways to
serve them.  When insurance companies&#146; profits are artificially restricted
by government fiat, consumers have no way to reward insurers that do a better
than average job, and insurers have no incentive to develop new insurance
products that meet the needs of underserved market segments.  Consumer
satisfaction with the insurance industry generally declines when governments
impose limits on insurance companies&#146; profits.<p>
	The ability of insurance companies to earn profits also directly affects the
supply of insurance available.  The amount of insurance that an insurer can
have in force at any given time (its &#147;capacity&#148;) is determined by the
insurer&#146;s financial capital  (its owners&#146; share of the assets of the
firm).  To add more capacity and to increase the number of new policies it can
write, an insurance company must increase its paid-in capital and surplus.  <p>
	In the absence of active government participation, insurance companies cannot
force individuals to do anything.  Neither a single insurance company nor the
insurance industry can require people to buy insurance products.  In a private
market, consumers purchase insurance only when the protection they receive is
worth the price they pay.  Only the government can insist that individuals buy
insurance products they do not believe are worth the price.  Insurance
companies cannot prevent people from taking risks.  Insurance companies can
only provide incentives for safer behavior through their pricing policies.<p>
	Insurance cannot undo many of the harms caused by insured-against events.
Insurance often cannot make individuals 100 percent whole.  What insurance
provides is some financial compensation, agreed to in advance, to help reduce
the burden of fires, accidents, floods, and other insured-against injuries.<p>
	In the long run, private insurers can only compensate policyholders to the
limits of the insurance contracts in force.    Private insurance cannot survive
as an after-the-fact compensation scheme.  Insurers cannot pay out (for long)
more than they take in.  Insurance is a business, not a charity, and if it is
treated like the latter, capacity will evaporate.<p>
	Private insurance is generally not available for events that are either
extremely unlikely to occur or for events that are extremely likely to occur.
In the first case, there is no demand for insurance.  In the second case, the
premiums are so high that potential insurance consumers are better off saving
their money and insuring themselves.  There are losses that are too small to
insure, and there are losses so large that private insurance cannot provide
coverage, except perhaps for a part of the loss.  Although there are limits to
the coverage private insurers provide, the trend has been (and remains) to find
ways to offer more coverage, ways to expand the limits of what is insurable.<P>

<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
<BR>
<CENTER>

