<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Environmental Foreign Aid</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental Foreign Aid</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Since the end of the Cold War, environmental protection has become a prominent
justification for foreign aid programs.  The Clinton administration&#146;s 1997
budget proposed to spend $3.75 billion to promote &#147;sustainable
development&#148; worldwide.  Such foreign aid giveaways squander taxpayer
dollars and empower bureaucrats whose environmental record is abysmal.  These
budget items should be eliminated.<p>
	<a href="/ebb/global.html">Sustainable development</A> is a broad term that encompasses a wide-ranging social
agenda not supported by most American taxpayers.  In addition to global
environmental restrictions, it encompasses international efforts, through the
United Nations and other organizations, to promote population control,
environmental trade restrictions and the creation of multinational regulatory
bodies.<p>
	A substantial portion of foreign aid is channeled through the World Bank, an
institution which has simultaneously impeded economic growth and degraded
environmental quality in the Third World for fifty years.  The Bank&#146;s
massive construction projects have subsidized rainforest destruction and forced
migration, and even contributed to the outbreak of disease.  Bank projects
routinely face intense opposition from local communities and environmental
advocates.  In 1995, for example, this type of opposition forced the Bank to
abandon the giant $1 billion Arun dam project in Nepal.  <p>
	The World Bank has responded to environmental criticism by increasing its
&#147;environmental&#148; lending for global climate and biodiversity policies
through its Global Environmental Facility (GEF).  Yet the GEF, already plagued
by management failures, focuses only on potential global problems in the
distant future.  Meanwhile, real environmental hazards are made worse by the
World Bank&#146;s insistence on statist economic policies and wealth-destroying
regulatory controls.<p>
	The World Bank is not the only recipient of &#147;environmental&#148; funds
that do little for the environment.  Similarly wasteful projects are funded
through the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID), the
Inter-American Development Bank, the United Nations, and the North American
Development Bank, which was established by NAFTA.<p>
	The earmarking of aid funds for environmental protection only underscores the
unfortunate fact that fifty years of massive wealth transfers have failed to
alleviate world poverty. The legacy of foreign aid has been Third World
dependency and indebtedness.  Foreign aid will also fail to deliver its
promised environmental benefits. Instead of inventing new reasons to send money
abroad, Congress should end the giveaway of foreign aid.<p>
<i>Q:  Isn&#146;t it cheaper to give aid to foreign governments now, to prevent
environmental problems from developing into full-blown crises?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Protecting the environment has been a poor rationale for foreign aid for
many years already.  Foreign aid to Somalia, for example, did not prevent
famine and civil strife from overwhelming that country, which eventually led to
U.S. military intervention.  The history of foreign aid shows that it is more
likely to cause environmental degradation than to prevent it.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Isn&#146;t World Bank aid necessary to create new markets for U.S.
exports?  </i><p>
<p>
A:  The World Bank has tried to nurture export markets for many years, without
success.  In Mexico, for example, twelve years of World Bank lending and advice
failed avert to the 1994-5 peso devaluation and financial collapse.  Instead of
generating consumer demand for U.S.-made products, the World Bank generated an
overwhelming debt burden for Mexico&#146;s people.  The job of selecting
appropriate export markets should be left to private businesses, not to
government agencies. Moreover, if the purpose of the World Bank&#146;s
environmental funds is to promote environmental protection, why are we
concerned about the benefits for business?<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Don&#146;t we have to pay for cleaning up Mexico&#146;s pollution in
order to make NAFTA a success?</i><p>
<p>
A:  U.S. taxpayers should not be forced to subsidize environmental cleanup in a
foreign country.   Environmental foreign aid violates the &#147;polluter
pays&#148; principle of sound environmental management.  The Mexican government
should do a better job of protecting private property rights, so that
environmental harms to individuals can be properly redressed.  Because
wealth-creation is a pre-requisite for environmental improvement, U.S. policy
toward Mexico should be trade, not aid.  NAFTA&#146;s environmental bank is a
waste of taxpayer dollars and should be scrapped.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  As the sole remaining superpower, should not America promote sustainable
environmental policies worldwide?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  The U.S. should remain actively involved in the world.  However, foreign
aid has not been successful in promoting freer markets or economic progress in
recipient nations.  It has only propped up corrupt government bureaucracies,
promoted statist economic policies, and accelerated environmental degradation.
Worst of all, foreign aid distorts markets by subsidizing domestic exporters
and picking winners and losers in international trade. 
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
