<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Trade and Environment</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Trade and Environment</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The U.S. has entered into several international treaties that aim to regulate
or restrict international trade under the guise of environmental protection.
More are on the horizon.  These treaties represent a threat to the global
trading system, and will do little to safeguard the environment.  U.S. imports
and exports are facing a growing array of political controls in the global
economy because of these international treaties:<p>
<UL>
<LI> The <b>Basel Convention </b>establishes burdensome international regulations
and standards for the production, transport, and disposal of
&#147;hazardous&#148; materials. Basel&#146;s wide-ranging definitions
encompass the byproducts of nearly all agricultural and industrial processes.
Trade in &#147;hazardous&#148; products for disposal and recycling purposes is
forbidden between industrialized OECD nations and developing countries
(non-OECD), as well as between signatories and non-signatories.  The U.S. has
signed but not yet ratified the treaty.<p>

<LI>	The <b>Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species</b> (CITES),
regulates commerce in wildlife and wildlife products, prohibiting trade in
certain categories of endangered and threatened species.  The treaty bans trade
with non-parties, and enables governments to impose trade barriers based on
environmental considerations outside their domestic jurisdiction.  Most
notably, international trade in elephant ivory has been banned under CITES.
The U.S. has imposed trade sanctions on Taiwan to express displeasure over its
failure to prevent trade in endangered wildlife products.<p>

</UL>	
<P>Environmental trade barriers are one of the biggest threats to freer world
trade. The aforementioned environmental treaties were first incorporated into
the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). The regional trade bloc also
set up a Commission on Environmental Cooperation (CEC) to conduct environmental
investigations, to adjudicate disputes, and to promote environmental
enforcement.  Similarly, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade/World Trade
Organization (WTO), the international body which enforces global trade rules,
is considering ways to incorporate environmental treaties and trade barriers
through its Committee on Trade and the Environment.  This would be a mistake.<p>
	The &#147;greening&#148; of trade policies is an ominous development in
international affairs. Environmental trade barriers are simply a proxy for
tariffs, allowing governments to protect domestic industries from foreign
competition under the guise of phony environmental concerns. &#147;Green&#148;
protectionism is no less harmful than its economic variant.  The U.S. should
not be a party to international treaties which legitimize environmental trade
barriers.<p>
<i>Q:  Should the U.S. insist that its trading partners adopt equivalent
environmental standards?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Diverse countries have diverse environmental priorities.  Developing
countries, in particular, do not have sufficient resources to spend on
environmental controls, particularly the costly EPA-style regulations used in
the U.S.  It would be unfair to impose First World standards on Third World
countries.  We should not promote harmonization of international environmental
policies through NAFTA or the GATT/WTO.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Should the U.S. use trade sanctions to impose its environmental
standards on foreign countries.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: The U.S. has never been elected the world&#146;s environmental policeman.
Trade sanctions and other measures attempt to make enactment of U.S.
government-approved regulations a pre-condition for the right to trade with
American businesses.  The U.S. has tried to compel its trading partners to
enforce U.S.-style environmental policies with regard to resources solely in
their jurisdiction, as when we attempted to force Mexico to adopt our
&#147;dolphin-safe&#148; standard for catching tuna.  Trade embargoes and
restrictions based on &#147;process and production methods&#148; allow the
government to use vague and arbitrary criteria in closing markets from
competition. Environmental sanctions disrupt trade, burden U.S. importers and
exporters unfairly, and damage U.S. international competitiveness.  Trade bans
routinely fail to achieve their goals.  The CITES ban on trade in elephant
ivory, for example, merely destroyed market incentives to conserve elephants.
Closed mark! ets prevent economic growth, wealth creation, and higher incomes,
which are essential for enabling people in the developing world to afford a
cleaner environment.  Perpetuation of Third World poverty is neither an
effective nor ethical means of controlling pollution.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Are international controls needed for trade in hazardous materials and
wastes?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  The Basel Convention is an enemy of business, but no friend of the
environment.  The treaty&#146;s often vague definition of
&#147;hazardous,&#148; heavily influenced by Greenpeace, restricts trade in all
kinds of waste, scrap and recyclable materials.  Any products containing even
trace amounts of metals (e.g. lead, copper, gold) and their related compounds
are adversely affected.  The treaty arbitrarily bans trade for recycling
purposes between OECD and non-OECD countries, meaning that useful materials
which might be recovered abroad must instead be disposed of at home.  Congress
should not ratify this ill-considered treaty by implementing its provisions
into U.S. law. 
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/mandates.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
<P>
