<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Principles for Economic Freedom and Environmental Quality</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">


<BR CLEAR>
<P>

<CENTER>
<H3>
<IMG SRC="/images/globe4.gif" HEIGHT=71 WIDTH=142 ALT="CEI Global Update"><BR>
August 1996</H3>
<H2>Principles for Economic Freedom<br>
and Environmental Quality</H2>
<H3>A Free Market Response<br> to the President's Council on Sustainable Development</H3>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>
<H4>VISION STATEMENT</H4>

<P><B>PCSD:</B> "Our vision is of a life-sustaining Earth.  We are committed to the achievement of a dignified, peaceful, and equitable existence.  A sustainable United States will have a growing economy that provides equitable opportunities for satisfying livelihoods and a safe, healthy, high quality of life for current and future generations.  Our nation will protect its environment, its natural resource base, and 
the functions and viability of natural systems on which all life depends."	

<P><B>Alternative:</B> "Our vision of a life-sustaining earth is one in which environmental resources are fully integrated into a free market system based on private property. Expansion of individual liberty and creative ecological privatization offer the greatest promise of effectively enhancing economic growth and environmental quality."

<P><HR><P>

<H4>President's Council on Sustainable Development vs. the Free Market</H4>

<B>PCSD "We Believe Statement"</B>:	followed by 	<B>FREE MARKET PRINCIPLES:</B>


<p><B>1.</B> To achieve our vision of sustainable development, some things must grow
-- jobs, productivity, wages, capital, and savings, profits, information, knowledge, and education -- and others -- pollution, waste, and poverty -- must not.	

<p><B>1.</B> To achieve our vision of growth and prosperity, economic freedom must be restored. Economic freedom reduces pollution, waste, and poverty, making it the only true form of sustainable development.
<P><BR>

<P><B>2.</B> Change is inevitable and necessary fore the sake of future generations
and for ourselves.  We can choose a course for change that will lead to the
mutually reinforcing goals of economic growth, environmental protection, and social equity.	

<P><B>2.</B> In the face of future change and uncertainty, we must choose a course of
action which promotes the mutually reinforcing goals of human liberty and
environmental quality.
<P><BR>

<P><B>3.</B>  Steady progress in reducing disparities in education, opportunity, and
environmental risk within society is essential to economic growth, environmental health and social justice.	

<P><B>3.</B> Private property and a free marketplace are essential to the health and
viability of natural systems and provide the best mechanisms for realizing human concern for environmental quality. 
<P><BR>

<P><B>4.</B> The United States made great progress in protecting the environment in
the last 25 years, and must continue to make progress in the next 25 years. We can achieve that goal because market incentives and the power of consumers can lead to significant improvements in environmental performance at low cost.	

<P><B>4.</B> The United States has made its greatest environmental strides when it has allowed the institutions of a free society to flourish. Restoring and
reinforcing such institutions is the surest way to achieve significant improvements in the future. 
<P><BR>

<P><B>5.</B> Economic growth based on technological innovation, improved efficiency, and expanding global markets is essential for progress toward greater prosperity, equity, and environmental quality.	


<P><B>5.</B> Economic growth based on technological innovation and economic
efficiency is essential for progress toward environmental quality.
<P><BR>

<P><B>6.</B> Environmental regulations have improved and must continue to improve the lives of all Americans.  Basic standards of performance that are clear, fair, and consistently enforced remain necessary to protect that progress. The current regulatory system should be improved to deliver required results at lower costs.  In addition, the system should provide enhanced flexibility in return for superior environmental performance.	


<P><B>6.</B> Environmental laws and command-and-control regulation have undermined environmental quality and violated the Constitutionally-guaranteed rights of many Americans. Environmental degradation has resulted from government attempts to manage markets and to control resource use through the political process.  The current regulatory system must be revised, taking into account the basic institutional arrangements necessary for environmental protection. 
<P><BR>

<P><B>7.</B> Environmental progress will depend on individual, institutional, and corporate responsibility, commitment and stewardship.	

<P><B>7.</B> Environmental progress depends on free market institutions and private stewardship.
<P><BR>


<P><B>8.</B> We need a new collaborative decision process that leads to better decisions; more rapid change; and more sensible use of human, natural and financial resources in achieving our goals.	

<P><B>8.</B> Decision-making should be decentralized through voluntary transactions among free individuals in the private marketplace, allowing individuals and communities to pursue diverse environmental values.
<P><BR>

<P><B>9.</B> The nation must strengthen its communities and enhance their role in decisions about environment, equity, natural resources and economic progress so that the individuals and institutions most immediately affected can join with others in the decision process.	

<P><B>9.</B> Individual property owners and local communities most immediately affected should make decisions about environmental management, unhampered by federal mandates.
<P><BR>

<P><B>10.</B> Economic growth, environmental protection, and social equity are linked.  We need to develop integrated policies to achieve these national goals.	

<P><B>10.</B> The free-enterprise system is the best means of promoting prosperity, environmental quality, and social equity.
<P><BR>

<P><B>11.</B> The United States should have policies and programs that contribute to stabilizing global human population; this objective is critical if we hope to have the resources needed to ensure a high quality of life for future generations.	

<P><B>11.</B> The United States should not attempt to stabilize human population through reproductive health, sterilization, or abortion policies.  Arbitrary limits on human resources threaten our survival.
<P><BR>

<P><B>12.</B> Even in the face of scientific uncertainty, society should take reasonable actions to avert risks where the potential harm to human health or the environment is thought to be serious or irreparable.	

<P><B>12.</B> Environmental protection is not advanced by the precautionary
limitation of scientific, economic or technological progress. The risks to the future of technological and economic stagnation must be weighed against the risks of technological and economic progress.
<P><BR>

<P><B>13.</B> Steady advances in science and technology are essential to help improve economic efficiency, protect and restore natural systems, and modify consumption patterns.	

<P><B>13.</B> Advances in economic efficiency and technological innovation, arising through competition and the perceptiveness of entrepreneurs, are environmentally beneficial. Ensuring a free marketplace is the surest way to encourage scientific and technological advancement.
<P><BR>

<P><B>14.</B> A growing economy and healthy environment are essential to national and global security.	

<P><B>14.</B> A growing economy is essential to national prosperity and environmental quality. 
<P><BR>

<P><B>15.</B> A knowledgeable public, the free flow of information, and opportunities for review and redress are critically important to open, equitable, and effective decision-making.	

<P><B>15.</B> The public has the greatest access to knowledge and information in a free market system characterized by economic freedom and decentralized decision-making.
<P><BR>

<P><B>16.</B> Citizens must have access to high quality and lifelong formal and non-formal education that enables them to understand the interdependence of economic prosperity, environmental quality, and social equity -- and prepares them to
take actions that support all three.	

<P><B>16.</B> Citizens must be allowed to utilize their own creative energies, without direction from centralized government education programs.


<P>
<BR>


<HR>
