<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Marine Resources</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Marine Resources</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Valuable resources that are unowned are also uncared for; they fall prey to
the &#147;Tragedy of the Commons.&#148;  Property rights to marine resources
are the only way to reconcile competing commercial, recreational, and
environmental concerns, and prevent further degradation of the marine
environment.  Ownership in the oceans makes conservation an asset, not a
liability.<p>
	The recent collapse of the once-rich fisheries of the Georges Bank off the
coast of New England serves as a dramatic testimony to the failure of fishery
management in the United States. Traditional limits on seasons and gear ignore
the tragedy of the commons and encourage fishermen to vacuum the seas.
Regulatory approaches to improving fishing methods rarely consider the perverse
incentives they create, the costs they impose, the resentment they incur and
the creativity they stifle. <p>
	Without any form of ownership, it is unreasonable for any individual to
attempt to conserve or enhance resources because the benefits of doing so are
diluted throughout the fishery. Fishermen have no desire to destroy their own
source of livelihood, but as long as non-ownership encourages overfishing, fish
stocks will continue to decline.<p>
	One recent attempt to inject some form of ownership into fisheries management
is the Individual Transferable Quota (ITQ). ITQs have proven effective in other
countries and in the U.S., and can be an important first step acknowledging the
power of the market to protect the environment. On the other hand, ITQs are not
real property rights, and any limitation on ownership, such as
non-transferability, devalues rights and discourages conservation and
stewardship. Once created, they may also become similar to &#147;taxi cab
medallions,&#148; limiting competition and creating a vested special interest
in maintaining the status quo. <p>
	In the recent Congressional debate on fishery management the importance of
local control over management decisions was overlooked.  Efforts should be made
to devolve control over marine resources to as local a level as possible.  At
the very least, the regional management councils set up by the original 1976
Magnuson Act should decide the efficacy of proposed management plans. ITQs or
other ownership schemes will certainly not be perfect for every fishery, but
Congress should not eliminate them as an option.<p>
	While ownership may be difficult to conceptualize for fugitive resources, it
has a proven track record for conserving sedentary resources. From outright
fee-simple ownership of oyster beds in  Washington to proprietary ownership of
artificial reefs in Alabama, habitat has been protected and enhanced. One
well-documented study compared public oyster beds in Maryland to privately
leased oyster beds in Virginia before disease wreaked havoc all over the
Chesapeake. The study found that leased beds were better managed and far more
productive than their public, open access counterparts.<p>
	Under a system of clearly defined property rights, fishermen capture the
benefits of practicing conservation, using more efficient fishing methods and
protecting habitat. The self destructive incentives of the commons must be
alleviated before fishermen will seek creative and practical solutions to the
problems they face.<p>

<i>Q:  How can private property rights improve marine resource management when
they can&#146;t be enforced or monitored effectively? </i><p>
<p>
A:  Advanced technologies are often blamed for depleted fisheries, but these
same technologies offer tremendous opportunities for protecting and monitoring
marine resources. The oceans are similar to the American West in the early
1800s, when enclosing and monitoring land and cattle were unthinkable. But in
the West property rights were clearly allocated, and before long owners came up
with barbed wire and branding to effectively define and defend their property.
Technologies exist that could start &#147;fencing&#148; and
&#147;branding&#148; marine resources if only rights to them were clearly
defined.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Won&#146;t private property rights to marine resources destroy
traditional fishing communities?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Property rights do not preclude common property arrangements. Common
property rights regimes have successfully protected resources in traditional
communities like those of Maine lobster fishers for ages. Under some
circumstances common property is more suitable than private property, and
nothing would prevent these regimes from remaining or evolving.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  When property rights are initially allocated some people will always
feel cheated. Can an allocation ever be politically feasible?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Any group that does not think it will come out ahead will oppose any change
in the status quo, often smaller operations with less political clout. This was
the case in the recent ITQ debate in Congress and it led to a toothless
revision of the Magnuson Act. Efforts to allow property rights to develop will
face major hurdles until the allocation problem is addressed properly. Each
case is different, but care must be taken to include all of the stakeholders in
the allocation process.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Where is the justification for giving away a valuable public resource to
a select few?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Open access to valuable resources is an appealing concept but a proven
failure.  Access to all will leave a valuable resource for none. Under a system
of property rights everyone would still have an opportunity to fish, but the
destructive force of open access would be mitigated.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/ozone.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
