<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Sustainable Development</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Sustainable Development</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>&#147;Sustainable development&#148; is the <i>raison d&#146;&ecirc;tre</i> for
numerous environmental treaties and United Nations conventions.  It is the
environmental pretext for expanding the power of national and international
bureaucracies to control the economy.  This form of central economic planing is
seen as essential to prevent resource depletion, pollution, and the destruction
of biological diversity. Proponents of sustainable development are calling for
an international framework of restrictions on individual and economic freedoms
&#151; on trade, on economic and technological progress, on the use of energy,
on agriculture &#151; to ensure the survival of the planet.<p>
	Sustainable development is premised on the idea that the globalization of
technology and economic growth are inherently destructive to the environment.
However, the habitual predictions by environmental doomsayers of an end to the
world&#146;s abundant resources have never proven correct. The critics of
capitalism fail to account for the powerful forces of innovation which exist in
the marketplace.  In a free market, entrepreneurs compete to develop low-cost,
efficient solutions to the problems of resource scarcity, enabling people to do
more with less; Capitalism has produced more environment-friendly innovations
than any other economic system.  Though this dynamic was missing under
socialist economies, proposals for sustainable development would replicate
economic planning in the ecological sphere.<p>
The influential 1992 &#147;Earth Summit&#148; held in Rio de Janeiro put forth
sustainable development as the central organizing principle for global
environmental policy.  Since then, international bureaucrats, environmental
activists and federal government officials have developed a growing body of
international law, which includes such treaties and agreements as Agenda 21,
the Global Climate Convention, the Biodiversity Convention, and the Law of the
Sea Treaty.  These treaties call for the imposition of costly regulations and
increased government spending on wasteful foreign aid programs.  Wealth
transfers are funneled through the Agency for International Development, the
World Bank&#146;s Global Environmental Facility, and U.N. agencies. They are
the beginnings of a blueprint for central ecological planning.<p>
Global environmental initiatives enacted under the guise of sustainable
development also threaten the economic future of developing countries.
&#147;Eco-imperialism&#148; is a growing trend in which wealthier nations
impose global environmental standards.  Developing nations, home to most of the
world&#146;s poor, suffer the most from such restrictions on economic
opportunities, growth, and development.  These countries worry that their
efforts to rise out of poverty will be prohibited as &#147;environmentally
unsustainable&#148; by the industrial powers. <p>
Proponents of sustainable development fail to recognize the role of material
poverty in causing environmental degradation.  Affluent societies voluntarily
expend resources on environmental quality, without coercion from government,
but poverty-stricken populations can less easily afford environmental
amenities.  Those in poorer countries are particularly vulnerable to disease,
natural disasters, and nutritional deficiencies; more than 2 million die
annually worldwide due to inadequate sanitation alone.  Thus a global policy to
restrict economic development under the guise of sustainability will actually
harm people as well as the environment.<p>
The pursuit of &#147;sustainable development&#148; through the expansion of
regulatory authority and international bureaucracies will inevitably lead to
both economic and environmental failure.  True sustainable development can only
come through an embrace of market institutions.<p>
<i>Q:  What is wrong with &#147;sustainable development&#148;?</i><p>

A:  &#147;Sustainable development&#148; as pursued by the U.N. and the
environmental lobby has become a euphemism for <i>no</i> development.
International regulations, taxes, and other economic growth restrictions would
result in bigger government and a more restricted market.  History has shown,
however, that central planning caused severe environmental degradation in the
former Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.  True &#147;sustainable&#148;
development can only come from a reliance upon the market institutions of
private property, voluntary exchange, and rule of law.<p>

<i>Q:  Won&#146;t the global environment deteriorate without international
cooperation?</i><p>

A:  Giving the U.N. more power and financial resources is no way to help the
environment.  Environmental quality is a local issue, not a global one.
Therefore, too much centralization would actually cause environmental harm.
Proposals for environmental taxes, charges, and user fees would give the U.N.
new sources of revenue, but would diminish political accountability for the use
of government funds as well as natural resources.  Instead of enacting one
environmental policy globally, nations should compete with each other with
diverse approaches.  The countries which effectively deregulate their economies
are more likely to promote economic development, acquire cleaner technologies,
and create the wealth necessary to afford environmental improvements.<p>

<i>Q:  Shouldn&#146;t the international community do everything possible to
reduce the potential for harm to the environment? </i><p>

A:  This is the so-called &#147;precautionary principle,&#148; which requires
governments to impose economic restrictions preemptively, before the existence
and validity of an environmental threat can be discerned scientifically.  Under
this standard, most new technologies could be barred as an environmental
precaution, without regard to sound science.  In addition, this standard
mandates hasty government actions without regard to the risks that such
&#147;remedies&#148; would create.  For example, Congress accelerated the
phaseout of chemical refrigerants under the Montreal Protocol, due to
unconfirmed fears about the effects of ozone thinning above North America,
without any consideration of the severe economic and social consequences that
would result from the action. 

</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
