<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Land Rights Washington Roundup -- August 21, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="/ceiesp.gif" ALT="Environmental Studies Program" HEIGHT=65 WIDTH=270 ALIGN=LEFT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/landrts.gif" WIDTH=190 HEIGHT=115 ALT="LAND RIGHTS WASHINGTON ROUNDUP">
<H3><A HREF="/adler.html">Jonathan H. Adler</A>, August 21, 1996</H3>
<P>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<BR>

Hopes were high for a July vote on legislation to enhance the 
protection of private property rights and require compensation for 
regulatory takings.  Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott’s staff assured 
land rights advocates that the "The Omnibus Property Rights Act" would 
come up for a vote before the August recess.

<P>In preparation for a floor debate the bill was modified to blunt 
opponents’ criticisms. Of note, the 33 percent devaluation trigger for 
takings compensation was raised to 50 percent.  Nonetheless, rumors 
began circulating about ebbing support.  Several Republicans, concerned 
about attacks from environmental activists, privately urged that the 
bill be put aside, despite recent polling data reconfirming that 
property rights is a political winner.  As Democratic pollster Celinda 
Lake commented to the <I>National Journal</I>, "If one ever lets the 
Republicans convince voters that either the Democrats or the 
environmental groups are anti-private property, then I think it could be 
a very dangerous issue.  I think its one of the most serious issues that 
environmentalists should worry about because it is such a core value to 
people."

<P>On July 29, Lott met with former Senator Malcolm Wallop, Henson Moore of 
the American Forest and Paper Association and other supporters of 
takings legislation to discuss whether the bill will be scheduled for a 
vote after the August recess, but the Senate Majority Leader was 
unwilling to make a commitment without a hard vote count ensuring that 
the bill will receive a minimum of 53 votes.  As a result it is 
questionable whether there will be a Senate vote on property rights in 
1996.

<P>While takings compensation sits in the wings, there is increasing 
concern that Heritage Areas legislation will be folded into a bill to 
create an independent trust to manage the Presidio in San Francisco.  
The former military post is to become part of the Golden Gate National 
Recreation Area and houses several environmental groups, including the 
Tides Foundation.

<P>The Presidio bill has become something of a Christmas tree of late.  
Having passed both the House and Senate have passed the measure which 
now sits in Conference, loaded for bear with dozens of land-related 
measures and park barrel projects, leaving House and Senate negotiators 
to sort out what should be included in the final bill.  Heritage areas 
are on the table, as is a proposal to create the 25,800 acre Opal Creek 
Wilderness and National Scenic Recreation area in Oregon.  

<P>The inclusion of grazing reform was also on the table, but now the House 
is expected to move on a watered-down bill independently because Rep. 
Sherwood Boehlert (R-NY) convinced House Speaker Newt Gingrich that 
grazing would prevent passage of the Presidio package.  A vote on 
compromise legislation negotiated by Boehlert had been scheduled just 
before the August recess.  Yet this bill was put off as Boehlert did not 
want to anger the Sierra Club before receiving their endorsement during 
the Republican convention in San Diego.  On August 13, the Sierra Club 
gave Boehlert the Edgar Wayburn Award because he "has saved the nation 
from environmental disaster."  A vote on grazing is now expected in 
mid-September. 

<P>A bill to purchase the Sterling Forest was also slated for inclusion in 
the Presidio package.  Federal acquisition of the forest land has been a 
high priority for the Speaker who initially proposed a deal whereby 
federal grasslands in Oklahoma would be sold to pay for the Sterling 
purchase.  Yet this land swap was nixed after environmentalists 
complained.  A bill authorizing the feds to purchase the land passed the 
House by voice vote on July 30, and the Senate has yet to act.  

<P>On the heritage areas front, the Dole campaign is said to have chimed 
in, urging that any heritage area proposal include provisions to protect 
private landowners, such as a clause to allow landowners to opt-out of 
any heritage area in their community.  While this does not address all 
of the property rights concerns raised by heritage areas, it is a step 
in the right direction and could mute preservationist support.
	 
<P>In other news, House Speaker Newt Gingrich supported efforts by 
California lawmakers to authorize construction of the Auburn Dam, to no 
avail.  The House Transportation Committee voted against the project 
35-28.  The Speaker’s move was viewed as an effort to reach out to Rep. 
Richard Pombo (R-CA) and other Western lawmakers upset about the 
Speaker’s unwillingness to support reform of the Endangered Species Act 
and other efforts to reduce federal land-use regulations.  Some observe 
that Speaker only seems willing to support Westerners when they ask for 
more government, not less.
	
<P>Finally, Republicans rushed an overhaul of federal pesticide 
regulations, including the infamous "Delaney Clause," to the President’s 
desk just before the August recess.  While the House Commerce Committee 
and some trade associations have heralded the measure as a deregulatory 
success, the new law is more likely to clamp down on pesticide use and 
raise prices for consumers.  This should come as no surprise, as the 
bill was endorsed by arch-Green Rep. Henry Waxman (D-CA).


<P><BR>
<HR>
<P><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>
<A HREF="/adler.html">Jonathan H. Adler</A> is Director of <A HREF="/esp.html">Environmental Studies</A> at the <A HREF="/">Competitive Enterprise Institute</A> in Washington, D.C. (202)331-1010; 
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:jadler@cei.org">jadler@cei.org</A>

<P>Washington Roundup is a monthly feature of the <I>Land Rights Letter</I>, a national newsletter dedicated to educating landowners about private 
property rights issues.  It is published by the Land Rights Foundation, 
Inc., a tax-exempt 501(c)(3) educational corporation. Phone: (518) 
725-1090; fax: (518) 725-8239; e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:landrights@aol.com">landrights@aol.com</A>.  This article 
is reprinted with permission from Land Rights Letter P.O.Box 1111, 
Gloversville, New York, 12078.
</FONT>
