<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Property Rights and "Takings"</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Property Rights and &#145;Takings&#146;</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The &#147;takings clause&#148; of the Fifth Amendment to the Constitution
reads, &#147;nor shall private property be taken for public use without just
compensation.&#148;  Despite this clear admonition, federal environmental
regulations routinely &#147;take&#148; the property of American citizens
without compensation by denying them the reasonable use of their land.
Fairness demands that this practice be put to an end. Landowners should be
compensated for all regulatory takings of their land.<p>
	In the 1960 Supreme Court decision of <i>Armstrong v. U.S.</i>, the Supreme
Court wrote that the primary purpose of the Takings Clause is &#147;to bar
Government from forcing some people alone to bear public burdens which, in all
fairness and justice, should be borne by the public as a whole.&#148;  When a
landowner is forced to provide a portion of his or her land for public purposes
&#151; such as species habitat, wetlands, &#147;greenways,&#148; and the like
&#151; this principle should apply.<p>
	Environmental laws, such as the <A HREF="/ebb/esa.html">Endangered Species Act</A>, were passed by
Congress to benefit the public as a whole.  It is only fair that the burden of
these laws be paid for by the public as a whole, rather than by those
unfortunate landowners whose property happens to have characteristics that are
valued by the public at large.<p>
	Consider the following examples:<p>
<ul>
<li>	In Utah, Brandt Child planned to build a campground and golf course on his
property.  The project came to an abrupt halt when the Fish and Wildlife
Service declared that the land contained habitat for the endangered Kanab
Ambersnail.  The area was fenced off and Child was forbidden to work in the
area.  Child&#146;s land has been effectively taken by the federal government
because he can no longer use it.  He has estimated his losses at $2.5
million.<p>
<li>	Margaret Rector owns a 15-acre parcel of land in Texas, originally purchased
to fund her retirement.  The land was valued at over $830,000.  After it became
subject to federal regulation under the Endangered Species Act, the value
dropped to just over $30,000. <p>
<li>	In the case of <i>Dolan v. City of Tigard</i>, the Dolans learned that they
could only receive a permit to expand their plumbing supply store if they gave
the city of Tigard 10 percent of their land for use as a bike path and
&#147;greenway.&#148; The Supreme Court ruled in 1994 that this amounted to a
taking of private property without just compensation.<p>
</ul>	<p>Congress should reaffirm the Constitutional protections afforded to private
property rights.  In particular, Congress should:<p>
<ul>
<li>	Require federal regulatory agencies to compensate landowners for all
regulatory takings;<p>
<li>	Require that compensation be paid directly from the budget of the agency
responsible for the regulation that resulted in a &#147;taking&#148;;<p>
<li>	Instruct regulatory agencies to analyze their regulations to determine when
takings will occur; <p>
<li>	Reform the Tucker Act to remove obstacles that prevent victims of regulatory
takings from pursuing their claims in federal courts;<p>
<li>	Bar agencies from engaging in regulatory takings, even when landowners are
compensated, except in those cases where such actions are required to achieve
explicit statutory requirements.<p>
</ul>
Property rights are the foundation of a free society and a free market economy.
They must be protected.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Isn&#146;t the &#147;takings&#148; movement really about forcing the
taxpayer to pay polluters not to pollute?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Not at all. All individuals should have the right to use their property as
they see fit, provided that they are not inflicting harm upon others.  This
means that there is no right to pollute the property of one&#146;s neighbor,
and that government actions that prevent identifiable harms do not require
compensation.  Compensation for &#147;takings&#148; is about compensating
landowners when the government tells them that they cannot make reasonable use
of their land, such as building a home, planting crops, or perhaps just
maintaining species habitat.  Yet these are all examples of actions that have
been prohibited by the government on private lands. These are the type of
instances that &#147;takings&#148; compensation proposals seek to address.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Will compensating landowners for &#147;takings&#148; bankrupt the
government?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  If regulatory agencies continue to conduct business as usual, it certainly
could cost the government a lot of money to compensate landowners.  However,
ensuring that landowners are compensated for regulatory actions that deprive
them of the reasonable use of their land will restore accountability to
regulatory actions by forcing agencies to consider the costs, economic and
otherwise, of their regulatory decisions.  The Congressional Budget Office has
determined that requiring compensation for regulatory takings would not affect
federal receipts or the federal deficit if compensation for regulatory takings
is paid from pre-appropriated agency funds.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Will forcing regulatory agencies to engage in &#147;takings&#148;
assessments bog them down in red tape and prevent them from fulfilling their
duties, such as protecting the environment?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Adding this small requirement onto existing review, public notice and
comment procedures should not hinder any agency from achieving its mission.
The federal government is always required to file an environmental impact
statement when undertaking a new initiative.  All that &#147;takings&#148;
advocates ask, is that the federal government give the same deference to the
Constitutional rights of American citizens and assess how those rights may be
impacted by regulatory activities.  <p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Don&#146;t landowners receive government-conferred benefits
(&#147;givings&#148;) that increase property values and offset the costs of
regulatory takings?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Those benefits that government provides to citizens through building roads
and bridges, providing police and fire protection, and the like, are paid for
through taxes and user fees.  Therefore, property owners have already paid for
so-called &#147;givings,&#148; and will pay even more, in the form of higher
property tax assessments, if government actions increase the value of their
property.  Such generic &#147;givings&#148; to the public as a whole do not
justify the selective imposition of stringent land-use controls on private
landowners.</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/recfees.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
<P>
