<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Interstate Transport of Waste</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Interstate Transport of Waste</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The United States Constitution explicitly forbids state and local governments
from interfering with interstate commerce.  In environmentally-related cases,
the Supreme Court has consistently held that &#147;a State may not accord its
own inhabitants a preferred right of access over consumers in other States to
natural resources located within its borders.&#148;  This is also true of waste
disposal services.  Congress should respect the Constitution and not enact laws
permitting state and local interference with the interstate transportation of
waste, including so-called &#147;flow control&#148; statutes.<p>
	States that seek to limit the interstate transportation of waste argue that
some states should not be the dumping grounds for others.  In effect, they
argue that all states should be self-sufficient with regard to waste disposal
services.  This makes no more sense than arguing that all states should be
self-sufficient with regard to food production, energy generation, or mineral
supplies.  Different regions have a comparative advantage in the provision of
certain goods and services.  Unrestricted commerce throughout the nation
promotes the public interest by allowing specialization to increase efficiency,
lower prices and spur innovation.  This is as true in the field of waste
disposal as it is in any other.<p>
	Trade between states occurs for the same reason as trade between countries.
Trade occurs between parties that seek mutual advantage.  Trade encourages
specialization and greater productivity.  The ability of waste disposal
companies to attract business from other states increases the incentive to
develop the most efficient and environmentally-sound waste disposal processes.
Limiting the interstate transportation of waste eliminates these incentives,
and can actually have a negative impact on the environment.<p>
	Related to limitations on the importation of out-of-state waste are so-called
flow control ordinances.  These local ordinances require local businesses to
process and/or dispose of waste at a predetermined facility.  This prevents
companies that generate waste from seeking the most efficient means of
disposing of that waste.  The Supreme Court has properly ruled that flow
control ordinances are unconstitutional violations of the interstate commerce
clause.  Such ordinances are also unreasonable infringements upon the right to
contract.  They discriminate against out-of-state companies, increasing waste
disposal prices at the expense of the consumer and the environment.<p>
	Reauthorizing the use of flow control would be a step backward in the handling
of municipal solid waste.  Rather than encourage expanded markets in solid
waste management that would foster greater efficiencies and innovation, flow
control would establish protected government monopolies that have no incentive
to increase the quality of their services.  According to one study, flow
control can increase the cost of waste disposal by as much as 40 percent.
Waste management prices would be set by political forces, without regard for
market pressures. Equally important, flow control laws unnecessarily inhibit
the ability of recyclers and other ecological entrepreneurs to compete in the
marketplace. <p>
	It is one thing for governments to impose health and safety regulations that
affect the transportation of waste.  It is quite another for governments to
limit the transportation of waste, as several states have tried to do.
Congress should refrain from authorizing any state or local infringements upon
interstate commerce in solid waste and waste disposal services.<p>
<i>Q:  Which states are most involved in shipping waste elsewhere and
why?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Most states <i>both </i>import and export solid waste.  In 1992, for
example, 47 states exported waste and 42 states imported waste from other parts
of the country.  Interstate trade in waste occurs because communities and waste
disposal companies are always looking for the least expensive and most
efficient means of handling trash.  Sometimes this means using a local landfill
or recycling facility, in other cases it means hauling the waste to a facility
somewhere else, perhaps across state lines.  <p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Why should some states be the dumping grounds for the rest of the
country?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Each region of the country has particular features &#150; geography,
population density, natural resource deposits, access to water, etc. &#150;
that make it particularly suited for the provision of particular goods and
services.  Just as some parts of the country are more suited for coal mining or
orange growing than others, some parts of the country have a comparative
advantage in the provision of waste disposal sites and services.  Some
communities reap significant economic benefits by providing waste disposal
services for other parts of the country.  Indeed, these communities see
importing waste as an opportunity, not a burden.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Don&#146;t local flow control ordinances enable municipalities and
counties to manage solid waste in a more environmentally sound manner?</i><p>
<p>
A:  The experience of most communities with flow control laws is that such
rules are used to prop up inefficient facilities at the expense of consumers
<i>and</i> environmental improvements.  By mandating that local waste haulers
use particular management facilities, they are prevented from using less
expensive or more environmentally-sound alternatives that may exist elsewhere.
The Sierra Club, for one, has pointed out that these regulations often inhibit
the development of recycling facilities and other waste management alternatives
in the marketplace.  This is why most major environmental organizations oppose
Congressional authorization of flow control.  It is actually likely that flow
control laws do far more environmental harm than good.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/recycle.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
<P>
