<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Wetlands</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Wetlands</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The federal government has implemented regulations to prevent the destruction
or alteration of America&#146;s wetlands.  These regulations deny private
landowners the productive use of their land without compensation.  These
regulations have bankrupted landowners and even sent Americans to jail for the
&#147;crime&#148; of wetland modification.  The cause of wetland protection is
better served through private conservation efforts than it is by imposing
limitations on the use of private land.<p>
	Under the current, expansive interpretation of section 404 of the <A HREF="/ebb/cleanh2o.html">Clean Water
Act</a>, landowners must obtain a permit from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
before engaging in any activity that may affect a wetland.  Because of how the
federal government defines wetlands, there are over 100 million acres of
protected wetlands in the United States.  Nearly 80 percent of these wetlands
are on private property.<p>
	Wetlands regulations impose significant burdens on owners of private property.
Landowners are routinely denied permits from the Corps of Engineers to modify
wetlands, even when such activities have minimal environmental impact.   Under
these rules, one individual was even sent to jail for building duck ponds on
federally designated wetlands.<p>
	Federal wetlands protections also impse costs on state and local governments.
By prohibiting development, the regulations often depress land values and,
consequently, local government revenues from property taxes.  One study found
that local governments could lose over $180 million in revenue in the state of
Arkansas alone. If the Arkansas analysis is correct, local governments
nationwide could stand to lose up to $6.3 billion in property tax revenues.<p>
	While some argue that section 404 regulations are needed to protect
America&#146;s vanishing wetlands, recent evidence shows that America is
creating more wetlands than are being destroyed.  In 1994, the
government&#146;s top three wetland restoration programs restored a combined
total of 195,000 acres of wetlands.  At the same time, data from the
government&#146;s National Resource Inventory concludes that the U.S. converted
157,000 acres of wetlands to other uses.  In other words, by the end of 1994
there were tens of thousands more acres of wetlands than there were at the
beginning.  This does not even include the achievements of private conservation
organizations, such as Ducks Unlimited.<p>
	When the Clean Water Act is reauthorized, the wetlands protection program
should be reformed, if not eliminated.  Positive reforms would include:<p>
<UL>
<LI>	The compensation of property owners when reasonable use of their land has
been taken by wetland regulation;<p>
<LI>	Elimination of &#147;no net loss&#148; of wetlands as official government
policy;<p>
<LI>	The classification of all wetlands based not on their wetness but on their
ecological value;<p>
<LI>	The replacement of the Section 404 regulatory program with a non-coercive
incentive based program.<p>
</UL>
<P>These steps would enhance the protection of private property without
sacrificing the environmental goal of wetlands protection.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Some say that America is losing 300,000 acres of wetlands a year.  Is
this true?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  No. The 300,000 acre figure is based on an old study that did not account
for both public and private wetland restoration projects.  Current estimates
show that the U.S. has achieved and surpassed no net loss.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  What is wrong with a simple permit process for people who wish to
develop, and potentially destroy, ecologically-important wetlands?</i><p>
<p>
A:  While the permitting process may sound reasonable on paper to some, it has
been extremely onerous in practice.  Under current law, the Corps of Engineers
must approve or reject a wetland modification permit application within 60
days.  However, the average wait for a ruling on a permit application is
currently over a year!  Secondarily, if the federal government is to try and
protect America&#146;s wetlands for environmental reasons, it must account for
the fact that not all wetlands have equal ecological significance.  Some
wetlands perform important water filtration, flood mitigation, and habitat
enhancement functions.  Others are mere bogs and breeding grounds for pests.
It would be more appropriate for the federal government to seek to protect the
highest-value wetlands, and the ecological values they promote by encouraging
private conservation efforts, than to impose a blanket wetlands protection
policy.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  How can wetlands be protected without the Section 404 program?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Programs such as the North American Waterfowl Management Plan, the Partners
for Wildlife Program and the Wetlands Reserve Program are far more effective at
protecting and restoring wetlands than the 404 program.  These programs
routinely conserve wetlands at a cost of $500 per acre &#151; sometimes even
less.  Regulatory programs, on the other hand, conserve wetlands at far greater
cost &#151; as much as $300,000 per acre when both public and private costs are
considered.  Voluntary, incentive-based programs, in combination with private
efforts, are largely responsible for the current achievements on wetlands and
exceeding no net loss.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
