<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI Staff: Ike C. Sugg</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLPADDING=15><TR><TD>

<IMG SRC="/images/staff/sugg.gif" WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=183 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=13 VSPACE=5 BORDER=1>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>


<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Ike C. Sugg</B></FONT><BR>
<B>Fellow in Wildlife and Land-Use Policy<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:sugg@CEI.org">sugg@CEI.org</A></B>
</CENTER>

<P>
<BR>
Ike C. Sugg is the Fellow in Wildlife and Land-Use Policy at the <A HREF="/">Competitive Enterprise Institute</A>, a free market research and advocacy organization
headquartered in Washington, D.C.  CEI emphasizes the marketing and
implementation of classical liberal ideals and believes limited government
and competition best serve the public interest.

<P>At CEI, Mr. Sugg works on <A HREF="/topic.html#biodiversity">wildlife</A> and <A HREF="/topic.html#lands">land use issues</A>, focusing both on the failures of governmental programs and the successes of private conservation
efforts.  Through intensive research, writing and speaking, Mr. Sugg seeks
to heighten public awareness of how government abuses private property
owners and mismanages natural resources.  By showing how private property
rights and economic incentives can work for natural resource conservation,
rather than against it, his work is aimed at reforming failing public
policies (both here and abroad) and fostering greater appreciation for the
ethical and conservation values of human liberty.  

<P>Mr. Sugg has presented his views before Congress, the President's Council on Environmental Quality, the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species, National Public Radio, CNBC, C-SPAN and other fora.  Some of his recent writings include a chapter in the book <I>Elephants and Whales: Resources for Whom?</I> (Gordon and Breach Science Publishers, UK: 1995); <I>Elephants and Ivory: Lessons from the Trade Ban</I> (IEA Studies on the Environment No. 2, UK: Nov. 1994); "Defining 'Harm' to Wildlife" (<I>The National Law Journal</I>, vol. 16, no. 42; June 1994); "Caught in the Act: Evaluating the
Endangered Species Act, Its Effects on Man and Prospects for Reform"
(<I>Cumberland Law Review</I>, vol. 24:1, 1993-1994); "California Fires -- Losing Houses, Saving Rats" (<I>The Wall Street Journal</I>, November 10, 1993 [which sparked ABC News program "20/20"'s breakthrough coverage of that disaster]); and numerous other articles in <I>The Wall Street Journal, The Washington Times, National Review</I> and <I>The American Spectator</I>, among others.

<P>Contact Ike Sugg at <A HREF="mailto:sugg@CEI.org">sugg@CEI.org</A>.


