<DOCNO>WT14-B02-64</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000017-B021-327</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cei.org:80/ebb/fredint.html 207.33.42.44 19970101102352 text/html 6988
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 10:23:59 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6817
Last-modified: Mon, 11 Nov 1996 16:24:27 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Introduction</H2>
by <A HREF="/staff/smith.html">Fred L. Smith, Jr.</A>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Environmental concerns both unite and divide the American people.  Every
American supports the goals of clean air, clean water, and the conservation of
natural resources.  This does not mean, however, that everyone supports
today&#146;s environmental policies.  Indeed, the past few years have seen a
rapid growth in opposition to the form and cost of existing federal
environmental laws &#150; opposition that fueled efforts to reform
environmental laws in the 104<sup>th</sup> Congress, and still demands
significant change today.<p>
	Today&#146;s overly politicized environmental policies too often restrict
economic opportunities while doing little to address legitimate environmental
concerns.  Policies are evaluated more by the pain caused to the economy,
rather than their gain to the ecology.  Environmental priorities have become
more responsive to media-derived sensational fear stories than to sound
science.  As a result, state and local officials are forced to divert resources
from critical local programs to meet arbitrary federal mandates.  Similarly,
landowners throughout the nation find themselves forced to organize at the
grassroots level to defend private property rights against environmental
regulatory assaults.  Small business owners, too, become increasingly irate as
they face ever escalating compliance costs designed to address ever more
infinitesimal environmental risks.  The result?  A growing consensus that
environmental policy is broken and needs to be fixed. <p>
	At the dawn of the information age, it is time to replace a generation of
environmental laws written in the midst of the industrial era &#150; a time
before personal computers, fiber optics, and the internet, a time when wage and
price controls were considered sound economic policy, and a time when
relatively little was known about the human impact on the world around us.  In
short, there needs to be a revolution in environmental policy &#150; a
revolution at least as dramatic and sweeping as that which has transformed the
rest of society. <p>
	<A HREF="/">The Competitive Enterprise Institute</A> has spent much of the past decade
advocating that critical reappraisal of environmental policy.  As a former
staffer at the Environmental Protection Agency, I have seen first hand how
misguided many environmental policies have become, and how easily environmental
protection can become a pretext for sacrificing individual liberties and the
economic well-being of the poor to a green regulatory hydra.  What is needed is
for all of us to take environmental issues seriously and to open our eyes to
new approaches, to a new environmental vision.<p>
	The environmental vision that CEI advocates is one that empowers individuals
and communities, not government bureaucrats.  CEI believes that the best
defense of environmental resources comes from property rights, competitive
markets and common law liability rules, not politically determined and enforced
regulation.  This view is commonly referred to as &#147;free-market
environmentalism.&#148;  <p>
	Under this approach, private stewardship arrangements would be encouraged to
empower all Americans to protect those environmental amenities they value most.
Free market environmentalism relies on entrepreneurial creativity, voluntary
associations, and private property arrangements to rescue ecological resources
now exposed to the tragedy of the commons.  Such an approach would reform the
institutional arrangements for addressing environmental risk by incorporating a
recognition that regulations can create risks as easily as they alleviate them;
there are indeed risks in technological change, but there are also large risks
in technological stagnation.  <i>Both</i> should be considered. Free market
environmentalism seeks to integrate ecological and economic values &#150;
seeing people as a part of nature, rather than as alien transgressors in the
Garden of Eden.<p>
	This <i>Environmental Briefing Book</i> &#150; the second edition produced by
CEI &#150; is designed to help citizens, candidates, and policy-makers share in
the free-market environmental vision and to better understand a range of reform
policies that would reorient environmental policy to complement our political
and economic freedoms, rather than to restrict them.  It promotes the greater
use of voluntary arrangements and private institutions, over the continued
reliance upon the coercive power of the state.<p>
	The <i>1996 Briefing Book</i> is expanded &#150; and we hope improved &#150;
from the 1994 edition.  The first section of this book is a series of brief
essays to summarize the insights and policy prescriptions of  free-market
environmentalism.  The latter section consists of brief summaries on key issues
that will confront policymakers during the next few years.  We have included a
selected bibliography for those who wish to learn more about the free-market
approach to environmental issues.  The CEI environmental staff &#150; one of
the largest free market environmental programs in the world &#150; is also
ready, willing and able to explain CEI positions and to discuss the research upon which CEI&#146;s positions are based.<p>
	Free market ideas have swept across the world in the past decade, improving
both the equity and efficiency of the world economy.  The virtues of the free
enterprise system and the individual liberties upon which it rests are widely
recognized as never before in human history.  Tragically, current environmental
policies threaten a return to the errors of centrally-planned societies.  CEI is working to change that.  We hope that this monograph will encourage you to as well.

</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/reform.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
