June 20, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Clyde Wayne Crews</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Subcommittee on
Water and Power Resources</i><p>
CEI Fellow in Regulatory Studies Wayne Crews presents CEI's support for
the efforts to privatize the Power Marketing Administrations (PMAs) as a
manifestation of today's wide scale public commitment to fundamental
governmental reform.<p>
May 18, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Ike Sugg</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Endangered Species Act Task Force, U. S. House
of Representatives Committee on Resources </i><p>
Ike Sugg, CEI's Fellow in Wildlife and Land-Use Policy, discusses the
property rights perspective of  the Endangered Species Act.<p>
May 18, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan Adler</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Committee on Environment and Public Works
Subcommittee on Superfund, Waste Control, and Risk Assessment</i><p>
Director of Environmental Studies Jonathan Adler presents the
free-market perspectives of  flow control and the interstate transportation of
Solid Waste before the Subcommittee on Superfund, Waste Control, and Risk
Assessment.  <p>
March 1, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Marlo Lewis, Jr.</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Joint Economic Committee</i><p>
Marlo Lewis, CEI's Executive Director, presents CEI's
recommendations concerning three proposals which would provide enforcement
mechanisms to achieve a balanced budget by the year 2002 to the Joint Economic
Committee.<p>
February 16, 1995	$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan H. Adler</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Committee on the
Judiciary, Subcommittee on the Constitution.</i><p>
Jonathan Adler, Director of Environmental Studies at CEI, addressed the
Subcommittee on the Constitution concerning property rights.  In the past year,
the environmental movement has felt a backlash from property owners who have
lost their land or use of their land because of environmental takings.  Mr.
Adler testified concerning the need for just compensation  to property owners
for these losses.  <p>
February 10, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Fred L. Smith Jr.  </b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Appropriations
Committee, Subcommittee on VA, HUD, and Independent Agencies. </i>  <p>
Mr. Smith was asked to testify about the importance of restoring limited
government to America.  He covered many subjects including  the EPA's impact on
the economy, the Radon Action Program,  the Pollution Prevention and Waste
Reduction Program, and the Office of  Environmental Education.<p>
February 2, 1995 		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Sam Kazman</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Committee on
Science.</i><p>
Sam Kazman, CEI's Legal Counsel, testified in favor of Title III of H.R.
9, "Risk Assessment and Cost/Benefit Analysis for New Regulations."  CEI has
long had a special interest in raising public awareness of the hidden costs of
overregulation.  Kazman discussed the need for legislation that requires
agencies to ask a few simple questions before enacting a proposed rule:  Do we
really need this?  Will it work?  Is the cost worth it? What could we get
instead with the money we're about to spend on this?<p>
January 30, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Fred L. Smith Jr. </b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Appropriation
Committee, Energy and Water Subcommittee.</i><p>
In this testimony, Fred Smith urges Congress to eliminate many of the wasteful
energy and water projects supported by the Federal Government.  Regulatory
programs such as the Civil Works department with in the Army Corps of Engineers
should be dismantled because of the costly and inflammatory nature of its
"mission."<p>
Mr. Smith also discusses privatizing, sorting out, and eliminating the federal
R&amp;D energy research role.<p>
January 18, 1995		$4.00<p>
<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
