<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Portability--A Trojan Pony</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>


<CENTER>
<H1>PORTABILITY--A TROJAN PONY<BR>
</H1>
Tom Miller<P>
Cover Story, February 1996 <a href="publist1.html#update"><i>CEI UpDate</i></A>
<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P><BR>
<P>

Even as they fought the Clinton health care plan, many Republicans signed
on to warm and fuzzy incremental insurance reform bills to show they were
in favor of "something."  In late January, President Clinton raised
the ante.  He challenged Congress to pass one of those measures, the
Kassebaum-Kennedy "Health Insurance Reform Act" (S. 1028).  If
congressional Republicans bite, Clinton will yell "Gotcha" and
America will once again be on the road to Clintoncare.<p>
	The proposed Senate legislation aims at making it easier for people to renew
or acquire health insurance coverage regardless of their health status,
particularly when they change or lose their jobs.  S. 1028 applies new
portability rules to all employment-based health plans and prohibits these
plans from limiting or denying coverage for more than 12 months for most
"preexisting" medical conditions.<p>
	Kassebaum-Kennedy also prohibits insurers and other health coverage issuers
from denying, based on health status, whole group coverage to employers with
two or more employees, and prevents employment-based health benefits plans from
excluding any employee from coverage through requirements based on
health-related factors.  In addition, the legislation generally provides
"guaranteed renewability" of health plan coverage to employer groups
and individuals, at the option of the insured, and guarantees
"group-to-individual portability" for individuals who leave group
insurance plans and lack access to other group insurance coverage.<p>
	Although the bill's goals seem compassionate and caring, S. 1028
misdiagnoses the problem.  Its remedial efforts will achieve little measurable
progress in expanding total levels of health insurance coverage and may
actually do some harm.  More dangerously, the bill would restore momentum for
surrendering the principles of individual choice, personal responsibility, and
risk-based pricing in favor of government-controlled health care markets.<p>
	The purpose of preexisting condition limits and exclusions in health insurance
policies is frequently misunderstood.  By providing partial coverage of persons
with preexisting conditions, the contractual clauses actually expand the
insurance market.  They offer some protection to persons who would be wholly
uninsurable unless some limits and conditions were attached to their coverage.
The Kassebaum-Kennedy bill's permissible time period for preexisting
condition limits effectively eliminates their application to medical conditions
that will either not require immediate treatment or can be treated initially by
out-of-pocket payments until new insurance coverage is obtained.  New
restrictions on preexisting condition exclusions will also undercut the
incentive to prevent and avoid dangerous conditions in the first place.<p>
	If insurers are prevented explicitly from adjusting their premiums and
restricting their coverage to reflect the fact that different people have
different risks, they will resort to more indirect and less efficient means to
match the value of health insurance to the amount for which people will
voluntarily pay.  Insurers may devote more resources to pinpointing particular
high-risk individuals, industries, and small employer groups.  They then may
discourage such high-risk customers from seeking their coverage.  Techniques
will include more creative use of "objective" variables as health
status surrogates, selective marketing, geographic targeting, service-based
cues to customers, and so on.  <p>
	Employers also will respond to politically directed changes in the composition
of their risk pools.  On the margin, they may reduce or limit the number of
their employees; use more independent contractors; invest in more labor-saving
alternatives; relocate operations away from higher risk areas; or cut back the
scope of their group insurance coverage.<p>
	All of the above countermeasures will be set in motion by the political
impulse to "solve" a vastly overstated and mischaracterized problem.
Insurance coverage denials for medical reasons account for only a small portion
of uninsured individuals under age 65.  The much ballyhooed problem of
"job lock" is hard to prove and is not a significant impediment to
labor mobility.  The presence of more uninsured people does not lead to more
successful cost shifting and higher health care prices.  Nor do firms that do
not provide insurance succeed in shifting labor costs to other insured
businesses.  <p>
	Advocates of S. 1028 overlook the real factors that reduce the availability
and raise the cost of private health insurance coverage.  They include the
effect of poor health on earnings and labor supply, the rate of labor force
turnover in the small group market, the relative elasticity of small employer
demand for group health insurance, the higher-than-average risks of people who
switch health insurance policies, the effects of state mandated benefits, and
the inflationary effect of increased levels of insurance coverage.<p>
	Incremental insurance reforms such as guaranteed renewability, guaranteed
issue, and portability share several basic characteristics.  They restrict the
choices of most currently insured people and raise the cost of their insurance
policies, in exchange for subsidizing insurance coverage for a smaller group of
people with greater risks and higher likely health care costs.  The proposed
reforms force healthy people to subsidize sick people, regardless of income,
and undermine incentives to take personal responsibility for one's future
health care needs.<p>
	In a market where the purchase of health insurance is voluntary, raising the
cost of insurance will raise the number of uninsured people.  Estimates vary as
to the magnitude of this effect, depending upon how extensive the cost-raising
regulations are and who is affected by them.  A mid-range estimate of the
elasticity of demand for health insurance is probably -0.6.  That means that a
10 percent increase in the price of insurance may increase the number of
uninsured by about 6 percent.<p>
	Efforts to spread the cost of cross subsidies for a targeted population across
a wider base of insurance buyers is the public choice formula for politically
driven cost shifting (i.e., concentrated benefits, diffuse costs).  However, in
the group health insurance market segment where coverage levels are the most
disappointing -- small groups of 50 or fewer employers -- current
purchasers are very cost sensitive.  For them, relatively small changes in the
cost of health insurance create significant cutbacks in coverage.  The large
majority of the working uninsured, who pass up coverage not because of poor
health status but because it costs too much, place a low value on health
insurance relative to other forms of compensation.  <p>
	A voluntary insurance market can afford only a limited degree of premium cross
subsidies before the number of low-risk groups and individuals dropping
coverage exceeds the total of high-risk groups and individuals gaining access
to underpriced insurance.  At that point, one reaches a political no-man's
land in which the next logical step down the tunnel of cost shifting appears to
be mandatory universal coverage.  If the healthy are going to subsidize the
sick, it becomes imperative to round up as many overpaying conscripts as
possible.  <p>
	Therefore, S. 1028's guaranteed issue, renewability, and portability will
inevitably lead to tighter health insurance regulation on the federal level.
Renewal or issuance of insurance policies cannot be guaranteed without
involving the government in setting rating band limits on insurance policy
prices.  After all, in what sense can the availability  of an insurance policy
be considered guaranteed if it becomes too expensive for some policyholders to
buy or renew?  <p>
	Guaranteed issue, renewability, and portability also will increase pressure
for a policy of mandatory, standardized health benefits.  Variations and
changes in an insurer's package of health benefits can complicate those
mandated guarantees, because quality variation in health plans can be an
indirect means to exclude higher cost customers.  Addressing comparability
measures and integration rules for the varied quality and medical practice
style of health plans that mobile workers choose also will be difficult.  <p>
	Thus, despite its purportedly modest goals, the Kassebaum-Kennedy bill's
efforts to remove health status considerations from the pricing and scope of
private insurance coverage leads down a one-way street where the ultimate
destination is the same one that Americans rejected in 1994: mandatory purchase
of standardized coverage, where the only cost constraints are imposed through
price controls and bureaucratic rationing.  <p>
	Advocates of Kassebaum-Kennedy deny the bill will raise insurance premiums
very much, if at all.  However, if providing guarantees of continued insurance
coverage is so inexpensive, why don't more people voluntarily buy such
protection on their own?  On the other hand, if individuals do find that the
cost of those insurance guarantees is more than they can (or are willing to)
pay, it's time to reexamine the cost estimates and search for different
answers to continuity of coverage issues.<p>
	S. 1028 takes a large step toward mandating that insurance companies offer
only multi-year policies at a fixed premium.  It assumes that voluntary market
arrangements have failed to meet the demands of consumers to provide products
that protect them from the consequences of health risk redefinition on an
annual basis.  Actually, the lack of more effective protection for individuals
against the risks of changing health status reflects the barriers of tax policy
and state restrictions on voluntary health plan purchasing coalitions, plus
variations in job status, income level, and risk preference.<p>
	Individuals who receive group health insurance through their employer enjoy
favorable tax treatment of employer-paid premiums.  If they work for a large
company, they also are likely to gain several additional advantages
(community-rated premiums, purchasing clout, lower administrative and
regulatory costs per worker.<p>
	On the other hand, employer-paid insurance policies are likely to provide few,
if any, continuing benefits for workers once they change or lose their jobs.
Employers sponsoring insurance plans are also less likely than their individual
employees to resist insurance policy exclusions for potentially costly
preexisting conditions.  <p>
	Theoretically, individuals who prefer other health insurance options and want
long-term protection against changes in their health status can purchase the
appropriate insurance policies on their own.  However, tax benefits are very
limited for individual health care buyers, and such policies cost more for
insurers to underwrite, market, and administer.  Given those costs, many
consumers are simply not willing to pay for multiperiod insurance contracts on
their own.  <p>
	Moreover, consumers may not want to be locked into one insurer for a long
period of time when health plan choices have significant, ongoing service
consequences (e.g., claims administration, provider networks, contract
interpretation).  Some consumers also need the contractual flexibility to
change insurers in the event that they later obtain a job offering better,
employer-paid insurance coverage.  Finally, many consumers are unwilling to
risk redistributing their income (when younger and healthier) through premium
subsidies to others in a voluntary pool, when they can instead be "picked
off" as good risks by other insurers and pay lower premiums.  <p>
	Kassebaum-Kennedy can round up support from consumers who do not want to pay
an actuarially fair price for health insurance, but prefer to have healthy
people subsidize their higher costs.  What can market-based alternatives offer
to other individuals who would try to pay their own way if less expensive
alternatives were available?<p>
	A short list of structural remedies would include (1) tax neutrality for all
health insurance purchases; (2) preservation of risk-based pricing; (3)
targeted income-based subsidies for the poor and those with medically
uninsurable risks; (4) legal reform that restores private insurers' rights
to enforce voluntary contracts regarding medical care choices and innovative
economizing options; (5) preemption or repeal of state mandated benefit laws;
and (6) encouragement of voluntary purchasing pools offering multiperiod,
experience-rated contracts.  (Kassebaum-Kennedy attempts to do the latter, but
undercuts the effort with rate restrictions.)<p>
	The most powerful solutions, of course, come down to fundamentals.  Ensuring
vigorous competition, unfettered consumer choice, and voluntary arrangements in
the insurance marketplace; empowering individuals to balance the risks,
rewards, and responsibilities of health care decisionmaking; and adopting
growth-oriented economic policies will do much more to expand insurance
coverage than incremental reform legislation that temporarily makes politicians
feel better but undermines its own official goals.  <p>
<p>
<i>Tom Miller is CEI's Director of Economic Policy Studies.</i><p>


<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
