<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Greening of Trade Policy</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiesp.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Studies Program" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Greening of Trade Policy: "Sustainable Development" and Global Trade</B><BR>
by James M. Sheehan<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Trade-Related Environmental Standards</H2>
</CENTER>
<A NAME="green"></A>
<P><b>Green Protectionism</b><p>
<p>
     Various measures have been proposed to counteract &#147;ecological
dumping&#148; and to promote fair competition &#147;on a level playing
field.&#148;  Countries with lower standards should &#147;harmonize up&#148;
their standards; countervailing duties should be imposed against imports not
subject to certain environmental standards; and domestic industries subject to
higher environmental standards should be subsidized in order to restore their
trade competitiveness.<A HREF="trade7.html#53"><sup>53</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The many variations on these proposals to incorporate environmental standards
into trade claim to promote freer trade by minimizing the differences between
the environmental protection policies of separate countries.<A
HREF="trade7.html#54"><sup>54</sup></A>  Yet
precisely the opposite has happened when GATT has attempted harmonization of
other government policies in areas such as antidumping, subsidies, technical
standards, customs valuation, import licensing, and procurement.<A
HREF="trade7.html#55"><sup>55</sup></A>
The promulgation of new international rules on these matters has led to
increased litigation and disputes as countries have utilized the wording of
GATT codes to justify new forms of discriminatory protectionism and managed
trade.<A HREF="trade7.html#56"><sup>56</sup></A>  Anti-dumping laws have been the most
virulent of these
practices.  Prior to 1990, roughly two dozen countries had anti-dumping
statutes.  By 1994, 40 countries had adopted them, and soon all GATT
signatories will adopt anti-dumping laws pursuant to harmonization under the
Uruguay Round.<A HREF="trade7.html#57"><sup>57</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Harmonization of environmental policies would be no different.  Since 1979,
GATT standards codes have urged harmonization of technical regulations using a
set of international standards.  Though intended to improve the transparency of
standards for businesses, harmonization has led to heightened use of technical
regulations.  Between 1980 and 1990, GATT recorded 211 instances where nations
had adopted technical regulations under the standards code which had
significant adverse effects on trade.<A HREF="trade7.html#58"><sup>58</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Harmonization under GATT also discourages reform of excessive regulations,
because deregulation is perceived politically as a unilateral concession to
trading partners.<A HREF="trade7.html#59"><sup>59</sup></A>  In practice, then, harmonization
under the
auspices of GATT has served to codify existing measures, which were intended to
disguise protectionism through formalized procedures.<A
HREF="trade7.html#60"><sup>60</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Some standards impede trade only incidentally, as with the use of metric
versus imperial measurements; others pose far more serious non-tariff barriers,
such as pharmaceutical, cosmetic, and food standards coupled with rigid inspection and
customs procedures.  To the extent that such standards impose transaction
costs, they distort trade and protect domestic producers.  Even if such
standards treat all products equally, they still raise production costs.  If
product standards are strict
enough, causing foreign suppliers to withdraw from a market, they are no
different than an outright prohibition on imports.<A
HREF="trade7.html#61"><sup>61</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Harmonization of environmental policies would be inappropriate for many
reasons apart from free trade.  Environmental policies are unique to each
country, depending on factors such as natural resource endowments, pollution
absorptive capacity, and underlying material wealth, not to mention cultural
preferences.<A HREF="trade7.html#62"><sup>62</sup></A>  Some communities in rural or
coastal areas can
tolerate higher emissions than urban populations.  Some communities are better
equipped than others to deal with the income trade-offs involved in
environmental regulation.  Wealthier countries can afford greater trade-offs
than poorer countries.  Wealthier countries are also more likely to have
advanced technologies and equipment, while poorer countries and state-directed
economies typically make use of obsolete production methods.  Forcing higher
standards on Third World as a pre-condition for trade would be
counterproductive.<p>
<p>
     &#147;It is only in rare cases that [two countries] will have identical
environmental standards and expenditures in the same industry,&#148; argues
Columbia University&#146;s Jagdish Bhagwati; &#147;To demand that such
harmonization be made a precondition for free trade is therefore to ask for
something that makes no economic sense at all.&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#63"><sup>63</sup></A>  Bhagwati
also points out that in industrial countries, rapid economic development has
depended on higher levels of pollution in the early stages, with clean-up
coming later on.<p>
<p>
     If environmental policy differences are unfair trade distortions, the same
reasoning can be used to indict a myriad of other policy
differences.<A HREF="trade7.html#64"><sup>64</sup></A>  Tax rates and incentives, robust
education policies,
and skill-based immigration policies all impact a nation&#146;s trade
competitiveness.  Other intangible factors, such as technological, historical
and socio-economic circumstances, vary from country to country.  To view all of
these differences as sources of unfair advantage is to justify widespread use
of trade barriers, a justification easily exploited by businesses eager to
blame declining competitive performance on cost differences abroad.  In its
&#147;Trade and the Environment&#148; report, the GATT Secretariat properly
asks, &#147;Where is the line to be drawn if the competitive implications of
differences in so many government policies are to become a source of demands
for the neutralization of the consequences for trade?&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#65"><sup>65</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The requirement that trade with another nation be conditioned on its
environmental standards is a recipe for unbridled protectionism, particularly
when mixed with the inherent tendencies of bureaucracies.  If having lower
environmental
standards is considered an unfair trade practice, countervailing duties would
have to be imposed in the same way as U.S. laws remedy dumping and subsidies.
Thus, the amount of the duty would have to be calculated by a government
bureaucracy, which would make its decisions based on political factors and
objectives.  According to Bhagwati, &#147;anyone familiar with the way dumping
calculations are made knows that the Environmental Protection Agency could come
up with virtually any estimates it cared to produce.&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#66"><sup>66</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Even imputing the best possible motives to government officials, it would be
exceedingly difficult to achieve real environmental improvements using trade
measures.  Countervailing duties or tariffs would create new barriers to the
expansion of trade, certainly reducing potential income gains for both
producers and consumers.  Trade measures are relatively ineffective against
countries that strenuously object to outside pressure.  A government under the
threat of coercive trade measures is not likely to alter environmental policies
to suit the needs of a foreign government.  Trade measures are more likely to
inspire nationalism in the target country and resentment against foreign
interference.  Consequently, trade measures to promote reduction of trade
barriers have seldom achieved their objectives.<A
HREF="trade7.html#67"><sup>67</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Governments are easily influenced by interest group prodding for
&#147;unwarranted, trade-inhibiting restrictions,&#148; especially when setting
levels of environmental risk.<A HREF="trade7.html#68"><sup>68</sup></A>  Knowing this, many
experts see the
very purpose of harmonization as raising compliance costs for business:
&#147;common standards often result in a high degree of environmental
protection, not infrequently higher than any individual country would have been
willing to adopt on its own.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#69"><sup>69</sup></A>  Harmonized
standards, like
other multilateral environmental policies, promote &#147;coordinated
trade,&#148; not free trade.<A HREF="trade7.html#70"><sup>70</sup></A><p>
<p>
<A NAME="policy"></A>
<b>Policy Uniformity Breeds Cartelization</b><p>
<p>
     Harmonization of non-trade policies does not secure the efficiency gains of
free trade, it does just the opposite.  According to David Robertson of
Australian National University:<p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
[A]rguments that policies on the environment should be harmonized to avoid the
creation of new trade restrictions demonstrate misunderstanding of the
mechanisms that provide efficiency gains from international trade.  Worse, in
many instances these proposals are made jointly by environmentalists and
industry lobbies which implies a hidden agenda.<A
HREF="trade7.html#71"><sup>71</sup></A><p>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>     That agenda is the creation of a government-protected cartel.  Rather than
promoting trade, harmonization will result in cartelization of the global
economy into protected monopolies, and erosion of the free trade principle of
comparative advantage.<A HREF="trade7.html#72"><sup>72</sup></A><p>
<A HREF="trade7.html#"><sup></sup></A><p>
<A HREF="trade7.html#"><sup></sup></A>    Under true free trade, an international division of
labor arises
through each nation maximizing its own trade advantages.<A
HREF="trade7.html#73"><sup>73</sup></A>
Comparative advantage is partially determined by each nation&#146;s regulatory
policies toward business, with excessive regulation driving firms away from
more oppressive countries.  Environmentalists understand that harmonized
standards would alter this dynamic of competitive trade.<A
HREF="trade7.html#74"><sup>74</sup></A> <p>
<p>
     Harmonization reduces competition between governments, leaving them little
incentive to liberalize economies.  Harmonization fosters increased government
intervention, and reduces freedom to revise regulatory policies.<A
HREF="trade7.html#75"><sup>75</sup></A>
Thus, harmonization curtails industrial output by raising testing, production
and distribution costs for producers.  Yet harmonized standards also benefit
established industries by locking in familiar regulations and protecting them
from competition.  New entrants and foreign competitors are put at a distinct
disadvantage by harmonized standards.<p>
<p>
<A NAME="eco"></A>
<b>Eco-imperialism</b><p>
<p>
     When social values are injected into trade politics, the priorities of
developed countries inevitably prevail, a phenomenon known as eco-imperialism.
Yet such paternalistic environmental standards imposed on the Third World come
at the expense of economic development and the poor.  Industrialized countries
tend to support environmental trade measures to ward off some global
environmental crisis that may arise in the next century.  However, the greatest
environmental crises in the Third World involve immediate and local health
concerns.  Inadequate sanitation causes more than 2 million deaths and more
than a billion illnesses annually from water-borne diseases such as cholera and
typhoid.<A HREF="trade7.html#76"><sup>76</sup></A>  Environmental trade measures tend to
penalize the Third
World for its poverty, and force a diversion of resources away from real
problems in order to cater to the preferences of First World environmentalists.
Moreover, green trade measures intrude on the sovereignty of Third World
peoples, depriving them of the use of natural resources such as fisheries,
rainforests, and energy supplies.  Thus many developing countries have come to
suspect that the term &#147;sustainable development&#148; means minimal
development for them.<p>
<p>
     An illustrative example of eco-imperialism was the Tuna-Dolphin dispute
between the U.S. and Mexico.  The 1972 U.S. Marine Mammal Protection Act 
(MMPA) sets dolphin protection standards for the eastern tropical Pacific Ocean
fishery.  The law provides a ceiling on the number of dolphins that may be
incidentally killed by tuna fishermen, whose purse-seine nets encircle
yellowfin tuna and the dolphins that school with them.  The U.S. must embargo
tuna imports from any country that takes more than 1.25 times the number of
dolphins as the U.S. fishing fleet in a given year.  The embargo must also be
applied to intermediary countries that import tuna products from an embargoed
country.  Embargoes have been imposed against Mexico, Venezuela, and Vanuatu,
and against intermediate countries in Europe and Central
America.<A HREF="trade7.html#77"><sup>77</sup></A><p>
<p>
     In February 1991, Mexico brought the dispute before the GATT.  A dispute
settlement panel ruled that the MMPA constituted a discriminatory barrier to
trade.<A HREF="trade7.html#78"><sup>78</sup></A>  The regulation was applied beyond U.S.
jurisdiction,
involving an attempt to impose a standard on other countries.  The regulation
did not involve a standard relating to a product characteristic.  Rather, the
MMPA attempted to embargo a product based on a process and production method,
i.e., the manner in which the tuna was produced; thus the MMPA did not qualify
as an internal regulation under GATT.<p>
<p>
     The rejection of extra-jurisdictional enforcement was an important precedent
under GATT.  If allowed, numerous types of import bans could be carried out
&#147;merely because the exporting country pursues environmental or health
policies different from [the importing country].&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#79"><sup>79</sup></A>  The
decision drew visceral opposition from many environmental activists.  Despite
the decision, the U.S. did not withdraw the MMPA, and Mexico has refrained from
seeking adoption of the dispute panel report by the GATT Council, under
diplomatic pressure from the U.S. and under constraints relating to its trade
agreement negotiations with the U.S.<p>
<p>
     The Tuna-Dolphin dispute encapsulates the clash between trade and
environmental values.  The impact was most acute in Venezuela, whose fishermen
contend that U.S. standards are virtually impossible to meet for poorer Third
World countries.  There is no way for a country to predict what the U.S. take
of dolphins will be, making it difficult to remain under the ceiling that
triggers the U.S. embargo.  Venezuelan fishermen have limited access to
dolphin-safe techniques and gear, and cannot afford the prohibitive costs
associated with traveling to the western tropical Pacific, where tuna
congregate with dolphins less frequently.  Venezuela&#146;s tuna fleet shrunk
from 118 boats in 1988 to 34 four years later.  Embargoes under the MMPA have
disrupted trade, destabilized tuna prices, and thrown fishermen out of
work.<A HREF="trade7.html#80"><sup>80</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The MMPA reflects not only the peculiar supremacy of dolphins over human
needs, but also the supremacy of dolphins over other competing ecological
values.  Dolphin protection measures lead to overexploitation of marine
resources and foil sustainable management of the eastern tropical Pacific
fishery.<A HREF="trade7.html#81"><sup>81</sup></A>  Deterred from harming dolphins,
fishermen are forced to
pursue smaller, sexually-immature yellowfin and skipjack tuna.<A
HREF="trade7.html#82"><sup>82</sup></A>
For every dolphin saved, approximately 9,000 undersize tuna are
lost.<A HREF="trade7.html#83"><sup>83</sup></A>  According to James Joseph, director of the
Inter-American
Tropical Tuna Commission, avoiding dolphins also means higher incidental kills
of sharks, mahi-mahi, billfish, and many other marine species.<A
HREF="trade7.html#84"><sup>84</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The Tuna-Dolphin dispute demonstrates that trade-restrictive policies
undertaken for environmental purposes can effectively close markets, but do not
necessarily result in tangible environmental benefits.  Environmental arguments
and value judgments are easily manipulated for protectionist purposes, with
serious consequences for the world&#146;s poor.<p>
<p>
<b></b><p>



<BR>
