<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Greening of Trade Policy</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiesp.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Studies Program" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Greening of Trade Policy: "Sustainable Development" and Global Trade</B><BR>
by James M. Sheehan<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>International Environmental Laws and Principles</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>There is a growing body of international law involving trade restrictions for
environmental protection.  Emerging global environmental policies are beginning
to have profound impacts on trade and international economic affairs.
According to legal experts, international environmental agreements and treaties
may be harbingers of sweeping new global environment policies which &#147;use
trade restrictions as an integral element of their protective mechanisms and
link international regulation of environmental problems to complex questions of
trade and development.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#85"><sup>85</sup></A><p>
<p>
<A NAME="earth"></A>
<b>The Earth Summit: Defining Sustainable Development</b><p>
<p>
<u>Agenda 21:</u><p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Sustainability requires a process of national, regional, and local resource and
environmental planning, which is in direct conflict with the principle of free
trade.<A HREF="trade7.html#86"><sup>86</sup></A><p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<p>
     Proposals for &#147;socially responsible&#148; trade open up a
&#147;Pandora&#146;s box&#148; of regulations for various production sectors,
including energy resources, mining, metals, plastics, chemicals, agriculture,
lumber, pulp and paper, fisheries, and so on.<A HREF="trade7.html#87"><sup>87</sup></A> 
Environmental
standards for trade gained momentum in June 1992, when world leaders broadly
endorsed the concept of &#147;sustainable development&#148; at the United
Nations Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED) in Rio de Janeiro,
Brazil, also called the Earth Summit.  The conference produced <i>Agenda
21</i>, an 800-page blueprint for environmental planning and international
policy coordination covering a wide variety of issues, including trade,
forestry, desertification, ocean resources, rivers, and women&#146;s rights.
Under the agreement, governments commit themselves to adopt a national strategy
for sustainable development and to strengthen international cooperation on
sustainable development policies.  <i>Agenda 21</i> urges nations to:<p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
harmonize the various sectoral economic, social and environmental policies and
plans that are operating in the country. . .to ensure socially responsible
economic development while protecting the resource base and environment for the
benefit of future generations . . .[National strategies] should be developed
through the widest possible participation.<A HREF="trade7.html#88"><sup>88</sup></A><p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<p>
     Governments are expected to consider &#147;the implications of economic
instruments and incentives for competitiveness and international trade,&#148;
and &#147;global transboundary issues&#148; related to energy, transportation,
agriculture and forestry, water, wastes, health, tourism and other areas.  The
aim of sustainable development is to facilitate the &#147;integration of social
and environmental costs into economic activities,&#148; by promoting &#147;the
efficient planning and utilization of resources for sustainable development
through sound economic and social policies.&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#89"><sup>89</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Sustainable development was first conceived by the 1987 World Commission on
Environment and Development, which had specifically recommended that the GATT
&#147;reflect concern for the impacts of trading patterns on the environment,
and the need for more effective instruments to integrate environment and
development concerns into international trading
arrangements.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#90"><sup>90</sup></A>  The first program area of
<i>Agenda 21</i>
calls on all national governments to achieve Earth Summit goals by
&#147;promoting sustainable development through trade liberalization,&#148; and
by &#147;making trade and environment mutually supportive.&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#91"><sup>91</sup></A>
It encourages the completion of the Uruguay Round of GATT for &#147;greater
security and predictability to the international trading
system,&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#92"><sup>92</sup></A> and for &#147;better
management of natural
resources.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#93"><sup>93</sup></A><p>
<p>
     By &#147;trade liberalization,&#148; <i>Agenda 21</i> does not refer to free
trade, but trade &#147;supported by the adoption of sound environmental
policies.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#94"><sup>94</sup></A>  <i>Agenda 21</i> endorses the
use of trade
measures, i.e., trade sanctions, &#147;to enhance the effectiveness of
environmental regulations.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#95"><sup>95</sup></A>  <i>Agenda
21</i> calls for
integration of national governments into a strengthened &#147;international
trade policies system.&#148;  An important objective of the trade program is to
clarify the role of GATT and U.N. institutions &#147;in dealing with trade and
environment-related issues, including...dispute settlement.&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#96"><sup>96</sup></A>
The plan also requires the &#147;international community&#148; to adopt
&#147;commodity policies&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#97"><sup>97</sup></A> to raise prices
for products such
as cocoa, coffee, sugar, and tropical timber.<A HREF="trade7.html#98"><sup>98</sup></A> 
<i>Agenda 21</i>
urges compensation to developing countries for losses incurred by changing
commodity policies,<A HREF="trade7.html#99"><sup>99</sup></A> and puts a price tag of  $8.8
billion per year
on its own recommendations.<A HREF="trade7.html#100"><sup>100</sup></A><p>
<p>
<u>The Rio Declaration:</u><p>
<p>
     The Earth Summit participants also approved the Rio Declaration on Environment
and Development, a set of twenty-seven sustainable development principles.  <p>
<p>
     This global ecological charter effectively places environmental resources
within international jurisdiction.  In it, countries are warned not to degrade
the environment in &#147;areas beyond the limits of national
jurisdiction,&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#101"><sup>101</sup></A> and are urged to
&#147;cooperate in a spirit
of global partnership to conserve, protect and restore the health and integrity
of the Earth&#146;s ecosystem.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#102"><sup>102</sup></A> 
Countries are instructed to
&#147;enact effective environmental legislation&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#103"><sup>103</sup></A> that will
bring about the elimination of &#147;unsustainable patterns of production and
consumption.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#104"><sup>104</sup></A>  Industrialized countries
are blamed for
environmental degradation, and told to take financial responsibility for its
resolution, &#147;in view of...the technologies and financial resources they
command.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#105"><sup>105</sup></A>  Thus, wealth redistribution
is implicit in
sustainable development.<p>
<p>
     The Rio Declaration calls for environmental standards to be linked to trade in
&#147;a supportive and open international economic system&#148; that would lead
to &#147;sustainable development in all countries, to better address the
problems of environmental degradation.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#106"><sup>106</sup></A> 
Escaping poverty
through international trade would be discouraged, as countries are instructed
not to transfer &#147;activities or substances&#148;<A
HREF="trade7.html#107"><sup>107</sup></A> that are
considered unhealthy for the Earth&#146;s ecosystem.  Important chemicals and
industrial materials would be removed from ecologically permissible commerce.
The charter also endorses a &#147;precautionary approach&#148; to environmental
policy: &#147;Lack of full scientific certainty shall not be used as a reason
for postponing&#148; environmental regulations and
restrictions.<A HREF="trade7.html#108"><sup>108</sup></A><p>
<p>

<A NAME="multi"></A>
<b>Multilateral Agreements</b><p>
<p>
     There are approximately 180 international environmental agreements and
treaties.<A HREF="trade7.html#109"><sup>109</sup></A>  More than two thirds of these treaties
were signed
subsequent to the 1972 United Nations Conference on the Human Environment, held
in Stockholm, Sweden.  The U.N. has continued to provide the momentum for
international action since then, sponsoring a dozen major conferences on a
variety of global environmental issues, including population control,
desertification, ozone depletion, and climate change.<A
HREF="trade7.html#110"><sup>110</sup></A>  Of these
international agreements, 19 employ trade restrictions in varying ways to carry
out and enforce their objectives.<A HREF="trade7.html#111"><sup>111</sup></A>  Among the
most important and
far-reaching of these multilateral agreements are those dealing with
ozone-depleting substances, endangered species, and hazardous waste.<p>
<u>Montreal Protocol:</u><p>
<p>
     Signed in 1987, the Montreal Protocol on Substances that Deplete the Ozone
Layer restricts the production and consumption of certain substances thought to
erode the ozone layer, including chloroflourocarbons (CFCs), other chemical
refrigerants, and halons.  Signatories must reduce their consumption of these
controlled substances according to specific deadlines and
percentages.<A HREF="trade7.html#112"><sup>112</sup></A>  Parties must ban trade in
controlled substances and
related products that contain controlled substances, even from countries that
have not signed the Protocol.<A HREF="trade7.html#113"><sup>113</sup></A>  Parties are also
discouraged from
exporting technology that either produces or utilizes CFCs, such as
semiconductors washed with CFCs, and ultimately must ban such
trade.<A HREF="trade7.html#114"><sup>114</sup></A>  The Protocol also contains provisions for
financial and
technical compliance assistance and technology transfer for developing
countries via a Multilateral Fund.<A HREF="trade7.html#115"><sup>115</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The phaseout of CFCs will be very costly &#151; as much as $100 billion in
costs over the next decade for the U.S. alone, by one estimate.<A
HREF="trade7.html#116"><sup>116</sup></A>
The impacts will hit hardest in the Third World, however, where refrigerated
pharmaceuticals and foods are essential to the health and well-being of the
poor.  Refrigerants are responsible for reducing food spoilage and for enabling
a wider distribution of food products.  The Protocol is an exercise in
eco-imperialism &#151; developing nations are made to bear the burden of the
West&#146;s questionable environmental priorities.<p>
<p>
     The Protocol stipulates different trading terms for parties and for
non-parties.  It phases out trade in CFCs between parties, while it bans
imports from non-parties.  In addition, the Protocol bans exports of CFCs to
non-parties.  By restricting imports made with CFCs or other controlled
substances, rather than the substances themselves, parties are enacting trade
measures extra-jurisdictionally regarding a process and production method,
raising the same sort of trade barrier as the Marine Mammal Protection
Act.<A HREF="trade7.html#117"><sup>117</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The principal reason for these Protocol provisions is to encourage
non-signatories to join the agreement, and to prevent non-parties from
undermining the agreement&#146;s goals.<A HREF="trade7.html#118"><sup>118</sup></A>  By
compelling countries
to sign, it is hoped that greater environmental benefits will accrue from the
agreement.  Yet, there is no avoiding that such provisions constitute trade
barriers; they conflict with the free trade principle of non-discrimination
sought by GATT.<A HREF="trade7.html#119"><sup>119</sup></A>  For that reason,
environmentalists fear that a
GATT member could try to invalidate the Montreal Protocol under GATT&#146;s
dispute settlement procedures, proving once and for all that the agreement is
inconsistent with free trade.<A HREF="trade7.html#120"><sup>120</sup></A>  For action under
the Protocol to
be consistent with a country&#146;s obligations under GATT, a rules change or a
GATT waiver of the rules would be required.<A
HREF="trade7.html#121"><sup>121</sup></A><p>
<A HREF="trade7.html#"><sup></sup></A><u></u><p>
<u>Basel Convention</u>:<p>
<p>
     The Basel Convention on the Control of Transboundary Movements of Hazardous
Wastes and Their Disposal is a treaty &#147;designed to regulate, but more 
fundamentally, to bring to an end, international trade in a very large number
of materials,&#148; according to N. R. Evans.<A
HREF="trade7.html#122"><sup>122</sup></A>  The
Basel Convention was convened to manage the production, trade, and disposal of
waste materials according to baseline international standards.<A
HREF="trade7.html#123"><sup>123</sup></A>
It prohibits export of these waste, scrap and recyclable materials to nations
that prohibit such imports, to non-parties, and to Antarctica.<A
HREF="trade7.html#124"><sup>124</sup></A>
Exports are also prohibited if a party has reason to believe the materials will
not be managed sustainably.<A HREF="trade7.html#125"><sup>125</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Environmental restrictions on the waste trade will not make such trade safer
per se, but will make it less frequent.  Businesses engaged in the waste trade
must 
conform to detailed requirements for written information, in addition to
complex 
notification and consent requirements prior to shipment.<A
HREF="trade7.html#126"><sup>126</sup></A>
According to Evans, the Basel Convention will subject trade in recycled
materials to interminable red tape and bureaucratic delay:<p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
The extra transaction costs imposed on international traders in these materials
will tend to reduce that trade, perhaps very greatly . . .Where the margins on
a particular trade are low. . .then a dramatic increase in transaction costs
will kill the trade.<A HREF="trade7.html#127"><sup>127</sup></A><p>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
     Among those hurt will be developing countries which have begun to specialize
in industries based on secondary and scrap materials, which will become more
expensive and harder to find in global markets.<A HREF="trade7.html#128"><sup>128</sup></A> 
Evans describes
the Convention as a government cartel to prevent individuals from trading with
one another for mutual benefit.  Despite environmentalist fears of
&#147;hazardous&#148; wastes, there is no reason why international competition
in recycling and disposal will not result in safer practices.  According to
Evans, the waste trade contains none of the elements of global commons abuse
&#151; &#147;property rights are secure at all times in the
trade.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#129"><sup>129</sup></A>  Thus, internalization of costs is
accomplished by
competitive markets.<p>
<p>
     Like the Montreal Protocol, Basel Convention provisions are inconsistent with
free trade principles.  These provisions apply environmental measures
extra-jurisdictionally, and apply different standards to trade with parties
versus non-parties, making them inconsistent with GATT.<A
HREF="trade7.html#130"><sup>130</sup></A>
Likewise, the ban on exports to the Antarctic region may constitute an
arbitrary trade barrier under GATT.<A HREF="trade7.html#131"><sup>131</sup></A><p>
<p>
<u>CITES</u>:<p>
<p>
     The Convention on Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) strictly regulates
international trade in wildlife, with the intent of protecting biodiversity and
preventing extinction.  CITES puts threatened species in three categories, each
with different trade restrictions.  Parties are required to create complex
permit systems for trade in any listed species.<A
HREF="trade7.html#132"><sup>132</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Appendix I bans commercial trade in any species currently endangered,
including trade in the species itself or in species-derived
products.<A HREF="trade7.html#133"><sup>133</sup></A>  Appendix II requires trade permits in
species which
are nearing threatened status, but are not endangered currently.<A HREF="trade7.html#134"><sup>134</sup></A>  Appendix III lists species
that a party
wishes to restrict trade in, if a population or sub-species in its own
territory is threatened.  Certificates of origin are required for other
countries that wish to trade in species on this list.<A
HREF="trade7.html#135"><sup>135</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Under CITES, there are bans on imports of elephants, whales, flying foxes,
polar bears, fur seals, and migratory birds, among other species.<A
HREF="trade7.html#136"><sup>136</sup></A>
Because trade in non-domestic species can be banned, CITES may constitute an
extra-territorial environmental trade barrier of the type that was struck down
in the U.S.-Mexico
tuna-dolphin panel.<A HREF="trade7.html#137"><sup>137</sup></A>  Also, because CITES
parties are required to
regulate trade even with non-parties, the agreement may run afoul of GATT
prohibition against quotas, bans, and licensing schemes.<A
HREF="trade7.html#138"><sup>138</sup></A><p>
<b></b><p>
<A NAME="merging"></A>
<b>Merging international trade and environment rules.</b><p>
<p>
     By defining a steadily increasing number of environmental quality issues as
global commons problems, multilateral treaties are effectively expanding
international jurisdiction in these areas. Environmentalist advocates of
multilateralism welcome the expanding principles of international law, pointing
out that under the Law of the Sea convention, for example, &#147;the
international community has reserved jurisdiction over these [global] commons
areas.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#139"><sup>139</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The multitude of environmental restrictions mandated by international
agreements is having a growing impact on world trade.  Obligations under many
environmental agreements conflict with the obligations of multilateral trade
rules, which were originally intended to expand trade, not restrict it.
Political trade management regimes, such as GATT, have traditionally not
recognized much of a governmental role in environmental regulation outside of
national jurisdictions.  As multilateral action to regulate the global commons
continues to grow, environmental advocates argue that international
environmental policies should be incorporated into government-negotiated trade
rules so that there is no inconsistency between the two.<p>
<p>
     An even greater factor in the greening of trade policies is the environmental
establishment&#146;s desire to strengthen compliance with multilateral
agreements 
and to quicken the pace of multilateral action.  Implementation of
environmental agreements is frustrated in part by inadequate monitoring and
enforcement,<A HREF="trade7.html#140"><sup>140</sup></A> and by the chronic managerial
inefficiency of the
U.N. system.<A HREF="trade7.html#141"><sup>141</sup></A>  Some countries, especially in the
poorer Third
World, are deterred by the prohibitive costs of environmental restrictions and
by loss of national sovereignty.<A HREF="trade7.html#142"><sup>142</sup></A><p>
<p>
     To overcome these problems, a report by the General Accounting Office suggests
that a greater sense of urgency about global environmental crises might be necessary, and recommends more active participation by environmental
interest
groups in monitoring enforcement of multilateral agreements.<A
HREF="trade7.html#143"><sup>143</sup></A>  GAO
further recommends greater use of technology transfer programs and financial
inducements for Third World governments, such as the Global Environment
Facility, the financing instrument for the U.N. Biodiversity and Global Climate
Change Conventions.<A HREF="trade7.html#144"><sup>144</sup></A>   These proposals would
increase the foreign
indebtedness of developing countries, strengthen central governments, and
impede free market economic reforms.<p>
<p>
     Enforcement of multilateral environmental agreements can also be ratcheted up
gradually, as Worldwatch Institute&#146;s Hilary French explains: <p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Paradoxically, one way to make environmental agreements more effective is in
some cases to make them less enforceable &#151; and therefore more palatable to
the negotiators who may initially feel threatened by any loss of sovereignty .
. .[Such agreements] can help to create an international consensus, mobilize
aid, and lay the groundwork for the negotiation of binding treaties
later.<A HREF="trade7.html#145"><sup>145</sup></A><p>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
     Under this strategy, a non-binding framework convention is agreed to first,
which identifies a global crisis and establishes a political commitment to take
some undefined action at a later date.  Then, information from research and
monitoring programs is used by governments and environmental interest groups to
justify binding targets and timetables in protocols and treaties.<A
HREF="trade7.html#146"><sup>146</sup></A>
Along these lines, the World Resources Institute calls the creation of an
institution to monitor <i>Agenda 21</i>, the U.N. Commission on Sustainable
Development, &#147;one of the quiet successes of the Earth
Summit.&#148;<A HREF="trade7.html#147"><sup>147</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Ultimately, however, adequate enforcement of global environmental regulatory
policies is possible only through trade measures.  In some international
environmental agreements, like the Montreal Protocol, trade restrictions are
seen as integral to the agreement&#146;s purpose.  In others, trade measures
are necessary to induce additional countries to join an
agreement.<A HREF="trade7.html#148"><sup>148</sup></A>  Many environmentalists argue that
effective solutions
to &#147;transboundary&#148; pollution problems would be impossible without
greater coordination of trade and environmental policies, including trade
measures.<A HREF="trade7.html#149"><sup>149</sup></A>  For example, the threat of U.S. trade
sanctions has
been instrumental in pressuring whaling nations to adhere to the strictures of
the International Whaling Convention.<A HREF="trade7.html#150"><sup>150</sup></A><p>
<p>
     International institutions such as the OECD, GATT, and UNCTAD have each
attempted to address the need for coordinated, multilateral trade and
environment policies<A HREF="trade8.html#151"><sup>151</sup></A>  In 1972, the major
industrial powers of
the OECD collaborated to produce a report entitled &#147;Guiding Principles
Concerning the International Aspects of Environmental Policies,&#148; which
recommends more stringent environmental standards and that governments should
harmonize their standards.<A HREF="trade8.html#152"><sup>152</sup></A>  Since that time,
OECD efforts have
evolved, and in 1991 an OECD report declared that &#147;unlike sustainable
development, free trade is not an end in itself. . .&#148;<A
HREF="trade8.html#153"><sup>153</sup></A>  An
EPA trade and environment advisory committee, created in 1990, recommended that
the U.S. seek to integrate environmental concerns into multilateral and
regional trade agreements, and that the U.S. seek to harmonize international
environmental standards.<A HREF="trade8.html#154"><sup>154</sup></A><p>
<p>
     GATT&#146;s theoretical work has been marginally less sympathetic to
multilateralism than that of other international institutions.   Nevertheless,
even GATT concedes the environmentalist premise that multilateral solutions to
environmental problems are necessary, arguing that they &#147;offer the best
chance of ensuring that the policy changes deal directly with the problem at
hand and that they provide minimum scope for protectionist
abuses.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#155"><sup>155</sup></A>  Though GATT seeks to
minimize trade discrimination
and unilateral sanctions, it does not seek to prevent the growing use of trade
measures through multilateral environmental agreements.<A
HREF="trade8.html#156"><sup>156</sup></A>  In fact,
the GATT panel decision in the Tuna-Dolphin dispute argued that U.S. trade
restrictions on dolphin-unsafe tuna from Mexico could be GATT-consistent if
part of an international agreement.<A HREF="trade8.html#157"><sup>157</sup></A>  And in
1993, countries
participating in the GATT Working Group on Environmental Measures and
International Trade agreed that the underlying philosophy of GATT is basically
compatible with the guiding principles of <i>Agenda 21</i>.<A
HREF="trade8.html#158"><sup>158</sup></A>
Thus, the intellectual case for linkage of trade and environmental policies
remains fundamentally unopposed by traditional defenders of a free trading
system &#151; the United States, the other industrialized nations, and GATT.<p>
<p>




<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
<BR>
