<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Greening of Trade Policy</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiesp.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Studies Program" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Greening of Trade Policy: "Sustainable Development" and Global Trade</B><BR>
by James M. Sheehan<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Sustainable Development as &#147;Free&#148; Trade </H2>
</CENTER>
<A NAME="standards"></A>
<P><B>Environmental Standards and the European Customs Union</b><p>
<p>
     Tangible actions to incorporate environmental standards into trade policies
initially began in the European Community, which has long fancied placing
environmental protection, along with economic policies, under international
jurisdiction.  The EC can be seen as a model for regional free trade area
regimes, in that its trade and environment rules govern separate and distinct
sovereign nations.<A HREF="trade8.html#159"><sup>159</sup></A>  The EC model for
integration of trade and
environment policies could have significant influence on GATT.<A
HREF="trade8.html#160"><sup>160</sup></A><p>
<p>
     EC international law is based on the Treaty of Rome, as modified by the Single
European Act of 1987 and the Maastricht treaty of 1991.  The former eliminated
internal barriers to trade as of 1992 (hence the term &#147;EC-92&#148;) and
established a general framework for European environmental policies.
Maastricht, when fully implemented, will further amplify the relationship
between economic integration and uniform environmental
policies.<A HREF="trade8.html#161"><sup>161</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The establishment of a single market and customs union in the EC has provided
the basis for a harmonization of environmental standards to a uniform level.
According to an EC report on environmental policy, Article 100a of the Treaty
of Rome establishes a base level of environmental protection within a framework
that allows some flexibility to member countries.<A HREF="trade8.html#162"><sup>162</sup></A> 
Given that
different countries have different priorities, member countries&#146; standards
may exceed the stringency of the base level.  Yet they may not fall short of
the minimum EC level, so generally, standards are upwardly
harmonized.<A HREF="trade8.html#163"><sup>163</sup></A>  The EC report states: &#147;the
purpose of Community
level quality targets is to ensure that minimum standards are observed.&#148;<p>
<p>
     Rising environmental standards have become legally accepted in the EC despite
their status as non-tariff trade barriers.  The tone of European trade and
environment policy was set in 1981, when Denmark passed a bottle bill requiring
all beverages to be sold in returnable containers.  This requirement is
effectively a protectionist measure since it discriminates against producers
outside of Denmark, whose higher transportation costs make recycling
uneconomical.  However, the measure was upheld in the European Court of
Justice, which determined that Denmark&#146;s duty to avoid trade
discrimination was outweighed by its responsibility to protect the global
environment.  Denmark&#146;s victory has emboldened other countries to adopt
similar protectionist legislation justified as environmental protection.
Germany, for instance, subsequently passed legislation requiring recycling of
all forms of consumer product packaging.  &#147;Companies that are unable to
establish a return cycle in Germany will not be able to sell in that
market,&#148; writes Konrad von Moltke, senior fellow at the World Wildlife
Fund; &#147;presumably these regulations ...will set a pattern for the
EC,&#148; and possibly GATT.<A HREF="trade8.html#164"><sup>164</sup></A><p>
<p>
<A NAME="green"></A>
<b>NAFTA&#146;s Green Accords</b><p>
<p>
     Some hope that the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) could parallel
the EC.  Carol Browner, administrator of the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency, calls the NAFTA between the U.S., Canada, and Mexico, &#147;the
&#145;greenest&#146; trade agreement ever negotiated.&#148;  NAFTA was
remarkable in that the Clinton administration secured the endorsement of six
environmental groups for a trade agreement &#151; Natural Resources Defense
Council, National Wildlife Federation, Environmental Defense Fund, National
Audubon Society, Conservation International and the World Wildlife Fund.<p>
<p>
<u>History and Evolution:</u><p>
<p>
     Environmentalist support was cultivated throughout the NAFTA negotiations.
Environmental organizations participated in numerous public hearings, and
submitted advisory reports to the U.S. trade representative.  Representatives
of these groups were briefed extensively during the negotiations and the
ratification process.  Remarkably, some even received security clearances to
participate in an advisory role with U.S. negotiators.  In addition, several
environmental regulatory agencies were involved directly in the negotiations,
especially EPA, the Food and Drug Administration, the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, and the Department of Interior.<A
HREF="trade8.html#165"><sup>165</sup></A>
&#147;These participating agencies...incorporated many [business and
environmental] groups&#146; proposals into U.S. negotiating positions,&#148;
reveals the U.S. trade representative&#146;s office.<A
HREF="trade8.html#166"><sup>166</sup></A><p>
     The consultation process began under the Bush administration, and produced a
number of significant recommendations which guided the U.S. negotiating team.
Among them were commitments to:<p>
<UL>
<LI> maintain the right to maintain and enforce through trade              restrictions,
product standards and technical regulations            that are more stringent than
international standards. . .;<p>
<LI> maintain the right to impose trade restrictions pursuant to                U.S. health,
environmental, conservation, and endan-           gered species legislation and
international agreements;<p>
<p>
<LI> develop dispute resolution mechanisms that are sensitive              to
environmental
programs and values; and<p>
<p>
<LI> harmonize safety and environmental standards for motor                carrier,
hazardous
materials, and rail transportation.<A HREF="trade8.html#167"><sup>167</sup></A><p>

</UL>
<p>
     This process produced NAFTA&#146;s unprecedented environmental provisions,
widely seen as the model for &#147;greening&#148; future trade agreements.
They include:<p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<i>The preamble</i>: This commits the countries to conduct trade in &#147;a
manner consistent with environmental protection and conservation&#148; and
calls on them to &#147;promote sustainable development&#148; and
&#147;strengthen the development and enforcement of environmental laws and
regulations.&#148;<p>
<p>
<i>Primacy of international environmental agreements</i>: The treaty affirms
that trade obligations in international agreements supersede NAFTA.  Such
treaties include: Montreal Protocol, CITES, the Basel Convention, and two
conventions on migratory birds and game mammals with Canada and Mexico.<p>
<p>
<i>Upward harmonization</i>: Two treaty chapters on sanitary and phytosanitary
measures and standards-related measures commit the three countries to harmonize
health, safety, and environmental regulations without reducing them.<p>
<p>
<i>Anti-deregulatory measures</i>: Countries renounce the relaxation of health,
safety, or environmental standards to encourage or retain investment.<p>
<p>
<i>International bureaucracy</i>: NAFTA creates a Committee on Sanitary and
Phytosanitary Measures to strengthen food safety regulations and agricultural
standards.  A Committee on Standards-Related Measures is created to enhance
safety, consumer, and environmental standards.  Numerous other bureaucracies
are formed.<p>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
     The environmental lobby remained unsatisfied with these provisions, however.
Worried that environmentalists would oppose NAFTA, in early 1993 the new
Clinton administration commenced negotiations for additional environmental
commitments with Mexico and Canada.  Environmentalists outlined a detailed
proposal for an environmental side accord as a condition for their support of
NAFTA.  They demanded:<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
1) the establishment of a North American environmental bureaucracy;<p>
<p>
2) a role for the bureaucracy in promoting compliance with environmental laws
and authorizing trade remedies for non-compliance;<p>
<p>
3) substantial funding for border environmental spending projects and
conservation programs;<p>
<p>
4) access to the government decisionmaking process through &#147;public
participation&#148; measures; and<p>
<p>
5) a means to clarify NAFTA&#146;s rules regarding upward harmonization of
process standards.<A HREF="trade8.html#168"><sup>168</sup></A><p>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
     The supplemental environmental side accord of August 1993, negotiated by U.S.
trade representative Mickey Kantor, conforms broadly with the environmental
lobby&#146;s proposal.  The agreement establishes a new supra-national
bureaucracy, called the North American Commission on Environmental Cooperation,
to monitor environmental conditions, to promote compliance with environmental
laws and regulations, and to authorize trade sanctions for failure to enforce
environmental laws.<A HREF="trade8.html#169"><sup>169</sup></A>  The Commission is
comprised of a Council,
Secretariat, public advisory committees, and arbitral panels.  According to a
legal analysis commissioned by environmental organizations, the side
agreement&#146;s &#147;sanctions and penalty provisions are arguably stronger
than the penalty provisions proposed [by environmental
groups].&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#170"><sup>170</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The CEC&#146;s Council will develop recommendations for the upward
harmonization of regulations across the continent, &#147;without reducing
levels of environmental protection.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#171"><sup>171</sup></A>  The
agreement lists
several areas for consideration, including pollution prevention techniques,
endangered species protection, ecologically sensitive national accounts, and
eco-labelling.  The purpose of harmonization of rules and standards is to
prevent a country from gaining improper trade advantages through deregulation,
which is considered a kind of subsidy.<A HREF="trade8.html#172"><sup>172</sup></A>  The
CEC also provides for
a high degree of public participation and access to environmental
decisionmaking, features which will allow environmental groups to continue to
exert influence over trade and environmental policies in the region.  Citizen
petitions to the CEC, for example, can lead to formal dispute settlement.<p>
<p>
     The environmental agreement commits the countries to &#147;promote sustainable
development&#148; and to &#147;enhance compliance with, and enforcement of,
environmental laws and regulations.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#173"><sup>173</sup></A>  It further
provides that each
country &#147;shall ensure that its laws and regulations provide for high
levels of environmental protection and shall strive to continue to improve
those laws and regulations.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#174"><sup>174</sup></A>  To ensure
compliance with laws
and regulations, countries agree to utilize several enforcement measures:
on-site inspections, environmental audits, administrative orders, searches and
seizures, fines, imprisonments, and closure of facilities.<A
HREF="trade8.html#175"><sup>175</sup></A>   Alland regulations. 
Arbitral panels can levy fines on governments in the amount
of $20 million per infraction, or authorize the complaining party to impose
equivalent trade sanctions (maximum fine/sanction may rise with trade after the
first year).  Canada is exempt from trade sanctions, but must enforce rulings
in domestic courts.<A HREF="trade8.html#178"><sup>178</sup></A>  Fines are paid into an
environmental fund,
which the Commission may use to improve environmental enforcement.<p>
<p>
<u>The Formal Language:</u><p>


<p>
     Some environmentalists have discounted the extent of NAFTA&#146;s
environmental commitments.  Environmental groups such as the Sierra Club,
Friends of the Earth, and Greenpeace viewed the NAFTA as insufficiently
&#147;green&#148; because of the cumbersome process of securing trade
sanctions.<A HREF="trade8.html#179"><sup>179</sup></A>  Similarly, the Cato Institute reads the
harmonization
features of the treaty to be totally meaningless: &#147;no reasonable reading
[of NAFTA&#146;s environmental provisions] can possibly lead one to conclude
that upward harmonization of environmental law is required by those parts of
the treaty.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#180"><sup>180</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Others see NAFTA as a major innovation in trade and environment policy.  Legal
advisors to the EPA write that the U.S., &#147;in its negotiation of a NAFTA,
committed not to weaken U.S. environmental and health laws or regulations [and]
to maintain enforcement...&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#181"><sup>181</sup></A>  Daniel
Magraw, EPA&#146;s
associate general counsel for international activities, points to the NAFTA
obligation that each country provide for high levels of environmental
protection, and improve environmental laws and regulations.  Magraw calls that
provision, Article 3 of the environmental side agreement, &#147;an
anti-rollback provision...intended to prevent a country from reducing its level
of [environmental] protection...&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#182"><sup>182</sup></A>  And
the U.S. trade
representative&#146;s office, in its &#147;Report on Environmental
Issues,&#148; explains how the treaty commits the three countries to
&#147;upward harmonization:<p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
The NAFTA provisions on sanitary and phytosanitary measures were spec-ifically
negotiated to make clear that there would be no &#145;downward
harmonization&#146; of such measures...Article 713.1 explicitly states that [harmonization] is to be done &#145;<i>without</i>
reducing the level of protection of human, animal or plant life or
health&#146;....[Article 714.1 harmonizes the parties&#146; measures] in order
to minimize the differences between the three NAFTA countries&#146; sanitary
and phytosanitary measures...the text makes clear that these procedures must
not reduce the level of protection of human, animal or plant health or of the
environment. (Emphasis in original).<A HREF="trade8.html#183"><sup>183</sup></A><p>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
     The NAFTA countries are obligated to engage in harmonization talks through
various tri-national committees, which will encourage the countries to make
their standards equivalent.  The most widely respected authorities on NAFTA,
Gary Clyde Hufbauer and Jeffrey Schott of the Washington DC-based Institute for
International Economics, describe this process as harmonization of NAFTA
standards &#147;at levels that are not lower than the highest minimum standards
within the NAFTA region.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#184"><sup>184</sup></A>  <p>
<p>
     William H. Lash III, writing for the Center for the Study of American
Business, uses even stronger language: &#147;Under NAFTA, the United States,
Mexico, and Canada are expressly forbidden from lowering environmental
standards to attract investment.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#185"><sup>185</sup></A>  The
three countries
renounce the relaxation of environmental measures to attract or encourage
investment in NAFTA&#146;s investment chapter, and the side agreement&#146;s
dispute settlement provisions provide a mechanism to enforce that
commitment.<A HREF="trade8.html#186"><sup>186</sup></A>  Legally, a country may choose to
reduce its desired
level of environmental protection, but not for the purpose of encouraging
investment.  Determining a country&#146;s intent in relaxing its environmental
enforcement may become a controversial subject of future arbitral panels.<p>
<p>
     NAFTA&#146;s &#147;green&#148; provisions persuaded many environmentalists
that NAFTA would not reduce environmental protection in North America, but
might actually improve environmental regulatory enforcement.<A
HREF="trade8.html#187"><sup>187</sup></A>
EPA&#146;s Carol Browner claimed in congressional testimony that these NAFTA
provisions would lead to &#147;cooperation on region-wide environmental
planning, not just pollutant-by-pollutant controls.&#148;<A
HREF="trade8.html#188"><sup>188</sup></A>
Authorities in environmental law contend that NAFTA&#146;s provisions
&#147;should result in a major improvement in law enforcement. . . .these
provisions should ensure a sea change in how Mexico (and improvements in the
way the United States and Canada) develop, implement and enforce environmental
law.<A HREF="trade8.html#189"><sup>189</sup></A>&#148;  According to a Federal Reserve
Bank of Dallas study,
the NAFTA agreements &#147;open broader opportunities to protectionists to
reduce trade through appeals against environmental and workplace enforcement in
areas with little direct effect on the international exchange of goods and
services.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#190"><sup>190</sup></A><p>
<A HREF="trade8.html#"><sup></sup></A><p>
     NAFTA effects are expected to be visible more through international
cooperation than through confrontation.<A HREF="trade8.html#191"><sup>191</sup></A>  In the
future, the
effect of NAFTA will be the internationalization of environmental regulation.
According to Hufbauer and Schott, for example, the agreement has made possible
new cooperative environmental efforts such as an Air Pollution Control Zone
covering El Paso, Texas and Ciudad Juarez.  A joint project of the EPA, State
Department, and a Mexican agency, the Control Zone would initially entail
monitoring activities and voluntary emissions control programs.  Once the
Control Zone is operational, it &#147;will have the power to establish and
enforce emission standards.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#192"><sup>192</sup></A><p>
<p>
     This is but one example of the far-reaching implications of NAFTA&#146;s
environmental provisions.  EPA&#146;s Magraw claims that NAFTA&#146;s
institutional innovations represent if not a redefinition of traditional
notions of sovereignty, at least a refinement of those notions and a
development of types of social organization that allow countries to exercise
and realize the legitimate aspects of sovereignty in a way that reflects the
growing environmental, economic, and political interdependence of the world.<p>
<u></u><p>
<u>The Experience to Date:</u><p>
<p>
     Many opponents of trade with Mexico strenuously objected to its lower social
and regulatory standards, and cited fears that U.S. standards would be
undermined by NAFTA.  &#147;We have in fact seen the opposite, that is, Mexico
is rising to the same standards we have in the United States,&#148; reports
Susan K. Ross, a Los Angeles international trade attorney.<A
HREF="trade8.html#193"><sup>193</sup></A>  In
the environmental arena, the treaty has been the impetus for greater regulation
and government intervention, particularly on the Mexican side of the border.<p>
<p>
     In preparation for NAFTA harmonization negotiations, Mexico&#146;s transport
ministry published 125 pages of new regulations in March 1994, classifying
hundreds of important industrial materials as officially &#147;hazardous.&#148;
These classifications used United Nations-approved standards as a baseline.
Other rules are being issued for vehicle emission standards, engine
manufacturing requirements, fuel standards, and food inspection
regulations.<A HREF="trade8.html#194"><sup>194</sup></A> Before the end of 1995, the three
NAFTA countries
will harmonize standards for weights and transport regulations.  The regulatory
upheaval will not be as burdensome to large corporations used to dealing with
red tape.  But for small and medium-sized firms &#147;unfamiliar with the
regulations. . .it&#146;s going to be a tough time,&#148; complains Carlos
Cantu, a Mexico City international sales manager.<A
HREF="trade8.html#195"><sup>195</sup></A>  Over time,
this could represent a barrier to competitive trade.<p>
<p>
     In June of 1994, Mexican commerce officials published new regulations
concerning food and beverage labelling and packaging, which will require
product information to be included on all imports.  They also proposed new
rules on product safety and consumer information labels.  U.S. exporters fear
the regulations will create further delays at the already burdensome Mexican
border.  &#147;What winds up happening is you&#146;re just giving another tool
to some guy at Customs to hold you up,&#148; one trade expert told the
<i>Journal of Commerce</i>.<A HREF="trade8.html#196"><sup>196</sup></A>  When
confronted with this trade
barrier for entrepreneurs, Mexican president Carlos Salinas was unsympathetic:
&#147;We have to protect the interest of Mexican consumers,&#148; he
said.<A HREF="trade8.html#197"><sup>197</sup></A><p>
<p>
     By the end of 1994, Mexico will have upgraded its food inspection regulations
to meet U.S. standards.  The changes are causing substantial delays at border
crossings, where as many as 1,000 trucks per day must pass.  According to
agricultural producers, the Mexican distribution system is so plagued by
inefficiency and delay that 35 percent of Mexico&#146;s perishable items are
destroyed by spoilage.<A HREF="trade8.html#198"><sup>198</sup></A>  Inspection procedures
are in dire need of
streamlining, as eight government agencies are currently responsible for
inspecting perishables at the border.<A HREF="trade8.html#199"><sup>199</sup></A>  Beginning
in late June
1994, Mexican officials began placing every truckload of U.S. beef into cold
storage in order to verify compliance with Spanish-language labelling
requirements and meat inspection laws.<A HREF="trade8.html#200"><sup>200</sup></A>  The
U.S. Meat Export
Federation protests that &#147;the Mexican cattlemen are trying to stifle
imports&#148; by using inspections as new trade barriers.  But Mexican
officials say the barriers are fully justified by NAFTA: &#147;Now we need to
put together normal measures for nations that do trade &#151; safety standards,
health standards.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#201"><sup>201</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Upward harmonization will be very costly for Mexican entrepreneurs, small
businesses, and consumers.  Harmonization of an assortment of vehicle emissions
standards, engine manufacturing requirements, and fuel standards will force
substantial investment by Mexican motor carriers and drive up their operational
costs close to U.S. levels.<A HREF="trade8.html#202"><sup>202</sup></A>  One California
official revealed
that Mexicans have no choice under NAFTA: &#147;They will have to change to
meet our requirements, or they will not be allowed in
California.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#203"><sup>203</sup></A>  Many U.S. trucking
companies and exporters
have falsely assumed that NAFTA would allow direct shipments to clients in
Mexico, only to find barriers at the border in the form of customs brokerage
fees, complex interliner arrangements, and onerous paperwork
requirements.<A HREF="trade8.html#204"><sup>204</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Higher environmental regulations in Mexico are starting to take their toll on
small businesses, which are being forced to invest more in environmental
compliance.  Demand for pollution control equipment stands at approximately
$1.5 billion in 1994, but is expected to double over the next few years because
of government restrictions.<A HREF="trade8.html#205"><sup>205</sup></A>  Mexico&#146;s
Confederation of
Industrial Chambers expects that NAFTA will force Mexican businesses to
increase their spending on pollution control equipment, and is calling for tax
relief to offset losses in corporate profits.<A HREF="trade8.html#206"><sup>206</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Harmonization is also to be a costly barrier to trade, with regulatory
barriers being erected to compensate for lower tariffs.  The Border Trade
Alliance, a coalition of free trade businesses along the U.S.-Mexico border,
reports that a variety of government-imposed customs fees are being used as
non-tariff barriers against traders, transport companies, and even individuals
crossing the border.  For example, when the U.S. imposed a $30 fee for
phytosanitary certificates, within thirty days Mexico had imposed a $32
phytosanitary fee.  According to the Alliance, some traders fear that NAFTA is
becoming a &#147;fee-trade agreement&#148; in which tariffs are being replaced
with fees that are having the cumulative effect of raising cross-border trading
costs to pre-NAFTA levels.<A HREF="trade8.html#207"><sup>207</sup></A>  A customs broker
in El Paso, Texas
laments that NAFTA is &#147;a managed trade agreement.  Or a preferred trade
agreement.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#208"><sup>208</sup></A><p>




<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
<BR>
