<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Greening of Trade Policy</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiesp.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Studies Program" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Greening of Trade Policy: "Sustainable Development" and Global Trade</B><BR>
by James M. Sheehan<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P><BR><P>
<b>Global &#147;Free&#148; Trade: Greening the GATT</b><p>
<p>
<u>Historical development:</u><p>
<p>
     GATT was established in 1948 without any significant environmental provisions.
GATT&#146;s primary purpose was to expand trade by reducing tariffs and other
trade barriers.  GATT&#146;s general trade principles include
&#147;most-favored-nation,&#148; which provides that barriers to imported
products should be non-discriminatory (all GATT parties should enjoy equal trading privileges), and &#147;national
treatment,&#148; which requires equal treatment of imports and domestic
products in the application of non-tariff regulations.<p>
<p>
     Several significant features of GATT allow consideration of environmental
issues as they relate to trade.  According to the foremost authority on GATT,
University of Michigan Professor John Jackson, &#147;the GATT relatively easily
accommodates national government environmental regulations that concern the
characteristics of imported products.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#209"><sup>209</sup></A> 
However, an
exception to GATT&#146;s general trade principles is required for many
environmental measures that do not regulate product characteristics, but
instead regulate the process by which they are produced.<p>
<p>
<i>  Article XX:  </i>Defined in Article XX, environmental exceptions to GATT
principles, as qualified in a preamble,<A HREF="trade8.html#210"><sup>210</sup></A> provide
that:<p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Subject to the requirement that such measures are not applied in a manner which
would constitute a means of arbitrary or unjustifiable discrimination between
countries where the same conditions prevail, or a disguised restriction on
international trade, nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to prevent
the adoption or enforcement by any contracting party of measures:<p>
<p>
. . .(b) necessary to protect human, animal or plant life or health;<p>
<p>
. . .(g) relating to the conservation of exhaustible natural resources if such
measures are made effective in conjunction with restrictions on domestic
production or consumption. . .&#148;<p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

 <p>
     When these GATT clauses were written in 1947, they were not intended to cover
broad environmental protection issues at all.  The first was meant to exempt
quarantine and other sanitary regulations,<A HREF="trade8.html#211"><sup>211</sup></A> while
the second was
intended to cover efforts to conserve oil, minerals and other finite raw
materials.<A HREF="trade8.html#"><sup>212</sup></A>  As environmental issues have
become more politicized,
however, GATT has been forced to evolve.  The first consideration of an Article
XX exception came in 1982, when Canada disputed a U.S. ban on imports of tuna.
In that case, both parties agreed that tuna should be considered an
&#147;exhaustible natural resource.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#213"><sup>213</sup></A> 
GATT ruled against the
U.S. primarily because the trade measure was not taken in conjunction with
similar domestic restrictions.<p>
     GATT has come under mounting pressure to broaden its environmental exceptions.
For the most part, GATT has resisted this pressure, interpreting
environment-related exceptions very narrowly for fear that their abuse would
lead to disguised protectionism.<A HREF="trade8.html#214"><sup>214</sup></A>  Under
exception (b), dispute
settlement panels, notably in the first Tuna-Dolphin panel report, have
construed the word &#147;necessary&#148; to mean that the measure must be the
least-GATT-inconsistent measure available.<A HREF="trade8.html#215"><sup>215</sup></A> 
Panels have also
limited the exception to measures taken with regard
to resources within a party&#146;s own jurisdiction, reasoning that parties
should not impose trade barriers simply because other parties have differing
policies within their own jurisdiction.<A HREF="trade8.html#216"><sup>216</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Exception (g), in addition to impeding extra-jurisdictional environmental
measures, has been interpreted to require such measures to be &#147;primarily
aimed at&#148; conservation and to &#147;render effective&#148; complementary
domestic restrictions.<A HREF="trade8.html#217"><sup>217</sup></A>  Environmentalists
contend that such
narrow interpretations could virtually nullify the exceptions by hindering
trade measures taken under multilateral environmental agreements, and by
precluding use of unilateral measures aimed at environmental protection of the
&#147;global commons.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#218"><sup>218</sup></A>  Importantly,
they argue that
regulation of process and production methods are sometimes the only means to
protect global commons resources.<A HREF="trade8.html#219"><sup>219</sup></A>  <p>
<p>
     In the second Tuna-Dolphin panel decision in 1994, however, GATT suggested
that greater latitude exists in applying Article XX to resources outside of
national jurisdiction.  This was a dispute over the U.S. secondary embargo of
tuna products from countries which import tuna from countries under the Marine
Mammal Protection Act&#146;s primary embargo.  According to the panel report:
&#147;the Panel could see no valid reason supporting the conclusion that the
provisions of Article XX (g) apply only to policies related to the conservation
of exhaustible natural resources located within the territory of the
contracting party invoking the provision.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#220"><sup>220</sup></A> 
This statement
appears to reverse the first Tuna-Dolphin ruling on
extra-jurisdictionality.<A HREF="trade8.html#221"><sup>221</sup></A>  One commentator calls
the panel
report&#146;s argument &#147;a brave stance for the panel since virtually all
of the trade policy community holds to the opposite
conclusion.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#222"><sup>222</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Shortly thereafter, GATT ruled on a European Union complaint regarding the
U.S. fuel efficiency standards under the Corporate Average Fuel Economy law,
which acted to restrict imports of European automobiles to the U.S.  The most
significant part of GATT&#146;s decision related to the fleet averaging
requirement of the law, which was found to be inconsistent with GATT&#146;s
general trade obligations.  The panel found that the fleet averaging
&#147;clearly served the purpose of fuel conservation, and served to render
effective the [domestic] conservation measure...,&#148; thus meeting the key
requirements of Article XX (g).<A HREF="trade8.html#223"><sup>223</sup></A>  The decision
marks the first
time GATT has ever ruled that an environmental measure was GATT-legal.<p>
<p>
<i>  Technical regulations and standards</i>:  The GATT Standards Code was
adopted at the 1979 Tokyo Round in order to minimize obstacles to trade
resulting from the imposition of technical regulations and product standards.  The Code
encourages use of international standards and scientific justification in order
to avoid conflicts.  Some environmentalists feared that this would lead to
downward harmonization, though little empirical evidence exists that this has
occurred.<A HREF="trade8.html#224"><sup>224</sup></A><p>
<u></u><p>

<u>Demands for Change &#151; Greening GATT:</u><p>
<u></u><p>
     GATT&#146;s unusual historical beginnings have prevented it from addressing
the emerging issue of multilateral environmental protection.  By design, GATT
is relatively non-binding and powerless, lacking an international organization,
a charter, or enforcement provisions.  Originally, GATT was intended to be an
interim arrangement pending ratification of the International Trade
Organization (ITO), through the Havana Charter.<A
HREF="trade8.html#225"><sup>225</sup></A>  GATT was
continued after the failure of the ITO to come into force in 1948, but GATT
itself was never ratified as a treaty.<A HREF="trade8.html#226"><sup>226</sup></A>  
Substantively, GATT was
limited to commercial policy subjects, and did not deal with most of the
ITO&#146;s other objectives such as full employment policies, economic
development, and raw materials.<A HREF="trade8.html#227"><sup>227</sup></A><p>
<p>
     These historical circumstances bequeathed various institutional weaknesses
which have inhibited GATT from accruing excessive regulatory powers over
 world trade.  GATT&#146;s rigid voting procedures make it extremely difficult
to amend.  Formal amendments require unanimous consent of the parties, or in
some circumstances, a two-thirds majority.  Since amendments must be ratified
by over one hundred parties, consensus for broad expansion of GATT powers has
always been elusive.<A HREF="trade8.html#228"><sup>228</sup></A>  According to Jackson,
&#147;during the
history of GATT, it appears that there has never been a Contracting Party vote
that imposed a new obligation on GATT Contracting Parties.&#148;<A
HREF="trade8.html#229"><sup>229</sup></A>
Instead of revision through amendment, GATT has been progressively strengthened
by several protracted negotiating rounds which required ratification by
participating nations, but these rounds have not introduced dramatic changes
with regard to environmental policies.<A HREF="trade8.html#230"><sup>230</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The exercise of GATT&#146;s powers are also limited by its cumbersome dispute
settlement procedures.  GATT&#146;s ability to enforce its rulings against
losing parties has been curtailed by the single-nation veto, which enables any
country to block panel decisions, including the defendant.<A
HREF="trade8.html#231"><sup>231</sup></A>  Thus,
the remedy for violation of GATT provisions, trade sanctions, is almost never
authorized.  Since arbitration procedures are confidential, they have been
relatively immune to environmental special interest pleadings and influence.<p>
<p>
     GATT&#146;s convoluted institutional rules have prevented it from succumbing
to significant environmental policy entanglements.  Because the GATT is
inhospitable to rapid revision, environmentalists have bemoaned the
time-consuming process of creative interpretation that would be required in
order to reverse unfavorable dispute settlement panel precedents.<A
HREF="trade8.html#232"><sup>232</sup></A>
For environmental activists experienced in
&#147;public interest&#148; advocacy, only a comprehensive overhaul of
defective GATT trade rules can accomplish their objective.<A
HREF="trade8.html#233"><sup>233</sup></A><p>
<p>
     According to the World Wildlife Fund&#146;s Von Moltke, a sufficiently rapid
greening of trade can take place only under &#147;a formal treaty establishing
an international organization with authority to act within its charter to
identify emerging issues and bring them to negotiation in a timely manner
without requiring consensus on all details.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#234"><sup>234</sup></A>  For GATT to
embrace a new
environmental agenda, its legal authority over world trading policies would
have to be restored to the level intended for the ITO in the Havana
Charter.<A HREF="trade8.html#235"><sup>235</sup></A><p>
<p>
     A new institution with greater legal authority, the World Trade Organization
(WTO), was proposed during the latest Uruguay Round of
negotiations.<A HREF="trade8.html#236"><sup>236</sup></A>  The WTO accord was signed by
approximately 120
countries on April 15, 1994.  Peter
Suchman, a former Treasury Department trade official under three presidents,
explains that U.S. acceptance of the WTO had little to do with free trade:<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
The Uruguay Round final provisions on dispute settlement and the WTO represent
a major victory for U.S. negotiators, who had rejected the WTO concept as
proposed early in the Round by Canada and the EC.  The U.S. held out on the WTO
as a means to ensure that its own trade laws, including section 301, would not
be unreasonably limited.  And it worked!<A HREF="trade8.html#237"><sup>237</sup></A><p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
     Jackson describes the WTO charter as &#147;a fairly radical new technique for
changing the GATT,&#148; that would &#147;provide, for the first time, a
definitive legal treaty text to establish the organization, and put it on a
sounder footing for future evolution.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#238"><sup>238</sup></A> 
Although it is
unclear precisely how the new WTO will incorporate environmental standards into
world trading rules, the drafting history of the ITO suggests that the
WTO&#146;s earlier incarnation would have done so.<A
HREF="trade8.html#239"><sup>239</sup></A>  On strictly
environmental grounds, developing countries might not have considered a WTO to
be in their best interests.  However, they assented to the proposal in the
hopes that it would lead to enhanced access to global markets.<p>
<p>
<u>The WTO and Formal Environmental Language:</u><p>
<p>
     According to a report by the U.S. Trade Representative, the United States
considered several key environment-related provisions of early Uruguay Round
drafts to be inadequate, and began to seek substantial revisions in late 1992.
Almost entirely due to efforts by the Clinton administration, the final text of
the Uruguay Round accord incorporated several new environmental features.<p>
<p>
<i>  The preamble</i>: Early drafts made vague reference to the &#147;optimal
use of resources of the word at sustainable levels.&#148;<A
HREF="trade8.html#240"><sup>240</sup></A>  The
U.S. modified this provision in the final text, which now calls for &#147;the
optimal use of the world&#146;s resources in accordance with the objective of
sustainable development, seeking both to protect and preserve the environment
and enhance the means for doing so...&#148;<A
HREF="trade8.html#241"><sup>241</sup></A><p>
<p>
<i>  Standards Harmonization</i>:  The Agreement on Sanitary and Phytosanitary
Measures applies to a wide range of public health measures such as food safety
and pesticide standards, meat inspection rules, and quarantine procedures.  Early
drafts would have required all public health measures to be the &#147;least
restrictive to trade&#148; of available alternatives.<A HREF="trade8.html#242"><sup>242</sup></A>  Countries would be
required to base
their standards on international standards, with higher standards allowed only
with &#147;scientific justification.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#243"><sup>243</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The U.S. feared that it would not be able to maintain standards higher than
international standards (i.e., downward harmonization), and that U.S. measures
might not withstand scientific scrutiny.  The Clinton administration
successfully changed this provision, requiring only that food safety measures
are &#147;not more trade restrictive than required to achieve their appropriate
level of protection, taking into account technical an economic
feasibility.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#244"><sup>244</sup></A>  A footnote elaborates that a
health measure
will not be considered more trade restrictive than required unless there is
another measure significantly less restrictive to trade.  However, the
requirements for the alternative measure are very rigorous.  It must 1) achieve
the level of protection demanded by the importing country; 2) be considered
&#147;reasonably available&#148;; 3) be technically and economically feasible;
and 4) be significantly less restrictive of trade.<A HREF="trade8.html#245"><sup>245</sup></A> 
As the U.S.
Trade Representative explains, the first requirement alone would preclude
virtually any alternative measures that are &#147;demonstrably less effective
in protecting public health (for instance, warning labels are less effective
than product bans, and voluntary labelling is less effective than mandatory
labelling).&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#246"><sup>246</sup></A><p>
<p>
     As with earlier drafts, the final agreement requires nations to harmonize
their food safety and sanitary standards, basing them on international
standards set by international bureaucracies such as the Codex Alimentarius
Commission, a U.N. body.<A HREF="trade8.html#247"><sup>247</sup></A>  Due to U.S. efforts,
a provision
specifically enables countries to &#147;introduce or maintain sanitary and
phytosanitary measures which result in a higher level&#148; of protection than
international standards, provided there is scientific
justification.<A HREF="trade8.html#248"><sup>248</sup></A>  The U.S. insisted that only a
government itself
could determine scientific justification, not dispute settlement
panels.<A HREF="trade8.html#249"><sup>249</sup></A>  No specific provision is made at all for
measures to be
lower than international standards.  To monitor the harmonization process, this
agreement creates a Committee on Sanitary and Phytosanitary
Measures.<A HREF="trade8.html#250"><sup>250</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The requirement that no measure should be maintained without &#147;scientific
evidence&#148; was also changed, now simply barring measures maintained without
&#147;sufficient scientific evidence.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#251"><sup>251</sup></A> 
The final standards
provisions are so flexible, even the scientifically flawed Delaney Clause,
which sets a zero-risk level for food additives, could not be judged a barrier
to trade.<A HREF="trade8.html#252"><sup>252</sup></A>  The reason: The WTO gives sole
discretion to determine
the appropriate level of protection or health risk to central government
authorities, with little regard for the consequences of such decisions for
trade.<A HREF="trade8.html#253"><sup>253</sup></A>  As the U.S. Trade Representative boasts:
&#147;the mere
fact that a food safety measure may have a disproportionate effect on imports
is not sufficient to qualify it as a disguised restriction on
trade.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#254"><sup>254</sup></A><p>
<p>
<i>  Harmonization of Technical Barriers:</i>  The Agreement on Technical
Barriers to Trade applies to environmental, health, and safety standards, as
well as technical regulations and conformity assessment procedures.  The
agreement calls on
countries to harmonize technical regulations by participating in standardizing
bodies such as the International Standards Organization (ISO).  A Committee on
Technical Barriers to Trade is formed to monitor the harmonization process and
to guard against &#147;downward harmonization.<A
HREF="trade8.html#255"><sup>255</sup></A> The U.S. objected
to early draft provisions which suggested that environmental measures should be
&#147;proportionate&#148; to the risk, and had the provision
deleted.<A HREF="trade8.html#256"><sup>256</sup></A><p>
<p>
     One draft provision barred environmental measures if alternate measures could
accomplish the same objective in a less trade restrictive manner.<A
HREF="trade8.html#257"><sup>257</sup></A>
Fearing this would prevent countries from enforcing stringent environmental standards, the
U.S. pushed to modify the requirement such that environmental measures merely
must not be &#147;more trade restrictive than necessary to fulfill a legitimate
objective.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#258"><sup>258</sup></A>  A legitimate objective is
defined as &#147;. .
.the protection of human health or safety, animal or plant life or health, or
the environment.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#259"><sup>259</sup></A>  This provision makes
clear that any
alternate measures less restrictive to trade would have to fulfill a central
government&#146;s own determination of its &#147;appropriate&#148; level of
protection in satisfying a legitimate objective.<A
HREF="trade8.html#260"><sup>260</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The agreement&#146;s technical standards language prevents standards from
being applied &#147;with the effect of creating unnecessary obstacles to
trade.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#261"><sup>261</sup></A>  However, this hopeful language
is mitigated by the
agreement&#146;s definition of a technical regulation, which is one that lays
down product characteristics.  According to trade expert Kenneth Berlin of the
law firm of Winthrop, Stimson, Putnam and Roberts, since the only regulations
covered by the agreement are those that affect product characteristics,
&#147;environmental laws like the Clean Air Act, Clean Water Act and
regulations promulgated thereunder are not subject to review under the TBT
agreement.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#262"><sup>262</sup></A>  Likewise, the
agreement&#146;s provisions
&#147;do not permit a nation to argue that a market-based incentive is less
trade restrictive than a command and control regulation.&#148;<A
HREF="trade8.html#263"><sup>263</sup></A>
Moreover, the agreement does not require a nation to give any scientific
justification for technical regulations.<p>
<p>
<i>  Dispute Settlement</i>:  The Dispute Settlement Agreement broadens the GATT
language so that arbitration panels will be able to seek scientific and
technical advice from any individual or organization.  Each nation that is
party to a trade dispute must make summaries of its dispute-panel submissions
publicly available.<A HREF="trade8.html#264"><sup>264</sup></A>  In cases involving
environmental issues,
panels may consult with expert review groups regarding relevant scientific and
technical issues, meaning that it is possible for environmental matters to have
greater impact on panel decisions.  These public- participation\transparency
provisions are unprecedented in GATT, and can be used by industry,
environmental, and other special interest groups to influence the WTO.<p>
<p>
     Strict time limits are set for dispute settlement panels to adjudicate
complaints.  The WTO permits cross-retaliation, meaning that countries have
expanded rights 
to impose punitive trade sanctions as a way of enforcing WTO rulings.  These
features will give the WTO more binding authority than GATT.<p>
<p>
<i>  Subsidies</i>:  Government assistance to private businesses is given a
&#147;green light&#148; under the Subsidies Code.  Twenty percent of the cost
of adaptation to environmental regulatory requirements may be subsidized
without the threat of challenge under the WTO.<A HREF="trade8.html#265"><sup>265</sup></A>  
An exemption is
also available for subsidies which are part of a government&#146;s policies
focusing on research and development, and regional assistance.  Assistance for
up to 75 percent of industrial research costs, and 50 percent of development
costs are specifically permitted.<A HREF="trade8.html#266"><sup>266</sup></A>  In the U.S., this
provision
could effect subsidies for environmental technology under the green industrial
policy being promoted by the Clinton-Gore administration.<A
HREF="trade8.html#267"><sup>267</sup></A><p>
<p>


<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
