<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Greening of Trade Policy</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiesp.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Studies Program" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Greening of Trade Policy: "Sustainable Development" and Global Trade</B><BR>
by James M. Sheehan<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P><P>
<u>Future changes?</u><p>
<p>
     The environmental movement is far from satisfied with current progress in
greening the GATT.  Yet by threatening to sidetrack trade agreements in the
U.S. Congress, it has had a significant impact on environmental provisions in
GATT.  According to a business advisory report to the U.S. Trade
Representative, &#147;U.S. negotiators worked to obtain limited changes now,
while leaving more comprehensive [environmental] reforms to post-Uruguay Round
negotiations.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#268"><sup>268</sup></A><p>
<p>
     At the conclusion of the Uruguay Round on December 15, 1993, trade negotiators
agreed to a Decision on Trade and Environment and designed a work program for
modifying GATT.  Among the objectives of this program was &#147;the adherence
to effective multilateral disciplines to ensure the responsiveness of the
Multilateral Trading System to environmental objectives, including principle 12
of the Rio Declaration.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#269"><sup>269</sup></A><p>
<p>
     An outgrowth of the Decision was the creation of a Committee on Trade and the
Environment (CTE), which will recommend modifications to WTO rules.  The
Committee will consider economic instruments, pollution charges and
environmental taxes, recycling regulations, processes and production methods,
packaging and labelling requirements, and public participation rights.  It may
review any trade-related issue, including &#147;eco-dumping,&#148; carbon
taxes, levies on fossil fuels, and transportation restrictions.<A
HREF="trade8.html#270"><sup>270</sup></A>
Within the CTE, the Clinton administration intends to press the WTO to broaden
its environmental provisions by clarifying &#147;the circumstances under which
GATT rules permit countries to use trade measures to protect the
environment&#148; and also by clarifying &#147;the scope of the exceptions for
environmental measures.<A HREF="trade8.html#271"><sup>271</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Stronger environmental provisions could be established in several ways.
Member countries could vote to 1) waive WTO trade obligations under certain
conditions; 2) adopt authoritative interpretations of WTO obligations and
exceptions; or 3) amend WTO agreements and dispute settlement
rules.<A HREF="trade8.html#272"><sup>272</sup></A>  If the CTE determines that incremental
environmental
reforms of the WTO would be insufficient, it could recommend an entirely new
environmental charter for world trade.<p>
<p>
     The first item in the CTE&#146;s list of priorities is the legal relationship
between multilateral environmental agreements and the WTO.<A
HREF="trade8.html#273"><sup>273</sup></A>  This
relationship is critically important, since it could effectively create new
exceptions to general trade principles, and open the door further to green
protectionism.  Jackson suggests that multilateral treaties (and their process
and production regulations) could be made WTO-consistent very easily by
adopting a waiver of general trade obligations.  The current number of GATT
countries which have signed the Montreal Protocol would be a sufficient number
to sustain a vote for such a waiver.<A HREF="trade8.html#274"><sup>274</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Once exceptions are made for multilateral agreements, the WTO would be able to
consider exempting certain unilateral trade measures as well.  Once the
principle is established that the global commons are in need of protection via trade
policies, inevitably there will arise certain environmental problems that
multilateral agreements do not remedy.  The U.S. argues that there should be
international consensus for using unilateral trade measures as a valid means of
forcing &#147;rogue&#148; countries to sign multilateral environmental
agreements.<A HREF="trade8.html#275"><sup>275</sup></A>  In effect, the U.S. proposal would
obfuscate the
distinction between unilateral and multilateral trade measures, thereby
legitimizing a host of U.S. environmental laws within the WTO, including the
Marine Mammal Protection Act and the Pelly Amendment.<A
HREF="trade8.html#276"><sup>276</sup></A>  <p>
<p>
     WTO provisions on technical regulations and environmental product standards
could have profound effects on world trade.  The most recent set of standards
being developed by the International Standards Organization, the ISO 14000
series, and are scheduled to be implemented in early 1996.<A
HREF="trade8.html#277"><sup>277</sup></A>
Previously, the ISO merely set obscure technical and safety standards.  The ISO
14000 will now set standards for international environmental management
systems, auditing, performance evaluations, eco-labelling and life-cycle
analysis.<A HREF="trade8.html#278"><sup>278</sup></A>  Such standards are used in enforcing
government
regulations and international agreements, and could impose hefty costs on
exporters who must obtain ISO certification for their products to enter
international commerce.  Consequently, the WTO could result in an entirely new
layer of bureaucratic rules and regulations, non-tariff barriers whose costs
will be passed along to consumers.<p>
<p>
     If the WTO is to integrate broader pollution and conservation standards into
world trade, it must also resolve the problem of harmonizing such standards
among many countries at varying stages of economic development.  Many experts
have proposed global minimum environmental standards as a pre-condition for
access
to global markets.  Such standards would include general environmental
objectives and principles, protocols on minimum standards for pollution emissions, and
financing mechanisms.<A HREF="trade8.html#279"><sup>279</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Since the GATT/WTO has little experience in determining appropriate
environmental standards, some cooperation with relevant U.N. institutions such
as the Environment Programme (UNEP) and the Commission on Sustainable Development
(UNCSD) would be required.<A HREF="trade8.html#280"><sup>280</sup></A>  The U.N.
Commission on Global
Governance, the successor to the 1987 World Commission on Environment and
Development, is in the process of designing a comprehensive reform of
international institutions in the U.N. system and the GATT for this purpose.
Among its goals are &#147;multilateral free trade,&#148; &#147;sustainable
development on a global basis,&#148; and solutions to &#147;grave environmental
problems beyond national remedy. . .&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#281"><sup>281</sup></A> 
Greater cooperation
between existing multilateral institutions would likely be more practical than
consolidating their functions in a single body.<A
HREF="trade8.html#282"><sup>282</sup></A><p>
<p>
     According to Jackson, WTO-consistent rules to enforce minimum environmental
standards would ensure increasingly stringent standards.  International
cooperation on minimum standards would discourage deregulatory competition, and
thus reinforce the interplay between environmental lobbyists and government.
Jackson describes how this process would work in the trading system:<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
In many cases, domestic leaders find it politically difficult to implement a
preferred course of action unless there is some external pressure that help
them in their domestic advocacy, and also in some cases gives them an
&#145;excuse&#146; for taking that action.<A HREF="trade8.html#283"><sup>283</sup></A><p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
     Integration of environmental and trade policies cannot proceed without the
involvement of non-governmental organizations in the process.  Future change in
the WTO hinges on the degree of public participation in and transparency of the
organizations procedures.  Environmental interest groups have demanded access
to the WTO dispute settlement body, the Committee on Trade and Environment, and
all other aspects of WTO decisionmaking.  Environmental lobbyists describe the
goal of greater transparency as a &#147;battle cry&#148; for participation in
&#147;the formation, negotiation, and implementation of trade policies and
accords.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#284"><sup>284</sup></A>  Jackson illuminates the
motivation of
environmental lobbyists:<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
. . .the environmental policy groups, perhaps partly because they primarily
operate on the national scene, have become used to using the processes of
publicity and lobbying pressure on Congress or Parliaments, to which they have
considerable access.  There is, thus, a much broader sense of
&#145;participation&#146; in the processes, which the international processes
have not yet accommodated.  Furthermore, the environmental policy groups...have
a sense of power achieved through successes in the legislative and public
discussion processes.<A HREF="trade8.html#285"><sup>285</sup></A><p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<BR><BR>


<A NAME="implications"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Implications of the Greening of Trade</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>The merging of trade with environmental policies can only produce increased
protectionism, regulation and bureaucratic interference in international
commerce.  The historical development of environmental restrictions in the U.S.
offers an appropriate analogy.  For more than a century, environmental regulation was
strictly limited by the American system of federalism.  The Constitution&#146;s
decentralized structure placed wildlife under the exclusive jurisdiction of the
states, notwithstanding the federal government&#146;s superior authority under
the interstate commerce clause.  During the nineteenth century, the Supreme Court ruled that
national environmental regulations were precluded by this exclusive state
jurisdiction.<A HREF="trade8.html#286"><sup>286</sup></A><p>
<p>
     The roots of the federal government&#146;s centralization of power can be
found in an international agreement between the U.S. and the United Kingdom,
the 1916 Migratory Bird Treaty.  The Supreme Court, in <i>Missouri v.
Holland</i>, used that treaty to establish federal jurisdiction in regulating
the hunting of wild birds.  Later 
Court decisions built upon this decision&#146;s implication that relying on
states for conservation policies was inadequate,<A HREF="trade8.html#287"><sup>287</sup></A>
establishing
federal control over wildlife in interstate commerce.<A
HREF="trade8.html#288"><sup>288</sup></A>  Over time,
these trends permitted a virtually unlimited consolidation of federal power
over environmental matters through a gradual &#147;process of
accretion.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#289"><sup>289</sup></A><p>
<p>
     Federal consolidation would soon contradict the original purpose of the
interstate commerce clause: to free commerce from &#147;stifling
regulation,&#148; according to constitutional scholar Laurence
Tribe.<A HREF="trade8.html#290"><sup>290</sup></A>  The federal commerce power was
intended to create a
&#147;regulatory vacuum&#148; in which competing economic factions would
produce minimal regulation of private commerce by Congress.<A
HREF="trade8.html#291"><sup>291</sup></A>
Indeed, as long as Congress refrained from enacting strict national standards
during the 1940s, &#146;50s and &#146;60s, &#147;states sold themselves as
attractive sites for new industrial facilities at least in part because they
offered low costs, including lax pollution control requirements,&#148; writes
former EPA official Daniel C. Esty.<A HREF="trade8.html#292"><sup>292</sup></A><p>
<p>
     By the 1970s, however, centralized federal power produced a vast system of
heavily bureaucratized national laws and regulations which stifled competition
amongst the states for new investment and jobs.  Like federal wildlife
regulations earlier this century, comprehensive environmental laws were
installed to prevent states from engaging in an inevitable &#147;race to the
bottom&#148; of environmental destructiveness.<A
HREF="trade8.html#293"><sup>293</sup></A>  Major pieces of
restrictive national legislation, such as the Clean Air Act and Clean Water
Act, &#147;might otherwise have been impossible to achieve or enforce if
individual states were free to maintain lower standards,&#148; writes
Esty.<A HREF="trade8.html#294"><sup>294</sup></A>  Today, &#147;[T]he entire body of
environmental law and
regulation in the United States rests solely on the authority of the federal
government to regulate interstate commerce (an exception to the general rule
that powers not specifically ceded to the federal government are reserved to
the states).&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#295"><sup>295</sup></A><p>
<p>
     As the American system of federalism has evolved, the states have retained
limited authority to enforce environmental standards, provided they exceed
national standards, though even this auhority is preempted in some cases.  The
primary limit on the stringency of state standards is central government
oversight to ensure that such standards do not obstruct free trade amongst
states, functioning much as the NAFTA and GATT/WTO bureaucracies do
internationally.  In balancing trade and environmental considerations, U.S.
courts have grappled with many of the same issues surrounding the
interpretation of GATT&#146;s Article XX.  In fact, Esty advances U.S. commerce
clause jurisprudence as &#147;a valuable starting point for analyzing how
environmental considerations might be woven into the fabric of the
GATT.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#296"><sup>296</sup></A><p>
<p>
     What this analysis fails to take into account, however, is that centralization
in the U.S. has facilitated the creation of cartels &#151; large-sized business
groupings protected against competition from efficient new entrants.  According
to University of Chicago economist B. Peter Pashigian, &#147;Environmental
rules have not only reduced the number of plants in the affected industries but
have made it more difficult for small plants to compete with
large.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#297"><sup>297</sup></A>  Cartelization on a global scale
would benefit
neither trade nor environmental objectives.<p>
<p>
     On a global level, there is no Constitution or Supreme Court to interpret
international environmental law apart from the GATT/WTO.  International
environmental agreements are implemented only to the extent that individual
governments agree to enforce them.  Economic enforcement of international
environmental standards through trade measures has traditionally been minimal,
in large part due to the free-market orientation of GATT and other trade
agreements.  GATT in particular has provided a free-market safety valve,
allowing countries to escape the more onerous environmental commitments.  The
merging of environmental standards into trade agreements like NAFTA and WTO is
an attempt to close off that safety valve and to allow for enforcement of international
environmental laws through trade policy.  This can only result in more
stringent regulation of world trade; indeed, the evolution of GATT&#146;s trade
and environment jurisprudence is already beginning to resemble the U.S. federal
government&#146;s.<p>
<p>
     To the extent that the greening of trade rules makes international
environmental law more enforceable, it shifts responsibility away from nations,
sub-national units (states), and individuals, creating an even greater distance
between individuals and their governments.<A HREF="trade8.html#298"><sup>298</sup></A> 
Green-trade advocates
seem to view the loss of accountability to international bureaucracies (such as
the WTO) as necessary.  Esty, for example, argues that the global character of
all environmental problems implies that natural resources can only be protected
&#147;by surrendering a bit of national sovereignty and by participating in an
international regime.&#148;<A HREF="trade8.html#299"><sup>299</sup></A><p>
<p>
     In the U.S., environmental trade rules could be used by the federal government
to justify further unfunded mandates on the states, greater infringements on
private property rights, and higher trade barriers.  However, political
centralization of trade and environmental policies will have its most serious
effects in the Third World.  International environmental agreements attempt to
dictate the resource management policies of poorer countries.  Moreover, by
restricting development, international environmental regulations work to
perpetuate Third World poverty.  Such political domination through intrusive
environmental controls is resented by developing countries as
eco-imperialistic.<A HREF="trade8.html#300"><sup>300</sup></A>  Since all the major players
&#151; big
business and environmental lobbyists, the U.S. government, participants in the
WTO Committee on Trade and the Environment &#151; appear to accept the need to
incorporate environmental standards into world trade, the future of free trade
is in doubt.  In the end, competitive trade may depend on greater Third World
resistance to the environmental strictures being imposed on the world&#146;s
poor through trade agreements like the WTO, NAFTA, the Basel Convention, and
others.<p>




<BR>
