<A NAME="156"></A><sup>156</sup> See GATT Secretariat, pp. 30-31. The GATT
Secretariat generally
discourages environmental trade measures as discriminatory trade barriers.  Yet
it maintains that trade measures are acceptable for preventing the undermining
of a multilateral agreement, or to broaden participation in an agreement.  GATT
also endorses foreign aid incentives to developing countries.<p>
<A NAME="157"></A><sup>157</sup> Repetto, pp. 8-9.  Such exceptions to free trade in
GATT were
explicitly rejected during trade negotiations in 1946, when the U.S. attempted
to insert international agreements into the charter of the proposed
International trade Organization, but was rebuffed by Brazil.<p>
