<HEAD>
<TITLE>Wells Town Offices</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF TEXT=# LINK=#CEC6AD VLINK=#4A3929>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING WIDTH=420>
<TR>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=99 HEIGHT=104 SRC="gifs/seal.gif"></TD>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=279 HEIGHT=48 SRC="gifs/header.gif"></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD><BR></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=320 HEIGHT=203 SRC="gifs/townoffice80.gif"></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD COLSPAN=2><IMG WIDTH=420 HEIGHT=20 SRC="gifs/invisible.gif"></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD><BR></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT>
			<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADING=0 WIDTH=320>
			<TR>
			<TD ALIGN=LEFT><CENTER><I>A letter from Wells Town Manager - Jonathan Carter</I></CENTER><P>
The "business" of Winter in Wells is a term I signify with getting the Town ready for the awakening of the community in Spring.  It is capped off by the Annual Town Meeting on April 26 and 27, following an intense 15-week budget development process. The
finishing touches also go into the 1995 Town Report, dedicated this year to late   Selectman   Harry Margeson, to be ready for reading in March.<P>

The business of Winter also means the continual work on the big issues facing the community. These include fighting the LNG Tank Project and applying for  the Harbor   dredge/beach restoration permits.  Developments to watch for are with the construction of the York County Technical  College, the Intermodal Transportation
Center and the new movie theater. All are slowly moving forward.<P>

The  business  of this winter appears to be dodging the weather. No matter if you were fighting the snow, wind or rain, again our Highway Department did an excellent job cleaning the roads so that we got to where we were going safely.<P>
 
Finally, the business of Winter is traveling, either for pleasure or for work.  Traveling for work sometimes means conventions in warmer climates but, more often than not this Winter, above average stress and strain on ourselves was the norm as we have had to navigate through rough weather to make a living.  However, for   the lucky,  warmer climates became a reality and were very welcomed for some with a few days or months in the sun.<P>

Now we turn our attention towards Spring and Summer and thoughts of Route One traffic, walking the trails at the Wells Reserve,  and the reopening of seasonal businesses as we start welcoming many back to Wells.<P>
			</TD>
			</TR>
			</TABLE>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><IMG WIDTH=99 HEIGHT=104 SRC="gifs/manager.gif"><BR><IMG WIDTH=99 HEIGHT=4 SRC="gifs/invisible.gif"><BR>Town Manager<BR>Johnathan L. Carter</TD>
<TD COLSPAN=3 ALIGN=CENTER><H4><A HREF="http://www.communitynetwork.com/wells/gvt/gvtinfo.html">Town Information</A><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.communitynetwork.com/wells/gvt/wellsgvtboard.html">Board of Selectmen</A><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.communitynetwork.com/wells/gvt/wellsgvtclerk.html">Notices from the Town Clerk</A><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.communitynetwork.com/wells/gvt/wellsnotice.html">Notices for the Town</A><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.communitynetwork.com/wells/gvt/police/police.html">Wells Police Department</A><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.communitynetwork.com/wells/wellshome2.html">Return to Wells</A>
</H4></TD>
</TR>

