<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcalban.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>
<h3>ALBANIA</h3>

Albania held its third free parliamentary elections on 26 May. The result held few surprises with the ruling Democratic Party of President Sali Berisha securing a comfortable majority in the first round of voting. 
However the poll did `not meet international standards for free and fair elections' according to British, German and Norwegian observers from the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE). Voting rigging, manipulation, violent intimidation by the police and fraud were widespread, with reports that ballot boxes arrived at the polling stations stuffed full of votes for the Democratic Party. Many of the candidates not already banned refused to participate, with the opposition parties likely to boycott the new parliament.<br>
Demonstrations in Tirana by opposition supporters were ruthlessly supressed by the police with protestors beaten and arrested. Among those attacked was Servet Pellumbi, the leader of the Socialist Party.
<P>
Albania's first ever stock exchange officially opened for business on 2 May. The market is limited to trading in treasury bills and privatisation vouchers under the control of the Bank of Albania. 
Ten licenced dealers operate in the market, including three former street traders. The UK company GMA-Capital Markets Ltd trained the brokers with sponsorship from the British Know-How Fund.

Albania is set to receive its first mobile phone network following a US$8 million agreement between Albanian Mobile Telecommunications and Alcatel for the supply and installation of a GSM network. 
The service is due for launch in June and will initially cover Tirana as well as the Kavaja, Fier, Vlara, Shkodra and Durres regions.
<P>
Friends again? Albania and Greece signed a Friendship Treaty in March, setting aside tensions over the Greek minority in Albania and illegal Albanian workers in Greece. 
Greece has also agreed to support Albania's efforts at closer links with the EU and to legalise around 250,000 Albanians working in Greece.
<P>
A further sign of improving relations is that a subsidiary of the Greek National Bank will be opened in Tirana with a base capital of Lek200 million (US$2 million).
<P>
Albania's first legislation regulating the insurance market has been passed. The law will enable private insurance companies to operate in competition to the state owned Isig Insurance Institute. Insurance and reinsurance companies will require a minimum capital of Lek30 million.
<P>
The Egyptian company Kato Aromatik is nearing completion of nine factories in Vore, near Tirana. The investment worth, US$15 million, will manufacture children's food and pharmaceutical products. Production will begin in May.
<P>
Germany has granted Albania a credit of US$32.58 million to reconstruct the Rinas International Airport at Tirana. 
Siemens, the German construction company, will modernise the runway, taxi lanes and airport buildings. New lighting and navigation equipment will also be installed.
<P>
The International Development Agency has approved a US$29.5 million credit to fund the improvement and privatisation of the power sector.

<p>
