<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcarmen.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>
<h3>ARMENIA</h3>

The Midland Bank opened its first branch in the former Soviet Union in Yerevan on 16 March.
<P>
Armenia became the first Transcaucasian republic to gain guest status at the European Council, the first step in gaining full membership of the EU.
<P>
The energy systems of Iran and Armenia will be connected by the end of 1996. Armenia will receive 200 MW of electricity a day.
<P>
Armenia's largest chemical plant, Nairit, increased production in 1995. The factory, employing 4,000 workers, has developed trading links with companies in Russia, Georgia, Ukraine and Belarus and is working on co-operation plans with firms in the USA, France and Belgium.
<P>
Of over 200 privatised enterprises in Armenia foreign investors have become co-owners in 21, with stakes ranging from 1 to 30 per cent according to Armen Shamshian, Chief of the Government Auction Centre.
<P>
Although the Armenian economy has suffered a considerable decline since the collapse of the USSR, other areas of activity have been more fertile. Armenia's population grew by an impressive 9.5 per cent in 1995 to 3,763,000 according to the State Statistics Agency.

<p>
