<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcazerb.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>
<h3>AZERBAIJAN</h3>

In February agreements were signed with Russia to pipe up to five million tonnes of oil a year from Baku to the Black Sea port of Novorossiysk, and with Turkey to pipe oil through Georgia to Supsa, also on the Black Sea.
<P>
A consortium led by British Petroleum and Statoil of Norway have signed an agreement with the Azeri Government to explore and develop oil and gas fields on the Karabakh geological structure in the Caspian Sea.
<P>
The McDermott oil company has sold its 2.45 per cent stake in the Azerbaijan International Operating Company developing the Azeri, Chirag and Guneshli fields in the Caspian Sea. 
The stake has been bought by the Japanese Itochu Corporation. Itochu (formerly C. Itoh) will invest US$245 million in the development of the US$10 billion project.
<P>
A second American company, the Pennzoil Corporation is also set to reduce its stake in the Azerbaijan International Operating Company. 
Pennzoil's stake will be reduced from 9.82 to 4.82 per cent. The Japanese Itochu Corporation will also buy the shares for US$132 million, increasing its total stake to 7.45 per cent.
<P>
The IMF has agreed to loan Azerbaijan US$80 million to finance the privatisation of 8,000 small businesses.
<P>
The former Agriculture Minister Muzamil Abdullayez has been sentenced to death by the Supreme Court which found him guilty of treason over his role in the failed coup attempt in October 1994. 
The only person who can revoke the sentence is President Aliyev, the man he tried to topple.
<P>
In another development that will cement President Aliyev's grip on power Ayaz Mutalibov (Azerbaijan's first post-Soviet president) and Rahim Haziev were arrested in Moscow in April. 
Accused of several crimes, including alleged coup attempts in October 1994 and March 1995, they are likely to face the death penalty if extradited to Baku.
<P>
Elf Aquitane, the French oil company, has reached agreement with the Azeri Government for a 10 per cent stake in the Shakh Deniz oil field. BP and Statoil each hold 25.5 per cent stakes in the project, with the state oil company Socar holding 40 per cent and Turkish Petroleum  9 per cent. Socar's share will be reduced to 30 per cent. Other oil companies considering the venture include LUKoil of Russia, Total of France and Ramco Energy of the UK. The field has estimated reserves of 1.4 billion barrels of oil and 500 billion cubic metres of gas.

<p>
