<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbbelar.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>
<h3>BELARUS</h3>

In an attempt to strengthen relations and foster the independence and sovereignty of Belarus, the EU signed an Interim Trade Agreement on 25 March.
<P>
The trade deficit more than doubled in 1995 to US$572 million from US$225 million in 1994. Trade with countries of the CIS resulted in a deficit of US$630 million, only slightly eased by a surplus of US$58 million with non-CIS states.
<P>
GDP increased by 1 per cent in February according to the Bureau of Statistics.
<P>
Monthly inflation was 4 per cent in February.
<P>
The Belarussian Central Bank has reduced its refinancing rate to 55 per cent annually, effective from 21 March.
<P>
From bad... The 1996 state budget has been passed by parliament. The predicted deficit of US$500 million, 3.1 per cent of GDP, is well outside the target set down by the IMF. 
The final deficit is likely to be significantly higher as last minute subsidies to the agriculture sector of US$480 million were not taken into account. 
The IMF has given up any notion of resuming credits to Belarus due to the lacklustre and ineffective market reforms. A US$300 million standby credit agreed in 1995 will not go ahead.
<P>
To worse... The Belarussian legal, economic and political environment for attracting foreign investment is one of the weakest in the world, according to a report by the World Bank. 
The `extremely tangled, cumbersome and unstable' taxation system was identified as the principle obstacle to foreign investment, which is currently averaging a meagre US$20 million a year.
<P>
In December 1991 69 per cent of Belarussians felt the end of the Soviet Union was a positive move, yet only four years later a mere 6 per cent thought the decision to abolish the Soviet Union was the correct one. 
Playing on the memories of the good old days of a command economy Alexander Lukashenkaa is doing his best to end Belarus' brief dalliance with independence. 
Presiding over a ruined economy dependent on Russian subsidies President Lukashenka has become increasingly vocal in proclaiming integration with Russia as the panacea for his country's ills. 
Quite where Russia will find the money to solve Belarus' economic problems seems to have been conveniently ignored.

<p>
