<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<h3>BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA</h3>

Moslem and Croat leaders in Bosnia agreed to create a customs union in March. The agreement also includes a single state budget, a unitary banking system and a new federation flag. Whether any notice of the accord will be taken on the ground remains to be seen.
<P>
Bosnia became a member of the World Bank at the beginning of April. 
The president of the bank, James Wolfensohn, signed three loan packages worth US$270 million on a visit to Sarajevo. The projects to be funded by the money include rebuilding roads, bridges and airports, restarting agricultural production and repairing water and sanitation systems.
<P>
The Bosnian Prime Minister Hasan Muratovic estimates his country will need US$16 billion to fund post-war reconstruction. 
The most critical areas identified by the World Bank - health care, education and basic infrastructure, will require US$5.1 billion. He also estimated the total physical damage to Bosnia at a staggering US$80 billion.
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates have pledged US$100 million to assist the Bosnian army train and re-equip.
<P>
The US Congress agreed an aid package for Bosnia at the end of March. Small and medium sized enterprises will receive US$65 million, with US$80 million for infrastructure projects.

<p>
