<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcczech.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>
<h3>CZECH REPUBLIC</h3>

The Czech parliamentary elections on 31 May and 1 June succeeded only in creating confusion rather than a new government. Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus's ruling coalition of the Civic Democratic Party (ODS), the Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA) and the Christian Democratic Union (KDU) won 99 seats in the 200 member parliament. Despite slightly increasing their share of the vote they lost six seats and their majority.<br>
Support for the Social Democrats (CSSD) of Milos Zeman quadrupled from about 6 per cent to 26.4 per cent, making them the second largest party, and the real victors in the election.<br>
Although the overall vote for left-wing parties has not grown significantly since 1992, Zeman succeeded in consolidating that vote and creating a more united and therefore powerful opposition force. The passive campaign of the ODS, relying on past achievements, retained existing support but did not do enough to capture new votes.<br>
On 6 June President Vaclav Havel asked Klaus to form a minority government after the CSSD said they would accept Klaus as prime minister in return for certain conditions. These include the post of parliamentary chairman, decentralisation of power to the regions and the separation of the social-welfare fund from the state budget.<br>
The only party to lose a major share of the vote was the unreformed Communists, losing 13 seats. Six parties gained seats in parliament compared to nine in 1992, as those failing to gain 5 per cent of the vote have their share redistributed among the larger parties.<br>
Calling new elections is a possibility, however the Czech constitution prohibits the dissolution of parliament until elections to the Senate have taken place. The earliest date for another ballot would be the spring of 1997, with a government of `experts' ruling until then.<br>
The positive outcome of the election is that a clear mandate has been delivered to reformist and democratic parties, with extremist groups effectively sidelined. The long-term stability and the economic reforms of the Czech Republic are unlikely to be affected by the election result. What is guaranteed is a period of politicking, deals and compromises behind the scenes.
<P>

Full election results<br>

<table>
<tr><td>Party</td><td>Vote</td><td>Seats</td></tr>
<tr><td></td><td>%</td><td>No.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Civic DemocraticParty (ODS)</td><td>29.6</td><td>68</td></tr>
<tr><td>Social Democrats(CSSD)</td><td>26.4</td><td>61</td></tr>
<tr><td>Communist Party of Bohemia
  and Moravia (KSCM)</td><td>10.3</td><td>22</td><tr>
<tr><td>Christian Democratic 
  Union (KDU)</td><td>8.0</td><td>18</td></tr>
<tr><td>Republican Party (SRP)        
Civic Democratic</td><td>8.0</td><td>18</td></tr>
<tr><td> Alliance (ODA)</td><td>6.3</td><td>13</td><tr>
</table>
<P>
Party politics
<P>
ODS: centre-right party with a strong record on the economy and reform.<br>
CSSD: centre-left party supporting privatisation but opposes price liberalisation.<br>
KSCM: unreformed communists whose strong links to the past rule out a significant role in any government.<br>
KDU: centre party and part of previous coalition government, likely to demand more cabinet seats as price for co-operation.<br>
ODA: also a coalition partner, a centre-right party in favour of economic reforms and decentralisation, will also be looking for more cabinet seats.<br>
SRP: extreme right party, anti-German and gypsy policies exploited fears over crime and German influence in the economy.
<P>
British Petroleum entered the Czech liquid propane market at the beginning of April with the purchase of the Propan-Butan o.z. Plzen bottling facility for US$8 million.
<P>
Midland Electricity of the UK have announced plans to take a 20 per cent stake in the Vchodoceska energetika power distributor. The two companies have been co-operating for several years.
<P>
A 49 per cent stake in the Czech Republic's second mobile telephone network has been awarded to TMobil. 
The company will invest Kc5.5 billion for the 20 year licence. 
The majority stake will be held by the transmission agent Ceske radiokomunikace, although TMobil will have operational control until the year 2000. 
TMobil is a joint venture between the German mobile phone company DeTeMobil, who hold 85 per cent and the Italian firm Stet, with 12 per cent. The remaining shares are held by Sporitelni investicni spolecnost, Telekomunikacni montaze Praha and Podnik vypocetni. TMobil was a surprise winner, with at least three other consortia offering higher bids. However they won the license after offering the lowest user rates and pledging that the service would be available to 60 per cent of the population by September. Among the aerial sites TMobil will use are Catholic churches.
<P>
The government has ordered the National Property Fund (FNM) to sell shares in 66 companies, generating about Kc1.3 billion and providing a quick fix for the troubled Hornicka pojistovna health insurance company. The government has offered to pay 80 per cent of Hornicka's estimated debt of Kc1 billion to over 12,000 creditors. The proceeds from the sales were originally allocated to the health, pension and social funds.
<P>
One of Britain's largest clothing retailers, Marks & Spencer, has announced it is to open a 1,300 square metre store in Prague this October.
<P>
A `Top-20' list of advertising agencies released by the Association of Advertising Agencies (ARA), puts Mark/BBDO at the top, with McCann-Erickson a close second. Young & Rubicam, Grey Praha, and Ogilvy & Mather maintained their respective third, fourth and fifth positions from last year.
<P>
Young & Rubicam Praha announced a turnover of US$20.6 million in 1995. Local clients, including Colgate Palmolive, Kodak, Ringier, Nike, Ikea and Philip Morris, make up 70 per cent of the agency's business.
<P>
Czech GDP grew by 4.8 per cent in 1995, not 5.2 per cent as was originally thought according to the Czech Statistical Office. Josef Tosovsky, governor of the Czech National Bank (CNB), has predicted economic growth will be about 5 per cent in 1996. He also estimated inflation would fall by no more than 1 per cent.
<P>
Average monthly wages grew by 17.5 per cent during 1995 to Kc8,171.
<P>
Industrial production showed a 12 month growth of 12.3 per cent at the end of January. Over the same period the average industrial wage increased by 19.9 per cent.
<P>
Consumer price inflation increased by 0.5 per cent in February, a fall from January's figure of 2.3 per cent. Year-on-year inflation is running at 8.6 per cent.
<P>
The Deputy Prime Minister of Industry and Trade Miroslav Somol has predicted a trade deficit of between Kc150 and Kc160 billion (US$5.5 and US$5.9 billion) in 1996.
<P>
The Czech cabinet has approved proposals for individual and corporate tax cuts in 1997. The personal tax allowance will be increased from Kc26,400 to Kc30,000, with a reduction in corporate tax from 39 per cent to 35 per cent. The cuts will save Czech taxpayers an estimated Kc9.5 billion.
<P>
Construction of a Kc131.8 million factory producing rubber and polyurethane rollers for the printing, steel and textile industries is nearing completion. The new plant is being built by Felix Boettcher CR, a subsidiary of the German Felix Boettcher GmbH.
<P>
Skoda Plzen has paid Cimex Holdings, a private investor, Kc460 million for a 43.5 per cent stake in the truck manufacturer Tatra Koprivnice.
<P>
Good morning Vietnam: Skoda Plzen has also announced the creation of a joint venture in Vietnam to manufacture high voltage electric equipment. Skoda Isovina will be 65 per cent owned by Skoda and 35 per cent by the Vietnamese Government.
<P>
The Matsushita Electric Company is to invest US$66 million in a greenfield site near the city of Plzen. The US$66 million project is due to start production in April 1997, with 500,000 television sets produced in the first year. The Matsushita deal is the largest investment success of CzechInvest, the Czech Government agency responsible for attracting foreign investment.
<P>
The National Property Fund has announced a public tender for the sale of a 47 per cent stake in the aircraft hydraulics manufacturer Technometra Praha, worth an estimated Kc123 million.
<P>
Brno's first hyper-market will be opened by Globus CR this summer. The total cost of the project is Kc1 billion, involving 70 construction firms.
<P>
Going, going, gone: To Prague, where Christie's International, the London based auction house, will open its first eastern European office.
<P>
A new Skoda is due for launch in September based on the Volkswagen Passat. The `Octavia' is expected to cost under US$15,000.
<P>
Deutsche Bahn AG and Czech Railways have agreed a plan to modernise the Prague-Berlin train route. Investment worth US$202.9 million will be made by the year 2000 which will cut the journey time down to three hours 10 minutes.
<P>
Four banks have been recommended by the Czech Transport Ministry to finance a high speed rail link from Poland to Austria through the Czech Republic. The European Investment Bank and Kreditanstalt fur Wiederaufbau would grant a state-guaranteed loan of Kc11.5 billion, while the Deutsche Bank with Kc2.4 billion and Ceska sporitelna, the Czech savings bank with Kc6 billion, would finance the non-guaranteed part of the loan. The state budget would provide a further Kc7 billion.
<P>
Reconstruction work at Prague's Ruzyne Airport has been delayed, with completion now due for November 1997. The total cost of the project is Kc4.3 billion.
<P>
The Investicni a postovni banka has agreed to sell a 39 per cent stake in the private TV station Premiera TV. Although not revealing who the new buyers are, a spokesman hinted that the Bahamas based Stratton Investments and the insurance company Ceska pojistovna had already expressed strong interest in acquiring stakes in Premiera.
<P>
The visit by Queen Elizabeth II to the Czech Republic in March was the first by a reigning British monarch. The Queen expressed her hope that the Czech Republic would soon become a member of the EU and NATO.
<P>
Komercni Banka, the predominant bank in the Czech Republic, reported net profits of US$188 million in 1995, 6 per cent higher than 1994. The bank is planning a campaign to attract investors to a eurobond issue of between US$150 and US$300 million, lead-managed by CS First Boston.
<P>
The Czech media sector is facing a major shake-up following the announcement that Ringier CR is attempting to buy the daily Expres, the main competitor to the publishers own Blesk. If successful the merger would create one of the republic's largest newspapers with a combined circulation of 296,000. Mlada fronta Dnes is the market leader with a circulation of 330,000. Consolidation of the Czech newspaper sector has been expected as eight newspapers have daily circulations of less than 100,000.
<P>
A partial takeover of the Zemska banka has been staged by Banka Hana who will take over Kc4 billion (US$149 million) of Zemska's assets and liabilities. Zemska will use its remaining assets of Kc2 billion (US$75 million) to reform as a mortgage bank. Zemska lost Kc51.8 million in 1995.
<P>
The US company Grace, a manufacturer of air cleaners, is to transfer production from America and Sweden to southern Bohemia. The new production centre will take over the ZVVZ air conditioner and cleaner manufacturer in Milevsko.
<P>
Foreign portfolio investment in the Czech Republic increased by 47 per cent in 1995, with Kc36.1 billion entering the country in share and bond investments. By the end of 1995 foreign investors held Kc71.7 billion worth of securities, with UK investors leading the way with a 50 per cent share followed by US investors with 21.9 per cent and the Germans with 6.2 per cent.
<P>
The unhealthy state of the Czech medical sector was improved in early March with the opening of a new factory by Medicamenta, the country's largest distributor of medicines and medical products. Several years late in opening the new plant will help increase domestic production and reduce reliance on imported medicines and health products. However the Czech Republic will continue to lag behind its European neighbours in the domestic production of medical supplies.
<P>
The Union banka has purchased a 90 per cent stake in Banka Skala. Banka Skala has 15 offices and 20,000 customers.
<p>
