<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbalban.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>
<h3>ESTONIA</h3>

The Estonian Cellular Telephone Company had 30,000 subscribers by the beginning of January, an increase of 12,000 over the previous year. 
The GSM network covers 90 per cent of the population.
<P>
A 330-km fibre optic cable linking Tallinn and St Petersberg was opened on January, allowing the transmission of up to 30,000 calls simultaneously.
<P>
The annual report of the Estonian Investment Bank shows that Estonian industrial production increased by 1.4 per cent in 1995. 
The greatest increases were in the wood working and furniture sector (up 13 per cent), textiles (up 16 per cent) and the chemical industry (up 7 per cent).
According to the report the banks' assets grew by 47.5 per cent in 1995, increasing the consolidated balance sheet of Estonian commercial banks to EEK14.9 billion. 
The five leading commercial banks hold 75 per cent of the market. The number of banks in Estonia has fallen from 20 to 16 following several mergers and incorporations as competition intensified and the EEK50 million capital requirement came into effect on 1 January 1996.
<P>
Monthly inflation fell to 3.3 per cent in February, still the highest rate of the three Baltic states.
<P>
Hansapank was the largest bank in Estonia and the second largest in the Baltics at the end of 1995, with assets of US$293.6 million. In a move set to consolidate its position in the Baltic banking sector Hansapank has signed an agreement to take over the Latvian Deutsch-Lettische Bank, the eighth largest bank in the country.
<P>
Estonia's second largest commercial bank, Hoiupank, announced profits of EEK27.8 million (US$2.4 million) for 1995.
<P>
Elcoteq Baltic, the Finnish electronics company, is planning to expand its Tallinn plant by 8,000 square metres to meet growing demand. The company is Estonia's largest exporter.
<P>
The London law firm Denton Hall has begun advising the Tallinn Stock Exchange in a project sponsored by the UK's Know How Fund.
<P>
The decision by the Finnish Government to restrict the import of alcoholic drinks is likely to lose the Estonian economy US$85 million a year. The draft law prohibits tourists visiting Finland and Finns who have been abroad for a short period from bringing alcohol into the country. With one day shopping tourists making up the majority of visitors from Finland, the Estonian drinks industry is set for a dry period.
<P>
Top of the class: Estonia received top marks in a World Bank report on economic development and reform. With an economy regarded as one of the most successful in eastern Europe the World Bank will no longer help in the formulation of Estonia's macro-economic policy.
<P>
The Kohila paper mill which closed down two years ago should be operational again in mid-April following the installation of new machinery. The new equipment was bought with credit from the EBRD.
<P>
Statoil, the Norwegian oil company, is to invest US$8.6 million annually in Estonia over the next five years, increasing the number of petrol stations to 20 by 1999.

<p>
<hr>
