<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcgeorg.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>
<h3>GEORGIA</h3>

Following disastrous tea harvests in 1994 and 1995 Georgia is hoping to grow 100,000 tonnes of tea leaf in 1996, compared to just 37,000 tonnes last year. 
Over the last 18 months 33 tea factories have closed down and another 134 are operating at between 20 and 25 per cent capacity. The government is likely to introduce a number of measures to support the industry including lifting price controls and excise duty exemptions.
<P>
New legislation has been approved which will transfer the ownership of land to those who cultivate it, leading to over 670,000 hectares being placed under private ownership. The new law permits the selling, purchasing and bequeathing of land plots, although only by Georgian citizens.
<P>
Georgian GDP increased by 2.4 per cent in 1995 according to the State Statistics Directorate.
<P>
Monthly inflation grew to 3.2 per cent in February from 2.6 per cent in January.
<P>
In April the Georgian Parliament ratified an agreement with Azerbaijan and an international oil consortium to transport oil from the Caspian Sea to the Georgian Black Sea port of Batumi. The consortium, led by BP and Statoil of Norway will invest US$250 million in the project to upgrade and extend an existing pipeline.
<P>
Agreement has been reached with the Iranian Energy Ministry for a US$10 million credit for the construction of a diversion tunnel at the Zhinvali Hydro-electric power station. The tunnel will take two years to build after which the plant will have a capacity of 130 MW.

<p>
<hr>
<center><img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="besummy1.html">Summary Menu</a></center>

