<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bchung.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>
<h3>HUNGARY</h3>

In the US$3.4 billion privatisation frenzy at the end of 1995 the amount of German investment increased to US$1.5 billion for the year. The total amount of investment by German companies in Hungary since 1989 is US$3.9 billion, compared to US$4.5 billion from the USA.
<P>
Monthly inflation was 0.6 per cent in February, a fall from 4.4 per cent in January when central price increases fuelled inflation.
<P>
Figures released by the Central Statistical Office show that Hungary's GDP grew by 1.5 per cent in 1995, lower than initial estimates.
<P>
The number of registered unemployed remained at 11.6 per cent in March. The lowest rate, 6.1 per cent was registered in Budapest, the highest in Szabolcs Szatmar Bereg county at 21 per cent.
<P>
Depressing times: A survey conducted for the EU showed that a mere 10 per cent of Hungarians believe the country is on the right economic track, with 79 per cent pessimistic about the future.
<P>
The IMF agreed to grant a two-year standby credit facility worth US$387 million on 15 March after the government agreed to keep the 1996 budget deficit below 4 per cent of GDP and the social security deficit to Ft17.8 billion.
<P>
The meat packing plant Szekszardi Husipari has been sold to Metraco International Kereskedelmi for US$15 million.
<P>
The Hungarian American Enterprise Fund (HAEF), funded by the American taxpayer, is seeking US$50 million from private investors. However the HAEF has been attracting unwanted attention over its ability to get through employees. Since the beginning of 1995 five out of eight investment executives have left the organisation, a turnover rate described as a `joke' by a member of the Baring Asset Management emerging markets division in London.
<P>
Assets and real estate of the fruit juice and canning enterprise Dunakeszi Conserve Factory Rt have been purchased from the liquidator by Financial Investor Citizen Rt for Ft105 million. With registered capital of Ft150 million Citizen Rt predict net sales of Ft1 billion in the first year through the export of processed fruit products, principally to western Europe.
<P>
In an amendment to banking legislation foreign investors will not require government permission to invest in Hungarian banks from 1 July 1996.
<P>
Try, try and try again: A third attempt to privatise the broadcast monopoly Antenna Hungaria was launched in March. The prospective buyer will be required to raise the company's capital in return for a 60 per cent stake.
<P>
Closed tenders for the purchase of the Forum Hotel have been invited by the State Property Agency. Fifteen companies have been invited to bid for a 94.9 per cent stake worth Ft4.1 billion, including ITT-Sheraton, Holiday Inn, Intercontinental, Samsung, Daewoo, Forte, American Hospitality, HSBC and First Boston. The Forum has 400 beds, 22 per cent of the first class market in Hungary and sales of Ft2.3 billion in 1995.
<P>
A3 Television will become the first 24-hour television channel in Hungary during 1996. The station will also restructure it organisation with funds provided by its parent company the Hungarian Broadcasting Corporation, which was introduced to the New York NASDAQ stock exchange in December 1995.
<P>
Hungarian TV and Radio are on the verge of financial collapse. The chairman of the Radio and TV Board has asked the government for Ft4.5 billion (US$30 million) in immediate aid. Hungarian Radio alone faces a Ft800 million debt, with a potential deficit of Ft3 billion by the end of 1996.
<P>
The black market remains alive and kicking in Hungary, accounting for an estimated Ft1.8 trillion - the equivalent of nearly one-third of GDP - in 1995.
<P>
Loans of US$20 million by the EBRD and US$40 million from a consortium led by the Bankers Trust have been granted to the Hungarian Investment and Development Bank. The EBRD loan will be used to finance investments by small and medium sized enterprises, while the Bankers Trust money will be used for infrastructure projects.
<P>
The Scandinavian telecommunications company Ericsson has won a US$120 million contract to provide the Hungarian Telecommunications Company with digital switches for its fixed network.
<P>
At a cinema near you: The Australian entertainment company Village Roadshow Ltd is to build a nine screen cinema complex in the Duna Plaza shopping centre in Budapest. The new complex will be built in partnership with the Hungarian company InterCom. Village Roadshow, in which Anglia Television of the UK has a 17.55 per cent stake, has plans to become the largest cinema operator in Hungary, Greece and Italy.
<P>
Minority stakes in two power stations will be sold in April, a further three in July and in Hungary's largest electricity utility MVM Rt in the third quarter of 1996. Bids from international investors will be invited by the State Privatisation and Holding Company for the Budapesti Eromu Rt and Tiszai Eromu Rt power plants in April. Stakes of between 36 to 49 per cent in the Bakonyi Eromu Rt, Borsodi Eromu Rt and Pecsi Eromu Rt power stations will be sold in July and a 25 per cent stake in MVM in the third quarter of the year.
<P>
The Sony Corporation announced in early April that it will build a US$20.5 million greenfield multi-media factory at Godello. Construction of the plant is scheduled to finish in January 1997.

<p>
<hr>
