<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bclatvia.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>LATVIA</h3>

A video aimed at potential investors in the Latvian forestry sector has been produced by the <a href="http://www.lda.gov.lv">Latvian Development Agency</a>. The video, costing US$21, covers enterprises involved in manufacturing various boards, plywood and furniture.
<P>
Liquidators have been appointed to Bank Baltija, formerly the largest bank in the Baltics, which collapsed last June with debts estimated at over US$400 million. The UK chartered accountants Deloitte & Touche have been appointed by the Riga Regional Court following nomination by the Bank of Latvia. The liquidators will attempt to recover the bank's assets and investigate the causes of the collapse.
<P>
Latvia's monthly inflation fell to 1.8 per cent in February, the lowest in the Baltic region.
<P>
At the end of 1995 Unibanka was Latvia's largest bank and the sixth largest in the Baltics with assets of US$228.5 million.
<P>
The Bank of Latvia reported a Ls6.4 million (US$12.3 million) profit for 1995.
<P>
Initial reports suggesting that the LatGSM consortium had won the tender for Latvia's second GSM mobile phone network are likely to prove unfounded. Confusion over the make-up of the consortium and failure to submit the necessary documentation in time threw their success into doubt in March, with the Baltel consortium likely to prove the beneficiary. Baltel is 51 per cent owned by the Latvian company Alina with LatCom Inc, also Latvian, and the American companies Western Wireless International Corporation and Metro Media International Telecommunications Inc holding the remaining shares.
<P>
From 1 April all payments to off-shore companies and their representatives have been subject to a 25 per cent tax in a move aimed to stop money laundering through off-shore companies.
<P>
The Bank of Latvia suspended the operations of the Daugavas, Tukama, Dinastija, Doma and AKO banks on 2 April after they failed to accumulate Ls1 million capital by 1 April.

<p>
<hr>
<center><img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="besummy1.html">Summary Menu</a></center>

