<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bclith.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>LITHUANIA</h3>

The government has guaranteed a US$10 million loan granted by the American Commodity Credit Corporation to assist Lithuanian agricultural needs. About US$5 million will be used to buy cotton for domestic textile plants, with the remainder used to purchase wheat for the production of fodder.
<P>
The monthly inflation rate fell to 2.4 per cent in February.
<P>
Following Lithuania's failure to settle a debt of US$36 million with Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, supplies were reduced from 12 million to 2.8 million cubic metres a day at the beginning of March.
<P>
The World Bank has approved a US$30 million soft loan to support agricultural development. The money will be distributed to farming companies with more than 50 per cent private capital and to small and medium sized rural businesses.
<P>
The Lithuanian Agricultural Bank is the largest commercial bank in the Baltics according to the Baltic Association of Commercial Banks, with assets of US$315.4 million at the end of 1995. The State Commercial Bank is the third largest bank in the region with assets of US$271.6 million.

<p>
<hr>
