<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcmoldov.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>MOLDOVA</h3>

The Privatisation Minister Ceslav Ciobanu has predicted that 1996 will see the sell off of major hotels, including the Moldova and Chisinau.
<P>
Moldovan GDP shrank by 3 per cent in 1995, a significant improvement on the 31.2 per cent fall in 1994. The government is predicting growth of 7.7 per cent for 1996.
<P>
Monthly inflation fell to 2.5 per cent in February, from 3.5 per cent in January.
<P>
According to the National Bank of Moldova the country's external debt grew by 55 per cent in 1995 to US$576 million. Of the total debt, US$435 million was due to state purchases of energy, grain imports and the promotion of exports. Hard currency reserves increased to US$256 million during 1995.
<P>
The privatisation of Moldova's tourism sector has been completed, with 165 hotels, restaurants and other facilities sold off. Although tourism increased by 130 per cent in 1995 on 1994 figures, the total revenue was still only L19 million, less than US$5 million.
<P>
An agency for the development of the private sector has finally been established in line with World Bank guidelines. Created by the Ministry of Finance it has already received a US$35 million loan for public sector development projects.
<P>
Moldovan industry continues to be in heavy debt to the state - over L100 million by the end of 1995. The largest debtors are:<br>
Tractor Factory (L13.5 million)<br>
Refrigerator Factory (L2.5 million)<br>
Alfa IC (L3.7 million)<br>
Moldtelecom (L2.5 million)<br>
Vitanta-Intravest (L1.5 million)<br>
Aroma (L1.5 million)<br>
MoldovaHydroMash (L1.3 million)<br>
<P>
By 1 January 1996 2,278 enterprises had been privatised, 2,231 for National Patrimonial Bonds and only 47 for cash. A total of 3.2 million Moldovans have taken part in the privatisation process. Of all privatised enterprises 17.3 per cent are industrial, 11.9 per cent agrarian, 12.8 per cent medical, 11.6 per cent transport and distribution and 45.4 per cent trade and service.
<P>
In an attempt to reduce Moldova's dependence on Russia an agreement has been signed with Iran for the supply of two million tonnes of crude oil over the next five years.
<P>
Moldtelecom and Intracom of Greece have signed a contract to build automatic telephone exchanges with a total of 14,000 lines. The project will cost US$5 million.
<P>
The success of the government's economic programme in Moldova has been recognised by the IMF which has agreed a US$200 million three year loan to assist further reforms.

<p>
<hr>
<center><img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="besummy1.html">Summary Menu</a></center>

