<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcpolan.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>POLAND</h3>

Queen Elizabeth II became the first reigning British monarch to visit Poland at the end of March. She emphasised the strong relations between Poland and the UK and expressed her hope that Poland would become a member of NATO and the EU in the near future.
<P>
General Motors Corp (GM) has chosen a greenfield site at the southern town of Gliwice to build a car-assembly plant. The factory, costing US$340 million, will eventually produce 150,000 cars per annum with the first car rolling off the production line in autumn 1998. Gliwice beat off competition from three other short-listed sites due to a well developed communication and transportation network and a skilled local workforce. The project will create 2,000 jobs. The decision to build the new plant was made after GM was beaten by the South Korean conglomerate Daewoo in a race to buy the Fabryka Samochodow Osobowych (FSO) car plant.
<P>
That'll be the Daewoo: Minutes after the announcement of GMs investment at Gliwice, Daewoo revealed they will invest US$80 million in production at Daewoo FSO Motors during 1996, not to mention increasing the capital of the joint venture by US$20 million to US$200. Daewoo plan to produce over 300,000 cars a year in Poland by the year 2000.
<P>
Daewoo's Honker: Daewoo have purchased the rights to produce the Tarpan Honker off-road vehicle, until recently used by the Polish military. About 2,000 Honkers will be produced by the end of the year, with production eventually increasing to 40,000 a year.
<P>
Fiat Auto SA have also announced a US$250 million investment in Poland as part of its `World Car' project, the manufacture of cars based on the same chassis and similar parts on five continents. Poland will be one of four or five manufacturing centres. Fiat has invested US$1 billion in Poland since 1992 and is facing increasing competition from GM and Daewoo as it defends its 50 per cent market share.<br>
General Motors Acceptance Corp, a subsidiary of General Motors Corp, has bought a Warsaw based bank to offer car financing to Opel dealers and their customers. The purchase of a controlling stake in Polbank has been funded by the Polish-American Enterprise Fund and a private equity fund.
<P>
From 1 July 1996 the Zaklady Samochodowe car manufacturer will begin producing the Mercedes `Vitos' model. The plant, which plans to produce 30,000 cars a year, will receive DM50 million from Mercedes.
<P>
In - Two Polski Bank Rozwoju (PBR) vice presidents are facing jail sentences and fines of US$2,000 following the alleged failure to let government auditors inspect state property. The state has a 62.4 per cent stake in PBR who refused to let central bank auditors inspect the bank's non-credit activities, including corporate deposit accounts records.
<P>
Out - Anyone contemplating illegal parking in Warsaw faces a new threat with the creation of a 20 strong squadron of female meter readers. Part of the capital's city guard auxiliary police unit, the force will levy fines of between US$2 and US$200.
<P>
Bank Przemyslowo-Handlowy (BPH) has finally received US$6 million in aid from the Fund for Privatisation of Polish Banks. The money had been withheld while contributors to the fund waited to see if the already privatised BPH would be consolidated with two state-owned banks.
<P>
Poland's banks had a more profitable 1995, reporting an aggregate profit of Zl 2.8 billion (US$1 billion) following a loss of Zl 230 million in 1994.
<P>
The Polish Government has pledged to spend US$9 billion over the next five years in an attempt to clean up the country's environmental problems. Poland's 700 plus environmental consultancies will also be hoping to clean up.
<P>
The Privatisation Ministry has invited bids for a 30 per cent stake in the food trader Rolimpex SA.<br>
Industrial production rose 9.6 per cent in 1995 to its highest level since 1989, with domestic consumption and export growth fuelling the increase. Although an 8 per cent lower figure than 1994, the increased production involved a 20 per cent increase in the value of products sold.
<P>
The Central Statistical Office estimated February's inflation at 1.5 per cent.
<P>
The minimum monthly wage has been set at Zl 350 for the second quarter of 1996.
<P>
The Gdansk Shipyard is facing bankruptcy after losing US$22.2 million last year. The government, which holds 60 per cent of the equity, has announced plans to privatise the yard, selling more than 10 per cent to strategic investors. The remaining 40 per cent is held by the employees.
<P>
With the prospect of 2,000 jobs being lost, the shipyard took on another worker on 2 April, an electrician named Lech Walesa. The former president claimed he was returning to his old job after the government ruled he was ineligible for a state pension. Perhaps he just wanted to get his hands back on the levers of power.
<P>
The Swedish development company Skanska Building AB has won a US$130 million contract to develop a site next to the Atrium Business Centre in Warsaw. The Atrium South development will include a 230-room four star hotel, 25,000 square metres of retail space and eventually a 16-floor office block.
<P>
The Warsaw Stock Exchange will begin operating a new data transmission system from August.
<P>
The government announced on 16 March that 9.13 million mass privatisation certificates had been issued since 22 November.
<P>
The privatisation of the Polish tobacco industry should be complete by October. The government has already sold a 33 per cent stake in each factory it owns, with a further 20 per cent due for sale in the large Augustow, Radom, Cracow and Poznan factories.
<P>
Gdansk municipal bonds will be issued by a consortium of Bank Gdansk, Bank Handlowy and Merrill Lynch as the city aims to raise Zl l90 million. The bonds will be distributed in six tranches over three years, with 30 per cent on sale outside Poland.
<P>
The purchase by the publishing conglomerate Infor Sp of the economic weekly Zycie Gospodarcze from Przyjaciolka Sp, a Swiss-owned women's magazine publisher, gives Infor a near monopoly on legal and business publications in Poland.
<P>
Foreign investment in Poland increased to US$6.8 billion in 1995 from US$4.3 billion in 1994. The USA was the largest investor at the end of the year with investments worth US$1.7 billion, followed by Germany (US$680 million), France (US$570 million), Italy (US$460 million), Holland (US$410 million) and the UK (US$370 million).
<P>
A loan of Ecu1 billion from the EU's PHARE programme has been granted to increase the competitiveness of Poland's industry and help the country prepare for integration into the EU.
<P>
The corporate tax rate will be cut by 8 per cent to 32 per cent by the year 2000 according to the government. In a staged reduction corporate tax will fall to 38 per cent from 40 per cent on 1 January 1997 and then by 2 per cent every year until it reaches 32 per cent in 2000.
<P>
The dominant position of the state owned Powszechny Zaklad Ubezpieczen (PZU) insurance company is being eroded by western insurance firms. Amplico Life (USA) has sold over 100,000 policies and Commercial Union (UK) over 250,000 causing PZU to lose 7 per cent of its 95 per cent market share in 1995.
<P>
Poland's agricultural trade gap was US$474 million in 1995, an increase of US$126 million on 1994.
<P>
A restructuring programme for the debt ridden coal industry has been developed by the Ministry of Industry. The plan involves reducing output from 140 million to 120 million tonnes a year to cut losses on exports, which are currently subsidised, and laying off 80,000 miners.
<P>
Figures released by the Ministry of Privatisation show that 3,465 enterprises have been privatised since 1990, however nearly 40 per cent of these were liquidated outright or transferred to another firm. Privatisation revenue in 1995 was US$660 million.
<P>
Texaco and Tenneco, the American oil and gas companies have been awarded licenses to explore for natural gas near the city of Lodz. The joint venture created by the companies, Wielkopolska Energia SA, will begin the first phase of exploration within the next few months at an initial cost of US$6 million.
<P>
Texaco has also announced plans to build 150 petrol stations across Poland over the next five years.
<P>
About Time: A Polish language version of Time Magazine is set for publication before the end of the year, with an initial print run of 100,000 eventually increasing to 250,000.

<p>
