<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcroman.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>ROMANIA</h3>

The first distance learning programme for professional training has been launched by the Romanian Banking Institute(RBI). The programme is supported by the UK Know How Fund and run in collaboration between the RBI and Attitudes, Skills & Knowledge Ltd of the UK. It is the first such project in Romania. The course has been structured with respect to the Romanian banking system and will train participants in economic and banking theory.
<P>
Revised figures issued by the Ministry of Trade showed a US$1.89 billion trade deficit in 1995, rather than US$1.5 billion as was originally thought. The government has set the ambitious target of limiting the 1996 trade deficit to US$1 billion through a 13 per cent increase in exports and maintaining imports at 1995 levels.
<P>
Industrial production increased by 2.7 per cent in February, a recovery from January when output fell 10.5 per cent, according to the National Statistics Board.
<P>
The 1996 budget, approved by parliament on 17 April, has a planned deficit equivalent to 3.45 per cent of GDP, down from 4.1 per cent in 1995. The budget is in line with the IMF approved reform programme.
<P>
Romania has emerged as a major player on the international grain market following 1995's wheat harvest which produced a surplus of one million tonnes. However, antiquated storage, distribution and export infrastructure are preventing Romania from taking full advantage of buoyant wheat prices. The government predicts a wheat harvest of six million tonnes in 1996.
<P>
Increased demand and insufficient energy stocks led RENEL (the State Electricity Authority) to cut off electricity supplies to non-paying customers - principally large state-owned enterprises, in February. Priority was given to domestic consumers and companies which had paid their bills.
<P>
The National Bank of Romania (NBR) stripped all but four of Romania's banks of their foreign exchange dealership licences at the end of March.<br>
The severe measures were imposed following the alleged failure of the banks to comply with strict new legislation introduced at the beginning of March, which fixed daily ceilings on the amount of foreign currency commercial banks could hold. The four lucky banks to keep their licences were the Banca Comerciala Romana, Banca Romana pentru Dezvoltare, Banca Romana de Comert Exterior (all state-owned banks) and Banca Ion Tiriac, a private bank. Eight foreign banks lost their licences including ING, ABN Amro NV, Citibank and Societe Generale.<br>
The four dealer banks will operate as market-makers with non-licenced banks forced to operate as brokers, unable to hold overnight positions of over US$10,000. The move has been condemed as a politically motivated method of underpinning the weak looking leu. Private bankers have put the exchange rate at 3,100 per US$1 rather then the artificially strong 2,850 held by state banks.
The move has been strongly condemned as a backwards step in Romania's economic reform programme, although the NBR claims it it a positive move in raising standards without harming the development of a western style market. The central bank maintains that banks which prove themselves able and willing to work responsibly will soon be readmitted as dealers.
<P>
Daewoo Motors have completed the construction of the Rodae Automobile SA plant in Craiova. The plant has an annual capacity of 100,000 cars, which will be increased to 200,000 by 1998. Rodae, a joint venture between Daewoo and Automobile Craiove, is the largest overseas car plant built by Korean car manufacturers. Daewoo plans to have a 30 per cent share of the eastern European car market by 2000.
<P>
The start up of the 700 MW Cernovada nuclear power station has been postponed for six months. Reactor and safety tests are due to start in April or May.
<P>
South African Breweries Ltd (SAB), the fifth largest brewer in the world, is set to invest US$20 million in the Vultural beer factory. SAB is planning to acquire 70 per cent of the stock and invest US$10 million in upgrading and modernising the brewery. Vultural has an annual production of 500,000 hectolitres of beer and 11,000 tonnes of malt with a combined value of US$11 million.
<P>
Romania's first ever country rating by Standard & Poor's Corp and IBCA Ltd predict that the country will become the next eastern European destination for international investors. Irreversible reforms and low wages will attract investors as wages in the Czech Republic, Poland and Hungary reach western levels. Romania's foreign currency debt has been assigned a BB rating. Low inflation (25 per cent in 1995), unemployment (8.7 per cent) and external debt and a 6 per cent increase in GDP in 1995 are making the region's second largest market increasingly attractive to foreign investors.
<P>
A US$280 million financial and enterprise sector adjustment loan has been approved by the World Bank. A separate loan of US$120 million has also been granted to assist in the rehabilitation of Romanian railways.

<p>
