<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcruss.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>RUSSIA</h3>

In a historic meeting at the Kremlin Boris Yeltsin met with the Chechen leader Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev on 27 May. A ceasefire signed by the two parties is due to come into effect at midnight on 31 May, two weeks before the Russian presidential elections. The death of Dzhokhar Dudayev on 22 April in a Russian attack had thrown the possibility of a peaceful solution into doubt, with inter-factional fighting among the Chechen warlords expected. However Yandarbiyev, who had previously vowed to keep on fighting until every Russian soldier had left Chechnia, has succeeded in maintaining unity among the rebel groups.<br>
The ceasefire, as long as it is implemented on the ground, should give Yeltsin a timely boost as he runs for re-election on 16 June. From the Chechen perspective a Yeltsin victory would be preferable to one for the communist Gennady Zyuganov whose hardline attitude would leave little room for negotiation. Whether the agreement was merely a pre-election ploy by both sides will only become clear after the June election. Chechnia's future status, over which the 17 month conflict has been fought killing 30,000, was not discussed in the Kremlin talks.
<P>
Russia has upset the EU after imposing a minimum price of US$8.20 for a litre of vodka imported from the EU, compared to only US$3.80 from the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS). The Commission claims these measures are incompatible with the Interim Trade Agreement which came into force on 1 February, under which improved access to Russian markets for particular products including alcohol and cars was agreed.
<P>
The amount of foreign capital in the Russian oil company Chernogorneft is set to increase from the present 20 per cent following the registration of an American Depository Receipt (ADR) programme with the United States Securities and Exchange Commission in a move to attract long-term foreign investment. The company announced profits of US$31 million on gross sales of US$465 million in 1995.
<P>
ING Barings is planning to more than double the number of companies it offers through its Russian depository receipts by the end of 1996. Regional and second-tier manufacturing companies will be the main focus.
<P>
The troubled south Caucasus region of Russia received some sweet news with the announcement that Queen Margaret College of Edinburgh in Scotland will assist Ingushetia state (next door to Chechnya) in establishing a modern food production facility. The unlikely coupling will manufacture chocolate, biscuits and confectionary.
<P>
Taylor Woodrow International has won a US$15.4 million contract to modernise a tobacco factory for BAT in Saratov.
<P>
Good news and bad news: Monthly inflation fell to a mere 2.8 per cent in February, the lowest level since 1991 according to Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. However the improvement is likely to be shortlived as LUKoil and Yukos, Russia's largest oil companies, have announced that they will be increasing prices by up to 25 per cent.
<P>
Deutsche Telekom has bought a 40 per cent stake in Russkaya Telefonna Kompaniya, a Russian GSM mobile phone operator. The deal is part of the group's expansion by DeTeMobil, the mobile phone subsidiary, in eastern Europe. By 2000 the new venture expects to have 250,000 clients. DeTeMobil also has a 39 per cent stake in Mobile Telesysteme, a mobile phone operator in Moscow.
<P>
A joint venture between Royal Dutch/Shell and the Russian oil company Evikhon has been formed to develop and operate oil fields in western Siberia. Recovery of the estimated 139 million tonnes of crude oil are due to begin in 1998 and reach six million tonnes a year by 2003.
<P>
The Krasnoyarsk aluminium smelter is setting up a joint venture with the Swiss based Glencore trading group. The new operation, Krazpa Metal will give the second largest aluminium smelter in the world direct access to western markets.
<P>
Russian coal companies extracted 68.8 million tonnes of coal in the first quarter of 1996, a 0.3 million tonnes increase on the same period last year, although still short of official expectations.
<P>
The minimum pension was raised by 10 per cent on 17 April to R69,575 (US$14) a month. The increase was approved following a raise in compensation payments that pensioners receive along with their pensions. Those on an average pension will receive R350,000.
<P>
The fuel and energy sector owed the 1995 state budget R26 trillion (US$5.7 billion) principally due to non-payments of R105 trillion, according to Fuel and Energy Deputy Minister Anatoli Kozyrev. An estimated 24 per cent of enterprises in the sector were run with losses totalling over R2 trillion.
<P>
Collapsed: A landmark deal between the Russian central bank and Merrill Lynch, the US investment bank, to issue US$500 million of government bonds has collapsed. The deal, which would have attracted international investors into the Russian Treasury-bill market, was an attempt by the government to raise desperately needed revenue.
<P>
Russia reached an agreement with the Paris Club of sovereign creditors on 19 April to reschedule over US$40 billion of the former Soviet debt. Following on from a provisional agreement with the London Club of commercial creditors last November and the signing of a three year US$10.1 billion loan with the IMF, Russian finances are looking stronger than they have for several years. The Paris Club deal gives Russia a six year grace period on the principal repayments, with phased repayments of the remaining debt over 25 years. Annual interest payments will continue and are estimated at US$2 billion for this year. However the agreement hinges on Russian economic reform and the accord with the IMF.

<p>
