<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbserb.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>SERBIA & MONTENEGRO*<br>
*Federal Republic of Yugoslavia</h3>

Industrial output increased by 8 per cent in the first two months of 1996 compared to the same period last year according to the Federal Statistics Office.
<P>
Monthly inflation in March accelerated to 7.2 per cent according to the Federal Statistics Office, an increase from 4.7 per cent in February.
<P>
Economic growth of 20 per cent in 1996 has been predicted by the government, however economists at the Economic Institute seem to have a better grasp on reality, claiming that growth of 8 per cent would be an achievement.
<P>
In a US$1 billion agreement reached in March China will supply Serbia with one million barrels of crude oil a month from April. The deal with Sinochem, the Chinese state oil company is the biggest foreign trade agreement Serbia has reached since UN sanctions were lifted last November.
<P>
Pirot-based Tiger, a manufacturer of rubber products, has agreed a deal to export one million car tyres to western Europe in 1996. Michelin will receive 650,000 and the London based joint venture Tiger Europe 350,000.
<P>
The Greek state telecommunications company OTE and PTT of the rump Yugoslavia have agreed to build a fibre-optic cable linking the island of Corfu with the town of Bar and also a cable between Bar and Belgrade. The construction is due for completion in April 1997 and is costing between US$15 and US$20 million.


<p>
