<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcslovak.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>SLOVAKIA<br></h3>

Total foreign investment in Slovak companies by the end of 1995 was US$732.9 million, a 32.3 per cent increase on the December 1994 figure. Austria was the largest foreign investor, followed by Germany, the Czech Republic, the USA and the UK.
<P>
Annual inflation fell to 6.2 per cent in February, down from 6.4 per cent in January.
<P>
The Tatramat-Whirlpool joint venture increased turnover by 77 per cent, doubled exports and invested a total of Skc129 million in 1995.
<P>
The Central Europe Trust will manage a US$50 million fund geared to restructuring privatised enterprises in Slovakia. The London based company will take minority stakes in mid-sized companies with the view to floating shares on the Bratislava Stock Exchange or selling its stake to strategic investors. The project is being jointly funded by the EU and the EBRD.
<P>
The agricultural sector will receive a government subsidy of Skc7.2 billion in 1996.
<P>
Slovak National Telecommuni- cations have announced a Skc45 billion project to upgrade the country's telecommunications network over the next five years.
<P>
A modernisation programme for the Slovakian railways has been adopted by the government. Three lines will be upgraded, the Kuty-Bratislava-Sturovo line linking Germany and the Balkans, the Bratislava-Kosice line via Zilina, linking Austria and Ukraine, and the Zilina-Cadca-Skalite line going north to Poland. The project will cost between Skc25.5 to Skc35.5 billion and be completed by 2002.
<P>
Slovakia will receive Ecu20 million from the EU PHARE programme to finance 12 projects aimed at boosting border co-operation between eastern European countries.
<P>
The VSZ steel manufacturer is set to sign a US$125 million syndicated loan with 18 international banks led by ING Barings London. One quarter of the loan will be used to restructure existing loans with the remainder used for operational and investment needs.


<p>
