<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcsloven.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>SLOVENIA<br></h3>

Nova Ljubjanska banka became the first bank in Slovenia to launch on-line banking services in March. Customers will be able to order cheque books and apply for overdrafts in a development the bank describes as a `turning point' for the Slovenian banking sector. The bank's Internet site can be found at http://www.n-lb.si.
<P>
The Ljubljana international airport will be privatised in 1996, with the state retaining a 55.6 per cent stake. The remainder will be divided between an internal buy out, investment funds and a public sale for cash or privatisation certificates.
<P>
Foreign exchange income from tourism increased to US$1.16 billion in 1995, a 24 per cent increase on 1994.
<P>
The auction of shares in 226 enterprises by the Slovenian Development Fund took place in April. The starting price for the shares was US$188 million. The Development Fund has a 20 per cent stake in all companies which have taken part in the mass privatisation process. The Compensation and Pension Fund holds 20 per cent and 60 per cent were sold directly to employees and the public.


<p>
