<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bcukr.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>UKRAINE<br></h3>

On 28 May President Kuchma sacked Prime Minister Evhan Marchuk following accusations by the president that he was pursuing his own political career rather than managing the economy. Ukraine's new Prime Minister is Pavlo Lazarenko, a close ally of President Kuchma and a former collective farm manager. Mr Lazarenko, whose reformist creditentials are limited, was promoted from first deputy prime minister.
<P>
The Ukrainian Enterprise Corporation, a Toronto direct investment fund, was launched in February. The fund aims to raise US$36.5 million from institutional investors and the Toronto Stock Exchange. The money will be used to finance privatised and start-up companies in the food processing and energy sectors.
<P>
Following a sequence of banking crises in the Baltic states Ukraine has raised the minimum starting capital requirements to Ecu100,000 for local banks, increasing to Ecu1 million by 1998.
<P>
The Chernobyl nuclear plant has received Ecu2 million from the European Commission to support the continued monitoring and treatment of victims following the 1986 disaster.
<P>
The US Export-Import Bank has approved US$171.3 million in credit guarantees. The money will be used to buy agricultural equipment.
<P>
Off: Gas supplies have been cut to 86 large factories with unpaid bills. Total arrears stand at about US$840 million. This move follows the suspension of electricity supplies to 7,000 enterprises with outstanding bills, estimated at US$980 million.
<P>
On: The IMF has agreed to resume its programme of stand-by loans to Ukraine. The change of heart follows the adoption of a 1996 budget which set a maximum deficit of 6.2 per cent of GDP. By the end of the year nine tranches of the loan, worth US$100 million each, will have been distributed at monthly intervals.
<P>
Out: The coal miners strike in Donetsk which began at the beginning of April involved 16 mines and 2,000 miners by the middle of the month. The main cause of the strike is unpaid wages - some workers have not been paid since last September.


<p>
