<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1996.</i></font><br>
</center>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bctravel.html">Select Winter 1995</a></center>

<h3>TRAVEL BRIEF</h3>
The Polish national airline LOT has been awarded the title of Best Eastern European Business Airline by the Business Travel World magazine.
<P>
The Czech national carrier CSA has implemented a non-smoking policy on trans-Atlantic and European flights. The airline is also opening a city terminal in Prague near the Renaissance hotel.
<P>
CSA will be the launch airline for a new passenger aircraft built by the French-Italian consortium Avions de Transport Regional. The ATR 42-400 turboprop carries between 46 and 50 passengers and will increase performance, lower operating costs and offer greater comfort, according to the manufacturers.
<P>
From 1 April Canadians and Czechs can visit each others' countries without visas. The Czech Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec has also expressed hopes that the USA will follow Canada's example in granting visa free travel.
<P>
Air Baltic is replacing its Boeing 727s on the Riga-London Gatwick route with Avro RJ70s. The airline is planning services to Moscow and Kiev from Riga.
<P>
A three times a week on-board courier service between London and the Azerbaijan capital Baku has begun, operated by Inter-Logistic Ltd in conjunction with British Airways.
<P>
All airfares out of Budapest increased by between 3 and 10 per cent from 1 April following a recent decision by the International Air Transportation Association.
<P>
Dac Air, the private Romanian airline, will buy 24 aircraft from the Canadian manufacturer Bombardier over the next three years in a contract worth US$425 million.
<P>
The prospect of a Slovak national airline being set up grew stronger in February when the government agreed to accept four Yak 42s and one Tu-154 aircraft from Russia in a `jets for debts' agreement. The new airline, provisionally called the Slovak Air Transport System (SATS), would connect seven Slovak cities to all the major European capitals and carry half a million passengers a year.
<P>
Tatra Air of Slovakia is beginning flights to Zurich from the Stafanik airport in Bratislava.
<P>
In a fiercely contested bid CSA has chosen Boeing to supply 10 new passenger aircraft rather than the European Airbus Industries. The 737-500 airplanes have a capacity of between 120 and 150 passengers and cost between US$20 and US$35 million each.
<P>
Austrian Airlines began flights from Vienna to Skopje (Macedonia) and Kosice (Slovakia) in April and is planning to fly to Dnepropetrovsk in the Ukraine within the next few months.


<p>
