<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbalban.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>ALBANIA</h3>

Out - The Albanian Appeals court ordered the release of former president Ramiz Alia. In July 1994 Alia had been sentenced to a nine-year prison term. The release was widely seen as related to Albania's admission to the Council of Europe at the end of June.
<p>
In - Former Central Bank governor Ilir Holt has been sentenced to six years in jail for abuse of office in a US$1.6 million fraud scandal. Also jailed were three former directors of the National Commercial Bank. The fraud was based, somewhat improbably, on a payment of US$1.6 million for negotiations to resolve Albania's foreign debt. (See over).
Albania finally signed a technical agreement in late July to resolve the problems surrounding its US$501 million foreign debt. The deal effectively reduces Albania's total debt to US$100 million due to be repaid by the end of August 1995. This represents a `20 cents in the dollar' deal, probably the best terms secured by any of the region's debtor nations.
<p>
July saw the `soft' opening of the four star Europa Hotel in Tirana. The hotel is operated by the Austrian Rogner group, who also operate Prague's Don Giovanni hotel and formerly managed Warsaw's Sobieski hotel. Inter-Continental Hotel Corporation has announced plans to open a 262 room hotel in Tirana, which will be the city's first 5-star property. The hotel is to be constructed by the Kuwaiti Kaharafi Group.
<p>
Premier Oil of the UK has embarked on a renovation programme of the extraction equipment in the Kucova, Marinza and Amonika regions. Oil production in Albania fell by over 30,000 tonnes from 1993 to 1994, causing a sharp rise in oil related products.
<p>
Albania ranks sixth in terms of foreign capital invested per capita in the region according to IMF figures. Top of the list is Hungary with US$514 per capita, followed by the Czech Republic at US$200 per capita. The figure for Albania is US$21.00 per capital. Foreign investments in Albania make up 8.6 per cent of GDP, second only to Hungary (15 per cent of GDP).
Albania's Central Bank has cut its 12 month deposit rates from 14.5 per cent to 13.5 per cent. The year-on-year inflation figure for the end of June dropped to 2.1 per cent from 5.72 per cent in May.
<p>
Consumer goods imports in 1994 were up 12.5 per cent over 1993. Principal exporters to Albania were Italy (34.11 per cent), Greece (27.68), Bulgaria (8.75), Turkey (6.75), Macedonia (2.63). 
<p>
Albania - come bank with me
In June the bank of Albania approved new regulations for the establishment of private banks in Albania. The move has met with a favourable response from the international financial community. Albania could do with a few new banks: at present there are only six banks in the country - the National Commercial Bank, Italo-Shqiptare Bank (Italo-Albania Bank) and the Arab Albanian Islamic Bank are joint venture banks, with the National Commercial Bank holding 40 per cent in each. Dardania Bank, a Kosovan-owned bank, is the only private bank operating in Albania at present.
The initial capitalisation level for new, private foreign banks in Albania is set at US$2,000,000, one of the lowest bank captialisation levels in Europe. Foreign banks are also able to repatriate bank profits.
Planned revisions to the existing Law for the Banking System of Albania will bring it more into line with Albania's fast changing business environment. It's all very new to Albania's banking authorities, but they are well advised by consultants from the USA and the ubiquitous Irish. The policy is to make sure that the laws are, in practice, enforceable, and do not give rise to indecision on the part of banks in granting credit. The Central Bank maintains that it is receiving a growing number of enquiries, but to date no-one has signed on the dotted line.
<p>
