<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbarmen.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>ARMENIA</h3>
To no-one's surprise, the ruling All Armenian National Movement party won the country's 6 July elections. Western observers complained that the polls had been heavily biased in favour of the government and the ruling party, with the opposition Dashnak party banned for the duration of the election period. (See Armenian Elections, Media Brief, page 55).
<p>
Armenia's Metsamor nuclear power station, closed following the 1988 Spitak earthquake, was due to be reopened in September, boosting Armenia's electricity supplies by 40 per cent. Electricity supplies should be restored to between eight and 10 hours per day.<br>
Armenia's first foreign owned bank, the Midland Armenia has been licensed. A joint venture between UK-based Midland Bank Plc and Liechtenstein's Wing establishment, the new bank has an authorised capital of US$10 million. Four foreign banks - Bank Melli Iran, the Menatep and Russki Banks (Russia) and Inko Bank of the Ukraine have branches in Armenia, but Midland Armenia will be the first foreign owned local bank.
<p>
President Levon Ter-Petrosyan in a post election cabinet shuffle, has appointed new ministers for the Economics (Andranik Andreasyan) and Information (Grach Tarmazyan) portfolios. The new constitution, adopted after the June elections, abolished the institution of Minister of State. Grant Bagratyan continues as Prime Minister, Vagan Papazyan as Foreign Minister.
<p>

<hr>
