<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbazerb.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>

<h3>AZERBAIJAN</h3>

Azerbaijan's grain harvest for 1995 is expected to be up on 1994, at 1.1 million tonnes according to Azeri news agency Assa-Irada.
<p>
Germany and Azerbaijan have signed a new air agreement providing for a three times a week winter schedule, increasing to four weekly in the Spring of 1996.  Lufthansa already operates a twice weekly service from Frankfurt to Baku, and plans to start a weekly cargo service in 1996.
<p>
The State Oil Company of the Azerbaijani Republic (SOCAR) is ceding a 25 per cent stake in a Caspian sea offshore development to Elf of France. SOCAR will retain a 25 per cent stake, the balance of 50 per cent being held by US company Chevron.
<p>
Russia's LUKoil has purchased 500,000 tonnes of refined oil products from state oil company SOCAR at a price of US$131 per tonne. The deal followed a reduction in imports of Azeri exports of diesel fuel and kerosene to Iran. Talks with Iran on restoring deliveries to their original level broke up after Iranian demands for a 25-30 per cent reduction on the price of diesel fuel. Discussions are also under way with Turkey for the supply of oil from the Chirag 1 field.
<p>
The international oil consortium reached a compromise on the routing of Azeri oil. The initial output will be routed both through Russia's pipelines and through Georgia to the Black Sea.
BELARUS
President Alexander Lukashenko has approved a programme to privatise some 600 large and medium-sized businesses by the end of 1995. Included in the programme are clothing, textile and furniture manufacturers and food processing industries.

GDP for the period January-August 1995 fell by an estimated 12 per cent over the same period for the preceding year.<br>
Responding to pressure from the IMF, the Belarussian government has revised its 1995 budget, projecting a deficit of 2.9 per cent of GDP, down 0.3 per cent from the original figure of 3.2 per cent. Belarus had originally been set a 1 July deadline by the IMF to meet its conditions for a US$300 million standby loan. The loan, approved in September, is to be used for balance of payments support and will be drawn down in five equal instalments.
<p>
Rolling heads department: Central Bank Chairman Stanislav Bogdankevich a known opponent of government plans for closer links with Russia, has been sacked by President Lukashenko. Former Deputy Chairman Nikolai Kuzmich is to take over as the bank's acting head.
<p>
The government has announced the proposed sale of over 1,000 collective enterprises during the latter part of 1995. Most are in the agricultural sector and employ over 35,000. Total value of the enterprises up for sale is US$430 million.
<p>
The US Trade and Development Agency is to grant US$750,000 towards the cost of a feasibility study for the establishment in Minsk of a diesel engine manufacturing plant. The balance of the cost - US$897,000 - is to be provided by potential partners in the venture - Navstar Detroit Diesel and Lam Technicon.

The Soros Foundation will no longer provide aid to Belarus as the government refuses to exempt it from taxes and import duties. The foundation had budgeted donations of US$5 million for Belarus in 1995.
<p>
