<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbczech.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>CZECH REPUBLIC</h3>

Direct foreign investments made in the Czech Republic since 1990 now total US$3.46 billion according to investment promotion agency Czechinvest.
<p>
A consortium of PTT Telecom Netherlands, Swiss Telecom and AT&T of the US was awarded a 27 per cent stake in the Czech SPT Telecom telephone company. The consortium entered its bid of US$1.45 billion under the name of Telsource. 
<p>
Health Minister Ludek Rubas was dismissed in October by Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus for `failing to communicate with the medical profession'. He is replaced by Transport Minister Jan Strasky. 

Ceskoslovenska Obchodni banka a.s (CSOB) has agreed a US$75 million, three year revolving credit with a group of European, Asian and American banks. The loan is at 0.25 per cent above the London interbank LIBOR rate. CSOB is also in discussions with four American, European and Japanese banks for a US$150 million loan at 0.3 per cent over LIBOR. <br>Both loans are to finance Czech exports. The CSOB also disposed of a 70 per cent share of its holding in Cedok the formerly state-owned travel agency, for Kc1 per share (US$0.04). Cedok shares are quoted on the market at Kc213. The shares were sold to Ceska Inkasni Spolecnost as part of a debt settlement between the two organisations.
<p>
The UK's Midland Bank part of the HSBC banking group, is reported to be applying for a licence to open a branch in Prague.
<p>
Revenues from tourism for the first half of 1995 reached US$1.15 billion, an increase of over 15 per cent over the same period for 1994.
<p>
UK based British Midland now operates a London Prague service, providing competition to BA and CSA on the route.
<p>
Volkswagen subsidiary Skoda Automobilova a.s. reported a 13 per cent sales increase for the first half of 1995, with 105,344 units sold. Total production in 1994 was 173,586 units, with 210,000 targeted for 1995.
<p>
Top income tax rates have been reduced from 43 per cent to 40 per cent with a higher threshold introduced. Corporate taxes have also been reduced by 2 per cent to 39 per cent.
<p>
The annual inflation rate at the end of May stood at 10.2 per cent according to Czech National Bank figures. May inflation was a creditable 0.4 per cent, less than half April's figure of 1 per cent. Initial reports suggested that the June figure had jumped back up to 1 per cent.
<p>
Unemployment also continued its steady downward trend in May, dropping from April's 2.9 per cent to 2.8 per cent, with 143,200 registered unemployed.
<p>
A survey of bankrupt enterprises carried out in May showed a 100 per cent annual increase in the number of bankruptcies. Since bankruptcy proceedings started in October 1992, up to the end of April 1995, 3,986 bankruptcy proceedings had been filed and 502 bankruptcies declared. Financial institutions form the largest group of creditors and petitioners.
<p>
In the first quarter of 1995, 17.8 million foreign visitors arrived in the Czech Republic, an increase of 8.4 per cent compared to 1994. Tourist revenues for the period were US$390 million.
<p>
Since September 1995 the Prague Stock Exchange (PSE) has divided its trading activities into three markets - primary, secondary and open. Issuers now have to apply to enter the primary and secondary markets. The criteria for issue acceptance on the primary market will demand that the publicly tradeable proportion of the issue accounts for at least 20 per cent of the entire issue, that basic assets total at least 15 per cent of the whole issue and that economic information be provided on at least a quarterly basis. 
<p>
Prague's Atrium Hotel is now the Hilton. The international hotel group took over the hotel's management on 1 July 1995. The new general manager is David Durand.
<p>
French leave - again! State owned French companies seem set on maintaining their record of non-participation in Czech privatisations. French petroleum company Total withdrew from the International Oil Companies consortium. The other members Agip, Conoco and Shell confirmed their continued interest in purchasing, for US$200 million, 49 per cent of two Czech refineries Chemopetrol Litvinov and Kaucuk Kralupy. The majority share will continue to be held by the refineries themselves through their Unipetrol holding company. 
<p>
Representatives of the Czech Republic and the European Union (EU) signed the first multi-annual PHARE programme in Prague in early July. The programme will provide Ecu300 million for the period 1995-1999 to support the convergence of Czech laws with those of the EU. The funding will also be used to improve transport links and cross-border co-operation.
<p>
In its Macroeconomic Indicators Forecast the Investicni a Postovni Banka foresees a GDP growth rate of 3.9 per cent in 1996 and 4.5 per cent in 1997, with inflation at 8.3 per cent and 6.6 per cent respectively.
<p>
UK built Rover cars were launched on to the Czech market at Autosalon 95 the republic's major car show. Czech distributors ITec will open its first showroom in Prague, expanding to 10 showrooms throughout the country by the end of 1996.
<p>
The Czech Republic's trade deficit was 38.8 billion crowns (US$1.4 billion) for the five month period ending in May 1995, a sharp contrast to the surplus of 13 billion crowns (US$500 million) recorded for the same period in 1994.
<p>
Czech Bank Investicni s Postova has arranged a US$150 million loan with a bank syndicate headed up by the Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, at a rate 25 points above the London interbank rate.
<p>
Thomson Bankwatch-BREE has raised the rating of Komercni banka from BBB/A1 to BBB+/A1.
<p>
In the first quarter of 1995 the Czech economy grew by 3.9 per cent compared to the same period in 1994 according to figures supplied by the Czech Statistical Office. Real growth for all of 1994 was 2.4 per cent. In 1993 the economy contracted by 0.9 per cent.
<p>
Taiwan is planning to open a trade representative office in Prague before the end of 1995.
<p>

