<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbhung.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<p>
<h3>HUNGARY</h3>
In mid-September Hungary and the International Monetary Fund  (IMF) ended a round of talks without reaching agreement on new funding. Hungarian hopes were pinned on a US$300 million standby credit facility. Instead of agreeing to the loan the IMF warned that Hungary's indebtedness was increasing and that the government needed to do more to control its budget deficit, which had widened to a cumulative Ft206.2 billion by the end of July 1995. The government target for the end-year cumulative deficit is Ft156 billion.
<p>
Ministry of Agriculture officials are forecasting a US$1.5 billion surplus in agricultural trade for 1995. At the end of July the government approved the draw-down of a further US$55 million loan from the EBRD for the development of the agricultural sector. The 1995 budget originally allocated Ft35 billion to agricultural export subsidies. This figure was later augmented by an additional Ft1.4 billion. 
<p>
An impending strike by 55,000 electricity sector workers was called off in July. An innovative deal was struck whereby 5 per cent of revenues collected by privatising the MVM company would be set aside for retraining programmes for laid off workers. Electricity prices were due to be increased by 8 per cent on 1 September 1995, with a further increase of 18 per cent on 1 March 1996. Gas prices will also go up by 8 and 25 per cent on the same dates.
<p>
Hungary's Constitutional Court has ruled that some of Finance Minister Bokros' austerity measures are unconstitutional. Apart from yet more embarrassment for the hard pressed Horn administration (see below), the court's decision means the government has to find an additional Ft35 billion to cover a budget that is already starting to look optimistic. The austerity package was designed to reduce the budget deficit by Ft170 billion in total. Revised Ministry of Finance forecasts put the current account deficit at around 6 per cent, or US$3.2 billion, well up on the original forecast of US$2.5 billion but down on 1994's 8.5 per cent deficit. The increase in the deficit was attributed, by Finance Minister Bokros, to the weakening of the dollar. The Horn government appears to be targeting income tax as its immediate priority for increasing overall tax revenues. An already unhappy electorate are unlikely to welcome the proposed abolition of the zero tax rate for incomes up to Ft110,000. Equally unwelcome are proposed amendments in Hungary's record-breaking social security payments. At present, employers' contributions are 44 per cent of gross salary, employees' 14 per cent. Long term plans are to alter these to 30 and 14 per cent respectively.
<p>
Rolling heads: Minister of Trade and Industry Laszlo Pal was dismissed in July by Prime Minister Horn. The dismissal followed differences of opinion over the sale of electricity utilities to foreign investors. Mr Pal was replaced by his deputy, Imre Dunai. Mr Dunai immediately struck an upbeat note when addressing a meeting of the Hungarian Chambers of Commerce, claiming that capital investment had increased by 10 per cent in the first half of 1995, and that industrial production had increased by 9 per cent in the same period. (Central Statistical Office figures suggested a rise in industrial production of 7.4 per cent). Industrial exports were estimated to have risen by 30 per cent, those of machinery by 40 per cent. Plans have been announced by APV Rt, the Hungarian privatisation and holding company,  to sell a further 73 companies by the end of 1995. Companies for sale will include a hotel, bakeries, printing companies, building contractors and a financial training institute.
<p>
More rolling heads: Labour Minister Magda Kovacs Kosa tendered her resignation in October, agreeing to stay in the post until 30 November. Kosa resigned following a cabinet decision to extend the period of sick leave to be paid by an employer from 10 to 25 days.
<p>
Confusion still surrounds the privatisation plans for telecommunications giant MATAV. Press reports have suggested that the APV Rt privatisation agency has agreed to allow the US German MagyarCom consortium to increase its shareholding from the current 30.29 per cent to over 50 per cent. 
<p>
In the first four months of 1995, Hungary's imports grew at a staggering 18 per cent, to reach US$4,797 million dollars. Exports for the same period grew at a more modest 11 per cent, reaching US$3,252 million dollars, and leaving a trade gap of US$1,545 million. Exports to developed countries grew to over 71 per cent, of which 65 per cent was with EU countries, notably Germany. Figures for May showed some signs of improvement as the monthly current account deficit was cut from April's US$358 million to US$189 million.
<p>
Privatisation Minister Tamas Suchman has ruled out the possibility of foreign firms being able to purchase majority stakes in Hungarian energy utility MOL. The government plans to sell 50 per cent of the company through a public tender, 25 per cent is to be sold to the company's employees with 25 per cent being retained by the state. Newly appointed Industry and Trade Minister Imre Dunai optimistically forecast foreign investments of US$1 billion in the energy sector by the end of 1995. 
<p>
Hungary's largest bank, the Orszagos Takarekpenztar es Kereskedelmi Bank (OTP) has sold a 20 per cent equity stake through an issue of 5.6 million Global Depositary Receipts (GDR), each representing one ordinary share at a price of US$9.50 per GDR. The issue, which was managed by Schroders the UK merchant bank, together with Creditanstalt Securities Budapest of Austria, was only the second large privatisation to take place since Mr Horn's government took office in 1994. To the government's relief, the offer was over-subscribed, raising an estimated US$88.9 million, the country's largest capital transaction to date.
ING Bank of the Netherlands and the US based General Electric Capital Corporation have emerged as front runners in the bidding to buy the Budapest Bank. To date, only two banks, the Foreign Trade bank and the OTP Bank have been partially privatised.
<p>
The sale of a 28 per cent stake in Hungarian pharmaceutical company EGIS took place in August, the largest single transaction to date on the Budapest Stock Exchange. The shares were purchased by the UK's Natwest Securities. Reportedly, Natwest paid Ft2,560 each for 2.18 million shares, selling 20 per cent of its holding within 24 hours at a premium per share of Ft65. The Hungarian government also plans to sell a 19.5 per cent share in the country's largest pharmaceutical company Richter Gideon Rt. The government's share of the US$130.5 million company currently stands at 62.3 per cent following earlier disposals. 
<p>
British power company POWERGEN bought the Csepel Electricity Company for a reported US$13 million. 
<p>
Central Statistical Office figures show that 2,466 businesses with foreign participation opened in Hungary in 1994.
<p>
Revenues from privatisation for the first half of 1995 added up to Ft27 billion, of which Ft16 billion was in cash. Some Ft2.4 billion of the cash element represented foreign investments.
<p>
UK property consultants Healey and Baker have ranked Budapest sixth in the top 10 league of European industrial property growth. Healey and Baker's quarterly European Property Performance Index indicates that industrial rents have increased by 8.3 per cent in the past year.
<p>
Gyor based Graboplast is to receive an equity injection from the European Bank of Reconstruction and Development (EBRD). The EBRD has purchased 300,000 shares, corresponding to 9.2 per cent of the company's equity.
<p>
Agrobank, the troubled commercial bank which lost its senior management in June (see Business Europa issue 12), is to merge with Mezobank. The managing director of the merged banks is Istvan Bakos.
<p>
UK retailer Marks and Spencer is to open a new store on Budapest's Vaci ut. The M & S stores in Budapest are operated on a seven-year franchise basis by S-Modell Trading Rt a subsidiary of Skala-Coop Rt. The new shop will concentrate on women's apparel and lingerie. 
<p>
Insurance company Gloria Biztosito has sold the 51 per cent of its shares held by Il mare Assicurazioni SpA and Hungarian Mezobank to Swiss Life.
<p>
UK supermarket group TESCO has purchased a 28,000 square metre site on Budapest's Pesti ut in the 17th district. The site will be used for the construction of a 4,000 square metre supermarket site, the company's first in Budapest. 
<p>
The OECD on Hungary
The latest Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) survey on Hungary, published mid-September, concludes on a guarded, but somewhat optimistic note concerning the future. The current government has `shown its political determination to come to grips finally with the key macroeconomic imbalances' with its March 1995 policy measures, the report states in its final paragraph. `If the 1995 budget is held on course . . . and reinforced by further consolidation over the medium term, the Hungarian economy should once again justify the optimism in which it was previously held.' <br>This despite the authors citing numerous instances in the recent past when various stringent policies have been introduced at or beyond the 11th hour, only to be quietly eased after a public furore, thus much diluting their effect.<br>Indeed the essential message of this very readable 195 page report, which succinctly analyses the period from 1993 to mid-1995, is a story of seemingly strong measures applied too late in the day which are then regularly side-stepped by the worst offenders, who too often have the political clout to gain exceptional treatment. <br>This pattern applies to almost every aspect of economic policy, whether it be government spending, subsidies, the bankruptcy law, banks or the tax regime, according to the authors.
The report details failings and gives limited praise to improvements made in all aspects of economic policy. In particular recommendations are made in the following areas: fiscal and monetary policy, the banking system, subsidies, specific measures to improve the supply side of the economy, and privatisation.<p>
Among the numerous recommendations, the report notes:
The National Bank of Hungary (NBH) must be able to raise interest rates to whatever level is necessary to defend the exchange rate and prevent the onset of endemic inflation. The contradictory forces at work in the monetary system highlight the need for a centralised Treasury to manage cash flow.<br>
Allowing a period of high inflation to reduce real levels of debt, never officially advocated, but hinted at in some high circles, would in the medium and long term be counter-productive. Hungary's foreign debt cannot be reduced by increased monetisation and inflation, the authors warn.<p>
Hungary faces a debt trap and steadily rising interest payments. Fiscal adjustment to attain a moderate primary surplus is thus clearly called for. It is also necessary to achieve a sustainable current account by increasing domestic savings, and to preserve investor confidence and ensure gains in competitiveness from devaluations do not evaporate in higher inflation. This is most easily achieved by concentrating policy deliberations on the budget deficit, rather than the current account.<p>
Wage restraint in the budget sector is crucial in the fiscal consolidation foreseen for 1995. Broader administrative reform may be necessary beyond 1995 when it may prove difficult to maintain the compression of budget sector wages.<p>
Reform of the family allowance system, now taking effect, is welcome. However, the new targeted family support system may prove difficult to implement and be inefficient. Age structure assessment of the household, as is done in most OECD countries, might prove more efficient.<p>
Reform of the pension and health system to remain a key priority. Much more needs to be done to remove costly abuses of disability pensions and extended sick leave.
Short term prospects depend on the implementation of the March austerity package. If fully implemented, foreign investor confidence should be maintained, and foreign debt repayments of US$3bn to be rolled over, and the current account deficit to be financed.<br>
The consolidated budget deficit is larger than normally believed, especially when privatisation receipts are treated as financing rather than current revenues, and all fiscal entities such as the railways are considered. This represents a serious drain on domestic savings, and has contributed much more to stimulation of consumption than indicated.<<p>
The report has already stirred a reaction in some government circles, who disagree with its assertion that Hungary has lost its leading position among the economies in transition in the eyes of many western experts.
<p>
Little doubt though, that many of the conclusions must be sweet music to the ears of Finance Minister Bokros and NBH President Suranyi, who are no doubt now learning much of it by heart as additional ammunition to do battle with the left at future government meetings.
<p>
