<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bblatvia.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>

<h3>LATVIA</h3>

Final figures for the September/October parliamentary elections were: Democratic Party (18 seats), Alliance Latvia's Way (17 seats) and People's Movement for Latvia (Siegerist's Party) (16 seats). President Ulmanis has held talks with all parties and will not announce the name of the prime minister until 7 November at the earliest.
<p>
Failed Bank Baltija was officially declared bankrupt at the end of June. The bank was reported to owe US$32 million to other Latvian banks and over US$90 million to foreign banks. The bank's collapse prompted the government to introduce three draft banking laws in mid-July. The legislative package includes a deposit insurance scheme, rules on the recovery and the bankruptcy of commercial banks and a new law governing the establishment and activities of commercial banks. The insurance of individuals' deposits will now be obligatory for all commercial banks (except foreign banks) operating in Latvia. In the past year 12 banks have been declared insolvent in Latvia, three have been banned from trading and two have been declared bankrupt at the request of the Bank of Latvia.
<p>
Baltic International's apparently successful bid to purchase a controlling interest in Latavio Latvia's state airline has run into difficulties. Latavio was to be restructured in partnership with Scandinavian Airlines - SAS but the deal has been set back by a claim from failed Bank Baltija for the repayment of a debt of US$18 million. As a result of the Bank's claim, the Latvian Economic Court has frozen all the airline's bank accounts. To make matters worse, Latavio's employees have objected to the privatisation, passing a vote of no-confidence in the airline's new board and writing to President Ulmanis asking him to suspend the airline's privatisation.
<p>
Latvia's exports increased by 32.6 per cent in the first five months of 1995. But a 34.2 per cent increase in imports over the same period caused the country's trade gap to widen by 1.5 per cent, from 27.5 per cent to 29 per cent.
<p>
Unemployment at the end of June 1995 was 6.1 per cent, with a total of 77,874 registered unemployed according to the State Statistics Committee.
<p>
In the second round of privatisation held in June, 5,120,279 shares in 13 state-run enterprises were offered by the Latvian Privatisation Agency. 3,626,049 were bought by individuals, 1,456,184 by companies or institutions.
<p>
The Rural credit state stock company Laukkredits is to merge with the Hipoteku un Zemes banka (Mortgage and Land Bank. The move increases the Mortgage Bank's registered capital from Lats1.20 million to Lats1.43 million.
<p>
25 July saw the opening of the Riga Stock Exchange (RSE). The RSE will be the officially appointed auction agent in the State Privatisation Programme which will bring over 150 companies to the market over the next two years.
<p>
