<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bblith.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>

<h3>LITHUANIA</h3>

The International Monetary Fund (IMF) awarded Lithuania a loan of US$15 million (SDR10.35 million) in September. This brings to a total of SDR134.55 the loans granted to Lithuania by the IMF in the past three years.
<p>
Rolling heads department: Prime Minister Adolfas Slezevicius demanded in June the resignation of Economics Minister Aleksandras Vasiliaukas formerly responsible for Lithuania's lethargic privatisation programme. It seems that Mr Slezevicius had run out of patience at the snail's pace progress of the privatisation legislation through parliament. Mr Vasiliaukas had barely held the position for a year.
<p>
The Innovation Bank and the Litimpex Bank are planning to merge into the United Bank of Lithuania before the end of 1995.
<p>
Lithuania's unemployment rate rose to 5.9 per cent in June, well up on the June 1994 figure of 3.2 per cent.

End June inflation was 1 per cent, its lowest level since independence. For the first six months of 1995 the annual inflation rate was 16.7 per cent, down on 1994's 23 per cent.
At the end of June the Bank of Lithuania appointed an administrator to oversee the affairs of the troubled Aurabank.
<p>
Bitor Europe Ltd, a subsidiary of Venezuela's Petroven has signed a contract with the Lithuanian State Energy Co for the supply of 25,000 tonnes in 1995 of orimulcion fuel. The quantity is set to rise to an annual figure of 550,000 tonnes per year by the end of the decade as orimulcion becomes Lithuania's principal fuel.
<p><hr>
<center><img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="besummy.html">Summary Menu</a></center>

