<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbmaced.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>MACEDONIA</h3>
President Kiro Gligorov  was seriously wounded in an assassination attempt in early October, losing an arm and being partially blinded. Parliamentary Speaker Stojan Andov was appointed acting President.
<p>
The assassination attempt was seen by many as related to the agreement signed in New York on 13 September 1995 which went some way to normalising Macedonia's relations with Greece (although the dispute over the country's name is to be further discussed. Macedonia now has its own flag, carrying a rising sun motif curiously similar to that of Japan. The agreement should result in increased trade with Greece and, crucially, restores Macedonian access to its main sea port, Thessaloniki; sanctions against Serbia remain a problem.
<p>
Macedonian exports dropped dramatically in the first quarter of 1995. According to official figures `black' exports remained buoyant, however.

Macedonian officials were meeting with the Paris Club in July to discuss rescheduling Macedonia's debt. At the end of 1994 Macedonia owed some US$258 million to Paris Club members and a further US$1.1 billion to the so-called London Club of commercial creditors.
<p>
According to the Macedonian Privatisation Agency 130 companies have now been privatised, with a further 462 privatisations approved and due to be completed within a matter of months. 58.4 per cent have been privatised through employee buy-outs, 12 per cent through management buy-outs. At the end of June total revenue from privatisations was DM13.5 million.
<p>
A lot of rolling heads department: Macedonia's Prime Minister Branko Crvenkovski hinted at suspicions of corruption when, in July, he replaced six senior government officials - the directors of the public revenue administration and the directorate for legal and property affairs; the under-secretary for economic relations at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs; the under-secretary for Civil Engineering at the Ministry of Urban Planning and Environment and the chief market and labour inspectors.
<p>
Macedonia's mix
The former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia is a concoction of ethnic groups. After the majority Slav-speaking Macedonians, the main ones are Albanians, Turks, Rhomas (Gypsies), Vlachs and Serbs. Not for nothing is the term `Macedonian Salad' used to describe a hotchpotch of ingredients. Now some spice has been added to the dish - Egyptians.
`Most of us 3,000 Macedonian Egyptians are located in the south, around Lake Ohrid', says Usni Zemoski, 48 and a civil engineer. `But in Kosovo ther are 300,000 and in Albania there are 400,000.
His numbers of `Egyptians' are delivered in a sincere voice as we sit on a cafe terrace in the warm winter sunshine overlooking the southern lakeside city of Ohrid. Zemoski claims to be a direct descended of the original settlers in the Lake Ohrid area 4,000 years ago. For 20 years he has pressed for greater rights for Egyptian descendants and is a member of the Egipcani Association. His favourite phrase is `we have documents to prove this'.<br>
Unlike other ethnic groups in the country of two million people, these `Egyptians' are not linguistically distinct. `Not one of us speaks Egyptian or Arabic', he says. `Mostly, we speak Macedonian and Albanian. We aren't recognised as a distinct group by our governments but we are pressing for this'.<br>
Not many of the `Egyptians' can say they have seen Egypt, according to Zemoski. So a few years ago a little bit of Egypt came to see them, in the shape of the Egyptian ambassador in Belgrade. `We have had many contacts with the embassy.' he says, `It will be a happy day for us when Egypt recognises Macedonia'.
While the Greeks and the Macedonians fight over the who, when and where of the name Macedonia, Zemoski says he has the real answer: `An ancient Egyptian pharaoh sent one of his sons to rule this area. The son was called Makedon'.<p>
What exactly does the Egipcani Association want from the central government in Skopje? `We want official recognition as an ethnic group', he says. `We met with the heads of radio and TV and proposed several hours a week of programming dedicated to Egyptian history and topics.' The response, he says, was `positive'. `After all, the Albanians, Turks and Rhomas have their programmes'.<p>
Zemoski's struggle is peaceful. Militancy is not on their agenda, he says. `There is no hostility to us from other Macedonians.' Indeed, Zemoski's sincere and serious attitude to the subject of `Egyptian Macedonians' makes people of all other ethnic groups sceptical and they often smile at the mention of `Egyptians'. Later, and out of earshot of our departing guest, my Macedonian friends finally breaks into laughter. `Let's face it', she says, `they are really just upper class Rhomas!'
<p>
