<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbmoldov.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>

<h3>MOLDOVA</h3>
A three day investment forum - Moldova, Open to the World opened in Chisinau on 20 September. The forum was attended by an impressive 200 delegates from more than 20 countries. (Sadly, the Moldovan government forgot to invite the international press). Total foreign investment in Moldova has yet to reach the US$100 million mark.
<p>
Major General Valery Yevnevich, new commander of the Russian forces occupying the breakaway Trans Dniestr region got off to an unpromising start when he arrived in Moldova. Supporters of his predecessor, presidential wannabee Alexander Lebed blocked the runway at Tiraspol, Trans Dniestr capital, in protest at Lebed's sacking. The protesters, mostly women, surrounded Yevnevich's garrison quarters, eventually obliging him to beat a retreat to Moscow for consultations.
<p>
Moldova is set to become a grain exporter according to the Minister of Agriculture. This year's bumper harvest will allow exports of between 250,000 and 300,000 tonnes. In recent years Moldova has had to import up to 550,000 tonnes of grain.

Bread rationing was introduced in Tiraspol, capital of the Transdniestr region, on 24 August. Each citizen has a daily allowance of 500 grams. Bread can still be bought without rationing in the region's private bakeries, but at three times the cost of subsidised - and rationed - bread.
<p>
Moldova's industrial production increased by 9.4 per cent from May to June 1995, but remained a depressing 9.3 per cent lower than at the same point in 1994. Accurate GDP figures are not readily available in Moldova: however the country's Net Material Product (NMP) the communist measure that does not include the service sector, was down 15 per cent over the year.
<p>
The London office of US securities brokerage Merrill Lynch is reported to have expressed an interest in buying Moldovan Treasury Bonds to the value of US$50 million.
<p>
Monthly consumer price inflation dropped to 0.2 per cent in June 1995.
<p>
Privatisation Minister Ceslav Ciobanu announced that between 75-80 per cent of the National Patrimonial Bonds are likely to be used by individual purchasers. An estimated 30 per cent of the bonds remain in private hands, the balance invested in privatisation investment foundations (PIFs).
<p>
Varo Inform a Chisinau based advertising and information agency, has published Directory '95  containing information on 2,500 Moldovan enterprises.
<p>
Harsh commercial realities are being felt in Moldova, not least at the Chisinau Tractor Factory which in August refused to fulfil an order for Uzbekistan agreed between the countries' presidents. The `tractors for cotton' deal fell over because the tractor factory's management refused to sell the tractors at the stipulated unit price of US$7,800, saying that each unit cost US$10.500 to produce. (See Eyewitness Moldova).
<hr>
<center><img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="besummy.html">Summary Menu</a></center>

