<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbpolan.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>POLAND</h3>
Poland's inflation rate for 1995 is forecast at 25.6 per cent by the Institute of Market Studies and at 22 per cent by the Central Office of Planning, who also foresee a 6 per cent growth in GDP for the year. The free market Gdansk Institute for Market Economics calculated growth in the first quarter of 1995 at 7 per cent. Paris based Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) estimates that Poland's 1995 GDP growth will be 5.5 per cent, followed by a respectable 5 per cent in 1996. <br>This would make Poland the region's fastest growing economy, ahead of the Czech and Slovak Republics. Meanwhile, year-on-year inflation rates at the mid-year point stood at 32.4 per cent, although government austerity measures were forecast to bring down the rate over the second half of the year. June's monthly inflation rate was 0.9 per cent, half that of May.
<p>
Central Statistical Office (GUS) figures indicate that real wages rose by 1.2 per cent in the first quarter of 1995 in comparison with the same period of 1994. GUS figures give an average monthly gross wage of Zl670 (US$290), a 43.8 per cent increase over 1994.

Total reserves in the Polish banking system at the end of the first quarter of 1995 amounted to US$13.1 billion, an increase of US$1.8 billion over the end December 1994 figure.
<p>
Central Bank President Hanna Gronkiewicz-Waltz has formally entered the presidential race. Polls put her well behind the leading candidate, Aleksander Kwasniewski.
<p>
Poland's Central Planning Office (CUP) has come up with some sobering thoughts on the future of Poland's foreign debt, which totalled US$39.3 billion at the end of 1994. During 1996-97 the CUP estimates the annual cost of servicing the borrowing will be US$2.5 - US$3.0 billion, rising to US$4.5 billion after the year 2000. That's the good news. The worst period will be the years 2005-2008 when the annual costs will rise to US$6 billion. Phew!
<p>
Foreign investment in Poland for the first half of 1995 increased by US$1 billion, and now totals over US$5 billion. US companies top the list, with US$1.7 billion, followed by multi-nationals with US$872 million, and German companies in third place, with US$512 million invested.
<p>
The good news: July saw the go-ahead for the transfer of shares in 400 enterprises to the 15 National Investment Funds (NIFs) created to manage them. At the 11th hour 12 companies were withdrawn from the sale because they were bankrupt or holding insolvency discussions with their bankers. Joint foreign and Polish teams have been appointed to run the NIFs, which will control assets of over US$2,6 billion.
The first stage in the process was the transfer of controlling stakes in 28 companies, and minority stakes in a further 400 or so, to the NIFs, as the government handed over 60 per cent of its stock to the NIFs. A further 15 per cent is to be distributed free to the enterprises' employees with another 15 per cent being allocated to pensioners and social funds. The government will retain a 10 per cent stake. By the end of 1995 a further 300 companies are to be added to the NIFs portfolio.
<p>
At the end of September, the Polish government added another 101 state-owned enterprises to the Mass Privatisation Programme, bringing to 514 the total number of state enterprises being sold off through the NIFs.
<p>
The bad news: with admirable timing, the Sejm also approved the new Law on Commercialisation and Privatisation of State Enterprises. The new law removes any time constraints on the transition of state enterprises from Treasury-owned joint stock companies to genuinely private concerns. The new law is seen by many as a retrograde step vesting the responsibility and authority for transformation in the hands of the individual ministries. So much so that President Lech Walesa attempted to veto the legislation, but the move was overturned by parliament, by the narrowest of margins (three votes). Opposition leaders have joined forces with the president, claiming that the legislation, if introduced, will slow privatisation, centralise economic decision making, and act as an invitation to control by the government's supporters. By the end of July, the Solidarity trade union was contemplating calling a strike of its 1.5 million members to register their protest at the new legislation. 
<p>
More good news: Poland looks like becoming a net food exporter by the end of 1995 if exports to the CIS countries hold up over the second half of 1995. During the first three months of 1995 agricultural exports rose by 6 per cent. 
<p>
And even more good news: unemployment in August fell to 2.67 million, just over 15 per cent. The fall came after two months of rising unemployment figures. Labour Minister Leszek Miller forecast that the rate would continue to decline in September and October.
<p>
Polish State Railways (PKP) has, since 1990, reduced its payroll by almost half, to 246,000. Subsidies have been reduced from 18.7 per cent of the budget in 1990 to 13.4 per cent at the end of 1994. This compares favourably with Austria's 45.2 per cent and the UK's 18 per cent. 51 per cent of all goods in Poland are moved by rail. 
<p>
Too good to be true, news: in September the National Bank of Poland (NBP) cut its Lombard and discount base rates by a further two points to between 25 and 29 per cent. The reverse repo rate was also lowered. 
<p>
US investment banker JP Morgan acted as lead manager in Poland's return to the international bond market. High demand meant that the issue was raised from US$200 to US$250 million. The bond pays a fixed coupon at six-monthly intervals. 
<p>
The Koreans are coming: on 16 August Korean carmaker Daewoo announced that it had signed a memorandum of understanding to begin immediate negotiations with the Polish government to acquire a 60 per cent stake in FSO  the state-owned car manufacturer. At the time Daewoo announced plans to assemble its Nexia saloons in Lublin, with production rising to 50,000 per year by the end of the century.
Daewoo's announcement caused consternation at General Motors. GM has been in talks with FSO for some years, but to date the only concrete result has been the assembly of Opel Astras using CKD kits supplied by GM's German plant. Watch this space.
<p>
Daewoo has also initialled an agreement with the Polish government whereby it will take a 61 per cent stake in a joint venture with state owned Fabryka Samochodow w Lublinie. Daewoo will invest US$340 million over a five year period. The plant will build 90,000 passenger cars per year. Daewoo recently signed an agreement with Romania's Oltcit manufacturer (see Business Europa issue 13). 
<p>
Moody's Interbank Credit Service, the bank rating agency, has granted a non-investment grade Ba2 rating to long term deposits with the Bank Rozwoju Eksportu. Moodys also gave a Ba2 long term deposit rating to Krakow based Bank Przemyslowo- Handlowy.

Poland's Industrial Development Agency - Agencja Rozwoju Przemyslu (ARP) saw revenues drop by 8 per cent to Zl183 million (US$78 million) in 1994, although profits rose by 3 per cent to Zl27 million (US$11.5 million). Established in 1991, the ARP has restructured some 400 companies. In 1994 35 loans totalling US$9 million were made, with US$4.2 million invested as equity in new companies. 
<p>
German Chancellor Kohl's state visit to Poland was seen by many as a celebration of Germany's predominant role in Polish business. There are an estimated 6,500 German firms doing business in Poland, around 36 per cent of the total number of registered businesses. Germany is the second largest investor in Poland; major investors include Siemens and Commerzbank. 
<p>
Nestl‚ of Switzerland has purchased a 45 per cent stake in Winiary Poland's largest producer of powdered soups and deserts. 55 per cent of Winiary's equity was sold for US$75 million, the balance being purchased by Bank handlowy. A further 20 per cent of the shares are to be offered to employees, and 20 per cent to agricultural suppliers.
<p>
Gazeta Bankowa has produced its 1994 bank ratings, putting Citibank at the top of a controversial list, and dropping Bank Handlowy from its 1993 number one position down to sixth. Second in the ranking came Bank Przemyslowo-Handlowy followed by Katowice-based Bank Slaski whose share offering caused some palpitations on the Warsaw Stock Exchange in late 1993 and early 1994. See table below for full listing based on the Gazeta's jury ratings.
<p>


Gazeta Bankowa bank ratings

KEY: A = 1994 Bank name; B = Total; C = Dynamics; D = Portfolio structure; E = Efficiency; F = Security; G = Jury rating
<pre>
       A                    B       C        D        E        F        G

 1 Citibank SA            79.57    9.53    10.44    21.00    19.10    19.50
 2 Bank Przemyslowo-
     Handlowy SA          75.34    6.97    10.06    19.57    25.74    13.00
 3 Bank Slaski SA         71.40    7.03     9.42    18.18    21.27    15.50
