<p>
Source: Gazeta Bankowa, June 1995
</pre>
<p>

National Bank of Poland President Hanna Gronkiewicz-Waltz granted a licence to Germany's Deutsche Bank to conduct banking and foreign exchange operations. Deutsche Bank Polska, with a start-up capital of Zl20 million, is to bail out ailing Warsaw based Prosper Bank through the purchase of Prosper Bank bonds.
<p>
Lodz city council has approved a US$20 million project whereby US Polish Genesis Hotels Co Inc are to build an hotel and business centre. The company also plans to build hotels in Poznan, Szczecin and Wroclaw.
<p>
UK-based David S. Smith paper manufacturing group have paid US$15 million for a controlling interest in Kieleckie Zaklady Wyrobow Papierowych SA (KZWP). David S. Smith has committed itself to a US$12 million investment programme and has agreed not to reduce the payroll during a 27 month period. The International Paper Group of the USA has invested over US$290 million in Zaklady Celulozowo- Papiernicze mill, in which it owns an 80 per cent interest.

Krakow will shortly have a new bank; Malopolski Bank Regionaly is to open in the autumn with Zl300 million share capital (US$12.8 million). Bank Gospodarski Zywnosciowej is a major shareholder.
<p>
Sweden's SKF has paid US$6 million for 80 per cent of Polish roller bearings factory Fabryka Lozysk Tocznych. The company employs 1,300 people and had sales of US$12.7 million in 1994.
<p>
Poland is to grant three licences to cellular telephone operators - two by the end of 1995 and one in 1996. Tenders are to be invited for a Global Mobile System (GSM) operation in September 1995. At present Poland has only one cellular telephone operator, Centertel which uses an older, analog, system.
<p>

THE CHURCH, THE CANDIDATE AND THE CONFLICT
The first round of the presidential election went, predictably  - to former communist SLD candidate Alexandr Kwasniewski. The 41-year-old Kwasniewski had held a lead in the polls for some time, although this had been eroded in a late surge from incumbent Lech Walesa. Walesa's prospects had not been helped by the fragmentation of the non-communist vote following the entry into the race of Central Bank governor Hannah Gronkiewicz-Waltz and former Solidarity labour minister Jacek Kuron. His prospects in the 19 November run-off against Kwasniewski will depend on the number of his non-communist rivals' supporters that switch to him. At that stage, though, the issues become less straightforward. <br>Walesa has not been the most popular President, least of all among his former solidarity supporters. But better the devil you know. For Poland's Roman Catholic hierarchy, Kwasniewski and his SLD party have certainly become the devil they don't want to know. Ninety per cent of Poles are Catholics, so the church's opinion is not insignificant. In September Bishop Tadeusz Pieronek urged Catholics to vote against Kwasniewski. Later, Archbishop Tokeureuk went further, attacking government (i.e. SLD) policy for `conducting an open front battle against workers, the retired and the disabled and with the Church'.<p>
The Church's attacks brought immediate protests from Prime Minister Oleszky, who accused the Church of `creating a conflict between government and people.' While this was good news for the Walesa campaign managers, the Catholic bishops significantly omitted to endorse the Walesa candidacy. The Church's opposition seems to have had a negligible effect in the first round of voting.<br> Kwasniewski is more than a youthful, photogenic, well-tailored politician. He is a shrewd politician, very much the `eminence grise' behind the ruling coalition government. He has managed to retain the support of the communists - even the old-school die-hards, while attracting significant support from the younger voters, for many of whom these are their first Presidential elections. He also appears to have cast aside the stigma of having held ministerial office in Poland's last communist government, headed by Mieczyslaw Rakowski.<br>The image today seems to draw on early Fran‡ois Mitterand and Felipe Gonzalez; although Kwasniewski's suits would put either to shame.<br> Walesa fought his rear-guard action by presenting the electorate's choice in the 19 November run-off as a stark choice between building a free market economy, integrated into Europe or returning to a disguised communist rule. There is no doubt that the business community's sympathies do not lie with Kwasniewski. <p>The political uncertainty surrounding his election performance has led to unease in the business community: in October the Warsaw Stock Exchange registered a 10 per cent drop as investors anticipated his victory.<p>
Meanwhile, Kwasniewski and his electoral team have gone to great lengths to reassure the business community, with promises to guarantee the independence of the Central Bank, and not to raise taxes. But as one Warsaw banker observed: `They would, wouldn't they.'

<p>
