<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbroman.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>ROMANIA</h3>
Inflation for the first four months of 1995 was 1.5 per cent, the lowest figure since the liberalisation of prices in 1991 and well down on the 1994 figure of 6.3 per cent. However, fuel price increases look like pushing the rate up to around the 3.5 per cent mark.
<p>
Ministry of Labour figures put unemployment at 10.9 per cent at the end of March 1995.
<p>
In April 1995 the net nominal average salary was Lei199,030 (US$103) up on March's figure of Lei182,803. Employees in the banking sector had the highest monthly average net wage of around Lei524,000 (US$ 272.00). Lowest wages were found in the catering sector, with an average of Lei147,000 (US$77.00).
<p>
The Romanian Stock Exchange opened in June after a gap of 50 years. Operations are not due to start until the autumn. Housed in the National Bank of Romania building, the RSE is headed up by Stere Farmache of the Securities Commission.
<p>
Romania is expecting a good harvest this year. Wheat crops are expected to be around 7.835 million tonnes, an increase of over one million tonnes. Barley and maize are also expected to show gains. 
Brasov-based Intreprinderea Aeronautica Romana (IAR) is to manufacture 96 AH-1F Cobra helicopters under licence from Bell Helicopters of the USA. Bell is considering licensing IAR to produce the Cobra for export to other former Warsaw Pact countries.
<p>
The National Bank of Romania (NBR) signed a US$150 million syndicated loan at the beginning of June. Arranged by the London office of Citibank the loan was increased from its original figure of US$75 million after being heavily oversubscribed. The NBR will pay a group of 32 international banks a margin of 275 basis points over the London interbank rate.
<p>
Romania's budget deficit widened to Lei255.2 billion at the end of April, an increase of Lei38.5 billion over the March figure, according to figures issued by the National Statistics Board. The 1995 Budget Bill fixed a budget deficit of Lei1.93 trillion.
<p>
Romania's current account deficit for the period January-May 1995 was US$670 million, largely created by a negative trade balance of US$637 million. Although exports increased by 22.5 per cent during the first quarter, imports soared by 39.1 per cent. April's figures maintained the trend, with exports up 25 per cent over the March figure, at US$629.5 million although imports slackened a little, down by 6.6 per cent over March at US$732.7 million.
<p>
Romania's industrial output in the first quarter of 1995 registered an increase of 10.2 per cent over the same period on 1994. The manufacturing sector posted the highest gains with an increase of 13.1 per cent. The April 1995 figure showed a 6.5 per cent increase over March.
<p>
Total foreign investment in Romania by mid-May 1995 was US$1.339 billion, an increase of US$67.4 million since the beginning of 1995. Principal investing countries were Korea (US$158 million, the USA (US$122.3 million), and Germany (US$117.6 million). The five largest foreign investors are: Shell, Stima Engineering, AMOCO, Enterprise Oil and Coca Cola. 
<p>
Romanian-French bilateral trade in 1994 totalled US$677.3 million, of which Romanian imports were US$315 million. With US$105.7 million invested, France is the fourth largest investor in Romania. 
<p>
A satellite telephone link in Bucharest failed in late July, cutting off millions of homes and businesses. Engineers from Germany's Siemens were flown in to deal with the crisis, which reduced outgoing traffic to 20 per cent of normal levels, and incoming calls to 50 per cent. 

<p>
