<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbruss.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>RUSSIA</h3>
Russia's 1996 budget deficit is forecast to drop to 4.5 per cent of gross domestic product (GDP), down from  the 1995 forecast figure of 4.9 per cent. 
<p>
Russia's financial markets came to a halt in August when a credit crunch forced interest rates as high as 1,000 per cent. The Central Bank was forced to provide the commercial banking sector with around 300 billion roubles (US$65 million) in short term credits to solve a liquidity crisis which left a number of banks unable to meet their obligations. The credit crunch was attributed to the tight grip exercised by the Central Bank - under the direction of now acting head Tatyana Paramonova. The bank had moved to stop rouble speculation through the imposition of a rouble corridor allowing the rouble to fluctuate between 4,300 and 4,900 to the dollar.
<p>
The American Templeton Russia Fund (TRF) has become the first US investment fund exclusively geared to investments in Russia to trade on the New York Stock Exchange.
<p>
A reported 35 per cent of national carrier Aeroflot's fleet is out of action due to a lack of spare parts. Part of the problem is the high prices charged by Russian monopoly engine and spare part suppliers. The government has reportedly allocated US$110 million for improvements to Moscow's airports, but officials estimate that US$1.5 billion is needed to bring the city's four airports up to international standards.
<p>
A report produced by Moscow's Analytical Department of Police and Parliamentary Committee on Security provides a helpful guide to the going rate in the capital for various kinds of inducements, sweeteners or consultancy fees - oh, alright, bribes - to officials. These are:
<p>
Traffic policeman (for overlooking offence) US$6.00.<br>
District Housing Administrator (for finding your file) US$40.<br>
City Official (for doing something about your file): US$400.<br>
Senior Police Office (for losing your file): US$ 2,000.
Senior Ministry Official (for ignoring your file): US$3,000.<br>
Top State Officials (for designing your file): a Mercedes 300SL, or: BMW 7 Series (with smoked glass), or: a villa in Florida (must have air conditioning), or: an antique sword, or: a diamond ring, or: an English language course at Oxford for their children.
A recent test of police honesty found that only two officers out of 24 refused a bribe.
<p>

Khlebny Dom (House of Bread), St Petersburg's largest chain of bakers with 4,500 branches, launched the city's first public share offer at the end of August. The offer is aimed at individual Russian investors, with a minimum purchase of R11,250 (US$2.50). The lead managers for the offer Lenstroimateriali, St Petersburg's largest broker, hopes to raise R15.55 billion (US$3.45 million) from the offer. Lenstroimateriali are being advised by a group of foreign banks, funded by the UK's Know How Fund and led by Kleinwort Benson.
<p>
US petroleum giant Mobil is to open up to 50 petrol stations over a five year period under a joint venture with the Russian Balcar crude oil trading group. Mobil is to invest US$30 million in the project.
<p>
LUKoil Russia's largest oil company has accepted a bid by Atlantic Richfield (ARCO) of the US for an equity stake. ARCO has agreed to pay a fixed sum of US$250 million for its stake. The ARCO bid will give it between 4.5 and 6 per cent of LUKoil.
<p>
Vladimir Tokarev, General Director of Khantymansiyskneftegasgeologia (which surely qualifies for the longest one-word corporate name) has accused Shell and Amoco of delays in developing the West Salym and Priobskoye fields in Siberia. Officials from the two companies put the delays down to the lack of a legal framework to guarantee long term stability of the project.<p>
A World Bank report puts the number of Russians living below the poverty line at 30 per cent of the population. A 43 per cent fall in average incomes between 1991 and 1993, combined with price liberalisation has meant that an increasing number of people cannot afford the minimum subsistence basket, estimated at US$30 per month in November 1994.

Take my chevvy, Lev. US automobile giant General Motors is to begin assembly of the Chevrolet Blazer in Yelabuga, Tartarstan in the spring of 1996. An eventual annual output of 50,000 vehicles is projected. 
<p>
Export tariffs on a number of commodities have been reduced by 30 per cent. The move is designed to help exporters overcome the adverse effects of the appreciation of the rouble. The lost revenue is to be replaced by increased taxes on Gazprom. The duty on natural gas is to be raised by 10 per cent, from 25 to 35 per cent, an increase expected to produce an additional US$750 million in revenue.
<p>
Deputy Agriculture Minister Magomedtagir Abdulbasirov announced in late August that the 1995 grain harvest could fall to 67-69 million tonnes. The 1994 figure was 81.3 million tonnes. Grain reserves are put at 15 million tonnes. Andrei Sizov of agricultural analysts SovEcon forecast minimum imports of 10 million tonnes in 1995-96 to avoid livestock slaughter.

<p>
