</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbslovak.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>SLOVAKIA</h3>
Mystery still surrounds the 31 August kidnapping of Michal Kovac Jr, son of President Michal Kovac. Kovac Junior's car was stopped, he was later found in the car's boot outside a police station in Austria. Kovac Jr is detained in Austria pending enquiries relating to a suspected fraud in Germany dating back to 1992. Suspicion is rife in Bratislava that the Slovak Intelligence Service (SIS) were involved in the kidnapping. 
<p>
Slovakia's privatisation agency the National Property Fund (NPF) has sold its 15.2 per cent stake in Kosice based steel maker VSZ. The shares have been purchased by employee-owned Ferrimex sro. The purchase price was Sk502.5 million. Earlier this year VSZ's senior management departed (see Business Europa issue 13). 
<p>
Finance Minister Sergej Kozlik forecasts a 5 per cent growth in GDP in 1996 with a budget deficit of 1.5 per cent of GDP. The government expects unemployment will fall to 13 per cent in 1996, with annual inflation dropping below the 10 per cent figure.
<p>
`Sticks and stones may break my bones, but names will never hurt me. . .' unless I'm German. A dispute over the Slovak term for Germany has resulted in the latter taking umbrage and refusing to sign seven bilateral treaties with Slovakia. It seems that the Germans were happy with `Spolkova Republika Nemecko', the Slovak term for German Federal Republic. This, though, turned out to be grammatically incorrect, according to Bratislava's Ludovit Stur Institute responsible for maintaining Slovakia's linguistic purity. The Germans, though, don't like the grammatically acceptable `Nemecka Spolkova Republika, claiming it to be a cold-war term.' Good to know that while Bosnia burns, diplomats have got more important things to worry about.
<p>
The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) is paying the National Property Fund US$59 million for a 10.5 per cent share in petrochemical group Slovnaft, making it the company's biggest foreign shareholder. Slovintegra  a company set up by Slovnaft employees, has acquired a 39 per cent stake in the company for US$138 million.
<p>
Power company Slovenske Elektrarne is to issue five-year bonds totalling Sk1.5 billion following the deal's approval by the National property Fund in July.
<p>
Whatever else happens, the Mochovce nuclear plant is certain to claim a record for the longest construction period. Started before the fall of the wall, work on the plant has been on hold since 1990. Discussions over financing the project with the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development have been abandoned. Contractor Electricit‚ de France has seen its tender offer sidelined (and has withdrawn its staff) as the Slovak government seeks ways of making the plant affordable, probably by striking a deal with Skoda Praha of the Czech Republic, who are interested in the US$1 billion plus contract. In July the German contractor Bayernwerk announced that it was withdrawing from the contract. Economics Minister Jan Ducky announced at the end of July that Russia is prepared to provide Slovakia with a US$150 million loan to assist with the completion of the plant. But read the small print: only 30 per cent of the amount would be made available in cash. The rest in a predictable combination of `expert' consultation and `documentation' and the supply of nuclear fuel.  
<p>
Vseobecna Uverova Banka, Slovakia's largest bank, plans to open offices in London, Frankfurt and Zurich, according to incoming bank president Jan Gabriel. 
<p>
Citibank and Bank Austria are to open subsidiaries in Bratislava in late 1995. 
<p>
A new state holding company grouping Slovakia's arms manufacturers is to be established at the beginning of September based in Trencin. Slovakia's arms industry has been hard hit by the end of the cold war. The former arsenal of the Warsaw-pact countries has seen sales fall to less than 10 per cent of former levels, with unemployment in the industry averaging 22 per cent.
<p>
The National Bank of Slovakia has received a loan of Ecu50 million from the European Investment Bank (EIB).
<p>
