<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbsloven.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>SLOVENIA</h3>

The tolar was due to become convertible in international transactions from 1 September 1995, on the recommendation of the central bank Banka Slovenije. The convertibility was attributed by the bank to Slovenia's declining inflation rate.
<p>
At the end of August 1995 Slovenian unemployment was 14 per cent, with a total of 120,219 people unemployed, an increase of 0.1 per cent over the preceding month but 3.4 per cent below the August 1994 figure. 
<p>
Ljubljana's Lev Hotel is to become a part of the Inter-Continental chain. The hotel will be closed during a period of refurbishment.

A free trade agreement has been entered into by Poland and Slovenia. Signed by Polish Minister for Foreign Economic Relations Jacek Buchacz and Slovenian Minister of Economic Relations and Development Janko Dezelak, the agreement provides for a gradual lifting of tariffs and customs duties. Polish exports to Slovenia were US$22.5 million in 1994, while Poland imported US$96.2 million from Slovenia. The largest component of Slovenian exports is the pharmaceutical industry.
<p>
Slovenia, almost alone among the former Yugoslav republics, most of whom admittedly have other worries, continues to make inroads into its foreign debt liabilities. US$122.5 million dollars has been deposited in the fiduciary account of the Bank of Slovenia with the Dresdner Bank in Luxembourg, due to a US-based consortium of commercial banks, with a further US$20.9 million deposited into the country's trustee debt account in Luxembourg. Slovenia's total debt to international financial institutions at the end of May 1995 was US$530 million. US$1,207 million was also owed to the consortium of banks, the USA, Switzerland, Germany, Austria, UK, Italy and other countries, US$125 million more than at the end of 1994. Slovenia's total external debt is US$2.5 billion.
<p>
The average Slovenian gross salary in May 1995 was SIT111,313 (US$968), a 17.6 per cent increase over the May 1994 figure.
<p>
LB Leasing d.o.o., a wholly owned subsidiary of Nova Ljubljanska Banka a.s. has been granted an international credit facility. The syndicated credit facility, for US$7.5 million, is to be financed by the Washington based International Finance Corporation and Credit Suisse of Zurich. The funds are to be used for equipment purchase.
<p>
The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) is to lend Slovenski Plinovodi DM15 million (US$10.4 million) for the construction and operation of six gas distribution systems.

Revised estimates put Slovenia's forecast inflation rate at 10 per cent for 1995. In June 1995 the annual rate had fallen to 12.6 per cent, well down from December 1994's 18.3 per cent. 
<p>
At the beginning of June Slovenia reached agreement with its creditor banks over repayment terms. Slovenia has a relatively low level of foreign indebtedness at US$2.465 billion owed to directly assignable creditors. At the end of April 1995 Slovenian debt to foreign institutions, including the EBRD, amounted to US$527 million. 
Unemployment reached a total of 14.3 per cent in July, with 125,546 reported unemployed.

Pharmaceutical company Krka began the public sale of its shares in September. 27.1 per cent of shares were sold to employees, 72.9 per cent of the shares in the US$84.4 million company were made available to Slovenian citizens and companies. (See Slovenia - sunny side up  page 17). 
<p>
<hr>
