<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>

<img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="bbukr.html">Select Summer 1995</a></center>
<h3>UKRAINE</h3>
Some countries can, and some simply can't . . . introduce new currencies without difficulties. Since its introduction in 1992, the Ukrainian Karbovanet has been one of the world's less attractive currencies, depreciating 15-fold. The government's decision to replace the karbovanet with the Hryvna and to prohibit all hard currency transactions was hardly designed to maintain confidence in the tired old karbovanet. And it didn't. Within days of the decision to replace the karbovanet with the hryvna the rate dropped from 150,000 to the dollar - a rate it had held for some months, to 170,000 on the inter-bank currency auction. At one time the parallel market had reached 200,000. In mid-September the government appeared to accept that the planned date for the introduction of the Hryvna - October 1995 - was unrealistic although no official statement had been made.
<p>
President Leonid Kuchma celebrated 4 July with a cabinet re-shuffle. The key change was the replacement of Victor Pynzenyk as deputy prime minister responsible for the economy, to be replaced by Roman Shpek, a (reputedly) less radical reformer.  
<p>
Monthly inflation in the Ukraine dropped to 4.8 per cent in June but bounced up half a point again in July, casting a shadow over theories that the International Monetary Fund (IMF) austerity programme - linked to a US$1.57 billion standby loan - appears to be working. In June the Ukraine qualified for the second US$365 million instalment of the loan, with the third due to be drawn down in September 1995 if approved by the IMF board due to meet at that time. The government has promised the IMF that monthly inflation will be brought down to 1-2 per cent by December 1995.
<p>
Troubled Odessa-based shipping group Black Sea Shipping Co (Blasco), one of Europe's largest shipowners, is seeking to restructure its US$250 million debt. The company's cash crisis, allegedly due to the failure of state enterprises in other Soviet republics to pay their bills, has resulted in the arrest or embargo of 51 of the company's fleet of 220 vessels.
<p>
Deputy Economics Minister Tatyana Shandra confirmed the government's programme for the continued privatisation of state-owned enterprises. 483 enterprises, including 70 large and medium sized companies, are expected to be privatised before the end of 1995.

Foreign investors are being invited to bid for 30 per cent of the shares of nitrogen producer Cherkassy Azot as part of a plan to introduce foreign capital into the country's fertiliser industry.
<p>
