<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<center><i><font size=+2>W</font><font size=+1>inter 1995.</i></font><br>
</center>


<h3>TRAVEL BRIEF</h3>
Reverse thrust. Uzbekistan Airways has taken a 40 per cent stake in UK based European Airways for US$160,000. European Airways currently operates the Newcastle - Southampton route with two Jetstream 31s. A Newcastle - Hamburg route is planned. 
<p>
Hungarian flag carrier MALEV cut its losses for the first half of 1995 to US$3.3 million (same period 1994 US$5.5 million). The airline is forecasting a year end profit of US$900,000 as against a US$5.4 million loss in 1994.<p> Troubled Italian flag carrier Alitalia itself suffering from crippling losses, owns 30 per cent of the airline, with 64 per cent currently held by the Hungarian government. Rumours have persisted for some time that the Hungarian government is seeking to replace Alitalia as a shareholder in view of the Italian carrier's inability to increase its investment in the airline.<p>
Tajikistan International Airlines (TIA) plans to double its flights from the UK to Bombay via the Tajik capital Dushanbe. Since February 1995 TIA has operated two flights per week, one from London Heathrow and the other from Birmingham, using Lockheed L10-11-500 Tristars.
<p>
At last . . . the motorway linking Prague to Plzen has been completed, and opened on 26 October. That's the good news. The bad news is that motorists will still have to pick their way through Plzn itself until the city has a by-pass. The motorway section linking Plzen to the German border is due to be completed in 1997. However, the Bavarian government does not plan to extend the autobahn to the frontier until after the year 2000.
<p>
British Airways (BA) is to increase its London Gatwick-Sofia service to four flights per week. The airline is also rumoured to be considering the launch of a London-Bratislava service, having recently opened a sales office in the Slovakian capital.
<p>
Tirana's Rinas airport is now served by 12 airlines with 1,300 flights handled in the first half of 1995.
Airlines of Britain Holdings owners of British Midland in which Scandinavia's SAS has a 20 per cent stake, launched a daily London-Prague-London service at the end of October. The airline was reported to be planning to undercut rivals CSA (Czech Airlines) and BA (British Airways) by as much as Kc5,000 (US$160) off round trip fares. British Midland's proposed fare structure lead to complaints of `dumping' from Czech flag carrier CSA. The new fares are subject to approval from the Czech ministry of transport, which in mid-October appeared opposed to them, claiming that they contravened the terms of a bilateral treaty between the two countries. British Midland is reported to be considering other routes in the region.
<p>
Meanwhile Airlines of Britain Holdings has leased two ATP 42's to the Czech republic's second airline Air Ostrava. 
<p>
Deutsche BA a British Airways subsidiary has started services from Berlin to Vilnius and Riga. 
<p>
US aircraft manufacturer Boeing estimates the market in aircraft in Russia, CIS and the Baltic states to be US$70 billion for the next 20 years. 
<p>
Yugoslav airlines JAT started flying to Kiev (Ukraine) from Belgrade at the beginning of August. Ukraine International now operates four weekly flights on the London (Gatwick)-Kiev route.
<p>
A ferry service linking Constanta (Romania) with the Turkish port of Samsun was inaugurated on 9 August 1995.

LOT Polish Airlines has introduced a telephone check-in service for business class passengers travelling without baggage on the Heathrow-Warsaw route.

Make sure your news reaches the international business community. Send your press releases to: Business Europa, Newsdesk, 2 Market Street, Saffron Walden, Essex CB10 1HZ, UK.
Fax: +44 (0)1799 524805; E-mail: waldenpub@easynet.co.uk
<p>
