<P>
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="bsmenu.html">Bulgaria Subjects</A>
</center>
<P>
<a name="Country"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Country Name</h3>
Bulgaria
<P>
<a name="Official"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Offical Name</h3>
The Republic of Bulgaria
<P>
<a name="Type"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Type of Constitution</h3>
Presidential Republic
<P>
<a name="Head"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Head of State</h3>
President Zhelyu Zhelev
<P>
<a name="HeadGov"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Head of Government</h3>
Prime Minister Zhan Videnov (from January 1995) (leader of BSP)
<P>
<a name="Ruling"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Ruling Party</h3>
Bulgarian Socialist Party
<P>
<a name="Opposition"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Opposition Party</h3>
Union of Democratic Forces
<P>
<a name="Leader"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Leader of Oppostion</h3>
Filip Dimitrov
<P>
<a name="Size"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Size</h3>
110,910 sq km
<P>
<a name="Population"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Population</h3>
8.96 million (1992)
<P>
There is no official data on the number of ethnic groups in Bulgaria but 
there is a large Muslim Turkish minority of around 850,000. Most of these
live in four districts around Haskovo, Razgrad, Varna and Bourgas.
<P>
Other ethnic groups include Armenians, Greeks, Gypsies (around 577,000) 
and Jews.
<P>
<PRE>
Ethnic divisions (%)

Bulgarian     85.3
Turkish        8.5
Gypsy/Romany   2.6
Macedonian     2.5
Armenian       0.3
</PRE>
<P>
<a name="Capital"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Capital City</h3>
Sofia, population 1,107,613 (December 1992)
<P>
<a name="Religions"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Religions</h3>
There is now complete freedom in law to practise any religion. The main 
religion is Eastern Orthodox followed by Islam, Protestantism and 
Catholicism. There are in fact 16 legitimate religious denominations in 
Bulgaria. Latest estimates on the numbers of practising followers are:
<PRE>
                     	 	(%)
Bulgarian Orthodox		85
Muslim				13
Jewish				0.8
Roman Catholic			0.2
Protestant, Gregorian, 
Armenian & others     		0.5
</PRE>
<P>
In recent years there has been a strong return to the Church and religious 
practices. Renewed interest in religious education, rites and rituals has 
also been noted.
<P>
<a name="Labour"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Labour Market</h3>
In 1989 at the fall of the communist régime, around 46 per cent of the 
population was in the labour market. About 22 per cent of the working 
population was in the agricultural sector and 34 per cent in industry. The
appearance of unemployment in 1991 was an early sign of the transition to 
a market economy. Rates of unemployment fell more slowly than real 
production as businesses were keener to merely survive than attempt to 
maximise profits. Average payroll numbers fell in 1991 by 14 per cent. 
In the year ending mid 1991 the total population fell from 8.682 million 
to 8.623 million. At the same time the economically active population fell 
by 180,000 - this represented about 4.6 per cent of the total population. 
The steepest decline in employment between 1990 and 1991 was in the 
following sectors: construction (a fall of 25 per cent), trade 
(21.5 per cent) and industry especially mechanical engineering, machine 
tools, electricals, food processing, textiles.
<P>
In 1992 there was a labour force of 3.613 million, 3.113 million of whom 
were in employment - 2.653 million in the state and co operative sector and 
439,000 in the private sector. The unemployment rate in April 1994 was 
16.1 per cent.
<P>
<a name="GMT"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>GMT/Local Time Difference</h3>
GMT plus 2 hours. In summer time (daylight saving late March to late 
September) an extra hour is added.
<P>
<a name="Languages"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Languages Spoken</h3>
The main language is Bulgarian, a Slavic tongue written in Cyrillic script. 
Other languages spoken in some areas are Turkish and Greek. Among the 
business community there is much enthusiasm to learn English and German. 
Many people also have a working knowledge of Russian and French.
<P>
<a name="Currency"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Currency</h3>
The lev is divided into 100 stotinki. Notes are issued in denominations of 
leva: 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100 and 500. Coins are circulated in values of 
stotinki 1, 2, 5, 10, 20 50 and leva 1, 2, 5 and 10.
<P>
<a name="Exchange"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Exchange Rate</h3>
Lev 53.7755 per US$ (June 1994)
<P>
GDP
US$6.2 billion (1993)
<P>
GDP Per Capita
US$750 (1993)
<P>
GDP Real Growth
3.8 per cent (1993)
<P>
GNP Per Captia
US$1,330 (1992)
<P>
GNP Real Growth
3.0 per cent (1993)
<P>
<a name="Unemployment"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Unemployment</h3>
15.9 per cent (October 1993)
<P>
<a name="Inflation"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Inflation</h3>
Monthly inflation rate for November 1993: 4.55 per cent. 1993 annual rate 
72 per cent.
<P>
<a name="Interest"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Interest Rate</h3>
Central bank rate: 12 month Lev deposits 60 per cent per annum (May 1994)
Basic nominal interest rate (average annual): 48 per cent (1994 estimate)
Lending (3 months to general public): state commercial banks 40.00 43.75 
per cent per annum; private banks 40.08 57.00 per cent per annum (January 
1994)
<P>
Deposit (demand): state commercial banks 5 14 per cent per annum; private 
banks 5 17 per cent per annum (January 1994)
<P>
Deposit (3 months): state commercial banks 20 30 per cent per annum; 
private banks 26 34 per cent per annum (January 1994)
<P>
Central bank rates: refinancing 35 per cent per annum; rediscount 29 per 
cent per annum; Lombard 33 per cent per annum (January 1994)
<P>
<a name="Trade"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Trade Balance</h3>
US$700m (1993)
<P>
<a name="Current"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Current Account</h3>
US$900 million (1993)
<P>
<a name="Foreign"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Foreign Debt</h3>
US$13.3 billion (1993)
<P>
<a name="Central"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Central Bank Foreign Exchange Reserves</h3>
US$1.3 billion (end 1993)
<P>
<a name="Direct"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Direct Foreign Investments</h3>
US$263 million (end 1993)
<P>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<P>
