<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HEAD>
<title>Business Euro</title>
<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name buseur02.html-->
<!--Last update 17/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
</CENTER>
After nearly 50 years of isolation from the democratic process, Bulgaria's
first free elections in June 1990 were won by the former Communist Party, 
now known as the Bulgarian Socialist Party (BSP). The BSP government did 
not last long - popular opposition and unrest forced the resignation of a
number of politburo members and, in October 1991, fresh elections.
<P>
The second elections were won by an improbable coalition of the anti 
communist Union of Democratic Forces (UDF) and the mainly ethnic Turkish 
Movement for Rights and Freedoms (MRF). With the UDF candidate Zhelyu 
Zhelev as president, Bulgarian politics seemed to have settled down. But 
in late 1992 the MRF, for reasons best known to themselves, withdrew from 
the coalition and brought down the government. In December 1992 a so called
`government of experts' was voted in by the BSP and MRF, headed by Zhelev's
former economic adviser, Lyuben Berov. Ironically, this government - which 
stayed in power throughout 1993 - has no socialist minister and only one 
from the MRF.
<P>
The continued political resilience of neo communism in Bulgaria has 
adversely affected its relations with the west. Full Bulgarian membership 
of the European Union (EU) and, even more, NATO, remains a long term 
proposition. Meanwhile, Bulgaria has suffered large losses as a result of 
the imposition of UN economic sanctions against rump Yugoslavia. Many 
Bulgarian enterprises have had to indulge in sanctions busting activities, 
further complicating Bularia's relations with the west.
<P>
No real economic recovery can be expected before 1995. The recent fall in 
new fixed investment is not expected to reverse until the year 1995 96. In 
1993 new investment fell by 8 per cent. Sectorally Bulgaria's capital growth
orientated and state controlled industries are the weakest component of the 
economy. In 1993 industrial output fell by 9 per cent, against a fall of 16 
per cent in 1992 (see INDUSTRY).
<P>
The 1994 government budget assumes tax increases will result in revenues of 
Lev100 billion, generally accepted as a hopelessly unrealistic figure. 
Projected expenditures will push the budget deficit to 7.6 per cent of 
projected GDP in 1994.
<P>
In February 1991 the first liberalisation package supported by the IMF was 
introduced, with profound results. Prices more than doubled in the first 
month, and the lev crashed from its rate of 1.27 to the US dollar to over 
20. Annual interest rates of over 50 per cent have kept inflation to around 
5 per cent per month (70 80 per cent per year). The budget deficit 
mushroomed to an estimated 8 per cent for 1993, causing the IMF to have 
second thoughts about renewing its stand by agreement with Bulgaria in 
March 1993.
<P>
Privatisation in general - and small scale privatisation in particular 
has been the achilles heel of Bulgarian economic reforms. All the Bulgarian 
parties initially rejected privatisation schemes based on the Czech, Russian
or Romanian models. But foreign investment - a paltry US$50 million per 
year - has not proved an alternative. This low level is attributed to three
factors: disarray in the Bulgarian privatisation agency, lack of 
international awareness of Bulgaria and the fear of more widespread war in 
the Balkans. Having declared itself to be the `government of privatisation', 
the Berov government is now hard pressed to demonstrate some successes. 
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="bsmenu.html">Bulgaria Subjects</A>
</center
<P>
