<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HEAD>
<title>Business Euro</title>
<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name buseur03.html-->
<!--Last update 17/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>Political Structure</h2>
</CENTER>
<UL>
<LI>Head of State: President Zhelyu Zhelev
<LI>Head of Government: Prime Minister Zhan Videnov (leader of BSP)
<LI>Ruling Party: Bulgarian Socialist Party (BSP)
<LI>Opposition Party: Union of Democratic Forces
<LI>Leader of Opposition: Filip Dimitrov
</UL>
<P>
As with many other former communist countries of Europe, 1989 was a year 
when democracy was reborn. Bulgaria's new constitution came into effect in 
July 1991. Its substance arose from a desire to move quickly from 
totalitarian government to democracy and a free market economy. Among its 
provisions were freedom of the individual, protection of investments and 
the division of powers.
<P>
Parliament consists of a single chamber, the people's assembly, with 240 
deputies elected for a four year term of office. The right to initiate new 
legislation is vested in the deputies and the executive - the council of 
ministers. The head of state is the president of the republic assisted by 
a vice president. The president of the republic is elected by direct 
popular vote for a period of five years. A president must be Bulgarian born 
and at least 40 years old. Among the duties of the president are to 
announce elections to the parliament, conclude treaties, promulgate laws 
and act as supreme commander of the armed forces.
<P>
The president cannot initiate new laws and cannot veto illegal acts although
he can bring a law back to parliament for further consideration. The council 
of ministers is the supreme executive body of the government and normally, 
though not necessarily, consists of elected members of parliament.
<P>
Local government is based on a division into provinces (oblasti) and 
municipalities (obstini). Each oblast is ruled by a governor appointed by 
the council of ministers. Local government is provided at obstini level by 
municipality councils each led by an elected mayor.
<P>
The country had its first free elections in 1990. The result was the 
overthrow of Todor Zhivkov the dictator who had held power for over 30 
years. The winning party was made up of former communists who blocked most 
of the important reforms needed for a return to a market economy. This 
position changed after further elections in October 1991 when the Union of 
Democratic Forces (UDF) an alliance of anti communists, won a small majority
in parliament. Governing for over a year with the help of the (mainly 
ethnic) Turkish Movement for Rights and Freedoms (MRF) party, fundamental 
reforms began albeit slowly. The UDF came to power on the back of support 
from various powerful groups such as the church, trade unions and private 
sector. The MRF is a party representing the country's one million ethnic 
Turks. Although it only holds 10 per cent of parliamentary seats, the MRF 
held the balance of power in a chamber where the largest parties (UDF and 
the Socialists) are fairly evenly matched.
<P>
In early 1992, a former leading dissident Zhelyu Zhelev was re elected as 
president in a contest with an arch conservative candidate. 
<P>
After a four month government crisis, in January 1993 the Bulgarian 
parliament elected Lyuben Berov as the new prime minister; it also 
elected his new cabinet. Trouble had been simmering since August 1992 when 
President Zhelev criticised the ruling party, the Union of Democratic Forces
(UDF), for causing rifts with other important political groupings in the 
country. After a deep cabinet split, the then prime minister, Philip 
Dimitrov lost a vote of confidence and consequently resigned. After the 
failure of the UDF and the second biggest party, the BSP (Bulgarian 
Socialist Party - former communists) to form a government, President 
Zhelev asked the third largest party, the Movement for Rights and Freedoms 
(MRF) to choose a prime minister. Splits within the UDF allowed the MRF 
candidate to come through forming a government of national responsibility. 
This government of `experts' was the creation of Zhelev and was headed by 
his former economic adviser, 67 year old Lyuben Berov. Although loosely 
supported by the BSP. There is no Socialist member of parliament in the 
cabinet, and only one from the MRF. 
<P>
Last elections: December 1994 (general)
Next elections: 1997 (presidential)
Cabinet ministers
Minister of Agriculture: Georgi Tanev
Minister of Culture: Ivailo Znepolski
Minister of Defence: Valentin Alexandrov
Minister of Education and Science: Marko Todorov
Minister of the Environment: Valentin Bossevski
Minister of Finance: Dimitar Kostov (from January 1995)
Minister of Foreign Affairs: Georgi Pirinski (from January 1995)
Minister of Industry: Roumen Bikov
Minister of Internal Affairs: Victor Mihailov
Minister of Justice: Peter Kornazhev
Minister of Labour and Social Welfare: Evgeni Matinchev
Minister of Public Health: Tancho Gougalov
Minister of Regional Development and Construction Hristo Totev
Minister of Transport: Kiril Ermenkov
<P>
<HR>
