<P>
<a name="List"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>Industry</h2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><a href="#Production">Production</a>
<LI><a href="#Contribution">Contribution to Economy</a>
</UL>
<P><center>
<IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="bsmenu.html">Bulgaria Subjects</A>
<P>
</center>
<HR>
<P>
Up to 1990, Bulgaria's growth rate was quite high. Wealth is based on a 
large iron and steel industry (with a new mill at Burgas). Much of the 
production methods are ecologically unsound and investment has been targeted
at dealing with this problem. Engineering industry focused on transport 
equipment such as motor cycles, ships, electric cars, fork lift trucks and 
on agricultural and electrical equipment. There is a growing machine tools 
industry and a developed chemicals sector specialising in artificial 
fertilisers, plastics, pharmaceuticals, synthetic rubber, paints and 
petrochemicals. Woollen textiles are produced and there is a significant 
carpet industry.
<P>
Bulgaria's foreign trade in 1992 amounted to Lev162,000 million, of which 
51 per cent was exports and 49 per cent imports. Exports in 1993 totalled 
US$3.6 billion and imports totalled US$4.3 billion.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<P>
<a name="Production"></a>
<H3>Production</H3>
<P>
The decline in industrial production slowed in 1993 to  9 per cent, against 
16 per cent in 1992. Up to 1993, the involvement by foreign firms in 
Bulgarian industry had been quite small. Net foreign direct investment in 
the first half of 1993 was US$22 million, against a total of US$42 million 
for 1992. The lethargic pace of reform and liberalisation had done little 
to encourage inward investment in  manufacturing. Among the more promising 
areas is vehicle assembly. There was existing capacity to produce Russian 
designed Moscovitch cars. In the spring of 1992, there were reports of a 
possible joint venture between the government and Rover cars. This would 
involve the supply and possible assembly of Maestro cars and vans. There 
were talks about a possible joint venture between the Ministry of Defence 
and Rover. It was believed that up to 50,000 units per year could be 
produced in Bulgaria.
<P>
In 1992, the privatisation of the national electronics industry was 
announced. Consultants were called in to identify components of the industry 
which have the potential to compete in world markets.
<P>
Economic activity in Bulgaria is increasingly dominated by a small number 
of companies controlled by Bulgaria's new entrepreneurial class. Known as 
the Group of 13 (G13) these enterprises have interests in steel, banking, 
newspapers, agriculture and insurance. The largest - Multigroup - is 
estimated to have a turnover in excess of US$1 billlion.
<P>
With its sea resorts, skiing and historic places of interest, Bulgaria has 
long enjoyed a thriving tourist industry. By the beginning of 1993, all 
tourist organisations were transformed into joint stock companies. 
Privatisation began in February 1993. About 30 per cent of all hotels were 
expected to be privatised by the end of 1993, the whole process would take 
5 years to complete. It was thought that only 6 per cent of high class hotel
s would come up to acceptable European standards. In 1992, the tourist 
industry seemed to recover with about 90 per cent of hotels fully booked 
during the winter season. About one million people vacationed in Bulgaria 
in 1992; more than 60 per cent visited the country between June and 
September. Western Europe was the largest incoming market, accounting for 
41 per cent of foreign holidaymakers. Of these, 70 per cent were Germans. 
In 1993, tourist numbers were expected to rise by 3 to 4 per cent. Tourist 
revenues were Lev5,000 million in 1992 - resulting in a 37 per cent increase
in profits since 1991.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="List" align=right border=0></a>
<P>
<a name="Contribution"></a>
<H3>Contribution to Economy</H3>
Industry contributed 50 per cent of GNP in 1992 and employed 44 per cent of 
the working population.
<P>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="List" align=right border=0></a>
