<DOCNO>WT14-B02-299</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA047-000828-B040-49</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.business-europa.co.uk:80/buseur06.html 193.132.29.223 19970119090120 text/html 7905
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 09:01:13 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 7734
Last-modified: Mon, 08 Jan 1996 16:43:58 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HEAD>
<title>Business Euro</title>
<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name buseur06.html-->
<!--Last update 17/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>Investment, Companies & Stock Exchange</h2>
</CENTER>
<ul>
<li> <a href="buseu06a.html">Foreign Investment Regulations</a>
<li> <a href="buseu06b.html">Top National Companies</a>
<li> <a href="buseu06c.html">Multi National Corporations</a>
<li> <a href="buseu06d.html">Stock Exchange</a>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
The Trade Law of 1991 sets out the business structures which are available 
in Bulgaria. Limited liability and joint stock companies are the main forms 
of business structure in what is still a fledgling market economy. The 
minimum share capital for a joint stock company is Lev1 million unless the 
capital is to be raised by  public offer when the sum is Lev5 million.
<P>
<PRE>
Economic results
% change on previous year
                      1990    1991    1992
GDP                   11.6    23.0     8.0
Industrial output     13.1    25.0    13.0
Agricultural output    8.9     9.0     6.5
Fixed investment      17.0    18.0    11.0
Consumer prices       19.3   334.0   100.0
</PRE>
<P>
The economy continued to decline in 1993 with the biggest falls in 
industrial output and sales felt in petrochemicals, electronics and 
electrical engineering. There was some growth: ferrous metals, mechanical 
engineering, printing and power generation.
<P>
In September 1992, Bulgaria's Privatisation Agency began operations. It 
replaced the former body whose task it was to lay the foundations of the 
privatisation process in terms of the law and expert advice. The agency has 
11 regional offices and employs over 100 experts. Its aim is to privatise 
around a quarter of all businesses where capital exceeds Lev10 million. 
According to official statistics, 18.5 per cent of the economy is now 
controlled by the private sector. The actual share is probably somewhat 
larger. About 60 per cent of all claims for resititution of property 
appropriated under the communist régime have been settled, either by the 
return of the property to its rightful owners or by payment of compensation.
Outside experts are called in to evaluate schemes on a project by project 
basis. The 1992 Privatisation Act lays down the means by which companies 
are to be privatised. The process is to be initiated by the government. It 
was thought that early candidates for privatisation would be in the 
construction sector or municipally owned companies. In theory foreign 
investors are allowed to be involved in a privatisation on equal terms 
with locals. In reality, foreign investment is beset with numerous 
difficulties, casting doubt on government estimates of up to US$400 
million in new direct foreign investment from equity sales to foreigners 
in 1994 95. Many Bulgarian state enterprises are technically insolvent, 
particularly in the capital goods sector. In practice, most foreign 
investors' interest is limited to the service and agriculture food 
processing sector. Direct foreign investment in agriculture itself is 
unlikely due to the ban on foreign ownership of land in Bulgaria.
<P>
Western consultants were drafted in to advise on which companies were ready 
for privatisation. These experts were drawn from Bankers Trust, Boston 
Consulting Group, Arthur Anderson, S.G. Warburg, Ernst and Young and others.
<P>
By mid 1993 the Privatisation Agency had only completed one major 
transaction, the sale of the Tsarevichni Produkti maize processing plant 
to Belgian Amylum for US$20m. Tsarevichni Produkti owed its bankers US$20 
million, part of which has been converted to equity. Delays on regulations 
concerning the proposed Mutual Fund which was to be part recipient of sales 
proceeds were also cited as reasons for the slow progress towards a 
privatised sector. Despite this lack of real progress, the government set 
its privatised targets for 1993 as 292 enterprises. Of these, the plan 
envisaged that 83 would be privatised by the Privatisation Agency. The 
rest to be handled directly by various government ministries. Priority 
areas were recognised as being industry, agriculture, trade, tourism, 
construction, transport and telecommunications. Privatisation proceeds 
were expected to be in excess of Lev 9.2 million although the slow and 
uncertain pace of privatisation makes this figure hypothetical.
<P>
In June 1994 Bulgaria began its long delayed mass privatisation through 
vouchers. The scheme, modelled on the Czech pattern, entitles Bulgarians 
to privatisation vouchers representing assets with a book value of 
Lev25,000 ($450) on payment of Lev500. The vouchers can be exchanged for 
shares in around 500 state owned enterprises, with assets totalling 
Lev110.8 billion. Private investment funds will be created to manage and 
invest the vouchers on behalf of the public. Officials from the newly funded
Centre of Mass Privatisation are drafting a separate law to govern 
investment funds.
<P>
In September 1992, Bulgaria's Privatisation Agency began operations. It 
replaced the former body whose task it was to lay the foundations of the 
privatisation process in terms of the law and expert advice. The agency has 
11 regional offices and employs over 100 experts. Its aim is to privatise 
around a quarter of all businesses where capital exceeds Lev10 million. 
According to official statistics, 18.5 per cent of the economy is now 
controlled by the private sector. The actual share is probably somewhat 
larger. About 60 per cent of all claims for resititution of property 
appropriated under the communist régime have been settled, either by the 
return of the property to its rightful owners or by payment of compensation.
Outside experts are called in to evaluate schemes on a project by project 
basis. The 1992 Privatisation Act lays down the means by which companies 
are to be privatised. The process is to be initiated by the government. It 
was thought that early candidates for privatisation would be in the 
construction sector or municipally owned companies. In theory foreign 
investors are allowed to be involved in a privatisation on equal terms 
with locals. In reality, foreign investment is beset with numerous 
difficulties, casting doubt on government estimates of up to US$400 million 
in new direct foreign investment from equity sales to foreigners in 1994 95.
Many Bulgarian state enterprises are technically insolvent, particularly in 
the capital goods sector. In practice, most foreign investors' interest is 
limited to the service and agriculture food processing sector. Direct 
foreign investment in agriculture itself is unlikely due to the ban on 
foreign ownership of land in Bulgaria.
<P>
At the beginning of 1993 there were 105,564 private companies registered in 
Bulgaria but only 72,863 had submitted annual reports according to the 
National Statistics Institute.
<P>
