<HEAD>
<title>Business Euro</title>
<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name buseur09.html-->
<!--Last update 11/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>Energy</h2>
</CENTER>
<UL>
<li> <a href="buseu09a.html">Production</a>
</UL>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="bsmenu.html">Bulgaria Subjects</A></center>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
Electricity output in 1992 was 35,600 MkWh, down from 38,900 in the previous 
year.
<P>
Bulgaria is dependent on imports for 70 per cent of its energy supplies.
There are virtually no supplies of oil and small reserves of gas 
(although it is hoped that preliminary discoveries in the Black Sea by 
Texaco Bulgaria will prove to be commercial) and there is a high level of 
oil and gas import dependency. Traditionally most came from the former 
Soviet Union. Since 1991, Bulgaria has had to pay in hard currency at world 
market prices. Supplies have become less reliable. A typical problem is 
faced by the coal fired station at Varna which used to burn hard coal 
imported by barter from the Ukraine and which now has to buy supplies on the 
world market.
<P>
Electricity was also traditionally imported from the former USSR but some is
also exported to neighbouring countries. Oil was also exported to 
contribute to hard currency earnings.
<P>
Electricity is mostly generated by the National Electric Company (NEC) 
although all power stations including Kozloduy operate as separate companies.
Capital spending is controlled by the NEC and policy on pricing and output 
is controlled by the government.
<P>
There are large deposits of brown coal although quality is quite low. The 
bulk of coal reserves are lignite and most hard coal has to be imported. 
Yearly production of lignite is around 34 million tonnes, hard coal 200,000 
tonnes. As this coal is insufficient for power station needs, most has to be 
imported. Hydroelectric power provides just over 5 per cent of total energy 
capacity is limited by the uncertain flow of the rivers and priorities 
given to agriculture.
<P>
A paucity of natural resources and the existence of uranium shifted 
attention to nuclear power. One nuclear station at Kozloduy accounts for 
40 per cent of all Bulgaria's needs. It has the capacity to produce 3,760 
MW of electricity. This power station was the focus of a visit by 
international nuclear power experts and donor agencies in early 1993 to 
consider ways to enhance safety at the plant. 
<P>
In May 1994 the NEC announced that it was to invest a further US$200 million
to upgrade and increase the safety of four Soviet designed 440 MW reactors 
at the Kozloduy plant. The NEC has already spent US$50 million on upgrading 
the plants. Concerns over safety, especially following the Chernobyl 
disaster, led to the shut down of some older capacity and the cancellation 
of the building of new plants such as one in Belene. There have been severe 
energy shortages with frequent blackouts in Sofia and the industrial sectors.
<P>
There are 16 210 MW coal fired stations and a number of smaller units 
burning oil, fuel oil and gas some of which provide combined heat and power 
(CHP) and centralised heat only units for domestic and industrial customers.
<P>
In March 1992, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) 
approved an Ecu40 million loan to help Bulgaria's energy crisis. It costs 
Bulgaria US$500,000 a day to import 600 MW of electricity. The funds were 
set to secure the completion of part of the Maritza Power Plant. Funds were 
also allocated for the improvement in environmental standards by building 
the country's first desulphurisation plant for the coal industry.
<P>
<HR>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="bsmenu.html">Bulgaria Subjects</A></center>
<P>

