<title>Business Euro</title>
<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name buseur11.html-->
<!--Last update 17/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>Agriculture</h2>
</CENTER>
<ul>
<li> <a href="buseu11a.html">Production</a>
<li> <a href="buseu11b.html">Contribution to Economy</a>
</UL>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="bsmenu.html">Bulgaria Subjects</A></center>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
Agriculture has the greatest long term potential to act as a motor for 
economic growth in the Bulgarian economy; but only if it is radically 
restructured through privatisation, its export performance improved and its 
capital base strengthened through new fixed investment.
<P>
The political upheavals of recent years as well as a bad drought in 1993 
have had a severe dislocational effect on Bulgarian farm trade. In 1991 
Bulgarian exports to its erstwhile major trading partners in the former 
Soviet Union fell by 80 per cent, imports also fell by 84 per cent. With 
the smaller volume of traded produce, the countries of the EU took a larger 
share of total trade than the former Soviet Union. Dollar export earnings 
fell by 68 per cent between 1991 and 1992. The slump in trade was most 
marked in farm produce such as beef, lamb, eggs, grapes, pears and canned 
produce.
<P>
A key issue in agricultural policy has been what to do about land formerly 
owned by private farmers before the days of communism. It was expected that 
60 per cent of all lands subject to restitution would be returned by the 
end of 1993. The Ministry of Agriculture expected that up to 20 per cent of 
owners would receive title deeds in 1993. Land reform is a key political 
issue with the main opposition party putting land restitution as a priority 
area. There is a feeling that there was ill advised haste in the liquidation 
of the co operatives. By the end of 1992 although the co operatives had all 
but disappeared, only about a quarter of land had actually been reallocated 
the result was that much of the land was unworked. Further criticisms were 
levelled at the policy of dividing up land into small plots worked by 
townspeople with little experience of working the land. Fears were expressed 
about the ability of the agricultural sector to produce surpluses for 
markets at home or abroad. Outside the wheat growing area of Dobrudga the 
average pre communist smallholding was 5 hectares or less. Disputes over 
who exactly owns a piece of land led to further smaller divisions of farms. 
Financial problems have also prevented farmers from investing in machinery, 
seed or fertiliser. Loans were mostly prohibitive with base rates at more 
than 40 per cent.
<P>
In the agro business field there has been interest in Bulgaria's fruit and 
vegetable industry. The Austrian company IBG has invested in cold storage 
facilities costing 60 million schillings. The store will hold 1,500 tonnes 
of fruit destined for export and will include strawberries, cherries, 
raspberries and plums. Bulgaria already exports canned fruits, vegetables 
and juices.
<P>
Maize Products Combined Works based in north east Bulgaria was one of the 
first enterprises to be privatised. Operations started in June 1993 and 
Maize Products will produce starches, gum, glucose syrups, maize butter and 
ethanol. The company is to operate under a US licence and with investment 
funds coming from Creditanstalt Investment Bank, Vienna, the highly 
modernised production facility will aim at producing for export principally 
to western Europe.
<P>
<P>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
