<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>Education, Health, & Welfare</h2>
</CENTER>
Education in Bulgaria is free and compulsory for all children between the 
ages of seven and 16. The standard of literacy is extremely high and many 
children go on to higher education.
<P>
There are three state universities, the oldest being the Kliment Ohrid in 
Sofia (it has over 15,000 students and 1,500 teachers). The other two state 
universities are the Kirill i Metodii in Veliko Turnovo and the Paisi 
Hilendarski in Plovdiv. In 1990 an independent university in Burgas was 
founded with 500 full time students, its aim was to specialise in law, 
management and political science.
<P>
<PRE>
<B>Education (1990 91)

                     Institutions    Teacher   Students</B>
Kindergartens               4,590         28,776       303,779
Secondary (unified)         3,458         72,310     1,110,733
Secondary (vocational)        236          6,602       113,139
Technical colleges
and schools of art            257         10,865       125,728
Higher educational             38         20,716       151,510
Source: Statistical Yearbook
</PRE>
<P>
Bulgaria's health care system is free although in 1991 the state allowed 
the development of private medicine. There are about 260 hospitals offering 
over 88,000 beds. There are about 28,500 doctors and just over 6,000 
dentists.
<P>
Retirement pensions are paid on the basis of previous wages and the 
percentage paid varies between occupations. Family allowances are paid for 
all children under 16.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="bsmenu.html">Bulgaria Subjects</A></center>
