<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Membership of International Organisations</H2>
</CENTER>
Bulgaria is a member of the following international organisations:
<UL>
<LI>Customs Co operation Council (CCC)
<LI>European Convention for Human Rights
<LI>European Travel Commission
<LI>European Conference of Transport Ministers (CEMT)
<LI>International Atomic Energy Agency
<LI>International Lead and Zinc Study Group
<LI>International Medical Organisation
<LI>International Organisation of Journalists
<LI>International Radio and Television Organisation 
<LI>Inter Parliamentary Union
<LI>United Nations (UN) and its agencies, including:
<LI>Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO)
<LI>International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (World Bank)
<LI>International Civil Aviation Organisation (ICAO)
<LI>International Labour Organisation (ILO)
<LI>International Maritime Organisation (IMO)
<LI>International Monetary Fund (IMF)
<LI>International Telecommunications Union (ITU)
<LI>UN Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organisation (UNESCO)
<LI>UN Industrial Development Organisation (UNIDO)
<LI>Universal Postal Union (UPU)
<LI>World Health Organisation (WHO)
<LI>World Intellectual Property Organisation (WIPO)
<LI>World Meteorological Organisation (WMO)
<LI>World Tourism Organisation
</UL>
<P>
In December 1992, Bulgaria signed a full Association Agreement with the 
European Union (EU). This will allow the country to gain greater access to 
European markets. Bulgaria was keen to sign as a step towards eventual full 
membership. Earlier agreements were signed with Poland, Czechoslovakia and 
Hungary, but political instability and lack of progress towards 
modernisation held Bulgaria's case back. 
<P>
