<P>
<a name="Country"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Country Name</h3>
Ukraine
<P>
<a name="Official"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Offical Name</h3>
Republic of Ukraine
<P>
<a name="Type"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Type of State</h3>
Parliamentary republic; independence declared 24 August 1991
<P>
<a name="Head"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Head of State</h3>
President Leonid Kuchma (from 10 July 1994)
<P>
<a name="HeadGov"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Head of Government</h3>
Prime Minister Pavlo Lazarenko
<P>
<a name="Size"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Size</h3>
603,700 square kilometres (233,028.2 square miles)
<P>
<a name="Population"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Population</h3>
51.87 million, July 1995 estimate; annual growth 0.04 per cent; birth rate 12.31 births/1,000
population; life expectancy 70.11 years (1995 estimates).
<P>
Age structure (end 1991)
<P>
Children (0-15 years)   11.8 million<br>
Working population (16-60 years)  28.9 million<br>
Elderly people (60 years and over)  11.2 million<br>
Source: EVD Oekraine 1993<br>
<P>
Ethnic makeup
<P>
Ukrainian 73 per cent, Russian 22 per cent, Jewish 1 per cent, other 4 per cent.
<P>
<a name="Capital"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Capital City</h3>
Kiev; population 3.13 million, 1994 estimate.
<P>
<a name="Religions"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Regligions</h3>
Ukrainian Orthodox-Moscow Patriarchate, Ukrainian OrthodoxjKiev Patriarchate, Ukrainian
Autocephalous Orthodox, Ukrainian Catholic (Uniate), Protestant, Jewish.
<P>
<a name="Labour"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Labour Market and Unemployment</h3>
Labour force 27.6 million (1995)<br>
Unemployment rate 1 per cent (1995)<br>
139,200 (0.5 per cent of the workforce) officially registered unemployed (February 1996).<br>
Approximately 19 per cent of the workforce are employed in agriculture, 3 per cent in mining,<br>
37 per cent in industry and 41 per cent in services (1994 estimates).<br>
<P>
There is no official data on the number of ethnic groups in Bulgaria but 
there is a large Muslim Turkish minority of around 850,000. Most of these
live in four districts around Haskovo, Razgrad, Varna and Bourgas.
<P>
Other ethnic groups include Armenians, Greeks, Gypsies (around 577,000) 
and Jews.
<P>
<a name="GMT"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
