<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>Political Structure</h2>
</CENTER>
A nationally elected presidency was instituted on 1 December 1991. The 450 member
Supreme Rada (Council) is the highest legislative body, with the president holding executive
power. The president is elected for a five year term and appoints the prime minister and the
cabinet, which the Supreme Rada have to approve.
The Ukrainian political system still operates on the basis of the old Soviet constitution.
Numerous amendments and alterations have left the division of power unclear and confused,
with neither parliament nor the president willing to accept alternative constitutional proposals
from each other.<br>
Local government is based on 24 regional divisions (oblasts) and one autonomous republic
(Crimea). The oblasts are further divided into rayons.
<P>
