<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>Political Situation</h2>
</CENTER>
<P>
Head of state: President Leonid Kuchma (from 10 July 1994).<br>Head of government: Prime Minister Pavlo Lazarenko (from 28 May 1996).<br>At the end of the First World War Ukraine disintegrated - six separate factions fought for control with Kiev changing hands five times in one year. Western Ukraine was ceded to Poland as an international protectorate, with the eastern half eventually falling to the Bolsheviks, supported by Russia. Ukraine became a founding member of the USSR in 1922 and was rewarded by Stalin with an engineered famine in 1932 and 1933, killing between five and seven million people.<br>The Ukrainian steppes were one of the bloodiest of the Second World War battlefields with an estimated six million Ukrainians dying during the conflict. At the end of the war the USSR retained the Polish area of Ukraine it had invaded in 1939. Guerrilla resistance to the Soviet regime, particularly in the nationalist western areas continued into the 1950s as millions of Ukrainians were sent to Siberia on suspicion of `disloyalty'. The combination of war, famine and purges are thought to have cost the lives of half the male population and one quarter of the female population between 1900 and 1950.<br>Although Ukraine's history is characterised by domination and subjugation, the Ukrainian nationalist movement, although rigorously suppressed never died (the national anthem is `Ukraine has not died yet').<br>The explosion at the Chernobyl nuclear reactor in April 1986 marked a turning point for Ukraine. The failure of a Soviet showpiece and the subsequent delay in admitting the disaster released pent up nationalist feelings. By 1990 the Ukrainian People's Movement for Restructuring (Rukh), an independence movement, won local elections across the republic, with the greatest gains in the west where control of the Lvov city council was won. Protest marches organised by students in Kiev during October 1990 forced the resignation of the communist prime minister.<br>Following the failed Moscow coup attempt in August 1991 the Communist Party of Ukraine (CPU) was banned and in December 1991 90 per cent of the population voted for independence in a national referendum. The former chairman of the CPU, Leonid Kravchuk, was elected president. However a second vote of no confidence forced the government to resign in September 1992, as their inexperience, tension with the west and Russia and economic collapse caught up with them.<br>Differences between western and eastern Ukraine grew following independence, with those in the west looking to create a strong national identity and close links with western Europe, while the more Russified east wanted to retain close ties with Russia. The adoption of Ukrainian as the official national language in 1990 caused controversy, with the majority of eastern Ukrainians speaking only Russian while those in the west demanded that Ukrainian should be enforced as the only language. The severe economic crisis experienced during the first five years of independence exacerbated regional differences and held back much needed structural reforms.<br>Ukraine's first free parliamentary elections in March 1994, which centred around the disintegrating economy and the east-west split, saw the recovery of the CPU which won 86 seats, the largest single block, followed by Rukh with 20.<br>The presidential election in July 1994 was also fought over these differences, with the pro-Russian Leonid Kuchma (a former prime minister) beating the nationalist Kravchuk. The voting pattern mirrored the geographical split between east and west. Kuchma has championed the strong reformist policies his predecessor was unwilling to introduce and (slightly surprisingly) reasserted Ukraine's independence from Russia. However, vocal opposition from hard-line communist deputies have slowed the reform process and prevented the president from implementing the widespread reforms desperately needed.Prime Minister Vitaly Masol, originally appointed by Leonid Kravchuk, was forced to resigned in March 1995 after his anti-reform stance finally proved too much for President Kuchma. His replacement, Yevhenii Marchuk (a former head of the Ukrainian secret service), lasted only slightly longer. He was sacked in May 1996 after criticism from the president that he was pursuing his own political career rather than managing the economy. Kuchma's third prime minister, Pavlo Lazarenko, is a close ally of the president and a former collective farm manager. Lazarenko, whose reformist credentials are limited, was promoted from first deputy prime minister.<br>In May 1995 parliament approved a bill increasing the power of the president and enabling him to select his cabinet without parliamentary scrutiny. The legislation also gives the president the right to issue decrees guiding the economic reform process and overrule recalcitrant local authorities.<br>By June 1996 Ukraine still had no official constitution, with a draft proposal rejected by parliament in April 1996. Apart from a few modifications Ukraine has continued to use the constitution of the former Soviet Union, which has left the division of power between the president and parliament hopelessly confused. Frequent clashes between the president and parliament have hindered the reform process. Adoption of a constitution clearly defining presidential and parliamentary powers is essential; progress in this direction has been prevented because of disputes between the two sides.<br>Ukrainian control over the separatist Crimean peninsular, a predominantly Russian populated area ceded to Ukraine by Russia in 1954, increased in 1995. Direct rule was imposed in March 1995, although the region's autonomy was not revoked. The Russian experience in Chechnya and a more conciliatory tone from Kiev reduced the possibility of Russian intervention in the Crimea, and a constitutional rather than a violent secessionist solution remains the long-term likelihood. Pro-Russian groups were well beaten in local elections in June 1995 leading to the election of a Crimean leadership favouring closer links with Kiev.The cancellation by the Russian President, Boris Yeltsin, of a meeting with his Ukrainian counterpart in April 1996 for the sixth time was blamed on continuing differences over the status of the Sevastopol port on the Crimean peninsular, with both nations demanding that their navies be stationed there. The fate of the 300 strong Black Sea Fleet was agreed in June 1995, when Ukraine gave most of its share to Russia. Although any threat to Ukraine's sovereignty is remote, relations between the two states are highly sensitive with the nationalistic posturing of Russian politicians in the run up to the June 1996 Russian presidential elections not helping the situation.<br>Ukraine joined NATO's Partnership for Peace Programme in September 1995, however full membership is unlikely, with strong Russian opposition to NATO expansion into the former communist bloc in central Europe, let alone the former USSR.<P>
Last election: March 1994 (parliamentary); July 1994 (presidential).<P>
Next election: 1999<P>
Cabinet ministers (May 1996)<P>
