<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HEAD>
<title>Business Euro</title>
<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name cr06.html-->
<!--Last update 17/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>ECONOMY</h2>
</CENTER>
<ul>
<li> <a href="#Overview">Overview of State Sector</a>
<li> <a href="#Main">Main Companies</a>
<li> <a href="#Manufacturing">Manufacturing and Service Industry</a>
<li> <a href="#Labour">Labour Market</a>
<li> <a href="#External">External Trade</a>
<li> <a href="#Privatisation">Privatisation</a>
<li> <a href="#Banking">Banking</a>
<li> <a href="#Investment">Investment and Trading</a>
<li> <a href="#Financial">Financial Markets</a>
<li> <a href="#Foreign">Foreign Investment Activity</a>
<li> <a href="#Taxation">Taxation</a>
</UL>
<P>																																			
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
<b>Summary</b>
<P>
Ukraine has suffered a severe economic crisis since independence; GDP fell by 11.8 per
cent in 1995 following a decline of about 50 per cent between 1990 and 1994. Although the
1995 economic performance was an improvement, the continued intransigence of the left-
wing dominated parliament has prevented significant progress with the privatisation
programme, with only 39 per cent of 8,000 medium and large-scale enterprise and 51 per
cent of small enterprises privatised during 1995. The government had planned to privatise
them all. The 1996 privatisation programme is as ambitious as in previous years, with the
sale of small enterprises due for completion by July.<br>
From a high of 4,735 per cent in 1993 inflation fell to 380 per cent in 1995, with the monthly
rate down to 2.4 per cent by April 1996 as the central bank's tight monetary policy hit home.
Until a structural reform programme capable of cultivating and encouraging a genuine private
sector (rather than partly restructured state enterprises) is undertaken, the `bread-basket' of
the USSR will be left wallowing in economic decline.
<P>
<b>Background</b>
<P>
Leonid Kravchuk's spell as president saw little progress in introducing the reforms necessary
to create the stable and liberal environment essential to the establishment of a market
economy. The communist dominated parliament elected in 1994 has made life difficult for
his successor Leonid Kuchma. No significant progress has been made in creating a dynamic
private sector capable of dragging the Ukrainian economy out of Soviet, state-owned mode
and into a free market system. Large state enterprises have continued to receive subsidies
as the government proves incapable of consigning the central planning system to history,
while attempting a few half-way reform measures. Political connections (the ability to obtain
subsidies) are the measure of success at the enterprise level, rather than quality and
efficiency.<br>
Ukraine contributed 20 per cent to the USSR's economy, but the decline has been rapid
since independence. Disagreements with Russia combined with total dependence on Russian
energy supplies (which were raised to world price levels after the collapse of the USSR) have
exacerbated Ukraine's foreign trade problem. The guaranteed supplies and markets of the
Soviet era are a thing of the past, with Ukraine's industrial enterprises struggling to survive
against the backdrop of domestic decline and increased competition.<br>
Government subsidies have avoided mass unemployment but slowed the reform process
and the creation of a private sector. By 1994 a mere 10 per cent of Ukrainian enterprises
were in the private sector, producing 20 per cent of GDP compared to 40 per cent in Russia.
The introduction of competitive forces and world prices caused inflation to soar to a
staggering 4,735 per cent in 1993. Not surprisingly wages have failed to keep up with the
price rises, leading to falling purchasing power and living standards.<br>
The worst of the recession has been weathered, with the five year decline bottoming out
slightly in 1995 with GDP `only' falling by 11.8 per cent compared to 23 per cent in 1994. The
1995 budget deficit was greater than expected as the government granted subsidies in order
to prevent mass unemployment, despite estimated `hidden' unemployment of 3.6 million, 13
per cent of the workforce.<br>
Almost the entire formal economy remains monopolised with a high degree of integration and
concentration. Regional leaders, particularly in the agricultural sector, have retained the
power and influence they enjoyed in the communist era. When combined with the communist
deputies in parliament they have prevented the widespread structural reforms essential for
the creation of a functioning market economy.
<P>
<b>Macro-economic performance</b>
<P>
The Ukrainian economy shrank by 11.8 per cent in 1995. Although an improvement on 1994
when GDP fell by 23 per cent, five years of declining output are a strong indication of the
failure of the economic reform programme.<br>
The reduction of inflation from 21 per cent a month in January 1995 to 2.4 per cent by April
1996 helped to give the karbovanets (the `temporary' currency introduced in November
1992) some real value and also kept the international financial institutions happy. The
government's tight monetary policy has been one of its few successes, however further price
liberalisation due in 1996 will increase inflationary pressures.<br>
Ukraine's external debt grew from US$6 billion in 1994 to US$8 billion by 1 January 1996.
Approximately US$4.6 billion is owed to other former Soviet Republics, principally Russia
and Turkmenistan for energy supplies. Western financial institutions were owed US$2.1
billion. Ukraine reached an agreement in March 1995 to restructure US$2.5 billion of its debt
to Russia.<br>
By the beginning of June 1996 only 60 per cent of housing and utility costs were met by
charges to the population. The government plans to remove all subsidies by the end of 1996.
<P>
<b>Monetary policy</b>
<P>
The central bank's tight monetary policy has provided the government with its one economic
success story, reducing inflation to 2.4 per cent a month by April 1996.<br>
Hyper-inflation in 1993 forced the government and the central bank to increase the
refinancing rate to 300 per cent by the end of 1994. The policy proved successful as inflation
fell from 891 per cent in 1994 to 380 per cent in 1995.<br>
By mid-1995 the rate had fallen to 60 per cent, however it was forced up again as inflation
increased to 5.2 per cent a month in May 1995. Since the beginning of 1996 the central bank
has again reduced the refinancing rate as inflation fell. By May 1996 it stood at 70 per cent.
<P>
<b>External aid</b>
<P>
Support from the international financial organisations is vital, with hard currency loans
essential to pay for Russian oil and gas and other imports. With loans and credits to Ukraine
dependent on the government's reform programme President Kuchma is faced with a stark
choice: give in to the communist dominated parliament and reign in the reform programme
and therefore lose the support of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank, or
attempt to follow the recommendations of the financial institutions and further alienate
parliament and the subsidy hungry industrial and agricultural enterprises.<br>
The pressures facing the president caused the IMF to refuse the release of the second half of
a US$1.5 billion stand-by loan in January 1996 after a larger than expected budget deficit
and the central bank had been forced to print more money by parliament. The loan was
renegotiated with an extra US$200 million added, however the IMF froze it again in April
1996 after the government overshot its first quarter spending target. The adoption of a
revised 1996 state budget enabled the IMF to resume its programme of stand-by loans in
May 1996. A budget deficit equivalent to 6.2 per cent of GDP was agreed by both sides, an
increase from the initial 6 per cent. The extra deficit will be covered by National Bank credits
worth about US$200 million. The US$900 million loan will be granted in US$100 million
tranches over a nine month period. Ukraine received US$760 million in stand-by credits from
the IMF during 1995.<br>
The importance of external financing and aid to Ukraine is clearly demonstrated when
compared with foreign direct investment. By the end of 1995 foreign investment totalled
US$783 million; external aid equalled US$1.65 billion.<br>
The major loans granted to Ukraine include: a US$160 million credit facility from the
European Union (EU), the first US$50 million of which was released in June 1996 with a
second US$50 million instalment due in September 1996 and the remainder before the end
of the year; the Japanese Eximbank agreed to grant Ukraine an economic stabilisation loan
of US$235 million in January 1996; and the USA agreed commercial credits and grants worth
US$119 million for the 1996 fiscal year in February 1996.<br>
Balance of payment loans include Ecu220 million from the EU in 1995 and US$250 million
from the USA in direct support for the 1995 balance of payment.<br>
About half of the US$1.65 billion in aid received by the beginning of 1996 had gone on
technical assistance (consultancy fees).
<P>
<b>Budget</b>
<P>
In 1992 the budget deficit was equivalent to a massive 30.4 per cent of GDP. This was
reduced to 11.6 per cent in 1993 and 8.6 per cent in 1994. Although the deficit fell again in
1995 to 4.1 per cent (according to IMF rather than government figures which put the deficit at
about 8.1 per cent of GDP), this was still above the 3 per cent target of the IMF as the
government continued to release subsidies to industrial enterprises.<br>
The 1996 deficit was initially predicted at 6 per cent, however this was increased to 6.2 per
cent in May 1996 following an agreement with the IMF. The deficit will be financed by foreign
loans (US$1 billion), government bonds (US$800 million) and National Bank credits (US$600
million).
<P>
<b>Economic outlook</b>
<P>
GDP is expected to fall by only 1.8 per cent in 1996, with the first post-Soviet growth
predicted for 1997. The government is also predicting small increases in industrial output (up
0.8 per cent) and agriculture (up 0.2 per cent). Inflation in 1996 is expected to be between 50
and 55 per cent.<br>
With vast agricultural potential and the second largest market in the region, after Russia, the
longer-term future of Ukraine is more encouraging. However, until real structural reforms
take place, particularly privatisation in the industrial sector, the Ukrainian economy will
continue to stagnate. The first, small, signs of macro-economic stability were experienced in
1995, however such stabilisation remains fragile, particularly with the anti-reform left-wing
parties dominating parliament and powerful local forces remaining opposed to change.
<P>
<a name="Overview"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Overview of State Sector</h3>
Background and government policy<br>
<P>
The political intransigence of Ukraine's first democratically elected government meant that by
the end of 1992, 96 per cent of the economy remained in state hands. By 1994 a mere 10
per cent of enterprise were in the private sector, producing 20 per cent of GDP.
Private sector companies face numerous daunting challenges attempting to survive in the
face of state sector monopolies and restricted practices. Wholesale, state-owned, trade
organisations prevent private companies gaining access to the supply and distribution
networks vital to their success.<br>
Parliament is determined to retain control and prevent the privatisation of as many areas of
the economy as possible. Gas and oil enterprises have been removed from the privatisation
programme and communist deputies have attempted to renationalise agricultural enterprises.
<P>
<a name="Main"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Main Companies</h3>
<P>
Main state owned companies
<P>
