                Sea Shipping Company and the Danube Shipping Company</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ukrnafta</td><td>Oil company</td></tr>
<tr><td>Utel</td><td>Telecommunications</td></tr>
</table>
<P>
<a name="Manufacturing"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Manufacturing and Service Industry</h3>
<b>Summary</b><br>
<P>
Seen as a strength upon independence, Ukraine's vast industrial complex (much of it military
orientated) has proved anything but. Highly concentrated and integrated it has proved almost
immune to the weak restructuring efforts of the government. Production has collapsed as
subsidy dependent enterprises found themselves ill-equipped and prepared to cope with the
advent of market forces. Saddled with outdated, inefficient and poorly maintained equipment
the dire financial state of most enterprises, with many unable to pay their workers, has
prevented any investment in new equipment or techniques.<br>
Industrial output fell a disastrous 28 per cent in 1994, and although the 9 per cent fall in 1995
was not as bad, chronic energy shortages and huge inter-enterprise arrears prevented any
recovery in output.
<P>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The Ukrainian industrial sector is concentrated around the heavy industries of the
metallurgical, mining and mechanical engineering sectors. However, raw material shortages,
the disappearance of guaranteed markets in the former Soviet Union, obsolete equipment
and the complete lack of the finance required to improve production methods and quality has
left the sector struggling for survival.<br>
Ukraine inherited a vast industrial complex from the USSR. In 1989 Ukraine produced 34 per
cent of the Soviet Union's steel, 46 per cent of iron ore, 53 per cent of sugar and 36 per cent
of all television sets. However the industrialised legacy of the former USSR has proved more
of a handicap than a help, with massive industrial dinosaurs sucking up state credits while
contributing less and less to the economy.<br>
State subsidies, particularly for energy, have prevented any major reforms. No large state-
owned enterprises have been closed down, as weak factories survive on cheap credits and
inter-enterprise debt. Bankruptcy is a taboo subject and with President Kuchma's supporters
concentrated in the industrialised eastern half of Ukraine, it is likely to remain so.
Ukraine's enterprises are mired in a massive debt trap; by 1 March 1996 the country's
enterprises owed a total of Krb3,949.7 trillion and were themselves owed Krb2,946.1 trillion.
Confusion over taxation (particularly value added tax on exports), a tax system that favours
imports, incomplete bankruptcy legislation, lengthy delays in the restructuring process and
the high proportion of barter trade are the principle problems.
<P>
<b>Recent output</b>
<P>
Industrial output fell by 11.5 per cent in 1995 according to the government, a significant
improvement on the disastrous fall of 28 per cent in 1994. Chronic energy shortages were the
main cause of falling output, with the removal of state energy subsidies for local enterprises
in December 1994 a further blow.<br>
Industrial output fell 2.5 per cent in the first four months of 1996, compared to a fall of 12.7
per cent on the corresponding period in 1995. The worst performing sector was light industry,
particularly textiles, while output from the metallurgy sector began to stabilise.
<P>
<table>
Industrial output<br>
% change<br>
