<P>
<b>Defence industry</b>
<P>
Ukraine had the most advanced rocket industry in the former Soviet Union and was also a
major producer of tanks and aircraft.<br>
Since independence the arms sector has remained a substantial export earner. In 1995
earnings from the industry were estimated at Krb2.93 billion, with prices often 20 per cent
cheaper than other international manufacturers. Weapons on offer from Ukraine include the
T-84 and T-90 tanks, Grad missile launchers and equipment, Tu-160 and Tu-95 MS strategic
bombers and missile carriers. Russia, India, Pakistan and several Latin American states are
among the largest customers. The defence industry has been excluded from the privatisation
programme. The industry has survived mainly because of the high standard of product, with
the majority of specialists in the sector remaining in Ukraine. The production of NATO
standard weapons is planned.<br>
Three projects totalling US$64 million were agreed in October 1995 to convert military
production facilities to commercial joint ventures. The United States Department of Defense
contributed US$47 million in contract awards, with the American companies involved
contributing US$17 million in cash, technology and licensing. The contracts include the
conversion of Monolit, a manufacturer of aircraft, spacecraft and missile systems, into a
manufacturer of digital instrumentation and control systems for nuclear power stations; the
creation of a joint venture with Meridian of Kiev to convert an electronic and radar equipment
facility into a factory manufacturing die cast consumer products; and a joint venture between
the American Industrial Development Corporation and Orizon.<br>
The conversion of naval shipbuilding yards into commercial yards began in 1992 when a joint
venture at the Zaliv shipyard in Kerch on the Crimean coast was established by Pepsi-Cola
and Fram Shipping, a Bermuda based shipping company. The first three ships of an order for
six product tankers were delivered in mid-1995. A well trained and low wage labour force also
attracted a British joint venture in 1995. British Ukrainian Shipbuilders was formed by the
London based Ukrainian Development Corporation and the Ukrainian ministry responsible for
military production and developing commercial activities. The venture plans to construct hulls
at Ukrainian yards using local steel with the remaining equipment and services supplied by
UK companies. British Ukrainian Shipbuilders will construct 70,000 tonne bulk carriers for
between US$25 and US$26 million, compared to US$34 million in Japan or US$30 million in
South Korea.<br>
The once important satellite rocket industry received a boost in December 1995 with the
signing of the Sea Launch Project in Norway. The US$600 million programme involves 60
commercial satellite launches using Ukrainian rockets, with the first launch due in 1998. The
project includes Norway (which will provide a disused oil platform from which to launch the
rockets in the Pacific Ocean), the USA (principally through the Boeing aircraft company) and
Russia (which will provide the engines for the Ukrainian Zenit booster rockets). The NPO-
Yuzhmash plant in central Ukraine, the largest rocket nuclear missile plant in the world during
the Soviet era, has re-orientated production to commercial rockets and now manufactures
the Zenit rockets. The plant was formerly run by President Kuchma. Zenit boosters will also
be used to launch 20 American Government backed satellites, 11 within the Sea Launch
programme. Ukraine has also won a tender to launch 36 satellites for the US
communications company Global Star.
<P>
<b>Automobile industry</b>
<P>
Ukraine was a major manufacturer of buses, trucks and cars in the Soviet Union, however
demand from the other republics has collapsed. As with other sectors dependent on the
markets of the USSR the automobile industry has struggled to compete internationally, and
with domestic demand slumping as living standards decline the sector is in desperate need of
investment and rationalisation.<br>
Ukraine's largest car manufacturer, AO AvtoZAZ, requires investment of US$800 million in
order to modernise and replace existing machinery and equipment. The plant produced
59,000 cars in 1995, down from 150,000 during the 1970s and 1980s. The government is
trying to attract a foreign investor willing to commit the finance necessary to increase output
to 300,000 units a year. The plant, in the eastern city of Zaporizha, employs about 29,000,
with a further 130 firms dependent on its survival.<br>
The Italian truck manufacturer Iveco set up a joint venture with the Ukrainian truck company
Kremenchug Automobile Plant (KrAZ) in 1995. Iveco-KrAZ plan to produce 2,000 trucks in
1996 and 30,000 a year by 2000. Iveco, a subsidiary of Fiat, invested US$60 million for a 35
per cent stake in the joint venture with a further US$40 million to be invested in new
equipment and upgraded production facilities. The European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development (EBRD) took a 30 per cent stake for US$18 million with KrAZ (Ukraine's largest
commercial vehicle manufacturer) holding the remaining 35 per cent.
<P>
<b>Metallurgical industry</b>
<P>
Ukraine is the fourth largest steel producer in the world (after Japan, Russia and the USA).
There are 10 integrated steel plants, the largest three at Krivoy Roj, Azovstal and Iliyich. In
the international markets Ukrainian products can only compete at the lower quality end of the
market.<br>
Ukraine steel exports to the EU are regulated by a two year quota agreement which expires
at the end of 1996. If subsidies to the industry are cut and EU style regulations limiting future
state subsidies are adopted, a free trade agreement with the EU on steel exports is possible.
Ukraine's sole alumina refinery at Nykolayev produced 996,000 tonnes of alumina in 1995.
Output is predicted to reach 1.03 million tonnes in 1996, with production increasing to 1.5
million tonnes by 2000. Total capacity of the plant is over one million tonnes a year.
Aluminium smelters in Russia and Tajikistan received 90 per cent of the plant's output, with
the majority of ore coming from Guyana in west African. Aluminium output fell to 95,100
tonnes in 1995, down 2.7 per cent on 1994. Ukraine's only aluminium smelter is in Zaporizha.
<P>
<b>Light industry</b>
<P>
Ukraine's largest textile factories are centred around Kherson, Kiev, Ternapol and Donetsk
(cotton); Zhytomyr and Rivne (linen); Lugansk, Odessa and Chernihiv (woollen fabrics); and
Kiev and Cherkasy (silk). Although well developed the textile, leather and footwear industries
do not satisfy domestic demand.<br>
The Swedish-Swiss engineering group Asea Brown Boveri (ABB) formed a joint venture with
the Ukrainian Rovno High-Voltage Equipment Plant in April 1996. ABB will invest US$19
million over a five year period in return for a 51 per cent stake in the ABB REVA venture
which will manufacture high and mid-voltage switches.
<P>
<b>Services</b>
<P>
The service sector is one of the most underdeveloped areas of the economy and therefore
one with great potential. Tourism in particular offers possibilities, although large-scale
investment is required to upgrade existing facilities and develop new resorts.<br>
The Crimean Black Sea resorts, centred around Yalta, were the traditional summer retreats
of the Tsarist courts and Soviet Politburo. However Ukrainian independence and tension
between the region's Russian population and the Kiev Government has deterred Russian and
Ukrainian holidaymakers. Those with the disposable income now jet off to the south of
France, Italy and Turkey leaving the tourist industry struggling. Yalta's hotels operated at
about 70 per cent capacity during the 1995 summer, compared to a decade earlier when
demand exceeded supply. The number of tourists visiting the Crimea was two million in
1994, falling from a peak of between eight and 10 million during the 1980s. Tourism is the
main industry in the Crimea, with 635 resorts and hotels with 142,000 rooms. The Black Sea
coast has enormous tourism potential, with a good climate and excellent beaches and
coastline.<br>
The first foreign involvement in Crimea's tourist industry was announced in October 1995. A
Canadian consortium of Smith Carter and Hemisphere Engineering announced a US$6.6
million plan to renovate and operate the Hotel Tavrida in Yalta.<br>
Kiev is due to receive its first five-star hotel by 1999. Central European Investments (UK)
agreed to refurbish and operate the Moscow Hotel in April 1996. Previous attempts to open a
western style and quality hotel were blocked by the city council which owns the Intourist
hotels where western prices were charged for Soviet style and standard rooms and service.
<P>
<a name="Labour"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Labour Market</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
Employers in Ukraine are required to comply with one of three types of labour agreements: agreements of unrestricted duration; agreements for a specified duration; or agreements for the duration of a specific project. Employment contracts also include agreements on working hours (usually a maximum of 41 hours a week), wages, frequency of payment (minimum once a fortnight), holidays etc. Every foreign enterprise employing local workers must have a work register detailing the full information on employment contracts. The register also forms the basis for deducting social contributions and pension claims.<br>
The average wage in October 1995 was US$55.07, an increase from US$30.59 at the end of 1994. In 1995 real wages increased for the first time since independence. A survey at the end of 1995 found that Ukrainians earn on average US$15.90 a month in their official job and a further US$29.30 through secondary activities (private vegetable lots, taxi driving etc).
The proportion of the workforce employed in the service sector had grown to an estimated 41 per cent by 1994, overtaking the traditionally largest employer, industry, which employed 37 per cent. Agriculture employs 19 per cent and mining 3 per cent of the labourforce. The retirement age for men is 60 and for women 55.
<P>
<b>Unemployment situation</b>
<p>
Hidden unemployment of up to 3.6 million by the beginning of 1996 (about 13 per cent of the workforce) is on the rise as workers are left unpaid and part-time employment increases. At the same time the number of officially registered unemployed increased to 139,200 in February 1996, 0.5 per cent of the workforce of 27.6 million.
<P>
<b>Trade unions</b>
<P>
The power and influence of trade unions, traditionally little more than a subservient branch of the communist party, has grown since independence. Their increased strength has been felt particularly in the coal mining sector. A series of strikes in the first few months of 1996 over non-payment of wages put the government under pressure and forced them to water down closure and restructuring plans.
<P>
<a name="External"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>External Trade</h3>
<b>Summary</b>
<P>
The collapse of the COMECON trading bloc had a detrimental effect on Ukraine's foreign trade as the allocated and free markets of the Soviet period closed almost overnight. Payment problems for Russian oil and gas, now priced at world market levels, has reduced the supply of imported energy, which has contracted industrial output and limited exports.
Trade with the west has declined since independence, with a deficit of US$1.9 billion in 1994 compared to US$1.6 billion in 1993. The demand for imports, centred around energy but including machinery and consumer goods, has increased Ukraine's foreign borrowing. Increasing imports can only be sustained if the country's export performance in western markets improves significantly.
<P>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The government liberalised the trading environment following independence, with numerous enterprises authorised to undertake external trade. Businesses wishing to carry out foreign trade require must register with the Ministry of Foreign Economic Relations. State sector enterprises remain the dominant force in foreign trade transactions, principally because they have maintained their contacts from the Soviet era.<br>
An interim trading agreement with the EU came into force at the beginning of February 1996. A free trade agreement with Estonia was ratified by the Ukrainian Parliament in February 1996, lifting all trade barriers between the two countries.<br>
Excise duties range from 10 to 200 per cent. Customs duties range from five to 10 per cent on most goods, with luxury goods levied at between 20 and 50 per cent.<br>
Barter trade remains commonplace, especially with the states of the former Soviet Union. Energy imports from Russia, Turkmenistan and Kazakhstan dominate Ukraine's foreign trade. The imposition of world market prices forced the government to reduce energy raw material imports and increase the amount of barter deals involving agricultural products in particular.
<P>
<b>Imports</b>
<P>
Import licences are only required for goods which pose a danger to health or the environment. Trade samples of no value are exempt from import duties, as are presentation samples. Samples with a trade value are exempt from duty as long as they are re-exported within 12 months, although that period may be extended.<br>
From 1 July 1995 the government imposed a 15 per cent tax on imported light fuel products and a 15 per cent retail tax on imported petrol and diesel fuel.<br>
Imports in 1995 totalled US$9.8 billion, a fall of US$300 million compared to 1994. States of the former USSR accounted for about 53 per cent of all trade.<br>
Imports from Russia fell by more than US$500 million to about US$5.8 million in 1995, from 59.1 to 51.2 per cent of total imports. Although the economy continued to shrink in 1995 trade with non-Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) countries increased, with imports growing by 48 per cent an exports by 21 per cent.<br>
Ukrainian imports are centred around energy (from Russia), timber and industrial equipment and machinery.
<P>
<b>Exports</b>
<P>
An October 1994 decree liberalised export operations, with licences only required for grain, scrap metal, pig iron, ferrous and non-ferrous metals. A licence is not required for other goods exported from Ukraine.<br>
Export quotas are applicable to certain goods which are of essential significance to the Ukrainian economy. Legislation preventing the dumping of Ukrainian goods abroad was introduced in 1994. Quota regulations are subject to frequent change.<br>
In 1995 exports were US$10.2 billion. Exports to Russia increased by nearly US$1 billion to over US$5 billion in 1995. Russia's share of Ukrainian exports grew from 39.6 to 43.5 per cent of total exports.<br>
Principle exports include coal, iron ore machinery and manganese ore.
<P>
<table>
