<P>
<b>Balance of trade</b>
<P>
The trade deficit in the first quarter of 1996 was US$553.3 million, almost double the US$280 million on the corresponding period in 1995. In 1995 there was a trade surplus of US$400 million, due to lower imports. However government figures are notoriously unreliable. If the black market and unrecorded trade was taken into account it is likely that Ukraine recorded a trade deficit in 1995.<br>
Ukraine's trade deficit with Russia fell from US$42 billion in 1994 to US$1.2 billion in 1995, with Ukrainian exports, particularly of agricultural products, increasing. Ukraine's total trade deficit with the former Soviet Republics was US$1.126 billion in 1995
<P>
<a name="Privatisation"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Privatisation</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The 1994 privatisation programme succeeded in offering only 700 companies for sale from a planned 1,300 medium and large scale enterprises and about 9,000 small-scale enterprises. A moratorium placed on the privatisation process by parliament in July 1994 halted the programme.<br>
In January 1995 the cabinet attempted to revive the privatisation process by approving an ambitious programme to privatise 22,700 large, medium and small enterprises and 1,200 unfinished construction sites by the end of 1995. However Parliament again blocked the proposals as insufficient (a stalling measure) while adopting a list of objects not subject to privatisation. President Kuchma eventually got his way in June 1995 when he passed a decree `On measures for Providing for Privatisation in 1995'. However privatisation in the first half of the year was minimal: only 2,166 small scale enterprises were privatised from a target of 9,647, and 1,087 large enterprises from a targeted 3,971. The majority of privatisation between 1992 and mid-1995 had taken place through worker buy-outs or leasing association buy-outs on a non-competitive basis.<br>
In July 1995 President Kuchma signed a decree permitting the privatisation and leasing of non-agricultural land for business purposes. The decree increases access to greenfield sites for foreign investors by providing clear ownership rights. Although the decree grants Ukrainian citizens and legal entities the right to privatise land, these rights are not extended to non-residents. However a Ukrainian registered company (subsidiary or joint venture) can participate in the land privatisation process. The sale of the land is carried out by local councils on a competitive bidding basis where more than one party is interested. The decree also resolves the question of ownership of land on which buildings have already been privatised. The purchasers of buildings have the right to buy or lease the land on which their buildings are on. Industrial property can be leased for a maximum 50 years, after which the leasee has the priority right to extend the lease for another 50 years.<br>
The State Property Fund (SPF) is responsible for privatising state enterprises. As state enterprises become desperate for investment the government's attitude to foreign involvement is relaxing, particularly as domestic privatisation does not involve any injection of capital or management experience.<br>
The direct sale of stock to a single strategic investor on the basis of an individual business plan aims to ease the transfer of enterprises on the brink of bankruptcy. To participate in the privatisation process a foreign investor must formally apply through the SPF, whereupon the percentage available to the investor is determined after negotiation. In July 1995 the SPF revealed a list of 15 large enterprises to undergo preparation for privatisation and a further 86 in which foreign participation would be sought - the first time the SPF has made a concerted effort to attract foreign investment.<br>
Reform of the energy sector was planned for 1995, with the monopoly electricity producer broken up into autonomous suppliers competing on the national market and bidding for contracts with local distribution companies. Although most energy prices were liberalised, Kuchma and his cabinet lost their nerve and had put the programme on indefinite hold by the end of 1995. Parliament has removed all energy sector enterprise from the privatisation process.<br>
Residential privatisation has been more successful, with 8.5 million flats privatised between 1993 and mid-1995. There has been no land restitution in Ukraine.<br>
By 1 April 1996, 32.64 million Ukrainian citizens had received privatisation certificates, which have to be used by 31 December 1996 when the mass privatisation of medium and large enterprise is due for completion. The certificates have a nominal value of Krb1 or Krb2 million, with a total value of Krb3,910 billion. A network of regional centres has been established where auctions are held in which Ukrainian citizens can purchase shares with their certificates. Because the certificates are `named' investors cannot obtain, either through sale or gift, certificates which are not in their name, making it extremely difficult to gain a majority holding in an Ukrainian enterprise. Certificates can be acquired through financial intermediaries - trust companies, investment funds and companies. However investors should be very cautious and careful when dealing with financial intermediaries.<br>
The so called `trust companies' are estimated to have defrauded the Ukrainian population of about US$18 million during 1994 after collecting money and privatisation certificates and then disappearing. The first decree on trust companies permitted anybody to register a trust company with a minimum capital of Krb1 million. No licence was required from the national bank. The government was finally forced into action in 1995, suspending 17 companies in April and revoking the licences of 34 in June 1995. Revised accounting and operating regulations were introduced at the end of 1995.<br>
By the beginning of 1996 there were about 600 registered trust companies, 315 of which had licences to operate with privatisation certificates. Violations of tax and operating regulations are common.
<P>
<b>Current programme</b>
<P>
In February 1996 President Kuchma pledged that privatisation would be one of the government's top priorities during 1996 following the limited programme in 1995.
Also in February 1996 the president vetoed a communist backed plant to give a free 51 per cent stake in Ukraine's food industries to collective farm directors, including those enterprises already privatised. Under the proposals the vertical monopoly in the agricultural sector would have been retained, as well as removing about half of the companies due to be sold in the mass privatisation programme. Kuchma vetoed a similar plan in 1995.<br>
The small-scale privatisation programme (including agricultural enterprises) is due to be complete by 1 July 1996.<br> 
The privatisation of Ukraine's most attractive sectors, oil, gas, defence production and agribusinesses has been blocked by parliament. Parliament also banned the privatisation of the gas transit sector in January 1996 due to fears that Russia would gain control of pipelines and storage areas. A gas debt for ownership swop had been proposed.
<P>
<b>Major privatisations</b>
<P>
The purchase of an 88.4 per cent stake for US$25 million in the leading confectionery company Ukraina in February 1995 by Swiss based Kraft Jacob Suchard (a subsidiary of Philip Morris) is exceptional by its rarity. The first large-scale involvement of a foreign investor in Ukraine's privatisation process, the deal was unusual in that Ukrainian citizens were excluded from bidding for shares in the company with their privatisation certificates (the remaining 11.6 per cent was allocated to the workers). The purchase of a majority stake giving absolute operational control, without which Kraft would not have gone ahead, set a precedent whereby the mandatory allocation of shares to the Ukrainian population can be bypassed in order to attract foreign investment.
<P>
<b>Extent of success/failure</b>
<P>
The Ukrainian privatisation programme has failed to attract the investment, and therefore modern equipment, technology and management techniques Ukraine desperately needs. Although the investment environment is improving, the communist dominated parliament is proving a serious obstacle to the privatisation efforts of the president. The drastic restructuring essential to the Ukrainian economy, especially the large state-owned enterprises, is ultimately dependent on a resolution of the conflict between parliament and president.<br>
In 1995 only 39 per cent of about 8,000 medium and large enterprises and 51 per cent of small enterprises were privatised; the government had planned to privatise them all. A combination of the communist controlled parliament, ineffective privatisation bodies and obstructive local authorities left the privatisation process in turmoil.<br>
Privatisation targets were exceeded in the first quarter of 1996. According to the SPF the privatisation of 6,097 enterprises was launched or completed between January and the end of March 1996, including 5,104 small businesses and 941 medium and large businesses. Since 1992 the total number of small firms privatised is 27,297, with over 3,800 medium and large enterprises privatised.
<P>
<a name="Banking"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Banking</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
A two-tier banking structure was created in 1991, with the National Bank of Ukraine (NBU) taking the role of the central bank. The five successor banks of the former Soviet state-owned specialist banks dominate the private sector, with a further 220 smaller private banks. Two of the former specialist banks remain directly state-owned with the other three majority owned by state enterprises.
<P>
<b>Role of the central bank</b>
<P>
The central bank is responsible for monetary policy including setting interests rates, regulating and supervising commercial banks and currency regulations.<br>
From January 1995 the minimum capital requirement for new banks was increased to Ecu3 million, to Ecu5 million for minority owned foreign banks and Ecu10 million for majority owned foreign banks. Existing banks were required to increase their capital to Ecu0.5 million by January 1996. Also from January 1995 banks were required to make provisions for possible credit losses. The provision amounts are zero for a standard credit, 5 per cent for satisfactory credits, 30 per cent for marginal credits, 80 per cent for doubtful credits and 100 per cent for irretrievable credits. The upper limit for credit to a single borrower is 40 per cent of the capital.
<P>
<b>Commercial banks</b>
<P>
The Ukrainian banking sector is highly concentrated, with the top five banks holding about 70 per cent of the total banking assets (compared to 33 per cent in Russia).<br>
There were over 220 banks in Ukraine by mid-1995, all but two owned by non-government entities, however the majority of larger banks remain under indirect state control. The State Savings Bank and Foreign Trade Bank are state-owned, while the former state banks Prominvest, Ukraina and Ukrosotsbank have retained their links with industry, agriculture and housing and co-operatives respectively and are owned by state enterprises.<br>
The state-owned banks are the largest and have the most experience, however they continue to make loans to uncreditworthy enterprises which has left them with outstanding debts. The sector has too many small commercial banks and a period of rationalisation is inevitable, with the high levels of inter-enterprise debt exacerbating the situation.<br>
In February 1996 the EBRD announced it was setting up the Kiev International Investment Bank in association with Bank Ukraina and the Ukrainskaya Finansovaya Gruppa. The bank, with a starting capital of Ecu5 million, will be 49 per cent owned by the EBRD with the two Ukrainian banks taking the remaining share.
<P>
