<P>
<b>Foreign banks</b>
<P>
The French bank Credit Lyonnais was the first foreign bank to establish operations in Ukraine.
<P>
<a name="Investment"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Investment and Trading (regulations and policy)</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
A law passed in March 1996 and coming into effect on 1 July 1996 requires all retail trade outlets, currency exchange bureaux and gambling businesses to obtain licences. The licences cost Ecu160 a month for retail traders and between Ecu350 and Ecu8,000 a month for gambling businesses. Trading activities by enterprises and organisations of the Ukrainian co-operative union or domestic producers selling their own products do not require licences.
The Agency for Insurance Protection of Private Entrepreneurship and Small Business was created on 26 July 1995, as was the Fund for Support of Private Entrepreneurship and Small Business Support.<br>
A Law on Bankruptcy was adopted in May 1992, although enforcement has been minimal.
<P>
<b>Foreign investment (regulations and restrictions)</b>
<P>
Foreigners may wholly own and manage limited responsibility partnerships or joint-stock companies with the free repatriation of profits. Approval of the central bank is usually required to transfer convertible currencies abroad. Government approval for foreign investment proposals is only required in joint ventures with state enterprises or in key sectors. Full compensation is payable if private property is expropriated.<br>
All foreign investments must be registered with the Ministry for Foreign Economic Relations. The registration period for limited liability and joint-stock companies is usually about two months. Licences are required for specific activities including the production and sale of alcohol and tobacco and the exploitation of mineral resources. Applications to establish an enterprise in Ukraine must be submitted to the district or local authority of the area where the business is to be established. Following approval from the local authorities the company will be registered with the Ministry of Finance in order to receive a tax registration number and be eligible for tax exemptions. A karbovanets bank account must also be opened.<br>
Investment options available to foreign investors include acquiring stock through the privatisation process. In February 1996 the government listed over 100 joint stock companies and state-owned enterprises to be privatised with foreign investment. Investors will be chosen on a competitive basis through the sale of blocks of shares. The acquisition of private enterprises (made easier since the beginning of 1996 as the privatisation of small enterprises has speeded up), the creation of joint ventures or developing greenfield sites are also possible.<br>
The Ukrainian foreign investment environment had improved by mid-1996, with the potential rewards of the huge market no longer justifying the inactivity of western companies. With Ukrainians starved of quality goods and services there is little competition to satisfy their growing demand.
<P>
<b>Currency</b>
<P>
Ukraine left the Russian rouble zone in November 1992, introducing the karbovanets (Krb), a `temporary' currency. In January 1993 there were Krb700 to US$1; by December 1994 spiralling inflation sent the exchange rate soaring to around Krb130,000 and in May 1996 the exchange rate was Krb184,200 to the US$1. Hard currency can be changed in hotels or at the numerous street kiosks. Changing money on the black market is illegal and with little difference in the rates not worth it. The sight of illegal money exchangers carrying plastic bags stuffed with notes is a common one in hotel foyers.<br>
The multiple exchange rates were unified in October 1994, with the official rate determined at the Ukrainian Interbank Currency Exchange.<br>
The karbovanets was due to be replaced by a permanent currency, the hryvnia, in October 1995. However, the new currency, printed in 1993 and stored in national bank vaults since then, had not been introduced by June 1996. Failure to stabilise the karbovanets at the end of 1995 led to the postponement of the hryvnia until 1996.<br>
The karbovanets is not convertible and can therefore not be used in international payment transfers, bids and invoices, all of which must be issued in convertible currencies.<br> Businesses registered with the Ministry for Foreign Economic Relations can purchase hard currencies to pay for import transactions.<br>
A December 1995 National Bank resolution requires Ukrainian citizens to obtain a licence before receiving hard currency from foreign lenders.<br>
Hard currency transactions were prohibited in mid-1995, affecting the 1,200 businesses permitted to trade in dollars rather than the karbovanets.
<P>
<a name="Financial"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Financial Markets</h3>
<b>Background</b>
<P>
The Ukraine Stock Exchange, founded in 1991, is the most regulated and centralised trading system in Ukraine. The average trading volume in mid-1995 was US$3,000 a day. No independent and transparent share registration and share custody exists and the rights of minority shareholders are not protected. The creation of a state committee to regulate the securities market was decreed in June 1995. The stock exchange also trades investment certificates of investment funds.<br>
At the beginning of 1995 there were 91 exchanges operating in Ukraine, 14 trading in stocks, four in real estate and the remainder in commodities, with trading concentrated in Kiev. The majority of trade took place through an unregulated over-the-counter market.<br>
Ukraine's main currency exchange, the Interbank Currency Exchange, announced it would conduct secondary trading in government securities three times a week from March 1996. The exchange plans to hold daily trading in treasury bills eventually.
<P>
<a name="Foreign"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Foreign Investment Activity</h3>
<P>
By the end of 1995 Ukraine had attracted US$783 million in direct foreign investment since independence. Confused and inconsistent taxation laws, slow privatisation and an absence of investment security have hampered government attempts to attract substantial investment. The largest investors in Ukraine are the USA (US$171.4 million), Germany (US$129.6 million) and the UK (US$46.3 million).<br>
During the same period Ukraine has received around US$1.65 billion in aid from the USA and the EU, half of which was spent on `technical assistance' (consultancy fees).
<P>
<table>
Foreign investment in Ukraine<br>
(US$ million)<br>
<tr><td>1991-92</td><td>171.4</td></tr>
<tr><td>1993</td><td>209.4</td></tr>
<tr><td>1994</td><td>244.6</td></tr>
<tr><td>1995 </td><td>157.6</td></tr>
<tr><td>TOTAL</td><td>783.0</td></tr>
</table>
Source: Ministry of Statistics
</pre>
<P>
The level of foreign investment in Ukraine is disproportionately low considering its size and population, only US$11.4 per person compared to US$700 per person in Hungary. The Ukrainian State Credit and Investment Corporation estimates that Ukraine needs about US$5 billion in foreign investment (including US$1.7 billion for oil processing, US$2 billion for metallurgy, US$500 million for machine production and US$250 million for the energy sector).<br>
The enormous potential of Ukraine - an untapped market of 52 million people with a well educated workforce and rich farmland - presents an exciting opportunity, but only once the investment environment is clear and stable. The consumer goods market remains particularly under-developed, and although foreign brands are beginning to enter the market the sector has huge potential in the medium to long-term.<br>
As the financial climate has begun to stabilise (with help from the IMF) interest in Ukraine has picked up. By May 1996 companies reported to be interested in Ukraine included Cargill of the USA (construction of a sunflower processing plant); Philips of the Netherlands (lamp factory); McDonalds; Coca-Cola; Daewoo of South Korea (joint venture with the AvtoZaz auto manufacturer); and Hughes Network and Boeing Aircraft (a joint venture involving satellite launch rockets). However several multi-nationals, including General Motors, have made it clear they will not invest in Ukraine until the taxation environment becomes more attractive.
<P>
Companies that have invested in Ukraine
<P>
<table> 
