<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>Hydrocarbons and Electricity</h2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<li> <a href="#Electricity">Electricity</a>

<center>
<IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
<b>Summary</b>
<P>
Ukraine is heavily dependent on imports of Russian gas and oil to satisfy domestic energy requirements. The increase of energy supplies to world levels led to non-payment and the reduction of Russian exports to Ukraine in 1993. The Ukrainian state energy sector is on the verge of bankruptcy due to the large number of defaulting customers. Continued disputes between the two countries led to oil supplies to the Drogobych refinery being cut off in February 1996 and widespread energy shortages have prevented any recovery in industrial output.
<p>
Ukraine produced 25 per cent of the coal used in the former Soviet Union. The country's seven oil refineries have a total capacity of 1.24 million barrels per day (bpd). Ukraine's proven oil and gas reserves were not exploited during the Soviet era, when other regions (Siberia and central Asia) could be developed more cheaply.
Background and government policy<br>
Privatisation of the oil and gas sector was planned in 1995, however parliament threw out the proposals as oil and gas enterprises were excluded from the privatisation process. Without structural reform of the sector the investment required to repair and renew ageing pipelines and develop oil and gas fields will not be made available. Hardline deputies were primarily concerned with preventing Ukrhazprom, the company responsible for operating Ukraine's gas pipelines and exploiting the country's gas fields, from floating its shares. The parliamentary vote also prevented the Russian gas giant Gazprom from converting US$1.4 billion in Ukrainian bonds into equity in Ukrainian enterprises, including gas reserves and pipelines. Gazprom was given the bonds in 1993 and 1994 in a debt rescheduling deal over Ukrainian payment for Russian gas.<br>
Ukraine's coal mining sector, once a Soviet showpiece, is saddled with antiquated machinery and technology and exhausted pits. The sector began a restructuring process in January 1996 when the Coal Industry Ministry incorporated all state-owned enterprises subordinate to it. Twenty-six state-owned joint-stock coal mining and ore-enrichment companies were also created. The state will retain a minimum 51 per cent stake, under the control of the Coal Industry Ministry.<br>
In May 1995 the cabinet cut off state subsidies to loss making pits (worth US$50 million a month in 1994) and announced it would close 15 mines. However the closures were postponed in the face of strong parliamentary opposition. With whole towns dependent on the coal mining industry any closures would have considerable social consequences. In early 1996 the government again announced that it planned to close down at least 28 loss making pits over the next few years, with the possibility of up to 70 mines facing closure in the long-term. The number of miners at Ukraine's 257 pits had fallen from 529,000 to 426,017 by the end of 1995 as unpaid wages forced many workers to look for employment elsewhere.Two thousand coal miners at 16 pits in the Donetsk region resumed strikes over wage arrears in April 1996 after the government reneged on its promise to clear all debts to the coal industry. The original strike was suspended in February 1996 after assurances were reached that arrears would be paid.<br>
The World Bank agreed a US$15.8 million loan to the coal sector in May 1996 to assist in restructuring the industry. The money will principally be used to ease the social and environmental consequences of pit closures. Three mines in the Donetsk region in eastern Ukraine have been selected for the project.
<P>
<b>Reserves</b>
<P>
The Black Sea shelf has estimated gas reserves of 70 billion cubic metres. However the legal clarification of the Russian-Ukrainian border is required in order to legalise the ownership of planned drilling sites. The Crimean Peninsular is also estimated to have reserves of 1.3 billion barrels of oil-equivalent. Once (or if) the reserves are fully exploited Ukraine would become a net exporter of energy.<br>
Ukraine also has oilfields in the north and east in the Pridniprovsky, Prykarpatia, Chernihiv, Poltava, Kharkov and Sumy regions.<br>
The Donetsk region has estimated coal reserves of 56 billion tonnes, with smaller reserves in the Lvov-Volyn region (one billion tonnes).
<P>
<b>Exploration</b>
<P>
Until independence Ukraine had not been explored for oil since the early 1970s.<br>
A licensing agreement was signed between the Ukrainian Government and Epic Energy Incorporated (USA) in March 1996 covering the exploration and development of the shallow oil fields in the Kerch peninsular area. The agreement also provides for the future development of deeper oil and gas fields in the same region. Epic Energy and its Ukrainian partner Kyrmgeologia, already had a production sharing agreement to explore and exploit an 11,000 square km area around the Crimean Peninsular for the huge oil-equivalent reserves.
<P>
<b>Production</b>
<P>
Oil and gas production is expected to increase in 1996 for the first time in 20 years. Gas output is expected to rise from an estimated 17.44 billion cubic metres in 1995 to 18.2 billion cubic metres in 1996. Ukrhazprom accounted for 14.59 billion cubic metres of gas production and the oil company Ukrnafta 2.85 billion cubic metres. Crude oil production is expected to increase by 20,000 tonnes in 1996 from 4.2 million tonnes in 1995.<br>
Coal production in 1995 was estimated at 83.97 million tonnes, lower than expected and a fall of over 10 million tonnes on 1994 production. In 1990 coal output was 179 million tonnes. The industry has the highest worker casualty rate in the world, with five miners dying for every one million tonnes of coal mined.
<P>
<b>Commodity output</b>
<P>
<table colspan=9>
<tr><td>1992</td><td>1993</td><td>1994</td><td>1995</td></tr>
<tr><td>Coal (million tonnes)</td><td>133.7</td><td>115.8</td><td>94.4</td><td>83.97</td></tr>
<tr><td>Natural gas (million cubic metres)</td><td>20,882</td><td>19,221</td><td>18,316</td><td>*17,440</td></tr>
<tr><td>Crude petroleum ('000 tonnes)</td><td>4,474</td><td>4,248</td><td>4,198</td><td>4,200*</td></tr> 
</table>
Government estimates<br>
Source: OECD Short-term Indicators

<P>
The EBRD's first private sector loan to Ukraine was granted in April 1995. The US$8 million deal provided support to the Poltava Petroleum Company, a joint venture involving JKX Oil and Gas of the UK which holds a 49 per cent stake. The project, at the Nova-Nikolaevskoye field near Poltava, intends to increase daily production of oil to 1,700 tonnes of oil and 1.3 million cubic metres of gas by the second half of 1996. The field contains proven reserves of 1,100 billion cubic feet of natural gas and 60 million barrels of oil and oil condensate.
<P>
<b>Refining</b>
<P>
Ukraine's seven oil refineries, Lischansk (supplied with oil from western Siberia), Kremenchug, Kherson, Odessa, Drogobych, Nadvornaya and Lvov, have a capacity of 1.24 million bpd, the second largest in the region after Russia. The domestic market consumes the majority of output.<br>
The Drogobych refinery in western Ukraine had its oil supplies from Russia temporarily suspended in February 1996 due to a disagreement between the Ukrainian and Russian Governments over oil transit tariffs for the Druzhba pipeline. Ukraine increased the transit tariff from US$4.73 to US$5.20 per tonne on Russian oil going to eastern and central Europe on 1 January 1996. Hungary receives 22,000 tonnes a day and Slovakia and the Czech Republic a combined 28,000 tonnes. The pipeline, 715 km of which runs through Ukraine, has an annual flow of 18 million tonnes.<br>
The SPF proposed selling a 45 per cent stake in the Lisichansk oil refinery in a competitive tender between its Russian suppliers in May 1996. The winner would pay off some of the refinery's debts to the Italian company Tecnimont which constructed a polypropene manufacturing complex at the plant in 1994. The most likely contenders for the stake are Yukos, Rosneft, the Eastern Oil Company and the Tyumen Oil Company.
<P>
<b>Consumption</b>
<P>
Natural gas accounts for about 40 per cent of energy consumption in Ukraine, making it one of the most gas intensive economies in Europe.<br>
Gas supplies were cut to 86 large factories in March 1996 due to unpaid bills. Total arrears are estimated at US$840 million.
<P>
<b>Imports</b>
<P>
The high level of industrialisation and energy consumption means that Ukraine has been a net importer of energy since the 1970s. Compared with industry in western Europe Ukraine uses about 40 per cent more energy per capita.<br>
Ukraine imports 87 per cent of its oil and 83 per cent of natural gas requirements, principally from Russia and Turkmenistan. About US$6 billion of natural gas is bought from Russia annually. Other suppliers are being sought, however the limited unloading capacity of the Black Sea ports makes importing large quantities of oil impractical.<br>
Over 3,500 trading companies import fuel products into Ukraine. The largest are Nordex (Swiss/Austrian), Slavutitch (Ukraine), Roskontract (Russia) and the Russian Ukrainian Oil Company. Ukraine imports between seven and eight million tonnes of petrol a year, between nine and 10 million tonnes of diesel fuel, nine million tonnes of fuel oil and between one and 1.5 million tonnes of different oils and lubricants.<br>
Once a massive exporter of coal Ukraine is expected to import 20 million tonnes in 1996 as output has fallen to nearly half 1990 levels. Russia and Poland will supply the bulk of the coal at a cost of about US$500 million. Import payments will be through barter and countertrade deals.
<P>
<table colspan=9>
Ukrainian hydrocarbon imports<br>
(US$ million)                
<tr><td></td><td>1993</td><td>1994</td><td>*1995</td></tr>
<tr><td>Crude oil</td><td>1,589.9</td><td>1,508.7</td><td>2,380.0</td></tr>
<tr><td>Natural gas</td><td>3,463.3</td><td>3,511.9</td><td>4,197.0</td></tr>
<tr><td>Coal</td><td>137.3</td><td>70.6</td><td>427.7</td></tr>
<tr><td>Petroleum products</td><td>500.1</td><td>736.7</td><td>603.0</td></tr><br>
</table>
* estimates<br>
Source: Ukrainian Government and World Bank
<P>
<b>Exports</b>
<P>
Although required to import ever growing amounts of coal Ukraine is predicted to export three million tonnes to the west in 1996 in return for desperately needed hard currency
<P>
<b>Transport</b>
<P>
A Russian-Ukrainian joint venture, AO Gaztransit, created to transport Russian gas through Ukraine to western Europe, was established at the end of 1995. Ukraine's gas transit network stretches for 35,000 km and is capable of handling over 120 billion cubic metres of gas annually from Russia to western Europe. However, with a third of the pipeline system over 25 years old it is in desperate need of repair or replacement.<br>
A reconstruction project to boost the capacity at the Odessa oil terminal from 16 to 20 billion tonnes annually should be complete by the end of 1996. The terminal, built in 1985, handled 12.005 million tonnes in 1995, down from 12.397 million tonnes in 1994. The US$24 million project included deepening the harbour to 235 metres to allow 60,000 tonne tankers and a new loading-unloading system. The terminal will eventually handle 40 million tonnes a year.<br> 
The construction of a new terminal in the Crimea was agreed in January 1995, however by May 1996 little progress had been made. The US$790 million project was due for completion by the end of 1996, but this is extremely unlikely. The terminal, near the deep water port of Yuzhny, will have an annual capacity of around 40 million tonnes of crude, with the oil refined at the Odessa and Kherson refineries. With a refining capacity of nearly 62 million tonnes a year Ukraine's refineries could develop an export market in northern Europe once the project is complete.<br>
Ukraine's other oil terminals are at Reni on the Danube and Kerch and Feodosia in the Crimea.
<P>
<a name="Electricity"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Electricity</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The consequences of the Chernobyl disaster in April 1986 continue to affect Ukraine. The
remaining two reactors still produce electricity for Ukrainian homes and factories, and
although the Ukrainian Government has pledged to shut them down by the year 2000, until
the finance is made available to replace their generating capacity this could prove optimistic.
A total of US$2.7 billion has been promised by the EU and the G7 industrialised nations,
however little of the promised funds have yet been made available. A fire in 1991 caused the
shutdown of a second reactor at Chernobyl.<br>
The 1986 explosion affected about 3.5 million people, including 350,000 who lived and
worked in the Chernobyl area, 120,000 who were resettled and a further 90,000 children
exposed to high levels of radiation. Annual payments to the Chernobyl Fund, which
accounted for 15 per cent of the state budget in 1993, were reduced to 5.2 per cent in the
1996 budget. An estimated 7 per cent of Ukraine (equivalent to the size of the Netherlands)
was contaminated to varying degrees by the explosion and is now unusable, with 40 per cent
of forests contaminated. The nuclear fallout from the disaster is estimated at 200 times that
of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombs combined.<br>
The list of `incidents' in the Ukrainian nuclear sector is endless: in November 1995 an
employee was accidentally exposed to high levels of radiation; there were 68 fires at
Ukraine's nuclear reactors between 1990 and 1995; and with an estimated 70 per cent of
equipment at nuclear power stations obsolete and insufficient funds to maintain safety
standards the potential for a serious accident or disaster is great.<br>
An EU funded early warning system to detect increased radioactive levels in Ukraine is due
to be in operation by mid-1996. A network of radiation monitors around nuclear stations are
linked by radio to local response centres where the information is collected and analysed.
The system monitors the Rivne and Zaporizhya nuclear power plants.<br>
In April 1995 a presidential decree created a national electricity pool, authorised the
denationalisation of four power plants and established 27 local electricity distribution
companies.
<P>
<b>New projects</b>
<P>
A nuclear fuel plant supplying Ukraine's nuclear power stations is due for completion by
2000. The Russian energy company TVEL beat off competition from Westinghouse of the
USA and Asea Brown Boveri, the Swiss-Swedish engineering giant. The plant will cost about
US$100 million. Once complete the plant will provide Ukraine's 11 VVER-1000 nuclear
reactors.<br>
The G7 group of industrial nations agreed to assist in financing the completion of two nuclear
reactors, Khmelnitsky 2 and Rovno 4, at a cost of US$1 billion in 1995. In January 1996
Switzerland agreed to assist upgrading Ukraine's hydroelectric power stations and improve
safety measures with a US$34 million loan.<br>
The World Bank granted a loan of US$114 million as part of a US$190 million project to
shore up Ukraine's hydro-electric plants on the Dnepr river in April 1995. The five year
project will rehabilitate eight plants.
<P>
<b>Production</b>
<P>
Ukraine has the 10th largest power generation capacity in the world, 56 million kilowatts.
However the sector was designed as an integral part of the Soviet electricity production
system, not for Ukraine as a separate state. Imported fossil fuels are vital to the sector, and
although nuclear stations contribute about 36 per cent of output Ukraine is totally dependent
on imported raw materials.<br>
Electricity is supplied from 48 thermal power stations, hydro-electric plants on the Dnepr
River and five nuclear power stations (from 15 reactors). In March 1996 Ukraine agreed to
pay for imported electricity from Kyrghyzstan by building a hydroelectric power plant in the
central Asian state.<br>
Total electricity output in 1995 fell 1.5 per cent short of the government's target. With the
exception of the Zaporozhye power station, Ukraine's nuclear facilities exceeded production
expectations. In 1996 output is expected to increase at the Rovno and Zaporozhye plants,
while the Chernobyl, South Ukrainian and Khmelnitskiy plants are set to reduce production.
The nuclear industry is owed about US$500 million in unpaid bills, which in turn means that
the sector is falling behind in payments for deliveries of Russian nuclear fuel.
<P>
<b>Consumption</b>
<P>
Electricity supplies were cut to about 7,000 enterprises in March 1996; outstanding electricity
bills are thought to be about US$980 million.<br>
Russia disconnected Ukraine from a joint power grid in February 1996, causing widespread
power cuts. Combined with the coal miners strike many major industrial enterprises were
forced to stop production, while domestic and agricultural consumers were also left without
power during the particularly cold spell.
<P>
<table>
Growth in power consumption<br>
<tr><td>(% change)</td></tr>
 <tr><td>1990</td><td>1991</td><td>1992</td><td>1993</td><td>1994</td></tr>
 <tr><td>1.0</td><td>-2.2</td><td>-6.2</td><td>-7.8</td><td>-11.7</td></tr>
</table>
Source: EBRD Transition Report
<P>
Exports<br>
Ukraine is a net exporter of electricity
<P>
<table>
Ukrainian electricity exports<br>
(US$ million)<br>
