<P>

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>NATURAL RESOURCES</h2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<b>Summary</b>
<P>
Ukraine is rich in mineral deposits including iron ore (of which it produced 50 per cent of the
entire Soviet output), manganese ore (of which it produced 40 per cent of world output during
the Soviet era), mercury, titanium and nickel.
<P>
<b>Production</b>
<P>
The largest iron ore deposits are in the Krivoy Roj area, with estimated reserves of 18 billion
tonnes, Kremenchuk with 4.5 billion tonnes, Kerch and Belozerskie in the Donetsk region with
210 million tonnes.<br>
The manganese deposits around Nikopol are estimated to be the largest in the world.
Gold deposits in the Trans-Carpathian region containing an average of between five and six
grammes of gold per tonne of ore are due to be developed by the end of 1996. The site also
contains deposits of zinc and lead. Although Ukraine had no active gold mines in mid-1996,
the government predicts that 15 tonnes could be mined annually within eight to 10 years.
Total investment required to reach full capacity is estimated at US$250 million over 12 years.
Ukraine consumes about 400 tonnes of iodine a year, importing about 80 tonnes from other
former Soviet Republics and Chile.<br>
Other natural resources present in Ukraine include salt (in the Donbas, Prykarpatia and
Zarkarpattia region), lime (in the Crimea and Donbas areas), limestone (in Elenovskoye),
china clay (in Hluhovestie and Turbovske), sulphur (around Lvov) and granite (in the
Zhytomyr region). Phosphorus deposits of about 20 billion tonnes are also present.
<P>
<hr>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A></center>
<P>

<hr size=3>
<h5>This site is hosted by <a href="http://www.ipl.co.uk/">Information Providers Limited</a>,
<i>Tel:</i> +44 (0) 1689 860000, <i>Fax:</i> +44 (0) 1689 860330
<i>Email:</i> <a href="mailto:webmaster@ipl.co.uk">webmaster@ipl.co.uk</a></h5>
</body>
