<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name cr09.html-->
<!--Last update 11/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>FARMING, FISHING AND FORESTRY</h2>
</CENTER>
<UL>
<li> <a href="#Farming">Farming</a>
<li> <a href="#Fishing">Fishing</a>
<li> <a href="#Forestry">Forestry</a>
</UL>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A></center>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<b>Summary</b>
<P>
The dormant potential of the Ukrainian agricultural sector has yet to be fully realised, as half-
hearted reforms, disintegrating infrastructure and the abandonment of cheap credits for
agricultural enterprises led to output falling by a disastrous 16 per cent in 1994. The general
inefficiency of the sector, late payments and a lack of finance for fuel, machinery and
fertilisers have exacerbated the problem. With the world's biggest sugar beet crops,
extensive grain, potatoes and fruit harvests together with large livestock herds, Ukraine has
the potential to become a significant exporter of agricultural products. However the
agricultural sector is traditionally the hardest to reform in the former communist states, with
slow land reform and state controls hampering the development of the private sector and
discouraging foreign investment.
<P>
<a name="Farming"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>FARMING</h3>
Background and government policy<br>
<P>
The agricultural policies of the Stalin era crippled Ukraine as farms were collectivised and
grain was confiscated to meet impossible quotas. Peasants working the land were prohibited
from keeping any grain until the official quotas were met, leading to the engineered famine of
1932 and 1933 when between five and seven million people died.<br>
The humus-rich steppes of Ukraine make it one of the most fertile areas of the world, with
agriculture a deeply rooted part of Ukrainian culture. Every house in a rural village has its
own garden where fruit and vegetables are grown. The `bread basket' of the Soviet Union,
half the country is covered with crops of wheat, barley, rye, oats and sugar beet, with large
areas for livestock. In 1991 Ukraine produced 1,033kg of grain per head compared to 445kg
in Germany.<br>
Ukraine has huge potential: the world's largest sugar-beet crops and extensive grain, potato
and fruit resources. However the infrastructure to take advantage of this potential is woefully
inadequate, with an estimated 40 per cent of the grain harvest lost every year due to poor
storage, distribution and theft. Ukrainians rely on their gardens for food rather than the
national agricultural industry.<br>
The slow pace of land reform is principally due to political opposition, but also a deep
aversion to private ownership - a completely alien concept to the vast majority of Ukrainians.
Comprehensive land reform is one of the most sensitive issues in Ukraine, with the powerful
conservative agricultural lobby in parliament against any major change while demanding
greater subsidies. Legislation passed by parliament in February 1996 giving Ukraine's
collective farm directors free 51 per cent stakes in the country's 4,270 agro-industry
companies was vetoed by the president for a second time.<br>
Every Ukrainian citizen has the legal right to become a farmer and may have land allocated
to them, however the maximum amount of agricultural land may not exceed 50 hectares
(ha). The plot may not be sold for a period of six years and workers are not allowed to be
employed on that land. Despite these restrictions, by the beginning of 1996 there were
34,687 private farms. However with an average size of only 23 ha their contribution to total
agricultural output was low. Production from these farms was principally used for private
consumption.<br>
By August 1995 about 75 per cent of all agricultural land was still managed by collective
farms, 12 per cent by families with plots of less than 0.5 ha, 2 per cent by private farmers of
less than 20 ha. The first public distribution of a collective farm's land and equipment was
held at Minkivka in March 1996, with the 640 members of the collective splitting the assets
and 4,500 ha between them.<br>
Some progress has been made in the supply sector, with about 40 per cent of farms
receiving seeds, fertilisers and equipment from private suppliers. Farmers can also sell their
produce on the commodities exchange or to western exporters. Although land reform has
been extremely sluggish, an estimated 40 per cent of all agricultural output comes from the
private sector, principally individual garden plots which have become a lifeline for many
families.<br>
However the development of private sector farms is being hampered by the inability of many
small private farmers to obtain working capital to buy fertilisers, seeds and machinery. The
monopolistic structure of the sector has yet to be broken, particularly in the storage,
distribution and food processing areas. Price controls and state orders have also hindered the
development of a free market.<br>
Ukraine received conditional approval for a US$700 million World Bank loan to support the
agricultural sector in April 1996. The loan depends on land reform measures including the
lifting of the moratorium on the sale of land for six years and the removal of the pre-emptive
right of collective farms to buy their land.<br>
Ukraine's first commodity exchange opened in January 1995 in Kiev. Farmers are permitted
to sell their produce freely on the commodity exchange or to trading houses, but only after
state quotas have been met. The exchange concentrated almost solely on grain, sugar and a
few other items, sold on spot contracts with delivery guaranteed within five days. The
agriculture ministry sets a minimum price, which may or may not be at that day's world level,
below which trading stops. The development of a fully liberalised and functional exchange is
a vital element of the agricultural reform programme, but with the majority of trade done by
barter this will be a lengthy process.<br>
<P>
<b>Production</b>
<P>
The 1996 grain harvest is predicted to reach 38 million tonnes, an improvement on the
disappointing 1995 harvest of 36.5 million tonnes which was held back by slow land reforms
and a summer drought. The 1994 grain harvest of 35.5 million tonnes was the lowest in over
a decade.<br>
The government estimates that the 1996 wheat harvest will be about 18 million tonnes,
compared to 16.4 million tonnes in 1995. The sugar beet harvest is also expected to increase
to 33 million tonnes from 30 million tonnes in 1995, while the sunflower seed crop is
predicted to increase from 2.8 to three million tonnes in 1996. However independent analysts
expect a harvest of 35 million tonnes at best, with the limited reform process hampering
improved production. Bad debts run up by collective farms mean many cannot get the funds
they require for fertilisers, new equipment and fuel. Although the state purchased over half
the 1995 grain harvest the government has pledged to buy just five million tonnes in 1996.
The 1989 grain harvest of 47.7 million tonnes has not been matched since.<br>
The production of tractors in Ukraine meant that the agricultural sector is relatively well
mechanised by Soviet standards. However a lack of specialist harvesting machinery and light
tractors has held productivity levels back, as has the lack of finance to replace and repair
existing machinery. The quality of Ukrainian built machinery is low however, and when
combined with a shortage of spare parts many farms are left struggling to maintain
production levels. Fuel shortages have also prevented harvesting of some crops - 100,000
ha of the 1994 sugar beet harvest went uncollected.
<P>
<table>
