<tr><td>Pig meat</td><td>1,180</td><td>1,013</td><td>910</td></tr>
<tr><td>Poultry meat</td><td>498</td><td>362</td><td>264</td></tr>
</table>
<tr><td>Source: FAO
<P>
<b>Food and tobacco industry</b>
<P>
Ukraine is a large producer of high quality sugar, wine, alcohol, salt, jam, oil and butter, flour,
fruit and vegetables and fresh and canned meat.<br>
The sugar industry, based in the south and south-west, involves about 200 enterprises. Many
factories are operating below full capacity as the government has paid for Russian gas and
oil with a large proportion of the sugar beet harvest. The sugar group Tate & Lyle invested
US$15 million in the Odessa Sugar Company in June 1995. The British company purchased
a 60 per cent stake in the enterprise which imports and refines raw cane before re-exporting
the finished product.<br>
Good quality wine is produced in the Crimean region, although the Gorbachev anti-alcohol
campaign of the mid-1980s caused considerable damage to the sector.<br>
The processed meat industry is spread throughout the country, however output has declined
since 1991 as livestock numbers have fallen. All food processing enterprises suffer from
outdated technology and equipment, with spare parts at a premium. With the state retaining
almost complete control over the agricultural sector, allocating harvests and animal products,
the food processing industry remains completely dependent on state organisations for raw
materials.<br>
Philip Morris of the USA announced plans to invest US$16 million to upgrade the Kharkov
Tobacco Factory in June 1996. Capacity at the plant will be boosted to 6.6 billion cigarettes a
year by the beginning of 1997.
<P>
<b>External trade</b>
<P>
Grain exports were heavily restricted by licences in 1995, with only a few privileged
companies permitted to export sunflower seeds. The low grain harvest in 1995 meant there
were negligible exports in an area that has the potential to be a major export earner.<br>
The US agricultural machinery manufacturer John Deere agreed a US$187 million contract
to supply Ukraine with 1,049 combine harvesters, with the first instalment due in June 1996.
The Ukrainian Ukragroprombirzha company (77 per cent state-owned) has purchased the
equipment which it will lease or sell.
<P>
<a name="Fishing"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>FISHING</h3>
<b>Production</b>
<P>
The Black Sea fishing industry is concentrated around the ports of Odessa, Mariupol,
Sevastopol, Berdiansk, Kerch and Izmayil.
<P>
<a name="Forestry"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>FORESTRY</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The 1986 explosion at the Chernobyl nuclear reactor contaminated an estimated 40 per cent
of Ukraine's forests, making them unusable for commercial activity. Fires in the Chernobyl
area have become common as forest management and clearing were suspended.
<P>
<b>Production</b>
<P>
The Zavarpattska and Polisia regions are the main centres for the forestry and paper
industries. However a lack of local raw materials means there is little room for development.
<P>
<b>External trade</b>
<P>
Ukraine imports paper products from Russia to meet domestic needs.

<HR>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
	<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A></center>
<P>

