<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>TRANSPORT</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<ul>
<li> <a href="#Road">Road</a>
<li> <a href="#Rail">Rail</a>
<li> <a href="#Inland">Inland Waterways and Ocean-Going</a>
<li> <a href="#Air">Air</a>
</UL>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A></center>
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<b>Summary</b>
<P>
The Ukrainian transport system was one of the most developed in the former USSR,
however a lack of maintenance and investment since 1991 has taken its toll as standards
have declined. The majority of components and spare parts were manufactured in the former
eastern bloc states and other Soviet Republics. With manufacturers demanding payment in
hard currency and prices not fully liberalised Ukrainian transport enterprises have
experienced great difficulty in maintaining, let alone modernising the system.<br>
Although separate business organisations have been established for each of the transport
sectors, there is still a long way to go before anything approaching a competitive free market
is established. Privatisation of the railways, the most extensive in the former Soviet Union,
has been ruled out by the government.
<P>
<a name="Road"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Road</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
Ukraine's road network extends for about 430,000km, approximately one-third of which is
metalled. The two most important routes, north-south and east-west, intersect at Kiev. There
are a large number of transport businesses operating services between Ukraine and western
Europe, however transport within Ukraine is unreliable with corruption widespread.<br>
Road maintenance and construction is the responsibility of Ukrdorstroi (Ukrainian State
Committee for Road Construction), a conglomerate of separate enterprises. Ukravtotrans
(Ukrainian State Committee for Auto Transport) controls the road transport system and is
responsible for about 21 per cent of all freight transport. Agricultural and industrial
enterprises have their own transport equipment. Ukravtotrans also provides about 65 per
cent of all passenger road transport, operating 52,000 buses. An increasing shortage of
buses due to a lack of spare parts is causing severe problems in most areas, particularly as
80 per cent of passenger transport is by bus.
<P>
<a name="Rail"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>RailL</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
During the Soviet era Ukraine's extensive 22,800km rail network transported 75 per cent of
exports and 65 per cent of all imports. However the collapse of the USSR led to an
immediate decline in rail transport between the republics and has caused severe financial
problems.<br>
Infrastructure, reliability and viability<br>
The different gauge track used in the former Soviet Union makes transporting goods by train
from western Europe a complicated process.<br>
Rail transport prices were increased by 10 per cent in January 1996. The government hopes
the increase will end the loss-making ways of the passenger and freight services.
<P>
<a name="Inland"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Inland Waterways and Ocean-Going</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
There are over 3,000 km of navigable inland waterways in Ukraine. The river Dnepr,
navigable for 1,000 km in Ukraine from the north to south through Kiev, is the most important
waterway. Principal cargoes carried on the river include sand, coal and iron ore. There are
ports at Kherson, Zaporozhya, Dnepropetrovsk and Kiev on the Dnepr.<br>
The effects of the five year war in the former Yugoslavia and the UN trade embargo on
Serbia virtually stopped all traffic on the Danube, hitting the Ukrainian port of Izmail
particularly hard. Trade with the former Yugoslavia and transit cargo going north from the
Black Sea to Hungary, Austria and Germany stopped between 1991 and 1995. However the
lifting of the embargo in November 1995 should kick-start operations at Izmail. The Ukrainian
Danube Shipping Company lost an estimated US$450 million in revenue during the embargo
as its fleet was left idle. Cargo handling at the port fell from 10 million tonnes in 1989 to four
million in 1995. The government estimates that the value of trade with Serbia should
increase from US$2 million in 1995 to US$2 billion in 1996.
<P>
<b>Infrastructure, reliability and viability</b>
<P>
Ukraine also has well developed sea ports on the Black Sea at Odessa, Izmayil, Kherson,
Yalta, Sevastopol, Kerch, Berdiansk and Mariupol (formerly Zhdanov).<br>
The state-owned company Ukrmorflot (Ukrainian State Committee for the Sea Fleet) was
created in 1992 to manage sea transport. Ukrmorflot owns three shipping lines, the Black
Sea Shipping Company (Blasco), the Azov Sea Shipping Company and the Danube Shipping
Company.<br>
Blasco has the largest fleet in the former Soviet Union, however its 250 rusting ships are in
desperate need of replacement. The company has experienced a series of scandals and
setbacks during 1995 and 1996. The company's president was charged with corruption and
the government cancelled plans to privatise the fleet during 1995. In May 1996, 26 of the
company's most modern vessels were impounded in foreign ports due to the company's
debts. About 200 hundred creditors are demanding the payment of maintenance fees worth
over US$207 million. The company had already been banned from several western ports due
to unpaid bills. Blasco also owes its employees US$5 million in outstanding wages.
The integrated Soviet transport system which established close links between road and rail
transport and the loading and unloading of ships has broken down, with cargoes often waiting
for days to be unloaded.
<P>
<a name="Air"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Air</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The portion of the Aeroflot fleet inherited by Ukraine was turned into a national carrier, Air
Ukraine.
<P>
<b>Infrastructure, reliability and viability</b>
<P>
Kiev airport has been totally refurbished with a grant from the EBRD and is now up to
western standards. Fuel and spare parts shortages mean that flights can be cancelled or
delayed at the last minute.<br>
Air Ukraine employs 40,000 people and has services to the USA and major western and
eastern European cities. In the long-term Air Ukraine aims to replace its Soviet made fleet
with western equipment and aircraft which consume about 20 per cent less fuel than the
Ilyushin and Tupolev planes.
<P>
Air Ukraine fleet<br>
(March 1996)<br>
<table>
<tr><td>Antonov An-24</td><td>52</td></tr>
<tr><td>Antonov An-26</td><td>14</td></tr>
<tr><td>Antonov An-30</td><td>10</td></tr>
<tr><td>Antonov An-32</td><td>4</td></tr>
<tr><td>Antonov An-72</td><td>1</td></tr>
<tr><td>Boeing 737</td><td>2</td></tr>
<tr><td>Boeing 737-200</td><td>1</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ilyushin II-18</td><td>2</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ilyushin II-62M</td><td>7</td></tr>
<tr><td>Let L-410</td><td>9</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tupolev Tu-134</td><td>28</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tupolev Tu-154B</td><td>32</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tupolev Tu-154M</td><td>3</td></tr>
<tr><td>Yakovlev Yak-40</td><td>15</td></tr>
<tr><td>Yakovlev Yak-42</td><td>21</td></tr>
</table>
Source: Flight International
<P>
Ukraine International Airlines, an Irish-Ukrainian joint venture, was established in 1992 and
flies to most western capitals from Kiev. Other airlines in Ukraine include: Air Urga operating
domestic passenger and cargo flights; Atlant SV Airlines operating international, regional and
domestic passenger and cargo flights; BSL Airlines offering regional and domestic passenger
and cargo flights; Crimea Krymavia Airline; Dneproavia Airline operating regional and
domestic passenger and cargo services; and Lvov Airline (subsidiary of Air Ukraine).
International carriers flying to Ukraine include Aeroflot, Air Canada, Air France, Austrian
Airlines, BA, Continental Airlines, Czech Airlines, Delta Airlines, Finnair, Iberia, KLM, LOT,
Lufthansa, MALEV, Northwest Airlines, Swissair, TWA and USAir.
<P>
<b>New projects</b>
<P>
The US$30 million reconstruction and modernisation of a runway at the Borispol airport,
funded by the EBRD, is due to begin by the end of 1996.

<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<hr>
<P>
