<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>MEDIA</h2>
</CENTER>
<ul>
<li> <a href="#Broadcasting">Broadcasting</a>
<li> <a href="#Print">Print</a>
</UL>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A></center>
<P>
<a name="Broadcasting"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Broadcasting</h3>
<P>
The state run broadcasters Radio 1, 2 and Promin Radio (Channel 3) dominate the radio
sector. However the number of commercial stations, particularly in the Kiev region, is
growing, including 101-FU, Radio Utar and Radio Rocks.<br>
The state television channels, UT1 and UT2 dominate the sector, with 63 per cent and 33 per
cent of the market respectively.
<P>
Ukrainian television channels
<P>
<table>
<tr><td>Station</td><td>Broadcast area</td></tr>
<tr><td>UT 1</td><td>National</td></tr>
<tr><td>UT 2</td><td>National (95%)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tet a Tet Local stations</td></tr>
<tr><td>IC TV</td><td>Local stations in 43 cities</td></tr>
<tr><td>UN TV</td><td>National (7-10pm)</td></tr>
</table>
Source: Socis-Gallup International
<P>
A Polish channel can be received in the Lvov area and the Russian channel Ostankino can
also be received in most areas.
<P>
<a name="Print"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
