<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>TELECOMMUNICATIONS</h2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<b>Summary</b>
<P>
In 1991 when Ukraine gained independence the country's telecommunications network was
antiquated, inefficient and unreliable. However, by the beginning of 1996 the majority of
Ukrainian telephones had direct dial international access, ending the practice of booking
international calls days in advance.
<P>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The telecommunications market was deregulated in February 1995 when the government
issued a second long-distance carrier licence. Utel, established in 1992 by 13 state-owned
local phone companies, was Ukraine's first long-distance carrier. The local phone companies
hold a 51 per cent stake, AT&T of America and Deutsche Bundespost Telekom of Germany
19.5 per cent and PPT Telecom Netherlands 10 per cent. The western partners had invested
US$60 million by mid-1995, principally in digital gateway switches. Utel plans to invest over
US$43 million in upgrading local networks during 1996, with digital exchanges planned for
the Kherson, Ternopol, Lutsk and Rovno areas.<br>
In the first quarter of 1996, 41,800 new telephone numbers were installed. The second stage
of a 896km fibre-optic cable linking Kiev and Odessa was also 80 per cent complete by the
end of March 1996. The cable is part of a US$53 million line linking Italy, Turkey, Ukraine
and Russia. By the end of 1996 about 224,000 new numbers should have been installed.
The French telecommunications company Alcatel opened a 30,000 line telephone exchange
in Kiev in April 1996. The exchange was the first of several deals with local telecomms
providers in Ukraine. A second 30,000 line exchange is due to open in November and a
23,000 line exchange early in 1997. A consortium of Canada's Northern Telecom and Italy's
Pirelli won a US$12 million EBRD funded contract to install a fibre-optic network in February
1995. The American company, Global Telesystems Group, agreed to invest an initial US$10
million in the Ukrainian telecommunications firm Bankomsvyaz in March 1996, and a further
US$25 million over the next five years. Bankomsvyaz plans to modernise its network and
install a new network in Kiev.<br>
In December 1995 Poland and Ukraine agreed to extend the existing telecommunications
highway between Lvov and Rzeszow in southern Poland. Once complete the US$100 million
link will reach from Kiev to Krakow in Poland.
<P>
<hr>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A></center>
