<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>Armed Forces</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<ul>
<li> <a href="#Army">Army</a>
<li> <a href="#Navy">Navy</a>
<li> <a href="#Airforce">Airforce</a>
</ul>
<P>
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The armed forces have had their combined strength reduced by around 65,000 since
independence. Equipment levels have also been reduced, with 600 tanks, one bomber
division and six fighter regiments eliminated.<br>
The Ukrainian Parliament signed the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty in November 1994.
The removal of nuclear weapons began early in 1994, with over 400 warheads returned to
Russia and 40 intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs) destroyed. The final outstanding
element in the removal of nuclear weapons from Ukraine was cleared up in May 1996.
Russia agreed to write off US$450 million of Ukrainian debt to compensate for the transfer of
short-range tactical nuclear weapons to Russia in 1992. The last nuclear warhead was
removed to Russia on 31 May 1996.<br>
The EU TACIS programme granted Ukraine Ecu7.36 million to assist in the retraining of
former servicemen in October 1995.
<P>
<a name="Army"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Army</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
Ground forces have been reduced by approximately 96,000 since independence, with the
majority of the attack helicopter force redistributed from the airforce to the army. Most army
corps now include an attack helicopter regiment. The Conventional Armed Forces in Europe
(CFE) treaty has reduced equipment levels, including 600 tanks and 400 armoured personnel
carriers.
<P>
Army personnel and equipment
<P>
<table>
<tr><td>Personnel</td><td>212,600</td></tr>
Equipment:<br>
<tr><td>Main battle tanks</td><td>4,775</td></tr>
<tr><td>Reconnaissance vehicles</td><td>1,500</td></tr>
<tr><td>Armoured infantry
  fighting vehicles</td><td>3,400</td></tr>
<tr><td>Armoured personnel
  carrier</td><td>1,770</td></tr>
<tr><td>Total artillery</td><td>3,685</td></tr>
<tr><td>Attack helicopters </td><td>204</td></tr>
<tr><td>Support helicopters</td><td>239</td></tr>
</table>
Source: International Institute for Strategic Studies, The Military Balance 1995-96
<P>
<a name="Navy"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Navy</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The fate of the naval fleet based in the Crimea has caused tension between Russia and
Ukraine since 1991. The dispute has centred around the allocation of naval bases on the
Crimean peninsular and the length of leases offered to the Russian navy. Agreement was
finally reached between the two governments in June 1995 to split the fleet's assets equally.
However Ukraine is selling 63 per cent of its share of the fleet's ships to Russia.
The principle naval bases are at Sevastopol and Odessa.
<P>
Naval personnel and equipment
<P>
<table>
<tr><td>Personnel</td><td>*16,000</td></tr>
<tr><td>Coastal patrol craft</td><td>2</td></tr>
<tr><td>Frigates</td><td>2</td></tr>
<tr><td>Other vessels</td><td>42</td></tr>
</table>
* estimate<br>
Source: International Institute for Strategic Studies, The Military Balance 1995-96
<P>
<a name="Airforce"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Airforce</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The CFE treaty led to the disbandment of one bomber division and six fighter regiments.
Russia agreed to buy 25 strategic bombers (TU-95s and TU-160s) and around 800 cruise
missiles from Ukraine in April 1996.
<P>
Airforce personnel and equipment
<P>
<table>
<tr><td>Personnel</td><td>151,000</td></tr>
<tr><td>Combat aircraft</td><td>846 (plus 380 in store)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fighter aircraft</td><td>482</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fighter, ground attack/
  bomber aircraft</td><td>166</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fighter, ground attack</td><td>34</td></tr>
<tr><td>Bomber aircraft</td><td>26</td></tr>
<tr><td>Transport aircraft</td><td>274</td></tr>
<tr><td>Attack helicopters</td><td>24</td></tr>
<tr><td>Support helicopters</td><td>168</td></tr>
<tr><td>Surface-to-air missiles</td><td>825</td></tr>
</table>
Source: International Institute for Strategic Studies, The Military Balance 1995-96
<P>
