<P>
<CENTER>
<h2>Education, Health, & Welfare</h2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<ul>
<li> <a href="#Health">Health</a>
<li> <a href="#Welfare">Welfare</a>
</UL>
<P>												
									
									
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
<b>Education</b>
<P>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
The reversal of the Russian dominated education system is the primary aim of the
government. Ukrainian is taught in all schools, although the choice to learn it is individual. An
increased emphasis has also been placed on Ukrainian history, culture and literature. The
Kiev-Mohyla Academy, Ukraine's first higher education institute founded in 1615, has been
reopened since independence.<br>
Education is compulsory for eight years after which students can enter the workforce, begin a
two-year trade-school course or continue in school before entering a technical college, a
speciality institute or a university.
<P>
<a name="Health"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Health</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
Extensive pollution is one of the most lingering legacies of the Soviet regime. Massive
industrialisation was pursued at any cost. The Chernobyl explosion is the most obvious
example with increased rates of thyroid cancer, leukaemia and birth defects, but all cities
suffer from pollution, both in the air as well as rivers and agricultural land. The Lvov region
has the most polluted water in the country.<br>
The health sector has experienced considerable pressure since independence, with
government funding insufficient to cover even basic building repairs. Preventive care is also
negligible, for example abortion is the principle means of birth control. Although there are
twice as many doctors as in the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development
(OECD) states, they have not had the funding, technology and training since 1991 to
maintain the levels of care pre-1991.<br>
Ukraine is more dependent on imported medicines and medical equipment than any other
European country, producing only 160 of the 3,000 different medicines required.
<P>
<a name="Welfare"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Welfare</h3>
<b>Background and government policy</b>
<P>
Following independence three separate extra-budgetary funds were established - the pension
fund, the social insurance fund and the employment fund. They are funded by employer and
employee contributions.<br>
The economic collapse, particularly hyper-inflation, experienced since 1991 has left many
Ukrainians struggling to survive as living standards have plummeted. Without the numerous
individual vegetable plots most Ukrainians cultivate the level of poverty and hunger would
have been disastrous.
<P>

<HR>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A></center>
