<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>GEOGRAPHY AND CLIMATE</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<b>Geography</b>
<P>
The largest country wholly within Europe (just ahead of France) Ukraine covers 603,700
square km, stretching 2,000 km from east to west and 1,000 km from north to south.
Bordered by Russia to the east and north, Belarus to the north, and Poland in the west there
are also short borders with Slovakia, Hungary, Romania and Moldova in the south-west. The
Black Sea is to the south.<br>
The average height above sea level in Ukraine is only 175m, due to the rolling steppes and
wooded plains. About two-thirds of the country is covered by a thick layer of humus rich soil,
making it one of the most fertile regions in the world. The only mountains are in the south on
the Crimean peninsular (maximum height 1,545 m) and the Carpathians in the west
(maximum height 2,061 m).<br>
Ukraine has four different types of state nature reserves, totalling around 92,340 ha.
<P>
<b>Climate</b>
<P>
The moderate continental climate varies little across the country. July is the hottest month,
averaging 23 degrees C, while January is the coldest, averaging around zero degrees C. The
Black Sea resorts around Odessa and Yalta are usually warmer and drier than the rest of
Ukraine. The average rainfall per year is 144 cm, with the Crimea only receiving 40 cm.

<P>
<hr>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A></center>
<P>

