<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HEAD>
<title>Business Euro</title>
<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name cr15.html-->
<!--Last update 17/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<CENTER>
<h2>VISITORS' GUIDE</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<li> <a href="#Dress">Dress Codes</a>
<li> <a href="#Social">Social Niceties, Traditions and Taboos</a>
<li> <a href="#Eating">Eating Habits</a>
<li> <a href="#Unusual">Unusual/Strict Laws</a>
<li> <a href="#Security">Security</a>
<li> <a href="#Health">Health for Visitors</a>
<li> <a href="#Banking">Banking and Business Hours</a>
<li> <a href="#Public">Public Holidays</a>
<li> <a href="#Getting">Getting About</a>
<li> <a href="#Little">Little Known Facts</a>
<P>
US dollars and German Deutsche Marks are the easiest hard currencies to exchange, but
avoid taking old or torn notes as they won't be accepted. Only change a small amount of
hard currency at a time as the exchange rate can fluctuate wildly.
<P>
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="crmenu.html">Ukraine Subjects</A>
</center>
<P>
<a name="Dress"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Dress Codes</h3>
Business clothes are appropriate for meetings - a suit or jacket with a tie for men and smart
business clothing for women.
<P>
<a name="Social"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Social Niceties, Traditions and Taboos</h3>
<P>
Tips are not expected at most caf,s, although at more expensive restaurants a tip of between
five and 10 per cent is appropriate.<br>
Small gifts for your host (or as bribes) are appreciated.<br>
Handshaking is customary on meeting and on leaving. The formal form of address, Mr (Pan)
or Mrs (Pani) is usual even after several meetings. The use of business cards is widespread.
It is important to be on time for meetings and appointments.<br>
Referring to Ukraine as part of the Soviet Union, or even worse as part of Russia, is a
downright insult. Decades of Russification have led to strong nationalistic feelings,
particularly in the west, and unless you know your Ukrainian host well avoid talking about the
more sensitive issues.
<P>
<a name="Eating"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Eating Habits</h3>
<P>
Ukrainian food is similar to Russian, with most dishes based around grains, vegetables
(potatoes, cabbage etc), beef, pork, poultry and fish seasoned with garlic, dill or vinegar.
Puddings are usually based on a combination of honey and fruits and often baked into sweet
breads.<br>
Restaurants leave much to be desired, with poor service and limited menus (often useless
anyway). The best Ukrainian cooking is found in the home, with eating out an unaccustomed
luxury for most Ukrainians. Yidalnya, stolova, kafe and bufet are caf,terias where drinks and
hot food are readily available, although the quality can vary.<br>
Traditional Ukrainian dishes include: varenyky (small dumplings filled with a variety of
ingredients, usually cheese or meat and a sour cream sauce), borscht (a beet and vegetable
soup in numerous forms, the best borscht is the thickest with the most vegetables), holubtsi
(cabbage leaves stuffed with rice, meat or buckwheat) and kotleta po-kyivsky (the original
chicken Kiev, although it can be difficult to find) and kasha (grain based gruel).<br>
Drinking is one of the few pastimes most Ukrainians can still afford. Vodka (neat of course) is
the favourite tipple of most people, downed in one, usually with the sole aim of getting drunk.
The recommended `morning after' cure is a swift bottle of beer. Once spotted, visiting
foreigners can soon become involved in a serious drinking session as the hospitable
Ukrainians welcome you to their country. Beer is not pasteurised which means it goes off
within a few days of production; check the date on the bottle. The Crimean and
Transcarpathian regions produce very good wine.
<P>
<a name="Unusual"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Unusual/Strict Laws</h3>
<P>
Driving having consumed any amount of alcohol is illegal.
<P>
<a name="Security"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Security</h3>
<P>
Anybody carrying hard currency becomes a walking goldmine in Ukrainian terms. Care
should be taken not to reveal large amounts of cash or expensive personal belongings,
especially on the street. Avoid travelling alone at night in Kiev, particularly on the metro or in
the city's parks.
<P>
<a name="Health"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Health for Visitors</h3>
<P>
Vaccination certificates are mandatory if you are travelling from a cholera or yellow fever
infected area. An HIV (AIDS) test is required for long-stay visitors only. Water precautions
are advisable, with water purification tablets useful. Visitors should be `in date' for the
following immunisations: polio (within 10 years), tetanus (within 10 years), typhoid fever,
cholera (within six months) and hepatitis `A' (moderate risk only). There have been a growing
and significant number of diphtheria cases. While the low dose adult booster is unavailable,
travellers are advised to be boosted with a reduced dose (0.1ml) of the paediatric single
antigen vaccine. If never immunised use a three dose course of the vaccine. Any medicines
required by the traveller should be taken by the visitor, and it is wise to have precautionary
antibiotics if going outside the major urban areas. A travel kit including a disposable syringe
is a reasonable precaution.
<P>
<a name="Banking"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Banking and Business Hours</h3>
<P>
Business: 0900-1800 (Mon-Fri).<br>
Government: 0900/1000-1700/1800 (Mon-Fri).<br>
Banking: 0900-1300 (Mon-Fri).<br>
Shops: 0800/0900-2000/2100; lunch: 1300-1400 (Mon-Sat).<br>
<P>
<a name="Public"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Public Holidays</h3>
<P>
<table>
<tr><td></td><td>1996</td></tr>
<tr><td>New Year's Day</td><td>1 January</td></tr>
<tr><td>Orthodox Christmas Day</td><td>7 January</td></tr>
<tr><td>International Women's Day</td><td>8 March</td></tr>
<tr><td>International Labour Day</td><td>1-2 May</td></tr>
<tr><td>Victory Day (1945) and
  Mother's Day</td><td>9 May</td><tr>
<tr><td>Independence Day (1991)</td><td>24 August</td</tr>
<tr><td>Liberation Day (1944)</td><td>28 October</td></tr>
<tr><td>New Year's Eve</td><td>31 December</td></tr>
</table>
<P>
<a name="Getting"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Getting About</h3>
<P>
National transport<br>
Air: The main airports at Kiev, Odessa, Lvov and Ivano-Frankivsk all handle domestic traffic,
as do 19 other regional airports. However several regional airports were closed down due to
a combination of fuel shortages and lack of money.<br>
Kiev's international airport, Borispol, is 27 km from the city centre. It is advisable to be met at
the airport as the few taxi drivers there rarely speak English or German.<br>
Road: Ukrainian's drive on the right, with speed limits of 60kmph in built up areas and
110kmph elsewhere. Have your car documentation papers ready for the enthusiastic traffic
police. Unleaded petrol is extremely rare, with only low-octane fuel available in most areas.
Ukraine has an extensive bus network, with routes to every city and most smaller towns.
Most buses are overcrowded, overheated and dirty, but are a good way to get to know the
locals.<br>
Rail: The Ukrainian rail networks links the major cities, most of which are at least one night's
travel apart. There are three types of sleeper carriage: the spalny vahon is the first class
compartment for two people; the kupe or kupeyny is the second class compartment for four
people; and the platskart is the third class open carriage with groups of six bunks in each
alcove, with more beds along the aisles - avoid them unless absolutely necessary.<br>
Remember to take your own food and drink, although the carriage attendants usually provide
cups of tea at the start and finish of the journey. Guard your belongings carefully; putting
them in the compartments under the bed is the safest option.<br>
Buying tickets for bus and rail travel can be awkward at the very least. The most effective
method is to write down your destination on a piece of paper and show it to the ticket clerk.
Foreigners can usually buy rail tickets from separate offices, although the price will be
slightly higher.<br>
Water: Passenger transport is available on Ukraine's rivers, but price increases, lack of spare
parts and cheaper land-based transport has seen a sharp decline in passenger services on
inland waterways.<br>
City transport: Kiev and Kharkov have metro systems; tickets can be bought at the stations.
Taxis: Payment is usually requested in hard currency. Agree a price before setting off.
Buses: In every city and town the buses, trams and trolleybuses are extremely crowded
where manners take a distant last place. If you are willing to take the consequences tickets
are very cheap and available from kiosks at most bus stops or from the driver.
Car hire: Cars can rented, but hiring a taxi for the day is often a cheaper and easier option.
<P>
<a name="Little"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#List"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Little Known Facts</h3>
<P>
The original cossacks came from the Ukrainian steppes in the late fifteenth century.
Cossacks, a Turkish word meaning outlaw, were runaway serfs, criminals, Orthodox refugees
and other outcasts from the Polish and Lithuanian areas to the north, together with a few
Tartar bands. At the height of their power in the seventeenth century they launched assaults
on Constantinople during campaigns against the Turks.
<P>
