<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>CZECH REPUBLIC</h3>

Czech GDP grew by 2.6 per cent in 1994, with an impressive 4.8 per cent growth posted in the fourth 
quarter. Real GDP amounted to US$15.76 billion (Kc 411.2 billion) in 1994. <p> 

On 7 June the Czech government cancelled its Ecu-denominated trade clearing agreement with the Slovak 
Republic. The arrangement, introduced shortly after the partition of the two republics, required only the 
deficit amount to be settled in hard currency, not the total value of goods traded. Trade relations had been 
soured by the unilateral Slovak imposition of a 10 per cent import surcharge. In 1994 there was a US$750 
million surplus in favour of Slovakia. <p> 

<b>Skoda Turbiny</b> a subsidiary of <b>Skoda Plzen</b> has signed a US$1.5 million contract for the 
supply of turbines to <b>General Motors</b> in Cadiz, Spain. <p> 

The Czech Republic ranked fifth in total foreign direct investment (FDI) in the region at the end of 1994, 
with 8 per cent of the total US$17.2 billion, behind Hungary (27 per cent), Poland (24 per cent), Russia 
(15 per cent), and Kazakhstan (14 per cent) according to figures published by the <b>UN Economic 
Commission for Europe</b>. Foreign investment in the Czech Republic was US$117.2 million in the first 
quarter of 1995.<p>  

Bids for the 27 per cent stake in <b>SPT Telecom</b> to be sold off closed on 6 June. <b>Telis</b>, a 
Czech telecommunications company, had appealed against the sale on the grounds that it had been 
excluded. The SPT sale is one of the largest to date in central Europe, estimated at US$1 billion. The 
bidders are <b>Telfar</b> (a consortium of <b>France Telecom</b>, and <b>Bell Atlantic</b>), 
<b>CeTel</b> (<b>Deutsche Telekom</b> and <b>Ameritech</b>), <b>Telsource</b> (<b>PTT Telecom 
Netherlands</b> and <b>Swiss Telecom</b>), <b>TeleDanmark</b> and <b>Stet International</b> (Italy). 
Twenty-six per cent of SPT has already been privatised through the vouchers system. <p>

<b>Welsh Water International</b> is to buy a 35.6 per cent share in <b>Severoceske vodovody a 
kanalizace</b> (SCVK) for US$11.53 million. In 1994 SCVK had a turnover of US$58 million and 
declared profits of US$6 million. <p>

German electricity companies <b>RWE Energie</b> and <b>OBAG</b> are taking minority stakes in 
joint ventures <b>Sko-Energo-Fin</b> and <b>Sko-Energo</b>. The Czech partner is <b>STE Stredoceska 
Energeticka</b> to provide and operate power and ancillary services for the Mlada Boleslav 
<b>Volkswagen</b> subsidiary, as well as providing heating for the inhabitants of Mlada Boleslav.  

<b>US West</b> has paid US$18.8 million (KC500 million) for a 28.6 per cent stake in Ostrava-based 
cable television operator <b>Kabel Plus</b>.<p> 

The <b>European Bank for Reconstruction and Development</b> (EBRD), in association with the 
<b>European Investment Bank</b> and the <b>Exim Bank</b> of Japan, is providing a 20 year, Ecu44.1 
million loan to Czech railways for the modernization of the Decin-Prague-Brno-Breclav line. The cash 
strapped railways have been unable to pay <b>Moravskosleszka vagonka</b> (MSV) the US$56.2 million 
(KC 1.46 billion) owing for 42 diesel rail carriages delivered in 1994.<p> 

The <b>Prague Stock Exchange</b> plans to move to real time trading in late 1995. 1995 has not been a 
good year for the exchange. The <b>HN-Wood 30 Index</b> has lost more than two thirds of its value 
since February 1994. The official <b>PX-50</b> index hit a record low in mid-March. Since 1 March 
shares in 674 enterprises issued under the second wave of privatisations can be traded on the exchange. 
The price at which they were first traded was allowed to vary 30 per cent from their indicative price, 
thereafter they were subject to the usual maximum of 5 per cent per day. During the course of March 613 
of the second wave issues were traded. Second wave shares accounted for around 30 per cent of the 
turnover in the 30 most traded shares in March.<p>   

<b>Skoda Plzen</b> Ghuangzhou subsidiary <b>Skoda Yinn</b> has started the production of electrical 
turbines. 1995 turnover is forecast at US$3.7 million. <p>

<b>Ministry of Trade and Industry</b> figures confirm 288 corporate bankruptcies (receiverships) in 1994, a 
dramatic increase over the 1993 figure of 68.<p> 

National airline <b>CSA</b> (now officially known as Czech Airlines) made a loss, by western auditing 
standards, of Kc740 million in 1994. <p>

<b>Jan Becher Karlovarska Becherovka</b>, producer of the famous liqueur, made a 1994 profit of 
Kc190 million on a turnover of Kc1.4 billion. Rumours of an investment by a west European distiller have 
circulated for some time. <p> 

The Czech Republic is the least expensive of the major central and eastern European capitals in which to 
employ managers, according to a survey published by consultants <b>Watson Wyatt</b>. When expressed in 
US dollar terms, a sales manager's basic salary in Russia would be US$20,035, in Hungary US$19,671, in 
Poland US$19,668 and in the Czech Republic US$17,726. The Czech Republic also compared well on 
basic pay to employees. The Czech respondents in the poll anticipated salary increases across the board of 
around 16 per cent on average, but those from neighbouring states foresaw much higher rises. Figures 
supplied by the <b>Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development</b> (OECD) suggest that 
average Czech salary levels are now only 10 per cent below those in Greece. More information from 
Watson Wyatt Data Services, tel: +44 171 222 8033 fax: +44 171 222 9182. <p>
