<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>HUNGARY</h3>

On 9 May the Hungarian parliament passed the long awaited <b>Privatisation Act</b>. The act is designed 
to rationalise the procedures relating to privatisation and make them more transparent. Privatisation has 
ground to a halt since the socialist government took office in July 1994. The government's target of 
raising Huf150 billion (US$1,200 million) in 1995 looks optimistic in the extreme. By the beginning of 
June not one major privatisation had been completed. Further information on the act, expected to come 
into force in late June or early July, can be obtained from the government's <b>Privatisation Information 
Services</b> tel: +361 269 8990, fax: +361 269 8991. 
<p>
UK supermarket chain <b>Tesco</b> plans to open 20 supermarkets in Hungary over the next five years, 
making it the first large UK retailer to open stores in eastern Europe.  
<p>
The 3 May AGM of the <b>Budapest Bank</b> provided the bank's 600 private shareholders and the 
city's banking community with a few surprises. It transpired that in December 1994 the government had 
clandestinely injected a further Huf12.3 billion into the bank. The news was particularly sensitive since 
the bank's CEO at the time was current `if it isn't hurting, it isn't working' Finance Minister Lajos Bokros. 
The capital injection was seen by many as an attempt to boost the bank's balance sheet before potential 
purchaser <b>Crédit Suisse</b> (who subsequently cried off) started its due diligence investigations. 
After the withdrawal of Crédit Suisse, Dutch bank <b>ING</b> said it was no longer interested.  
<p>
<b>Beslutsmodeller AB</b> creators <b>Scala International</b>, one of Hungary's leading suppliers of 
financial and management software, has merged with <b>Oracle Corporation</b>. 
<p>
Seven hundred members of the <b>International Advertising Association</b> gathered in Budapest for 
their annual global conference in May. The theme of the conference was, appropriately enough, 
`Globalisation'. 
<p>
Ailing <b>Agrobank Rt</b> was closed down by the State Bank Supervisory Office (SBSO) in mid-May. 
Bank president Mihaily Kovacs and Chief executive officer Peter Kunos were accused of corruption. Both 
men had been arrested at the end of 1994 on similar charges. SBSO officials claimed that the bank had 
managed to loan several times the amount of its declared assets. 
<p>
Budapest's <b>Gerbeaud Palace</b> home of the city's legendary patisserie has been put on sale for Ft1.5 
billion (US$12 million.) The sale is open to foreign purchasers.  
<p>
The newly created <b>State Privatization and Holding Rt</b> which combines the activities of the former 
<b>State Property Agency</b> (SPA) and the <b>State Holding Company</b> (AV Rt) looks likely to be 
headed by Imre Szokai, former diplomat and AV Rt board member. Under the arrangement, the new 
company will be responsible for all state disposals. Formerly the SPA handled non strategic companies, 
AV Rt those considered to be of vital national interest. 
<p>
Worrying news for the already unpopular Finance Minister Lajos Bokros. At the end of April the national 
deficit reached Ft147.1 billion, up Ft779 million in one month. The April figure already exceeded half the 
Ft282 billion forecast for the year. Not much cheer in the industrial production figures, for Bokros, either. 
This was down 54 per cent over the preceding month and 20.6 per cent below the February 1985 figure. 
<p>
An 8 per cent customs duty on all imports, except capital equipment and energy, was introduced as part of 
the overall austerity programme on 14 March. The former corporate tax rate was replaced by a two-tier 
structure under which declared profits are subject to an 18 per cent rate, while supplementary tax at the 
rate of 23 per cent is levied when profits are distributed. Tax holidays only apply to the 18 per cent rate on 
declared profits. Companies benefitting from tax holidays are still liable to pay the 23 per cent when due. 
<p>
The government has raised the consumption tax on new vehicles by 10 per cent to 20 per cent in an effort 
to control car imports, estimated at over US$1 billion each year. 
<p>
<b>Suzuki</b> <b>Hungary</b> is to expand the range of cars produced at its Esztergom plant. The 
expansion will see the plant manufacturing a hatchback version of its swift model, and beginning the 
assembly of four-wheel drive passenger cars for the <b>Subaru</b> group. Suzuki's Hungary operation 
posted sales of Ft15.5 billion in 1994 but made undisclosed losses. The company also plans to produce and 
sell 40,000 cars in 1995, half for Hungary, half for export, principally to the <b>EU</b>.  
<p>
<b>General Motors</b> subsidiary <b>Opel</b> is to double output of engines at its Szentgotthard plant. 
The new plant will have a capacity of 460,000 16-valve engines. 
<p>
<b>SEMA Group</b> of the UK has won a contract to provide the toll system for Hungary's first paying 
motorway link, a 60 kilometre stretch linking the city of Gyor (see Business Europa Issue 12) with the 
Austrian border. The contract was awarded by the <b>Transroute International Company</b> responsible 
for their equipment and the exploitation of the toll. 
<p>
<b>Pepsico Hungary</b> is to invest US$10 million in snack production in Hungary. Pepsico increased 
its soft drink sales by 40 per cent in Hungary in 1994, establishing itself as the country's market leader in 
colas, citrus drinks and mineral water. 
<p>
<b>Nutricia</b> the Dutch foods group has acquired a 22.5 per cent stake in <b>Hajdutej Tejipari</b> 
Hungary's largest regional dairy. Nutricia which already owns a distribution joint venture in Hungary, 
owns two dairy companies in Poland and two in the Czech Republic. The UK's <b>Unigate</b> holds a 
32 per cent stake in Nutricia. 
<p>
A consortium of <b>CS First Boston</b> and <b>Deutsche Bank</b> has won the mandate for the partial 
privatisation of <b>Matav</b>, likely to be central Europe's largest equity offering. The sale of up to 40 
per cent of Matav is expected to generate up to US$1 billion for the Hungarian state. The banks' fees for 
the privatisation are likely to be over US$60 million. The sale will complete the privatisation process 
begun with the sale of 30.3 per cent of Matav to <b>Deutsche Telekom</b> and <b>Ameritech</b> in 
December 1993. 
<p>
The Hungarian government has passed new laws to encourage greater price competition for public sector 
contracts, bringing the country closer into line with <b>EU</b> policy. Hungarian registered companies 
will still be allowed to win work even if their prices are 10 per cent higher than the lowest non-Hungarian 
bidder, as long as 50 per cent of goods and services are provided locally. 
<p>
<b>Sumitomo Bank</b> has arranged a US$60 million, five year syndicated loan for <b>Mol</b>, 
Hungary's oil and gas monopoly. The loan is to be used for the reconstruction of a gas field. <p> 
<hr>
