<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>LATVIA</h3>

Financial crisis and panic hit Latvia as, on 23 May, the central bank suspended operations at <b>Baltija 
Banka</b> the largest commercial bank in any of the Baltic States. The collapsed bank held accounts for 
400,000 depositors (Latvia's total population is 2.7 million) and 20,000 companies. The bank's collapse 
forced the resignation of Finance Minister Andris Piebalgs; his replacement, Ms Indra Samite announced 
that the government would be putting together a rescue package to reopen the bank quickly. The cost of 
the rescue plan was estimated at between Lats20-160 million (US$38-300 million). In June two more 
banks <b>Polarzvaigzne</b> and <b>Latintrade</b> were also declared insolvent. The governor of the 
<b>Central Bank</b>, Einars Repse, has gone on record that only 12-13 banks are commercially viable 
and capable of survival. This became a self fulfilling prophecy on June 12th when the <b>Deposit 
Bank</b> was declared insolvent. Accountants <b>Arthur Anderson</b> have been appointed as the 
bank's administrators. 
<p>
The newly appointed president of the failed <b>Banka Baltija</b>, Uldis Klauss, announced on 5 June 
that the bank had concluded an agreement with the <b>Latvian Shipping Company</b> whereby all the 
bank's real estate and intellectual `property' would belong to the company, which had a US$45 million 
deposit with the bank. US law firm <b>Baker Mackenzie</b> is to advise the Latvian government on the 
Banka Baltija case. 
<p>
Only one foreign bank, <b>Société Generale</b> of France has a branch in Riga. The <b>Dresdner 
Bank</b> has a representative office. 
<p>
A 9 June cabinet meeting agreed to decrease budget expenditures by 5 per cent across the board and to 
reduce the number of civil servants by 10 per cent in order to contain the budget deficit. May 1995 
(monthly) inflation was 1.4 per cent, unemployment 6.3 per cent, down 0.2 per cent from April. (Half the 
87,000 unemployed are female.) Industrial production declined by 2.1 per cent in April. 
<p>
Total direct foreign investment in Latvia reached US$371 million at the end-March 1995. 73 per cent of 
investment in Latvia is in the trading sector, 21 per cent in finance and 2 per cent in manufacturing. 
<p>
<b>Riga Airlines</b> is to increase its scheduled flights between London's Gatwick and Riga to six times 
a week, and will now offer a same plane connection to Moscow in association with Moscow based carrier 
<b>Transaero</b>. It has been rumoured that Transaero is a shareholder in Riga Airlines. 
<p>
<b>Ruhrgas</b> of Germany is involved in negotiations with <b>Latvijas Gaze</b> for the purchase of 
an equity stake in the Latvian utility. <b>Preussen Elektra</b> also of Germany, has expressed an interest 
in taking an equity stake in <b>Latvenergo</b>.  
<p>
Riga based <b>Tele Media</b> has issued a directory <b>Visa Latvija</b> with alphabetical listings of 
all major Latvian companies and enterprises. The volume covers all the major cities in Latvia - Riga, 
Daugavpils, Ventspils and Liepaja. 
<p>
Daily newspaper <i>Labrit</i> (Good Morning) with a circulation of 24,000 copies and a 6,000 
circulation Russian language edition, suspended printing on 17 April. It was reported that the paper's 
financial problems were due to the failure of certain shareholders to fulfil their obligations. 
<p>
The Latvian <b>Lat</b> is now included in the <b>Reuters 2000</b> foreign exchange dealing system.  
<b>Three Latvian banks -  Saules Bank, Riga Commercial Bank</b> and the <b>Latvian Capital 
Bank</b> are linked to the system. 
<p>
An <b>International Monetary Fund</b> (IMF) mission, lead by IMF Baltic department head Emanuel 
van der Mennsbrugghe visit Riga in early June. The mission may well decide to amend the Latvian-IMF 
memorandum which stipulates that Latvia hold its 1995 inflation rate below 15 per cent. This figure is 
seen as unrealistic by <b>Central Bank</b> President Einars Repse, who has said that inflation could 
remain above 25 per cent in 1995. The IMF mission held talks with newly appointed Finance Minister 
Indra Samite. 
<p>
Five Latvian commercial banks have applied to service a US$13 million line of credit. The five banks are 
the <b>Latvian Universal Bank Unibanka</b>, the <b>Commercial Bank of Riga</b>, <b>Latvian 
Investment Bank, Latvian Land and Mortgage Bank</b> and the <b>Bank of Latvia</b>. 
<p>
<b>Amoco/OPAB (Amoco Overseas Exploration Company/ Oljeprospektering AB</b> have held 
discussions with representatives of the Ministry of Economy to co-ordinate the text of an agreement 
relating to oil extraction in the Baltic. Neighbouring Lithuania has expressed its disapproval of the talks, 
although in early June Lithuania and Latvia reached a provisional - and still secret - agreement on 
extraction rights for a four kilometre wide area of the Baltic. 
<p>
<b>Shell Latvia</b> opened its first Latvian service station in Riga on 21 April. 
<p>
The <b><a href="http://www.lda.gov.lv">Latvian Development Agency</a></b> has published its annual <b>Latvian Export Directory 1995</b>. 
Copies can be obtained from the agency (Perses iela 2, Riga LV1442). 
<p>
The <b>Radisson SAS Daugava Hotel</b> in Riga opens on 1 July, with rates for the 365 rooms starting 
at US$135.00. 
<p>
Debt-ridden carrier <b>Latavio</b> looked in danger of closure at the end of May. <b>Latvian 
Privatisation Agency (LPA)</b> director Talis Linkaits announced that the LPA had assumed responsibility 
for all the airline's affairs. Earlier, LPA general director Janis Naglis had announced that the privatisation 
scheme for the airline was complete subject to agreement being reached over the airline's debts, estimates 
of which range from US$15 million to a mind boggling US$600 million. The airline's future has been 
further clouded by the collapse of its largest creditor, <b>Baltija Banka</b> and the intervention of 
Turkish `aviation consultancy' <b>INCOS</b>, thought by some to be a front operation for `Russian 
interests'.
<p> 
