<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>LITHUANIA</h3>

Lithuania reported a 0.6 per cent growth in GDP in 1994. The GDP figure for 1994 was US$650 million 
(Litas 2.6 billion). The government expects a 5-6 per cent growth rate for 1995. Prices increased by 2.2 
per cent in May, while unemployment was 5.8 per cent. Industrial production increased by 30 per cent in 
March, but fell by 5.8 per cent in April.
<p>
UK Consultancy <b>TEK</b> and the Lithuanian group <b>Sklenis</b> have prepared, with 
<b>Phare</b> assistance, an industry plan for the Lithuanian textile industry. The industry employs 
27,000 people, second only to the food processing industry with a work force of 48,000. 
<p>
Total foreign direct investment in Lithuania at the end of April 1995 was US$220 million. 
<p>
<b>ABN AMRO Bank</b> of the Netherlands is to oversee the activities of Lithuania's second largest 
bank, the <b>Vilnius Bank</b> 
<p>
The <b>European Investment Bank</b> has granted an Ecu5 million loan to the <b>Lithuanian 
Development Bank</b> for the support of small- to medium-sized companies operating in the services 
areas of tourism, energy conservation and environmental protection. 
<p>
Japan's <b>Export-Import Bank</b> (EXIM) is to provide US$145 million towards the financing of the 
<b>Butinge</b> oil terminal.
<p> 
<hr>
<center><img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="besummy.html">Summary Menu</a></center>

