<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>MACEDONIA</h3>

Macedonia and the <b>World Bank</b> reached agreement in April for a US$99 million credit for the 
<b>Bank of Macedonia</b>. The credit comes in two tranches, one of US$85 million is to support 
Macedonia's current structural reforms, the other US$14 million is for expenditure on social projects. 
<p>
The German parliament has approved a DM5 million grant for construction works on the Beljakovce-
Deve Bair railway. 
<p>
Retail prices increased by 1.6 per cent in March as compared to February. The rise was alleviated by lower 
prices in the agricultural sector according to the <b>State Statistics Bureau</b>. Services rose by 5.3 per 
cent. 
<p>
The <b>European Bank for Reconstruction and Development</b> (EBRD) has approved a US$22 million 
credit for a 113.5 km power-line to link the Bitola power station with Skopje. 
<p>
A <b>Special Agricultural Corridor '95</b> has been opened to facilitate exports and mitigate losses in 
the transportation of agricultural products to European markets. Officially designated border-crossings 
under the corridor scheme will be: Deve Bair - Gueshevo on the Macedonian/ Bulgarian border, Ruse - 
Ghurghu between Bulgaria and Romania and Barash - Artand on the border between Romania and 
Hungary. 
<p>
The <b>Macedonian Privatisation Agency (MPA)</b> announced in July that 130 companies have so far 
been privatised. A further 462 have received MPA approval. Government revenue to date is DM13.5 in 
cash while a further DM12.62m has been released from frozen foreign currency deposits. DM52m has 
been paid into the <b>National Pension Fund</b> (15% of each company's social, or community owned, 
capital).
<p>
The government has set a target of privatising 791 companies by the end of 1995. Larger companies are 
beginning to join the process, as are those seeking foreign investment participation. These companies 
include <b>Oteks</b> (textiles, DM35.4m turnover), <b>GP Beton</b> (construction engineering, 
DM35.7m turnover) and <b>Ineks Drim</b> (hotels, DM3.2m turnover). 
<p>
The <b>European Court of Justice</b>, in a preliminary opinion, took the view that the trade embargo 
imposed by Greece on Macedonia did not breach the <b>Treaty of Rome</b>. Advocate-general Francis 
Jacobs took the view that were it not for a safeguard clause in the treaty relating to internal disturbances, 
times of serious international tension or the need to carry out obligations to maintain peace and internal 
security, then the embargo would clearly have been in breach of the <b>EU</b>'s common commercial 
policy. 
<p>
