<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>POLAND</h3>

President <b>Walesa's</b> main rival for the presidency, Alexander Kwasniewski leader of the main 
group of the Democratic Left Alliance (SLD) formally declared his candidacy in mid-May having won the 
backing of 296 out of 300 delegates at the annual convention of the Social Democracy of the Polish 
Republic party. Opinion polls show Mr Kwasnieski leading the presidential contenders with 20 per cent of 
the vote, followed by  Jacek Kuron of the Union for Freedom party and the ombudsman Tadeusz Zielinski, 
both with 15 per cent. Mr Walesa's share is put at 8 per cent.
<p>
<b>Moody's</b>, the international credit agency, accorded Poland an investment grade credit rating in 
May. The move coincided with Poland's first Eurobond issue for US$200 million. The improved rating 
will enable Polish authorities to seek investment from new sources of private capital. Apart from Poland, 
Moody's has now granted its investment grade rating to two other countries in the region - the Czech and 
Slovak republics. 
<p>
<b>Coca-Cola</b> has ordered four <b>Asquith Shire</b> vans, at a cost of US$50,000 each for its 
operations in Poland and Croatia.  
<p>
A Polish banking consortium led by <b>Bank Handlowy</b> made history in May by providing a US$260 
million loan, the biggest financial package yet arranged by domestic banks, to <b>Plock</b> refinery. 
Bank Handlowy also lead the consortium that granted a US$250 million loan for the modernisation of the 
<b>Turow</b> power station by <b>Asea Brown Boveri</b> (ABB) and <b>Pyropower Corp</b> of 
California. 
<p>
<b>Grolsch</b> the Dutch brewer plans to take a minority stake in <b>Brewpole</b> which owns 51 per 
cent of market leader <b>Elbrewery</b> and <b>Hevelius</b> a smaller brewery. 
<p>
Agriculture Ministry Under-Secretary Ryzsard Smolarek criticised the protective stance of the 
<b>European Union</b> over food imports. Polish farm exports, US$2.1 billion in 1994, (1993 US$1.6 
billion) account for 12 per cent of total exports. 
<p>
UK estate agents <b>Healey & Baker</b> have been appointed to market the <b>Ilmet Complex</b> a 
32,500 sq.m. development of offices, shops, restaurants and a banking hall situated on the ONZ 
roundabout in Warsaw. The first phase of the scheme is scheduled for occupation in autumn 1996. The 
company has also been appointed by <b>Mahler Project International</b> to market the <b>Ochota 
Office Park</b> to the west of Warsaw. 
<p>
Cellular concrete manufacturer <b>Prefabet-Ostroleka</b> has been rescued from bankruptcy by the 
improbably named <b>Ytong Holding Gmbh</b>. Under the arrangement, Ytong assumes responsibilities 
for all of Prefabet's liabilities (estimated at DM1.6 million) and will invest DM10 million in the plant. 
Ytong paid DM4 million for an undisclosed shareholding in Prefabet. 
<p>
<b>Pol-Float Saint Gobain</b> the Polish subsidiary of French glass manufacturer <b>Saint Gobain</b> 
is to spend DM170 million on an environment friendly glassworks at Dabrowa Gornicza. The company 
has signed a DM16 million contract with <b>Mostostal Zabrze</b> for the building structure. The 
glassworks will produce 500 tons of glass per 24 hour shift, and employ 250 people. Meanwhile, in 
Sandomierz UK glassmaker <b>Pilkington's</b> subsidiary <b>Pilkington Sandomierz</b> is investing 
Zl400 million in a factory to produce 140,000 tons of float glass per year for the domestic market, as well 
as windows for the <b>Fiat</b> and <b>FSO</b> auto plants. 
<p>
<b>Armstrong World Industries</b> new plant for the manufacture of thermal insulation products is to be 
located in Sroda Slaska. (<b>Coca-Cola</b> was the first US company to set up in Sroda Slaska). The 
new factory will open in early 1996 employing 117. 
<p>
<b>DSS Holding</b> of the UK plans to invest US$10 million in Kielce-based <b>Kieleckie Zaklady 
Wyborow Papierowych</b>. Some secrecy surrounds the investment pending negotiations with trades unions 
over employment levels, social security and wages. 
<p>
<b>Grundig SA</b> of Germany is proceeding with plans to construct a factory, in Kalisz, to produce 
between 60,000 and 200,000 14-inch television sets per year. 
<p>
<b>Motorola</b> has purchased a 38 per cent stake in <b>Uni-Net</b> whose principal shareholder is 
<b>RP Telekom</b>. The joint venture, backed by a US$5 million investment from each partner, will 
develop a radio-telegraphic trunking network called <b>Radio-Net</b>. 
<p>
US fast food specialist <b>McDonald's</b> plans to open 15 new restaurants in Poland by the end of 1995 
creating some 1,500 jobs. Average investment per outlet is about US$1 million. McDonald's has already 
invested US$30 million in Poland. 
<p>
Finance minister <b>Grzegorz Kolodko</b> threatened to resign in May in protest at the coalition 
government's failure to cut social security spending and other anti-inflationary measures. Annual inflation 
in April 1995 reached a worrying 32.4, worse than the 31.2 per cent registered in 1994. The government's 
inflation target for the end of 1995 is 20 per cent. 
<p>
Minister Kolodko also considers it unlikely that the end 1996 deadline for the privatisation of nine major 
banks will be met. Two banks <b>Bank Gdanski</b> and  <b>Powszechny Bank Kredytowy</b> are 
scheduled to be sold in 1995. Kolodko is pessimistic about the prospects for privatising the remaining four 
banks <b>Powszechny Bank Gospodarczy, Bank Zachodni, Pomorski Bank Kredytowy</b> and <b>Bank 
Depozytowo-Kredytowy</b> in 1996. The 1996 deadline was put forward by the Polish authorities as a 
precondition for a US$700 million loan from western governments to support the bank privatisation 
scheme. Bank privatisations have become unfashionable with Polish investors: bank stocks now account 
for over 40 per cent of the Warsaw Stock Exchange's total capitalization.
<p>
Any similarities between Polish Prime Minister Jozef Olesky and <b>Uncle Fester</b> of the <b>Addams 
Family</b> have been strongly denied.
<p>
<b>General Motors</b> (GM) plans to expand its co-operation with <b>Fabryka Samochodow 
Osobowych</b> (FSO) and is considering taking a stake in FSO. GM and FSO are already joint venture 
partners in <b>GM Poland</b> where GM holds 70 per cent, the balance held by FSO. Under the 
arrangements being considered by GM, the FSO facility would be upgraded to produce GM models from 
CKD kits. Meanwhile <b>Ford</b> will start assembling its <b>Escort</b> model in Plonsk at the end of 
September 1995, followed by the assembly of <b>Transit</b> vans a month later. 
<p>
New car sales in Poland grew by 3.4 per cent in 1994 to a total of 250,000. Market leader is the 
<b>Fiat</b> group with 52 per cent (130,000 units, followed by <b>FSO</b> with 84,000. Other 
manufacturers come in well behind, lead by <b>General Motors</b> with 3.9 per cent and 5,869 units. 
<p>
National carrier <b>LOT</b> has expressed a preference for banks, rather than another carrier, to acquire 
a strategic 29 per cent stake in the airline. 51 per cent of LOT is to be retained by the state, 20 per cent 
sold to the employees and the balance to a third party investor(s). LOT has a code sharing agreement with 
<b>American Airlines</b>. The national airline has also banned smoking in business class on all its Boeing 
767 flights, including those on the London-Warsaw route. 
<p>
A seven mile stretch of Warsaw's first metro-line, with 11 stations, opened in April at a cost of US$1.5 
billion. 
<p>
<b>Philips</b> of Holland was preferred to Poland's <b>Elektrim</b> by the governor of Olsztyn 
province for a 60 per cent stake in the <b>Farel</b> household-appliance plant in Ketrzyn. Philips will 
invest 10 million guilders in the plant over three years and install a Zl3.5 million (US$1.5 million) 
production line. 
<p>
Poland accounts for 24 per cent of total foreign investment in the region (US$17.2 billion at the end of 
1994), putting it in second place behind Hungary, with 27 per cent. 
<p>
<hr>
