<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>ROMANIA</h3>

At the end of May Romania marked its return to international capital markets with the signing of a 
US$150 million one-year syndicated loan for the <b>National Bank of Romania</b>. The loan,  arranged by 
<b>Citibank</b>, was increased from US$75 million to US$150 million after being heavily over-
subscribed. The loan is designed to improve the country's foreign currency reserves. 
Romania's first stock exchange <b>Bursa de Valori Bucuresti</b> is due to open in the summer of 1995, 
two years behind schedule. Mr Ioan Mihaila, president of <b>Intertrust SA</b> is to chair the nine man 
committee running the exchange pending the appointment of a general manager. The stock exchange will 
have a budget of Lei1 billion (US$530,500) and will be housed in a section of the <b>National Bank of 
Romania</b>. 
<p>
Romania was rebuffed by the <b>International Monetary Fund</b> (IMF) following the one-week visit of 
an IMF mission in May. The IMF decided not to release a US$265 million loan originally due in March 
because the Romanian government had delayed privatisation and restructuring the public sector.
The government has also failed to meet the conditions for a US$250 million <b>World Bank</b> 
<b>Financial and Enterprise Sector Adjustment Loan</b> (FESAL). 
<p>
In May Parliament finally approved the <b>Mass Privatisation Programme</b> (MPP). The MPP aims to 
sell off shares in around 2,500 small- and medium-sized enterprises over a 12 month period, for a 
combination of cash and free privatisation vouchers. The MPP will give each Romanian vouchers worth 
Lei875,000 (US$464) to be exchanged for up to 60 per cent of the companies' equity. Since 1990, about 
1,000 companies have been privatised. 
<p>
Romania's industrial production stood at Lei3.8 trillion in February, up 9.2 per cent from January and up 
11.1 per cent on the preceding year. Industrial output rose by 7.5 per cent in the first two months of 1995 
as against the same period in 1994. 
<p>
The <b>European Investment Bank</b> is granting Romania US$100 million for the modernisation and 
development of the national telecommunications system. The loan will cover the installation, over a three 
year period, of between 20 and 30 new telephone exchanges and the expansion of existing exchanges.
<p>
<b>Romanian Development Agency</b> (RDA) figures for the first three months of 1995 show an 8.4 per 
cent increase in foreign investments since the end of 1994, from a total US$1.23 billion up to US$1.33 
billion. There are now 169 joint ventures with foreign equity participation in excess of US$1 million. 
<p>
Romania's unemployment rate dropped to 10.5 per cent in April, from 10.9 per cent in March. 
<p>
<b>Crédit Commercial de France</b> has been retained to advise on the sale of <b>Banca Romana 
Pentru Dezvoltare</b> the Romanian development bank, which will be the first state owned bank to be 
privatised. While the Romanian authorities want to privatise by the end of 1995, the general expectation is 
that it will take at least a year. 
<p>
The private sector accounted for 35 per cent of GDP in 1994, a 5 per cent increase over 1993. In the 
agricultural sector, private production averaged 80 per cent. The <b>National Commission for 
Statistics</b> estimates that 40 per cent of the labour force is now in the private sector.  
<p>
<b>Shell Romania SRL</b> opened its first petrol station in April at Otopeni on the outskirts of 
Bucharest. 
<p>
Korean industrial group <b>Daewoo</b> have taken a 51 per cent stake in <b>Rodae Automobile</b> 
the joint venture created from <b>Oltcit</b> the former state-owned manufacturer. Daewoo is to pay 
US$156 million in three staged payments for its stake in the company. The remaining 49 per cent is to be 
held by <b>Automobile Craiova</b>, which will assume responsibility for the debts and liabilities of the 
old company. The plant will manufacture the <b>Cielo</b> family saloon, initially from CKD kits, but 
eventually building up to 80 per cent local content. Annual production is expected to reach 120,000 units 
by 1998 with a targeted 50 per cent for export. 
<p>
Romania's long and medium term external debt at the end of 1994 totalled US$4.4 billion dollars, an 
increase of US$1.06 billion over 1993. Principal creditors are international financial organisations 
(US$2.71 billion), the <b>European Union</b> (EU) (S$550 million), the <b>International Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development</b> (IBRD) (US$666 million) and the  <b>European Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development</b> (EBRD) (US$138 million). Short term commitments at the end of 
1994 were US$889.1 million, with US$500.9 owed to Romania. 
<p>
Anglo-Dutch multinational <b>Unilever</b> is to take an additional 5 per cent stake in Ploiesti based 
<b>Dero SA</b>, its Romanian subsidiary. Unilever already holds 70 per cent of Dero's stock. 
<hr>
