<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>RUSSIA</h3>

The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has approved a US$6.8 billion loan for Russia, its second largest 
ever. The 12-month stand-by loan is designed to back up the economic reform programme aimed at 
reducing inflation to 1 per cent per month in the second half of 1995.
<p>
Monthly inflation fell to 7.9 per cent in May, a drop of 0.6 per cent over the April figure of 8.5 per cent. 
<p>
Russia accounted for 15 per cent of total foreign direct investment in the region at the end of 1994, behind 
Hungary (27 per cent) and Poland (24 per cent). If investments of less than US$10 million are excluded, 
Russia comes second with 31 per cent, behind Khazakhstan (39 per cent). 
<p>
Shares in a number of large enterprises are to be opened to bidding to both foreign and domestic 
institutions according to the <b>State Property Committee</b>. The decision reverses an earlier proposal 
whereby US$1.8 billion was to be loaned to the enterprises by a group of Russian banks using the 
companies' assets as collateral. The contentious bank proposal had aroused alarm among western banking 
circles as it risked concentrating enormous economic power in a very small group. Among those opposed 
to the deal was Finance Minister Vladimir Panskov, whose objections centred more on the terms and 
conditions of the loan proposal. 
<p>
Real GDP for the first four months of 1995 was down 4 per cent over the same period last year, suggesting 
that the recession was bottoming out. In 1994 GDP contracted by 4 per cent. 
<p>
The <b>Moscow Financial and Futures Exchange</b> is to begin trading on 17 July. The exchange will 
trade currency futures and equities in competition with the Moscow <b>Interbank</b> currency exchange. 
<p>
<b>General Alexander Lebed</b>, presidential wannabee, threatened to resign once too often at the end 
of May over Defence Ministry policy towards Moldova. This time his resignation was accepted by defence 
minister, <b>Pavel Grachev</b>. 
<p>
<b>Nearmedic</b>, a new pharmaceutical company, is to sell US$3 million worth of shares to fund its 
expansion. The company was originally established as a Soviet-British joint venture. The share issue is 
being handled by London based broker <b>Ice Securities</b>. 
<p>
<b>Lukoil</b> plans to convert shares in its subsidiaries into a single unified stock on the basis of one 
share in the main <b>Kogalymneftegaz</b> crude oil production unit. The company, which accounts for 
15 per cent of Russia's output, is also taking a controlling interest in six more enterprises, strengthening 
its grip on the industry. The six enterprises to be acquired include three oil producers - 
<b>Nizhnevolskneft, Permneft</b> and <b>Kaliningradmorneftegaz</b>, two distribution companies 
based in Kaliningrad and Astrakhan and the <b>Perm</b> lubricants factory. 
<p>
Meanwhile, <b>Rosneft</b> the oil company that accounts for more than a third of the country's output, 
is to be transformed into a joint stock company. The government will retain a 51 per cent share. 
<p>
<b>Association of Commercial Banks</b> sources estimate that only 10 per cent of Russia's 2,500 banks 
are adequately capitalised to meet the central bank's new reserve requirements and capital adequacy ratios, 
which came into force on 1 May. The reforms, spearheaded by `Iron Lady' <b>Tatiana Paramonova</b> 
acting chairwoman of the central bank have brought the authorities into conflict with the commercial 
banking sector. 
<p>
UK confectionery group <b>Cadbury Schweppes</b>, with its Russian partner <b>Rostel</b>, is to build 
a US$125 million chocolate factory at Chudovo near St Petersburg. With a 5 per cent share of the market, 
Cadbury is in second place behind the US <b>Mars</b> group. 
<p>
<b>AO Mosenergo</b>, the Moscow electricity and heat utility has retained <b>Salomon Brothers</b> as 
its international financial advisers. Salomon Brothers will advise Mosenergo on a long-term programme 
to increase its share value and make its debut in the international capital markets. 
<p>
Ex-boxer, and recently bankrupted UK entrepreneur <b>George Walker</b> through his company 
<b>SIS Telesport</b> is providing coverage of British dog and horse races to betting outlets in Russia. 
Over 700 outlets have applied for the service, which costs the proprietor between US$5,000 and 
US$25,000 per year. 
<p>
Russian nickel production is expected to reach 185,000 tonnes in 1995, an increase of 5,000 tonnes over 
the 1994 figure. Increased domestic consumption suggests that exports are likely to drop from their 1994 
level of 142,600 tonnes to around 110,000 tonnes.
<p>
Aluminium output for 1995 is forecast at 2.7 million tonnes, 25,000 tonnes up on 1994. 
<p>
<b>Irkutskenergo</b> of Siberia has appointed US citizen Mr James Rogers, Chief Operating Officer of 
<b>Cinergy</b> of Cincinnati to its board of directors. Mr Rogers does not speak any Russian. 
<p>
The <b>US Pentagon</b> is about to take delivery of a US$60 million <b>S-300 V</b> Russian built 
surface to air missile system. 
<p>
<b>Agrarian Party</b> Chairman Mikhail Lapshin forecasts a drop in agricultural production of some 
40-50 per cent in 1995. 
<p>
The <b>European Bank for Reconstruction and Development</b> (EBRD) is to grant US$1.5 million for 
the development of a Russian share registry. The registry will be set up with the technical assistance of the 
<b>Bank of New York</b>. The French <b>Commission des Operations de Bourse</b> is to sign an 
agreement to develop the equity market. 
<p>
A consortium of <b>Boeing</b>, Norwegian shipbuilder <b>Kvaerner</b>, <b>RSC Energia</b> and 
Ukrainian rocket builder <b>NPO-Yuzhoye</b> is to build a sea-based rocket launching centre for 
commercial satellites at a cost of between US$100-US$150 million. 
<p>
Moscow's <b>National Hotel</b> has reopened after refurbishment. The hotel  has 231 air conditioned 
rooms. Now managed by the UK's <b>Forte</b> group, room rates start at a US$310 per night. The price 
includes the bath-plug. 
<p>
Private Russian carrier, <b>Transaero</b>, has started regular daily flights between Moscow and St 
Petersburg. The service ends the 20 year monopoly of <b>Pulkovo Airlines</b>. 
<p>
The <b>Central Bank of Russia</b> has revoked the licences of 20 Moscow banks. In 1993 the total 
figure for the whole year was 26. Latest to go was that of the <b>Credit-Consensus</b> bank. 
<p>
`No plane, no gain' is the word as the private plane overtakes the mobile 'phone as <u>the</u> status 
symbol among Russia's business elite. <b>Raytheon Aircraft</b> has just sold the ninth <b>Hawker 
800</b> (secondhand, admittedly) to be operated in Russia. The aircraft are mostly operated by 
<b>Avcom</b> in Moscow, and serviced in Chester, UK. 
<p>
<b>Columbia-Presbyterian Health Services Inc.,</b> the <b>Fund for Large Enterprises in Russia</b> 
(FLER), and <b>Pepsico World Trading Inc</b> are operating the <b>Columbia-Presbyterian 
Moscow</b> medical clinic in Moscow. For an annual fee of US$475.00 Moscow residents have access to 
quality medical attention. Business travellers are eligible for a US$90.00 annual membership valid for 30 
days. (For more information: Sherrie Dulworth +1 914 767 7130). 
<p>
Office rents in Moscow are now the second highest in Europe. Only London is more expensive according 
to property consultants <b>Healey and Baker</b>. Moscow office rents average US$60 per square foot 
(US$600 per square metre), more expensive than Paris, Frankfurt or Brussels. Healey and Baker estimate 
a current shortfall of 75 million square feet (seven million square metres) with 1.9 million square feet 
(180,000 square metres) of office space coming on to the market in 1995. Since office development began 
in 1988-89, the take-up rate has been 100 per cent. Demand is set to outstrip supply for some time; Healey 
& Baker expect office rental levels to remain at current levels for at least three years. 
<p>
Expansive (and reputedly expensive) US lawyers <b>Squire, Sanders and Dempsey</b> have opened an 
office in Moscow in co-operation with the Moscow firm of <b>Kheifets, Binetsky & Kheifets</b>. The firm's 
Moscow office is to be headed up by Mr Mobbs - ( no connection, we're sure). 
<p>
The name <b>Smirnoff</b> is synonymous with vodka - and Russia. Once sole purveyors of vodka to the 
Imperial Russian Court with an annual turnover before 1917 of US$20 million, the Smirnoffs had to leave 
Russia - taking the recipe with them. 1994 saw Smirnoff vodka being distilled in Russia again for the first 
time since the revolution - using a pot still in the traditional way - to produce a new brew called Smirnoff 
Black, passed through Siberian Silver Birch charcoal. The Smirnoff company proposes to launch its 
Russian-produced Smirnoff Black in upmarket outlets in 1995. 
Vienna based <b>Carlton Partners</b> is suing its former partner, the <b>Nizhnevatovskneftegaz</b> oil 
company for breach of contract. Carlton claims that the Russian company refused to pay US$1.6 million 
in costs incurred by the partnership. 
<p>
Russian telecommunications provider <b>Central Telegraph</b> is to introduce a new radio-based data 
network using the <b>Widanet</b> system developed by the UK's <b>Racal Messenger</b>. With an initial 
order of some US$5 million, Racal is to supply Central Telegraph with 3,000 Radio pads - pocket sized 
modems, a number of base stations and a radio network management centre. 
<p>
<hr>
<center><img src="images/pinred.gif" alt="*"> <a href="besummy.html">Summary Menu</a></center>

</center>
