<html>
<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>SLOVAKIA</h3>

The Slovak crown (Koruna) was revalued by 4 per cent in late May.
<p>
Peter Hrinko, President of Kosice based metal industry giant <b>VSZ</b> was fired in April after 14 
months in the job, along with two other members of the VSZ board, Ferdinand Petrak, VP Finance and 
Vladimir Balanik, VP sales. Hrinko was replaced by his deputy Jan Smerek. The dismissals sent shock 
waves through the Slovakian business community. VSZ employs 25,000 and has some 100 subsidiaries. 
The official reason for the dismissals was `big differences in opinion on major issues and inability to 
communicate well'. VSZ declared an Sk695 million profit in 1994. There is a sense of `deja vu' about the 
dismissals. In December 1993 four of the company's five-man supervisory board were dismissed, 
including then President Zoltan Berghauer. The company has had five different presidents since 1989.  
<p>
Investment funds <b>First Slovak Investment Privatization Company</b> (PSIPS) and <b>First Slovak 
Investment Company</b> (PSIS) (no connection) have had their licenses withdrawn by the Ministry of 
Finance. PSIPS' closure was caused by the fund's failure, and apparent inability, to pay out the Sk20,000 
due to each of its investors in respect of each coupon book. The fund's administration was first entrusted 
by the Ministry to <b>Tatra Invest</b> a subsidiary of <b>Tatra Bank</b> and later to <b>VUB 
Invest</b> the parent company of <b>VUB Kupon</b>. Matters were further complicated when VUB Kupon 
trading was suspended for a period of three months, following moves by dominant shareholder 
<b>Nomura International</b> to break up the fund. The suspension was eventually lifted on 27 April. 
Ladislav Vaskovic, VUB Invest's general director revealed that the PSIPS fund's reserves meant that 
shareholders would only receive SK14,000 per book, and not the SK20,000 originally promised. The case 
of PSIS raised more eyebrows as the company appeared to have an exemplary record of service for its 
700,000 clients. The company managed four investment and three cash funds.
The background to the government's position is the Meciar administration's determination to keep control 
of major industries after the next privatisation round scheduled for July 1995. Finance Ministry officials 
have indicated a wish to cut from 20 to 10 per cent the maximum stake that an investment fund can hold 
in companies to be privatised. There are also reports of moves to reduce to 5 per cent the voting rights 
funds can exercise in a privatised company, regardless of the size of their stake. 
<p>
Slovakia's budget deficit dropped at the end of March to Sk4.1 billion (US$140 million), Sk1.2 billion less 
than at the end of February. 
<p>
The <b>Hungarian Bank for Foreign Trade, Magyar Kulkereskedelmi Bank MKB</b> opened a branch 
in Bratislava on 1 April. 
<p>
<b>Vasa Televizia (VTV)</b> the private television station started by Zarnovica based <b>VTV Cable 
TV Ltd</b> began broadcasting on 22 April. The station will initially transmit via a cable network, 
although it has been granted a satellite licence.  
<p>
<b>Creditanstalt Bratislava</b> a subsidiary of Austrian <b>Creditanstalt Bankverein</b> opened with a 
capital of Sk315.5 million (US$10.9 million). The bank is the first wholly owned subsidiary of a foreign 
bank to be granted a licence in Slovakia.
<p>
Despite its obvious success - for the past year the <b>Bratislava Options Exchange</b> (BOB) has been 
the most popular trading exchange by volume - the exchange's future appeared to be in the balance as 
deputy finance minister Jozef Magula prepared plans to rationalise the securities market by concentrating 
spot and forward trading activities on the <b>Bratislava Stock Exchange</b> (BCPB). To date there have 
been four accepted ways of trading shares in Slovakia: through the BCPB, through one day forwards on 
the BOB, through the <b>RM Slovakia</b> (RM-S) continuous daily auctions `priebezna' and through 
the RM-S fortnightly auctions. 
At the heart of the problem is the BOB `one day forward' trade, which has allowed the BOB to trade 
shares in a more sophisticated fashion than the cumbersome procedures of the BCPB, and grab the lion's 
share of the market - to the irritation of the BCPB.
Igor Junas, BOB chairman, claimed that the uncertain position had placed BOB `in crisis.' The BOB has 
been losing money since it was first created in 1993 and has reportedly used its start-up capital. The 
consensus in Bratislava's financial circles at the end of May was that the BOB would find it difficult to 
overcome the opposition not only of the Finance Ministry, but also of the BCPB, which has formed an 
alliance with RM-S. 
<p>
The <b>International Monetary Fund</b> (IMF) has approved an advance loan of Special Drawing 
Rights (SDR) 128.7 million for Slovakia, 45 per cent of the country's quota. The Slovak debt to the fund at 
the end of october 1994 was SDR428.5 million. 
<p>
<b>Philip Morris</b> the US tobacco and foods group is being threatened with legal action over the 
treatment of minority shareholders in its Slovakian chocolate subsidiary <b>Figaro</b>. Minority 
shareholders have accused <b>Kraft Jacobs Suchard</b>, the Philip Morris subsidiary that manages 
Figaro, of depressing profits by channelling sales through sister companies and raising exorbitant 
management charges. 
<p>
Slovakia's constitutional court has blocked a move by Parliament in November 1994 to overturn the 
privatisation of 50 state companies approved by the state government. The court ruled that the proposed 
legislation `breached the right of private ownership, the principle of the division of power and the 
principle that a law cannot be retroactive'. Parliament has six months in which to redraft the law, 
`Otherwise it will be annulled.' President Kovacs refused to sign the law and returned it to the legislators. 
A group of 40 opposition deputies submitted the law to the constitutional court for review. 
<p>
Consumer price inflation fell from an annual 11.5 per cent in February to 11.3 per cent in March. 
<p>
The future of the <b>Mochovce</b> nuclear power station remained unclear as the Slovak government 
expressed doubts about its ability to meet the financial conditions attached to the US$292 million loan for 
the project from the <b>European Bank for Reconstruction and Development</b> (EBRD). The 
government asked the EBRD to postpone a decision while it considered an offer from <b>Skoda 
Praha</b> of the Czech Republic to complete the plant for DM800 million, about one third less than the 
price quoted by <b>Electricité de France</b> (EdF). The Skoda Praha offer would not qualify for EBRD 
assistance. 
<p>
