<head>
<title>Business Europa Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<center><i><font size=+2>S</font><font size=+1>ummer 1995.</i></font></center><br>
<h3>SLOVENIA</h3>

<b>SKK Banka</b> has launched the region's first hostile take-over bid - for Gorenje based 
<b>Gorenjska Banka</b>. The bid of St11,000 (US$99.00) per share compares with Gorensjka Banka's book 
value of St15,000 per share. 
<p>
Figures produced by <b>GiroCredit Research</b> the research arm of the Austrian bank, put Slovenia's 
economic growth at 5 per cent for 1994. GiroCredit attributes the upturn to high educational standards, a 
well qualified labour force and increased private consumption. The bank anticipates a growing budget 
deficit and fears that, despite the liberal investment regime, foreign investment is unlikely to pick up. Low 
levels of foreign investment are attributed to the introduction of a new company takeover law in July 1995, 
which is designed to place foreign and domestic investors on an equal footing. Under the provisions of the 
law, share purchases that add up to a greater than 25 per cent interest in a company will be subject to 
investigation. 
<p>
<b>Nova Ljubljanska banka d.d.</b> Deputy President stated, in an interview with <b>Reuters</b>, that 
the bank is likely to be privatised and quoted on the stock exchange `within two years'. 
<p>
Italy appears to have dropped its objections to granting Slovenia an association agreement with the 
<b>European Union</b> (EU). The EU has agreed to allow Italy to establish a financial centre in Trieste, 
offering generous tax breaks to banks, insurance companies and financial intermediaries for business 
carried out in the former communist bloc. The EU Commission hopes that the concessions granted will 
diffuse Italian concerns over property rights in Slovenia, around which objections to Slovenian EU 
association have focused. 
<p>
Adolf Zupan, Director General of <b>Telekom Slovenije</b>, the new company formed after the split of 
<b>PTT Slovenije</b>, in an interview with Ljubljana <b>Busines$</b> magazine, has set out the 
company's development plans. With 30 lines per 1,000 inhabitants, Slovenia is well above the regional 
average of 14 per 1000, but still has a waiting list of 51,000 and more than 30 per cent of subscribers 
sharing party-lines.
<p>
