<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<h3>Basic Structure</h3>
<P>
Bulgaria has a two tier banking system with around 72 commercial banks. 
In July 1991 the National Bank Law was passed which set out the central 
bank functions of the Bulgarian National Bank. During 1992 some private 
banks began to compete with the state commercial banks.
<P>
In August 1992, the Bulgarian National Bank approved the establishment of 
the Bulgarian Credit Commercial Bank formed from the merger of 22 joint 
stock banks. The new bank's portfolio of more than Lev11 million accounted 
for just over 10 per cent of the total credit in the banking system. This 
was the first significant example of bank consolidation which will 
eventually affect all 80 plus commercial banks in the country. Such a move 
was supported by the World Bank and the IMF who wanted to encourage greater 
international competitiveness and a more solid credit base.
<P>
The country's first private bank was the appropriately named First Private 
Bank which by the end of 1992 had more than 70 branches and 650 employees. 
The bank was formed by a group of entrepreneurs who formed the Union of 
Private Economic Enterprises (UPEE). 1992 was the first year in which 
Bulgarian banks' financial statements were checked by independent auditors.
<P>
Economic reform began in earnest in February 1991. By that time GDP had fall
en by 13.6 per cent from 1989, prices had risen by 53 per cent and some 
50,000 were newly unemployed. The state still owned 95 per cent of fixed 
productive assets. Bulgaria's infrastructure was in a parlous state and no 
legal framework existed for a market economy. Foreign debt servicing had 
been suspended, there was no access to finance markets abroad and creditors 
of the Bulgarian government had little faith that things could improve. One 
year later very little had been achieved - the state was still paramount, 
GDP had fallen by 21.3 per cent from 1990, consumer prices had risen by 
640 per cent, unemployment had risen to 450,000. Reform was stimulated by 
an IMF inspired stabilisation programme involving a restrictive fiscal and 
monetary policy, income and credit austerity. The budget deficit became a 
key target with emphasis on cuts in expenditure and revenue enhancement. 
Such measures had a predictably deflationary short term effect. Yet while
the budget deficit came under some control, imported inflation and the 
rapid fall in the industrial base continued well into 1992. Supply 
bottlenecks were commonplace and the currency fell in foreign exchange 
markets. Price liberalisation led to speculative hoarding and further 
shortages. Incomes were indexed to the rapid rise in inflation thus causing 
further long term effects on prices. In terms of real change, the 
privatisation programme up to 1992, had made little impact. Substantial 
reform was hampered by unstable government and lack of political will.
<P>
An International Monetary Fund (IMF) mission to Sofia in July 1994 approved 
Bulgaria's reform performance and said it would ask the IMF Board for 
additional funds to support its debt reduction deal. In principle, US$100 
million would be released upon approval by the IMF Board later in 1994. A 
further US$200 million is expected to become available after the next IMF 
Review mission in October 1994. IMF loans to Bulgaria in the first half of 
1994 include US$97 million in standby credits and Systematic Transformation 
Facility, totalling US$320 million.
<P>
After the freezing of foreign debts in 1990, Bulgaria began paying off 
overdue interest on its US$13 billion of foreign debts (mostly owed to more 
than 300 commercial banks around the world.) The 1992 budget deficit was 
raised in order to help finance this debt. Support came from the OECD who 
urged creditors to allow Bulgaria to continue what it saw as praiseworthy 
economic reform. At the end of June 1994 Bulgaria was due to sign a debt 
reduction agreement with the London Club of commercial bank creditors. The 
deal will cut by 47.1 per cent Bulgaria's US$8.16 billion debt to more than 
300 commercial creditor banks, led by Deutsche Bank. The World Bank has been 
approached for funding to cover initial payments under the deal.
<P>
<PRE>
Bulgaria's private banks: 1992 results (ranked by profitability)
(Lev '000)

Bank                          Net profit   Capital      Assets
Bank for Agricultural Credit     143,807   259,605   3,639,735
