<P>
<a name="Trading"></a>
<h3>Trading Regulations</H3>
<P>
Exports and imports are subject to decree number 264. This decree allows
for the free trade of goods with the exception of certain goods subject to 
registration. These include the export of: livestock and poultry, dairy 
products, cooking oils, wine, oil, coal, ferrous and non ferrous metals 
and their alloys, ores, bread grain, wheat flour, hides, mineral waters. 
Similar registration requirements apply to alcoholic drinks, oil, coal, 
ingots of metals, perfumery.
<P>
There are also requirements for certain imports and exports to be subject 
to licensing; imports in this category include: pharmaceutical goods, drugs, 
tobacco products, dangerous substances, explosives, hunting and sports 
weapons, rare and precious metals.
<P>
<PRE>
From 1992 import quotas applied to the following goods:

         Import ceiling (tonnes)
Tobaccos          10,000
Oranges           30,000
Bananas           20,000
Ice cream          1,000


Goods liable for import taxes are:

Commodity         Tax (%)
Frozen beef and veal   25
Frozen pork            15
Frozen poultry meat    25
Butter                 15
Perfumery               5
</PRE>
<P>
In January 1993, a 15 per cent customs duty was imposed on all imported 
cars. Used cars more than 10 years old attract an extra 10 per cent.
<P>
<PRE>
Imports exempt from duties include:

Therapeutic baby foods
Farming machinery and spares
Plant protection chemicals
Unprocessed timber
Molasses
Medical instruments
</PRE>
<P>
