<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Tops"></a>
<h3>Foreign Investment Regulations</h3>
<P>
Foreign companies doing business in Bulgaria are regulated by the Law on 
Commerce (Commercial Code) and the Business of Foreign Persons and Foreign 
Investment Protection Act. The laws abolish the minimum investment 
requirement of US$50,000. Foreign companies can carry on business activities
in exactly the same way as Bulgarian citizens. Executive orders will no 
longer apply to foreign businesses (this was formerly a source of 
instability as government decree could change at any time in the old system).
<P>
Foreign companies may carry on any business which is not prohibited by law 
and which conforms to local legislation. Licences are required for the 
production and trade in armaments, banking and insurance activities, the 
exploration and exploitation of natural resources. Such licences that are 
required are issued by the government, banking permits are granted by the 
National Bank of Bulgaria. Foreigners are not permitted to own land, and 
joint ventures with foreign participation exceeding 50 per cent may not 
own agricultural land.
<P>
Foreign persons are permitted to carry on business in any legal form: sole 
trader, partnerships, limited liability companies and joint stock companies 
limited by shares. The size of a foreign interest in a partnership is not 
prescribed. Foreigners under the new laws are able to buy foreign currency 
from Bulgarian banks and transfer it abroad. Foreign persons are obliged to 
register with the local tax authorities within 14 days from the date on 
which the decision on their registration had been published in the Official 
Gazette. Foreigners must also register any investment made within 30 days.
<P>
Companies with foreign participation where the share exceeds 49 per cent 
and where investments equal US$100,000, are subject to a tax rate of 30 
per cent. Where there is a lower share of foreign participation, the ruling 
tax rate is 40 per cent (this also applies to firms where annual profits 
exceed Lev1 million.
<P>
Tax holidays apply to mixed companies operating in a designated free trade 
zone. For such companies, the first five years after registration are tax 
free, after this the rate is 20 per cent.
<P>
There are six free trade zones including the towns of Vidin, Rousse, 
Bourgas, Dragoman, Plovdiv and Svilengrad. Besides liberal profits tax 
treatment, these free trade zones offer duty free trading of all goods 
whether imported or exported, goods and services traded between the free 
trade zones and other areas of the country. Activities allowed within the 
zones include: manufacture of goods for export, loading and unloading or 
handling of duty free imported goods earmarked for export, commercial 
services, transport for international trade, banking, crediting and other 
financial operations. Labour relations and social insurance of Bulgarian 
citizens employed within the zones are the same as in the rest of the 
country.
<P>
Goods and services are subject to VAT which ranges from 10 to 60 per cent. 
Companies pay a 40 per cent profits tax regardless of the level of profit. 
Local authorities also charge a 10 per cent levy on taxable profit.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="buseur00.html">Home Page</A></center>
<P>

