<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">
<P>
<h3>Stock Exchange</h3>
The Sofia Stock Exchange began operations in the first months of 1992. In 
the first year of operation most of the securities traded were shares issued
by the banks with a majority state holding. By the end of 1992 no debentures
of either Bulgarian or foreign companies had been traded. Growth was 
expected in the market for government bonds which were first released in 
December 1992. Growth of the stock market was hampered by the absence of any
Securities and Exchange legislation which is usually necessary to establish 
legal framework for trading.
<P>
There are several commodity exchanges which have developed fairly quickly. 
In January 1992, 13 commodity exchanges across the country formed an 
association to establish a standard information system, closer contacts 
between brokers, and formal rules for fair and open operations. One of these 
exchanges deals in fish trading and is based in Varna. There were plans to 
hold regular sessions with a daily bulletin of contractual information. 
Other commodity exchanges are limited mainly to staples such as sugar and 
salt.
<P>
The Plovdiv Commodity Exchange specialises in farm products: fruit and 
vegetables, seeds, saplings, farm machinery, foods, oils and metals.
<P>
