<P>
<h3>Railways</h3>
6,597 km of track include 4,055 standard gauge, 2,609 km of which is 
electrified. There is a programme of rapid electrification and one of the 
government's transport development priorities is the modernisation of the 
main Dragoman Svilengrad Vidin Sofia Koulata line. The aim is to bring this 
and other routes up to modern European standards and help Bulgaria qualify 
for joining the European High speed System (TER). The first stage in the 
restructuring of the railways was completed in mid 1993. The project 
contract was awarded by the EBRD to CIE Consult (Eire), KMG Peat Marwick 
(UK office) and Kennedy & Donkin (UK). A five year strategic plan is to be 
drawn up to define the relationship between the state and the railways as 
an autonomous body.
<P>
<PRE>
<B>
Rail traffic			          1988    1989    1990</B>

Passenger km (million)      		 8,143   7,601   7,793
Freight ton km (million)    		17,585  17,034  14,132
</PRE>
