<P>
<h3>Ports & Shipping</h3>
The state owned Bulgarian United Shipping and Shipbuilding Corporation 
controlled the country's ports and shipping. The two most important ports 
are Burgas with a loading capacity for tankers of 20,000 tons; the other 
main port is Varna.
<P>
The Bulgarian Marine Fleet which carries around 80 per cent of Bulgaria's 
trade has been transformed into a joint stock company. In 1992, however, 
the fleet was on the edge of financial collapse. With the average age of its
 tankers at 18 years, its coal freighters in need of overhaul and falling 
wages which did little to encourage skilled people to stay, the merchant 
marine was facing a severe crisis of confidence. On the positive side, a new
21,000 tonne vessel was on order from the country's Varna shipyard.
<P>
In September 1992, the Rhine Main Danube Canal opened to traffic to help 
relieve congested east west road and rail routes. Ships using the canal 
can reach the Black Sea from ports such as Rotterdam and Duisberg. Bulgaria 
will take some time to take full advantage from this new freight artery as 
it had no ships of the right size apart from three push tug boats and some 
barges. Pressure will grow on local ports to increase capacity and enhance 
transport links with the rest of the country's infrastructure.
<P>
<PRE>
<B>Inland waterways

                           	         1988     1989   1990</B>
Passenger km (million)         	           12       12      3
Freight ton km (million)    		2,162    1,946  1,606


<B>Sea borne shipping

				          1988     1989    1990</B>
