<P>
<h3>Air Transport</h3>
One of three government priorities for transport development announced in 
1991, was the development of Sofia International Airport. Tenders were 
subsequently received from 67 foreign companies, 12 of which offered to 
handle the whole construction project. Halcrow (UK) is currently preparing 
the master plan for the extension.
<P>
Bulgaria's national carrier, Balkan Airlines, employs 4,000 people and had 
a sales turnover of US$210 million in 1991. Targeted for early privatisation, 
the merchant bankers S.G. Warburg were appointed advisors in 1992 to help 
expedite the transformation. Potential partners are yet to be identified 
one possible backer may be the European Bank for Reconstruction and 
Development. One problem has been valuing the carrier. In July 1993 the 
Bulgarian Economic Review announced that a price of US$80m had been 
established by the Privatisation Agency. Foreign shareholding is limited to 
49 per cent with 20 per cent set aside for staff. The state reserves the 
right to own at least 40 per cent of the stock. Balkan was granted a 15 year 
franchise to act as sole airline to 53 destinations worldwide. Warburg 
pointed to the potential profitability of developing charter flights to 
Bulgaria's Black Sea coast.
<P>
<PRE>
<B>Balkan Air 1992 results</B>

Sales US$m             		210.0
% change               		+23.40
1992 net result US$m      	n/a
1991 net result US$m     	1.90
Passengers million       	1.44
