<P>
<a name="#Production"></a>
<h3>Production</H3>
Current oil production in Bulgaria is virtually negligible, despite 
considerable investment over the years, given the country's lack of modern 
technological equipment, especially in seismic interpretation and offshore 
drilling. Under the Communist régime, Bulgaria lacked investment funds 
necessary to purchase the technology or invest in research. The post 
communist government has brought in foreign companies.
<P>
At least eight agreements have been signed for exploration offshore in the 
Black Sea and on the Black Sea coast. These joint venture arrangements or 
concessions - which could be extended to cover other parts of the country 
include those with:

British Gas: to explore in the Kamchia and Burgas blocks.Exploration is 
expected to continue for five years.
<P>
Texaco Exploration Offshore Bulgaria Ltd: an exploration and production 
licence covering Block 3 together with Enterprise Oil (UK) and OMV.
<P>
The nuclear power station at Kozloduy consists of six units, the last of 
which was brought into commission in 1991. Until the end of 1990 the oldest 
four units at Kozloduy had one of the best load factors in the world. 
Recent international concern about the station's safety record, however, has
led to calls for its complete closure. Although two of the six units at 
Kozloduy were shut down for safety and maintenance reasons, it was accepted 
that the complete closure of Kozloduy was seen as impractical, given the 
dependence on nuclear power.  Instead the government increased tariffs to 
reduce demand and increased the salaries to attract the best engineers. 
Independent observers have noted a marked improvement in safety at 
Kozloduy; this has been due to training, new investment and a marked 
increase in employee morale.
<P>
The French company Sofregas planned to set up a joint venture with 
Gasstroymontazh to design and build gas distribution networks in medium 
sized Bulgarian towns. Finance from the EU PHARE Programme helped to launch 
the venture which will provide gas lines to around 100 centres around the 
country.
<P>
Plans have been announced to close all 11 uranium mines by 1995. Government 
figures say that one kg of uranium costs US$61 to produce while the maximum 
sale price is US$43. State funds were used to help in the closing down 
process. Non payment of wages caused by falling orders led to industrial 
action.
<P>
<B>Refining situation and oil production 1992</B>
<PRE>
Crude production ('000 bpd)      	7
Number of refineries             	3
Refining capacity ('000 bpd)   		300
Refining throughput ('000 bpd) 		n/a
Source: OPEC Bulletin
</PRE>
<P>
Brown coal output dropped from 28.5 million tonnes in 1991 to 26.8 million 
tonnes in 1992.
<P>
About 40 per cent of Bulgaria's electricity is nuclear generated while 55 
per cent is thermal. Hydro represents the remaining 5 per cent.
<P>
