<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<h3>Production</h3>
Accounting for 26 per cent of employment and 16 per cent of GDP in 1993, the 
agricultural sector has declined less sharply than the country's industrial 
base. In 1993 agricultural output declined by  1.9 per cent, an improvement 
on 1992's figure of  7.7 per cent.
<P>
Due to lack of funds and disruption caused by the dismantling of the state 
co operatives, the areas sown for wheat and barley were already 10 to 15 per 
cent lower in 1992. The reduction in the sugar beet crop has meant that only 
10 per cent of domestic demand can be met. The cereal harvest in 1992 was 
estimated to be 6.8 million tonnes (it had been 10.2 million tonnes in 1980).
<P>
The state bought over one million tonnes of wheat for bread in the non 
producing regions. Drought led to the maize crop being about 750,000 tonnes 
lower than expected. There was a bumper harvest for sunflowers in 1992. Lack
of funds for fertilisers and other necessary chemicals brought the 1993 
crop level sharply downwards. The drought in 1993 has not helped matters. 
Farm animals have had to go without the required amounts of food as a result 
of the poor crop production. Many animals have died of starvation and the 
outlook for meat/poultry production does not look favourable.
<P>
Ninety per cent of Bulgaria's rice fields will be left uncultivated in 1994. 
Rice yields dropped to 10,000 tonnes in 1993, from a peak of 50,000 tonnes. 
In 1994 only 2,300 hectares are expected to be put under rice, meaning that 
Bulgaria will have to import rice to meet demand. The domestic cultivation 
of rice is no longer profitable.
<P>
<PRE>
<B>Principal crops
('000 tonnes)
		      1989    1990      1991    1992</B>
Cereals			9,652     8,216     9,020     6,845
Wheat			5,425     5,292     4,503    *3,270
Rye			  n/a        49        46       *40
Potatoes		  458       433       503      *550
Sugar Beet		  966       548       868      *350
Vegetables		1,662     1,565     1,334    †1,404
Fruit (inc grapes)	1,811     1,677     1,330     1,152
* estimate
Source: Bulgarian Statistical Yearbook, FAO


<B>Livestock
('000 head )
		      1989    1990      1991     1992</B>
Cattle			1,613     1,575     1,457      1,311
Pigs			4,119     4,332     4,187      3,010
Sheep			8,609     8,130     7,938      6,703
Poultry		       41,804    36,338    27,998    *21,000
* estimate
Source: FAO Production Yearbook


<B>Agricultural land in use		 1991</B>
('000 hectares)

Arable land                  		    4,642.7
Cropland                                    3,764.0
Orchards                                      293.2
Natural meadows                               288.4
Man made pastures, etc                        197.2
Natural pastures                            1,516.3
Source: Bulgarian Statistical Yearbook
</PRE>
<P>
Bulgaria's fishing industry was given a boost by the opening of a fish 
exchange in Varna. Catches range from Black Sea sprat, mackerel and turbot 
to fresh water fish such as carp and trout. There is a growing market for 
mussels and shrimps.
<P>
