<P>
<H3>Telecoms Network</H3>
Bulgaria has the highest telephone density of any east European country. 
About one in three Bulgarians has access to a telephone, a rate comparable 
to that of Spain and Ireland. There are about 2.7 million telephone 
subscribers. These ostensibly attractive statistics disguise the severe 
problems of Bulgaria's antiquated telecommunications system. The waiting 
list is over half a million, most users are unable to dial long distance 
directly, and only 25 per cent of calls get through.
<P>
The government plans to spend US$339.8m on improvements to the system. In 
April 1993 the World Bank approved a US$30m loan in support of the project, 
which is also financed by the EIB and the EBRD. The project will install 
123,500 new digital lines and some 1,700 km of long distance optical fibre 
cables.
<P>
The telephone system is operated by the National Automatic Telephone Network
(NATN). In 1991 NATN had an annual income of US$117 million. Independent 
consultants have estimated a 7 per cent growth rate over the 10 years to 
2001. Total investment required has been estimated at US$1 billion.
<P>
In 1992 93 the communications network was reformed in three ways: a 
Telecommunications Bill, a Mail Bill and ordinances relating to private 
radio stations and cable television. The first licences for cable television
were granted in early 1993. Reform of the system began in 1991 when the 
Mail and Telecommunications Committee assumed regulatory functions for 
postal services, broadcasting and space communications. In 1992, supervisory 
functions were transferred to the State Communications Inspectorate. From 
1 January 1993, the operation of the telecommunications system fell to two 
new bodies, Bulgarian Telecommunications and Bulgarian Mail. It was 
envisaged that some form of state monopoly would continue for several years 
although privatisation of part of the industry can be expected in the near 
future.
<P>
In cellular telephony, a joint venture between Cable and Wireless (UK) and 
Bulgarian Telecommunications was established to install a mobile radio 
telephone system in Sofia, Bourgas, Varna and along the Sofia Plovdiv 
motorway. The expected total cost of the project was US$50 million.
<P>
<HR>
