<P>
<H3>Broadcasting & The Press</H3>
Since the overthrow of communism, there has been a revival in the newspaper 
industry and the press in general. Censorship laws were liberalised in 1990 
and journals formerly banned were freely circulated. These included the main
organs of the large political parties: Demokratsiya of the UDF (circulation 
190,000), Druma - the BSP daily (300,000) and Trud - the union newspaper
(125,000).
<P>
<PRE>
<B>Other principal dailies include:

Title                Circulation (approx)</B>
24 Hours                           85,000
Faks                               86,000
Glas                               90,000
Otechestven Vestnik                70,000
Sport                             100,000
Svoboden Narod                     75,000
Vecherni Novini                   120,000
Zemya                             105,000
</PRE>

<B>Among the many specialist business journals are:</B>
<UL>
<LI>168 Hours (English language weekly business journal)
<LI>Bulgarski Biznes
<LI>Bulgarian Digest Monthly (English language)
<LI>Bulgarian Economic Review (English language)
<LI>Computer World
<LI>Delova Sedmitsa - (SBD Seven Business Days) (English language)
</UL>
Whilst television is still in the hands of the state organisations 
Bulgarska Televiziya and Bulgarsko Radio there are (end 1993) many private 
radio stations. There are two television channels (Channels 1 & 2), with 81 
and 45.2 per cent penetration respectively, and three radio stations on 
medium and short wave bands. There is a growing interest in satellite and 
cable television with foreign stations such as TV5 from France.
<P>
There are 2.5 million thousand television households.
<P>
