<P>
<H3>Eating Habits</H3>
<P>
Although western food is commonly available, there is much to be said for 
trying the local cuisine.
<P>
Breakfast in Bulgaria is a hearty affair with hamniks (a hot egg dish), a 
cold platter of eggs, meats, yoghurt (of which Bulgarians are proud), honey, 
jam and bread. The most important meal of the day is often lunch with 
salads, soup, a meat dish (or occasionally fish or chicken), and very sweet 
desserts such as baklava. Bulgarians have a sweet tooth. Coffee is usually 
served Turkish style - very thick, black and in small cups.
<P>
Bulgarian cuisine is centred around pork and lamb dishes using a wide 
variety of fresh vegetables. Specialist dishes include: shopska salad 
(diced tomatoes, cucumber and peppers) with sheep's milk cheese. Another 
famous dish is tarator, a cold soup of yoghurt, cucumber and walnuts. Street
snacks abound in Bulgaria with a strong Turkish influence: kebabcheta 
(grilled meats); kavarma (a meat and vegetable casserole); drob sarma 
(chopped lamb liver baked with rice and eggs); sarmi (stuffed vine leaves); 
banitsa (baked cheese and spinach).
<P>
Bulgaria produces its own full bodied wines. The national drink is the fiery 
slivova which is a plum, or sometimes grape, brandy. Typical of this part 
of the world, coffee is taken very strong and black, tea is usually served 
with lemon. In Sofia there are many high quality restaurants, some with 
nightclub or folksong entertainments. Food can also be enjoyed in the 
taverns or mehana, where the service is more informal (and often quicker).
<P>
