<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HEAD>
<title>Business Euro</title>
<!version 1.00>
<HTML>
<meta name="description" value="Business Euro">
<meta name "Admin-Email" value="mxp@ipl.co.uk">
<meta name "keywords" value="Industry, Political, Structure, Facts">
<!--File name buseu15h.html-->
<!--Last update 17/August/95-->
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#FF0000" alink="#000000" vlink="#0000ff">

<P>
<a name="Top"></a>
<H3>Getting About</H3>
<P>
<ul>
<li> <a href="#Air">Air</a>
<li> <a href="#Road">Road</a>
<li> <a href="#Rail">Rail</a>
<li> <a href="#Water">Water</a>
<li> <a href="#City">City Transport</a>
<li> <a href="#Taxis">Taxis</a>
<li> <a href="#Car">Car Hire</a>
</UL>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="buseur15.html">Visitors Guide</A></center>
<P>
<a name="Air"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<H3>Air</H3>
Balkan Bulgarian Airlines operate eight domestic lines connecting Sofia with 
all main towns. Shuttle service to Varna and Bourgas. Fares are generally 
inexpensive.
<P>
<a name="Road"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Road</h3>
Good road network. For those arriving by car, the main routes are the E80 
coming from former Yugoslavia - the crossing point is at Kalotina; the E870 
crossing from former Yugoslavia at Gyuesevo; the E79 from Greece or the E80 
from Turkey.
<P>
<a name="Rail"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Rail</h3>
Approximately 4,500 km of track connecting all main towns. First class 
travel recommended. Trains from the rest of Europe arrive at the Central 
Station which is in the north of Sofia. Travelling by train in Bulgaria can 
be frustrating unless tickets are bought in advance (avoid the stations and 
buy them at the reservation offices to be found in all major towns). The 
main routes from Sofia are to Varna, Burgas, Plovdiv, Dragoman, and Kulata. 
Trains are usually very busy and reservations are obligatory on express 
services. First class services are available on longer journeys and there 
are sleeping carriages on the Sofia Black Sea routes. Buffet car services 
are limited. A railway restructuring study was commissioned in February 1993 
and the Bulgarian State Railways (BDZ) announced plans to privatise all 
operations which are not central to its main activities.
<P>
<a name="Water"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Water</h3>
Some towns along the Black Sea coast and the Danube are linked by hydrofoil 
and there is a regular ferry linking Bulgaria with Romania over the river 
Danube.
<P>
<a name="City"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>City Transport</h3>
Efficient and cheap tram and bus service. Buses and trolleys in Sofia run 
fairly regularly, tickets are purchased in advance from a stand near the 
bus stop. A ticket is punched into the machine on boarding the bus. Inter 
city buses are often very crowded and are not recommended. All flights from 
abroad arrive at Sofia International Airport. There are several ways to 
travel the six mile ride into town; the cheapest method is by bus. There is 
an express service (number 284) and the slower number 84.
<P>
<a name="Taxis"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Taxis</h3>
Available and cheap. Official taxis have meters. A 5 10 per cent tip in 
local currency is usual. Telephone number (Sofia) 597108. Taxis can be 
picked up at the stand and can be hailed anywhere in the city.
<P>
<a name="Car"></a>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<h3>Car Hire</h3>
Service available from Balkantourist, large hotels and at Sofia 
International Airport. International driving licence not necessary. Most 
car hire accounts transacted in hard currency (between $0.40 and $0.60 per 
km). Drivers normally given special petrol coupons, which can be used 
throughout the country. Most of the main highways are good although often 
very busy. There are motorways linking Sofia with Plovdiv and the former 
Yugoslav border. Speed limits: out of town 80 kph and 120 kph on motorways, 
in town 60 kph. Drinking and driving strictly prohibited.
<P>
<hr>
<a href="#Top"><img src="images/arrowup.gif" alt="Top" align=right border=0></a>
<P>
<center><IMG SRC="images/pinred.gif"> <A HREF="buseur15.html">Visitor's Guide Page</A></center>
<P>

