<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02/06--Pumping Too Hard</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Daily%20Exclusives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-Pan.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02/06--Pumping Too Hard</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>Momentum players are flocking to oil drilling stocks, which is why you should avoid them.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Scott Satterwhite, manager of the $75 million Biltmore Special Values Fund, shops for bargain stocks where few investors dare to tread: among unknown companies, in turnaround industries, and wherever there's a business experiencing upheaval. He commonly tip toes around land mines like poor earnings, lack of liquidity, and perplexing balance sheets.<p>
But Satterwhite has an eye for overachievers dressed in underdog clothing--such stocks helped him bring investors in the Special Values Fund returns in excess of 30 percent last year.<p>
As bad as things may be for these down-and-seemingly-out stocks, Satterwhite does have his limits. "I don't want to come out with one leg and an arm," he says. "I look for companies with the staying power to get them through the rough times."<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Momentum players are flocking to the oil drilling sector.</font></b><p><p>
In 1994 the oil drilling sector was experiencing a dry spell. Rigs were docked and companies weren't making any money. Most money managers avoided the sector. But Satterwhite hit black crude with <a name="NASD:CLDR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13005"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cliff's Drilling Co.</b></a> (NASDAQ: CLDR). He was attracted to the company's low valuation and strong management. "It was debt-free and had a fair amount of cash," he says. The Special Values Fund bought the stock for $13.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Historical Stock Price Chart</font></b><p><p>
<img src="/imgs/Cliffs.gif" width=160 height=164>
<br><p>
In early 1996, the company borrowed $100 million to acquire a number of assets--including jack-up drilling rigs, land drilling rigs, and mobile off-shore production units. <p>
By all accounts, the move was an effective way to create value within the company. Too effective for Satterwhite. "In '94 you couldn't give the stock away," he says. "But then the stock price, earnings, and cash flow rose dramatically. Now the momentum players are here in a big way."<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>Oil drilling insiders have started selling.</font></b><p><p>
When Cliff's hit $40 last summer, Satterwhite sold, feeling that the built--in-discount was gone. "Now in the $60s, there is little margin of safety. The environment in this volatile industry can turn so quickly," he says. "At these levels, Cliff's looks like a speculative investment to me."<p>
Apparently insiders feel the same--they have been selling off shares since last spring, and have continued to sell. According to Insider's Research Wire, company CEO Douglas Swanson has reduced his actionable holdings 88 percent. Others in the company have done similarly. "I think they know what they are doing," he says. Satterwhite puts the company's Fair Value at $40.<p>
[Post your questions and comments about Cliff's Drilling Co. on the <a href="/forums/talkstocks/stock1/worthboard.html">"Pan of the Week"</a> message board. Worth OnLine will forward your questions to Satterwhite and post his response in a few days.]

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


<font size=+1><b>Table of Contents</b><p>
</font>						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB1">Momentum players are flocking to the oil drilling sector.</a><p>
						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB2">Historical Stock Price Chart</a><p>
						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB3">Oil drilling insiders have started selling.</a><p>
					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:CLDR">Cliffs Drilling Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
<font size=+1><b>Related Links</b><br></font>Browse the <a href="/articles/PZOL13.html">"Pan of the Week"</a> archives.
					<p>
					
<font size=+1><b>Related Message Board</b><p></font><img src="/imgs/smpin.gif" align=left>
<a href="/forums/talkstocks/stock1/worthboard.html">	Pan of the Week	</a>
 <p>

</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
