<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - A Penny Saved</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Daily%20Exclusives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>A Penny Saved</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Jim Rogers</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>Investors know how to save -- which is why they should only invest in nations that do, too.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						My last column focused on what I believe is the single most important ingredient to success for global investors: the ability to identify nations that have unfettered economies and free markets -- in other words, those that foster economic freedom. Countries that move toward economic openness invariably beat out nations that move in the opposite direction -- and by wide margins. This month, I will explore how countries get the most benefit from economic freedom: namely, through savings and investment. <p>
Investors often fail to realize just how often the deck gets shuffled in the global economy. Nations that lead the pack rarely stay on top for long, and countries can come seemingly from out of nowhere to grab the lead. In an average lifetime, three or four major upheavals can occur in the world economic order. In the 20th century, global economic leadership has shifted from England to the United States to Japan.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Historically, wealth has shifted around the globe.</font></b><p><p>
This is the way of the world. People accumulate massive amounts of wealth and continually fail to hold on to it. It's a truism that it is easier to make a lot of money than to keep it -- and it's as true for nations as it is for individuals. Examples from history abound. In the 15th century, the Portuguese were rich. In the 16th century, conquistadors discovered gold and silver mines in Latin America and bailed out Spain, thereby giving it wealth for the next couple of centuries. Peru and Mexico profited as enormously from their precious-metal mines in the 16th and 17th centuries as the Kuwaitis and Arabs have from oil in the 20th century. Burma was the richest country in Asia in 1962, but now it's among the poorest -- far, far behind Japan and others.<p>
As countries accumulate wealth, their politicians all too often submit to the temptation to tax that wealth and redistribute it one way or another -- which makes them popular at the same time they are corroding the vigor of the body economic, a proclivity we've seen in this century in Europe and North America.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
A savvy investor can tell which countries are saving their pennies and which are not.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
I find it unfortunate that so many people still believe in the zero-sum notion that profit in one area necessarily creates a loss somewhere else -- or that the haves can succeed only at the expense of the have-nots. This is simply not the case. The science of economics -- dismal as it otherwise may be -- has shown it is possible for everyone to win at the same time.<p>
Savings and investment make this possible. <p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Business operators with the best ideas attract the most capital. Economies that promote this type of environment benefit everyone.</font></b><p><p>
When people save by setting aside a portion of their earnings, a pool of capital is created. This money, in turn, attracts folks with ideas about how to put it to use. If the capital is held by a bank, these entrepreneurs will try to persuade the bankers to lend them some of it. If the capital is directed into the stock market, the folks with the bright business ideas will compete for it in that arena.<p>
Over time, the business operators who have the best ideas (and can therefore offer the best returns) generally attract the most capital. In this way, the smartest and most efficient producers in each field receive the money they need to exploit their ideas, skills, and resources most effectively. <p>
Economies that promote this type of environment -- high savings rates along with a market-driven system for putting the accumulated funds to the best use -- benefit everyone. Consumers get the best products at the best possible prices. Workers go to jobs at enterprises that are healthy and expanding. Businesses get the capital they need to put their good ideas to work.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>A nation's savings rate is a good way to determine if a country is a good investment.</font></b><p><p>
But it all starts with savings -- the fuel an economy needs to grow. This is why, in addition to examining a nation's economic climate (capital gets distributed efficiently only if markets are free), I advise global investors to take a close look at a nation's savings rate.<p>
Just as economic performance can vary widely from country to country, so can savings rates. According to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development in Washington, D.C., Japan's gross savings rate in 1995, measured as a percentage of disposable household income, was 13.4 percent. Germany's savings rate was 11.6 percent, and France's was 14.3 percent. In contrast, the savings rate in the U.S. was equal to only 4.7 percent of disposable household income (down from 9 percent in 1982). Canada's rate was 7.4 percent, and Finland's was 5 percent.<p>
These numbers alone do not tell the whole story, however, because governments can foul up the picture by managing their finances poorly. When a government runs a budget deficit, it must go into the market and compete with business for a share of the nation's savings pool. When this happens, a nation's hard-earned savings can end up getting diverted from investments in industrial production and business expansion toward such things as military spending, social welfare, and -- when a government runs deficits year after year -- interest payments on government borrowings that are many years old.<p>
<p><a name="SUB4"><b><font size=+1>In addition to checking out a country's savings rate, look into its national balance sheet.</font></b><p><p>
So another way to look at how well a country is doing on the savings front is to check out its national balance sheet: its assets minus its debt. In doing so, an investor can figure out which countries are net debtors and which are net creditors. Even though a country's coffers may be overflowing, you have to be sure the country doesn't owe so much that its assets are offset by its debt.<p>
The International Monetary Fund publishes the International Financial Statistics Yearbook, which offers pages of fascinating data on the balance sheets of most countries. With this information, a savvy investor can examine which countries are doing a good job of saving their pennies and which are not.<p>
Which countries stand out? Singapore and Japan all have huge net-asset positions on a per capita basis. In 1995, Singapore's 3 million people had $20,376 per capita and Japan's 125 million people had $3,574. Even Korea was a creditor, with a per capita position of $644. Thirty years ago, most of these Asian countries were struggling to break even. Compare those amounts with that of the U.S., which had a net debtor position of negative $628 per person in 1995.<p>
<p><a name="SUB5"><b><font size=+1>Another good indicator? A country's total reserve figures.</font></b><p><p>
A country's total reserves, including its holdings of gold, are another good number to look at. According to the IMF yearbook, total reserves grew 773 percent for all industrialized countries from 1965 to 1995. Of these countries, the total reserves of the U.S. grew a meager 285 percent while Switzerland's total reserves grew 696 percent and Japan's a whopping 5,668 percent. <p>
These figures provide a strong indication of which countries not only enjoy wealth today but are managing themselves in a way that will enable them to have even more wealth in the future. The knowledgeable investor who's done well only in the U.S. over the past decades needs to realize that he or she is long on the dollar, which weakens every month as the U.S. national debt grows.<p>
<p><a name="SUB6"><b><font size=+1>"It's not just knowing who has the money now but figuring out who's going to use it the right way."</font></b><p><p>
Ultimately, these history lessons don't mean much unless you understand the real point: It's not just knowing who has the money now but figuring out who's going to use it the right way. In 1975, the United States was in decent financial shape but was headed down a rocky path. Asian countries today are the ones that have the formula right: Their governments' policies produce high savings rates. They also tax lightly in an atmosphere of economic openness. The result is one all investors recognize: Asian Tigers. Chile is the tiger of Latin America; it's at the top of the heap in terms of promoting savings and investment and letting the market have a free hand -- measures that pulled it out of one of the most severe economic slumps ever seen in our hemisphere. Chile's per capita net assets have risen from a frightening negative $21,267 in 1965 to a positive $757 in 1995. This economic miracle took more than the legislature's passing a few laws -- it also required a people's sustained effort over two decades to put their house in order.<p>
As Charles Dickens is often incorrectly quoted as saying (it's actually from the musical Oliver!): "In this world, one thing counts: in the bank, large amounts." Just as a large savings account gives an individual tremendous power over his own life and others, it does the same thing for nations and peoples: A country has to have the discipline not only to make money but to save it and then put it to good use. That means spending it on things that contribute to a nation's wealth-generating capacity, such as plants and equipment, and not on luxury palaces (Saudi Arabia) or on interest payments on ever increasing old debt (the United States).<p>
The job for the global investor is to identify the nations that understand that a penny saved is a penny that can produce returns.<p>
Jim Rogers, senior contributing editor for Worth, is the author of Investment Biker, published by Adams.<p>
Read "Columns" in its entirety in the February 1997 issue of Worth (on newsstands today), or in the Worth archives on this site.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

