<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02/04--Peter Lynch Screen (Pt. 1)</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Daily%20Exclusives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-SS.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02/04--Peter Lynch Screen (Pt. 1)</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>We begin our Peter Lynch-style series with a quantitative filter.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The best way to find good investment ideas is to look around you. If you're a butcher, a baker, a candlestick maker, or a cocktail shaker you have a vast reservoir of specialized knowledge that makes you a true expert.  <p>
You know knives, flour, home decorating, and glassware. You know meat, sugar, wax, and leisure. You know countermakers, industrial ovens, metals, and bars. Whatever your business or trade, you know what you need and what companies serve you best--so you know a lot of what you need to know about investing.  <p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>We're hoping the market has overlooked some beautiful things.</font></b><p><p>
But we can't put that kind of knowledge into a series of screens. Instead, we begin this series with a quantitative filter, the only kind our computer understands. <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
We're hoping the market has overlooked some beautiful things about these companies.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
In this installment we screened for companies whose P/E ratios are below the median for their industry. We're hoping they're below the median because the market has overlooked some beautiful things about them. In most cases, that's not the case. The market is generally pretty good about pricing companies where they ought to be priced.<p>
So of the 1700-+ companies here that look cheap on a P/E basis, only a few are real bargains. Our Sangreal [Editor's note: post on the message board if you can't find this word in Webster's] is a neglected niche company, controlling a market segment, in an unglamorous industry that would be difficult and time-consuming for a competitor to break into. Stick with us for the quest.<p>
[Post your comments and questions on the <a href="/forums/talkstocks/screen/worthboard.html">"Stock Screen of the Week"</a> message board.]<p>
Stocks listed in "Stock Screen of the Week" are not meant to be an endorsement of any kind. The purpose of this column is to demonstrate how the entire universe of stocks can be filtered by fundamental mathematical criteria. <p>
Worth OnLine would like to thank The American Association of Individual Investors for providing data for "Stock Screen of the Week." 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


