<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02/03--Hope You Die Before I Get Old</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Daily%20Exclusives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02/03--Hope You Die Before I Get Old</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>What if the Social Security system bought marketable securities?</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Social Security chatter leaves me in a gray daze. Too many people retiring all at the same time can't all spend the same money. A recent note concentrated my attention wonderfully. Here are the stripped down essentials:<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Social security taxes are already high. But since the money hasn't actually been invested, we'll have to pay them again.</font></b><p><p>
1) Social Security collects more than it spends and now has $549 billion in investments. (Good news!)<p>
2) Well, the $549 billion isn't really invested, it's been spent by the Treasury Department. (That's bad.)<p>
3) No problem, the Treasury Department gave the Social Security system IOUs! (Oh, good news!)<p>
4) Guess who pays the IOUs? (Heh, heh, heh.)<p>
</wam-subhead>The Social Security system lends money to the Treasury Department which in turn give the system back nonmarketable IOUs.</wam-subhead><p>
Social security taxes are already high. But since the money hasn't actually been invested, we'll have to pay them again. That's the short-short of a brief and clear note on Social Security by Jack Lavery and Nancy Vanden Houten of Merrill Lynch. By the way, paying off the IOUs won't do anything to help the long term Social Security deficit.  <p>
Quickly now--the Social Security system runs a surplus as long as it collects more in taxes than it pays out. As of the end of 1996, the surplus was $549 billion and by the year 2018 it's expected to be $2.87 trillion. <p>
Where is the money invested? It's lent to the Treasury Department.  The IOUs that the Treasury Department gives the Social Security system aren't bonds. They can't be sold--they're nonmarketable. By the way, the military and federal employee pension systems also "invest" in the same kind of non-marketable Treasury securities.<p>
</wam-subhead>There are three neat alternatives to the current system.</wam-subhead><p>
Say that Social Security is a piggy bank. We put money into our piggy bank today when we pay social security taxes. Tomorrow, we take the money out to buy candy--all the things that make up the expense side of the budget deficit. We put IOUs in the piggy bank to cover our candy bill. How can we get cash out again? We have to put cash in again first--through some more tax. So we end up paying the Social Security tax twice.<p>
What if the Social Security system didn't buy non-marketable IOUs--what if it bought marketable securities instead? Now we're getting somewhere. But where?<p>
Prudential Security's Charles Gabriel has a neat breakdown of the alternatives in the current issue of Strategy Weekly. A White House Advisory Council on Social Security split around three reform proposals. The first basically retains the current system, allows a little investing in marketable securities, and still plans for a tax increase to replenish the piggy bank. The second plan would scale back benefits, and force people to save in government-managed Individual Accounts through a new tax. The third plan, the Personal Savings Account, would basically let people manage their own investment accounts by kicking back a share of the taxes they and their employers pay.<p>
By the way, when the Advisory Council talks investing, it usually means investing in index funds.<p>
The details do get a big mind-numbing, but Social Security reform has huge potential to impact the markets, your personal savings plans, your tax bills, etc. Well, what do you think? Post your comments, suggestions, solutions or complaints on the <a href="/forum/talkstocks/week/worthboard.html">"Market Week Ahead"</a> message board.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


<font size=+1><b>Table of Contents</b><p>
</font>						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB1">Social security taxes are already high. But since the money hasn't actually been invested, we'll have to pay them again.</a><p>
					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
<font size=+1><b>Related Links</b><br></font>Browse the <a href=/articles/PZOL04.html">"Market Week Ahead"</a> archives.
