	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - The Staff Of Worth And Worth Online</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/+Worth1.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth1.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>The Staff Of Worth And Worth Online</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<b>W. RANDALL JONES</b><br>
Chief Executive Officer<br>
Capital Publishing Company Inc.<br><p>
W. Randall Jones was named chief executive officer of Capital Publishing Inc., the parent company of Worth magazine and Worth OnLine, in April 1991. His goal was to "revolutionize personal-finance journalism with a publication that is intelligent, enterta
ining, and dynamic." If anyone was up to the task, it was Jones. An industry maverick, at 30 he became the youngest publisher of a major American magazine when he took the helm at Esquire. In 1987, he was recognized by Folio magazine as one of 20 under-35
 "fast trackers" in magazine publishing. A graduate of the University of Georgia, Jones holds a bachelor of arts degree in journalism.<p>
<b>JOHN KOTEN</b><br>
Editor<br>
Worth<br><p>
John Koten became editor of Worth magazine in January 1993, following a distinguished 15-year career at The Wall Street Journal. A senior editor at the Journal, Koten served as chief of the newspaper's Chicago bureau. During his tenure, the bureau gained 
a strong reputation for innovative coverage and storytelling and won such prizes as the Robert F. Kennedy Award, the American Heart Association's Blakesly Award, the Associated Press Award for feature writing, and the grand prize of the Aviation and Space
 Writers Association. The Chicago bureau's stories were also nominated for three Pulitzer Prizes.<p>
<b>LEWIS SCHIFF</b><br>
Executive Producer<br>
Worth OnLine<br><p>
In September 1995, Lewis Schiff was named the executive producer of Worth OnLine. Charged with revitalizing the magazine's online edition, Schiff overhauled the site's design and content and introduced daily, online-exclusive stories to the formerly month
ly site. "The financial markets are constantly changing. Wall Street professionals have long relied on the electronic medium for their livelihood," Schiff says. "Now we're able to bring Wall Street to Main Street by giving online readers Worth's unique pe
rspective on money--every day." Schiff began his career in magazine publishing with the launch of City Family/La Familia de la Ciudad, a two-language magazine for inner-city families, when he was 21. He is still involved in its nationwide growth. In 1992,
 he was hired at Roger Black Inc., a design firm that is internationally known for magazine makeovers, where he oversaw the digital production of new magazines. Prior to accepting his current position, Schiff was Worth's art production manager, a position
 he held since 1994. Schiff, a native New Yorker, attended Hunter College, City University of New York.<p>
<b>DAYANA YOCHIM</b><br>
Staff Editor<br>
Worth OnLine<br><p>
As staff editor, Dayana Yochim helped develop the daily content and permanent areas of the revamped site, and continues to look for ways to use the online medium to enhance Worth magazine. Before joining Worth OnLine, Yochim spent five years as associate 
editor at a business trade magazine, writing everything from in-depth corporate profiles to fanciful fashion pieces. Her story assignments took her around the world--everywhere from Italy to Taiwan. Although her new position has grounded her in New York, 
Yochim is enthusiastic about the assignment: "At least when I travel in cyberspace, I never lose my luggage," she says. Yochim grew up in Lawrence, Kansas, and graduated with a degree in newspaper and magazine journalism from the University of Kansas.<p>

<b>JESSICA ROBINSON</b><br>
Associate Producer<br>
Worth OnLine<br><p>
Setting the pace as associate producer is Jessica Robinson, who manages the hour-to-hour deadlines required to put out Worth OnLine every day. She also organizes the troops to take on the site's major projects. Before joining the publication, Robinson wor
ked for a non-profit group concerned with environmental/conservation issues and for which she organized conferences, and managed the organization's grants and budget. Robinson grew up in Boston and New York, and graduated from New York University with a d
egree in economics.<p>
<b>MATTHEW SHARFF</b><br>
Production Manager<br>
Worth OnLine<br><p>
Matt Sharff, Worth OnLine's production manager, lives and works in southern Vermont. He started out in New York as a technology consultant to many of the city's top design studios. He was instrumental in developing the creative-services department at one 
of the world's largest advertising agencies, Ogilvy & Mather New York. At Ogilvy, Sharff helped create campaigns for such notable companies as AT&T and American Express. In addition to his work for Worth OnLine, Sharff takes on various projects, from book
 and magazine production to multimedia design. Sharff graduated from Columbia University, New York, with a degree in history.<p>
<b>AMANDA MEFFERT</b><br>
Production Associate<br>
Worth OnLine<br><p>
As production associate, Amanda Meffert helps the Worth OnLine staff execute new projects and maintain the continually updated site. Meffert moved to New York and began working for Worth OnLine just prior to the site's February 1996 re-launch. A native of
 Ocala, Florida, Meffert graduated from the University of Georgia with degrees in journalism and Spanish.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
