<html>
	<head>
		<title>Search Tips and Guidelines Page</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="../imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000">
	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top>
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Miscellaneous>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>

		 </td>
		<td  width=150>
		<center>
		
		
		</center>
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top rowspan=2>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<p>
		</center>

	<blockquote>
	<center>
               <b><font size=+3>Search Worth OnLine</font></b>
               
	</center>
	<p>
It's easy! Simply enter a word or phrase relating to your area of interest. This can be a proper name or a fragment of a proper name (e.g., "Motor" or "Motorola" or "Eisner"), or a regular noun (e.g., "biotech" or "biotechnology"). (Quotation marks DO NOT need to be entered into the search fields.)
<p>
Here are some tips on searching using words and phrases.
<p>
<b><a name="single">SINGLE WORDS OR PHRASES</a></b>
<p>
Begin your search by entering a single word or phrase. This is approach works best when you have a specific term in mind. Let's say you want to find out about DreamWorks SKG, the entertainment company founded by Steven Spielberg, Jefferey Katzenberg, and David Geffen. Since "DreamWorks" is not a very common word, simply enter the company name to begin your search. If the first attempt doesn't work, do not despair! Try some of the other tips listed below.
<p>
<b><a name="frag">FRAGMENTS OF SINGLE WORDS OR PHRASES</a></b>
<p>
Let's say that you're not sure how to spell DreamWorks. In that case, you can search by fragment -- that is, by entering AS MUCH OF THE SEARCH TERM AS YOU KNOW. For example, entering "Dream" or "Dreamw" will produce a list of all articles which contain the word fragment you have designated. A search for "Dream" will probably return some articles that are not relevant--they simply mention the word "dream" somewhere. In this case, you should use the feature which brings up the list of articles with sample paragraphs. This will help you weed out articles that are unrelated to your area of interest. <p>
<b><a name="and">LINKING SINGLE WORDS OR PHRASES USING AND</a></b>
<p>
Example: Entering "Flat AND Tax" instead of just "Tax" will return a list of articles that contain both the words "Flat" and "Tax."
<p>
More on linking search terms using the word AND...
<p>
In general, the AND command is useful for helping you narrow down a broad search. Let's say you know that Steven Spielberg and David Geffen founded a company, but you don't remember what it's called. By entering "Spielberg AND Geffen" you'd get all articles that mention BOTH Spielberg AND Geffen. Or, let's say you're only interested in finding about a recent deal between DreamWorks and Microsoft, rather than pulling up all articles on DreamWorks. Entering the search words "DreamWorks AND Microsoft" would bring up only those articles that contain both company names. <p>

<b><a name="or">LINKING SINGLE WORDS OR PHRASES USING OR</a></b>
<p>
Example: Entering "Estates OR Trusts" instead of just "Trusts" will return a list of the articles that contain EITHER the word "Estate" OR the word "Trust" as well articles that contain BOTH words.
<p>
More on linking search terms using the word OR...
<p>
When you want to broaden your search you can look for articles that contain one of a number of words. For example, to find out as much about the founders of DreamWorks as you can, simply enter "Spielberg OR Geffen OR Katzenberg." This will return a list of all articles which contain any one of the three names as well as articles that contain two or all three of the names. (Entering "Spielberg AND Geffen AND Katzenberg" will give you *only* articles that mention all three, not stories about the individuals.) In general, the OR command is useful for making sure you don't miss an article which might be of interest to you.  

	<p>
		</td><td width=150 valign=top>
			
		<center>
		<img src="/imgs/searchbutt.gif">
		</center>
		
	
	<p>
	<b>You can also take a look at our Archives to browse our material
	by <a href="/archives/udx-subject.html">subject</a> or by <a
	href="/archives/udx-date.html">date</a>.</b> 	

<p>	<font size=-1><b>
				Search Tips:
				<p>
				<a href="#single">SINGLE WORDS OR PHRASES</a>
				<p>
				<a href="#frag">FRAGMENTS OF SINGLE WORDS OR PHRASES</a>
				<p>
				<a href="#and">LINKING SINGLE WORDS OR PHRASES USING AND</a>
				<p>
				<b><a href="#or">LINKING SINGLE WORDS OR PHRASES USING OR</a>
				<p>
				<hr width=80%>
				<p>
				Also:
				<p>
               	<a href="combquery.html#list">Return Simple Listing</a> 
               	<p>
               	<a href="combquery.html#samp">Contextual Results</a>
               	<p>
               	<a href="combquery.html#tick">Search by Ticker</a> 
               	<p>
               	<a href="combquery.html#comp">Search by Company Name</a>
        </b></font>
   
	</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=150 valign=bottom>
		<font size=-1><b>
				
			
				
				<a href="combquery.html#list">Return Simple Listing</a> 
               	<br>
               	<a href="combquery.html#samp">Contextual Results</a>
               	<br>
               	<a href="combquery.html#tick">Search by Ticker</a> 
               	<br>
               	<a href="combquery.html#comp">Search by Company Name</a>
	</b></font>
	 </td></tr>
	 
	 <tr><td width=390>

		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		</center>
	
	
