<DOCHDR>
http://www.worth.com:80/articles/PW01.html 204.141.48.165 19970209021701 text/html 7145
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 09 Feb 1997 02:17:42 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=20626028855454662327; path=/
</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title>General Interest Investing Sites</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>General Interest Investing Sites</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						<br>There are quite a few one-stop-shopping-style sites for the investors on the Web. Almost all of these sites provide 15-to-20 -minute-delayed stock and mutual fund quotes or link you to other sites that do. They also typically give business news, some kind of company profiles, links to corporate Web sites, and other minutiae.  
<br><br>
<a href="http://www.stockmaster.com/">Stock Master</a href> is one of the better known and more useful comprehensive investing locales on the Web. Here you can retrieve quotes, examine short investing snapshots of companies, and check out investor sentiment survey data all with relative ease. The best part: "All our services are free to individual investors," say the folks at StockMaster. StockMaster is also relatively easy to navigate. To get data on, say, the La-Z-Boy Chair Co., including colorful charts showing how the company's doing compared to the S&P 500, just enter the ticker symbol or click through to search by company name. You can also send in your opinion on the stock.<br><p>
<a href="http://www.stocksmart.com/">Stock Smart</a href> bills itself as "an independent advocate for truth on Wall Street" that has "no conflicts of interest" and comprises "the new paradigm for the brokerage industry." Phew. What the folks at StockSmart mean is that in addition to industry reports, SEC filings, and business news, you can also click through to a specific mutual fund or stock, sifting by industry, market cap, P/E, and/or valuation. While StockSmart's company snapshots don't bring up the same eye-grabbing charts and graphs as can be found in StockMaster, they do make it easy to find out who the major institutional holders are for a particular issue.<br>  <p>
<a href="http://www.hoovers.com/">Hoover's Online</a href> is the electronic offspring of Hoover's, Inc., a "business information company" located in Austin, Texas. Here you can search out company data by name or ticker symbol, get quotes, find out about IPOs, and get stock tips from various knowledgeable parties. In order to get more than a bare-bones profile of a particular company, you must be a subscriber ($9.95 a month). The "Business Tools to Build Your Bottom Line" icon brings you to a catalog and price list of Hoover's publications, including global company directories, career advice guides, and electronic resource locators.<br>  <p>
If <a href="http://www.investorama.com/">invest-o-rama!</a href> sounds like a bit of a free-for-all, it is. The site bills itself as "the hippest directory of the best sites on the 'net for individual investors." With about 2,800 links at last count, invest-o-rama! delivers a lot. You'll probably want to start at "The Directory," comprised of 53 categories of investing links, with a short summary of what you'll find on each site. Aside from the usual melange of quotes and company profiles, you can also check out job listings at major companies and take online seminars with titles like "Investing 101" (look under "education"). Also, have a peek at "ask doug!," a handy FAQ column written by the site's inventor, Douglas Gerlach. <br><p>
<a href="http://www.investools.com/">INVESTools</a href>, another general investing site, offers about half a dozen pull-down menus which permit you to sift through quotes, profiles, research sources (like Morningstar and Zacks), and investment newsletter titles. (If you're interested in finding out more about newsletters, you should visit the <a href="http://www.margin.com/">Newsletter Network</a href>.) As with other sites of this type, you may eagerly link through to another resource only to find it's subscribers-only. INVESTools is free, but you are encouraged to register.<p>
Other heftily be-linked hubs include <a href="http://www.wsrn.com/">Wall Street Research Net (WSRN)</a href>, <a href="http://www.infomanage.com/investment/">Infomanage International</a href>, <a href="http://www.networth.galt.com/">NETworth</a href>, and <a href="http://www.briefing.com/">Briefing.com</a href>. <p>
At <a href="http://www.wsrn.com/home/index.html/">WSRN</a href>, you can access some 16,000 company homepages but caveat emptor--parts of most corporate sites are created by companies themselves and are as much PR and advertising as real financial information. WSRN also links to more than 75 investment management, brokerage, and research firm Web sites, all of which is great for the electronic window shopper.<p>
<a href="http://www.infomanage.com/investment/">Infomanage International</a href> has the requisite links for a general interest investing site, but is noteworthy in that it pays special attention to tech stocks.  <a href="http://www.networth.galt.com/">NETworth</a href>, part of the Quicken Financial Network, is well laid-out, but beware the mutual fund "atlas": some parts of the financial globe appear to be missing. <a href="http://www.briefing.com/">Briefing.com</a href> offers sophisticated tools for real-time analysis for $6.95 per month or $70 per year; click on their "tour site" link to see if you want to subscribe. For $7.95 per moth you can subscribe to <a href="http://www.marketedge.com/">Thomson MarketEdge</a href>, a service that allows you to create and automatically track your own portfolio. Check out the site to see what "members only" can get through MarketEdge.

					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
					</blockquote>
					</font>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/InvestorResources.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<b>
					
					</b>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
