<DOCHDR>
http://www.worth.com:80/articles/PW03.html 204.141.48.165 19970209021714 text/html 5188
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 09 Feb 1997 02:18:03 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=20625986855454683469; path=/
</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title>Specialty Sites</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/+Worth1.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth1.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>Specialty Sites</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						<br>If your focus is a bit narrower, there are a number of specialized investing sites. The <a href="http://www.techstocks.com/">Silicon Investor</a href> for example, focuses on computer, software, communications, and semiconductor stocks. It's "opening letter" gives an overview of the site. You also may want to check out the similar <a href="http://www.techweb.com/investor/investor.html">TechInvestor</a href> home page. <p>
<a href="http://www.optionscentral.com/">OIC</a> is the Web site of the Options Industry Council. The Council, formed in 1992, seeks to "educate brokers and investors on listed equity options" and includes five exchanges: Amex, NYSE, CBOE, Pacific Stock Exchange, and the Philadelphia Stock Exchange. The options world can be a confusing one so the OIC page is a useful place for newcomers to learn more.
<br><p>
If you're looking for a more rarified approach, you might want to check out <a href="http://home.earthlink.net/~vp/">Dogs of the Dow</a href>. The Dogs page tells investors how to select underperforming securities based on a relatively simple approach involving dividend yield. The Dogfolk claim their approach has outperformed the DJIA by close to six percentage points annually since 1973. The <a href="http://www.HHconductor.com/">Conductor</a href> outlines a more complex form of investing wizardry consisting of four "unique but complementary technologies which shift the trading odds in your favor: neural networks, fuzzy logic, genetic algorithms, and knowledge-based systems." Cost: $39.95 per month. Go to the site to learn more.<p>
Futures traders should call up <a href="http://apollo.netservers.com/~waldemar/wl.html">Waldemar's List</a href>, a gathering of links to other Internet sites of use to the futures investor. The Waldemar site is the brainchild of Waldemar Puszkarz, a Ph.D. student in physics at the University of South Carolina who hails from Poland. Accessing Waldemar's resume reveal that "futures and options markets" are one of his "activities/interests," along with chess, ancient civilizations and "really good beer." Download Waldemar's photo and you might think you're looking at NYPD Blue star Dennis Franz's home page.<p>
Investors following Canadian companies should hook into the <a href="http://www.visions.com/">Canada Net Pages</a href>, which contains end-of-day quotes from the Toronto, Vancouver, Alberta, and Montreal stock exchanges (click on "Stocks & Bonds").<p>
The <a href="http://www.growthstockinvestor.com/">Growth Stock Investor</a href>, is affiliated with TKO International, a PR and financial relations firm that, among other things, acts as an intermediary between companies and broker/dealers. Growth Stock's relatively slender "featured companies" list probably reflects TKO's own client base.<p>
If you're interested in media companies, even smaller ones, you might want to check out the "Company Profile Index" at <a href="http://www.herring.com/">herring.com</a href>, a Web site produced by the publishers of The Red Herring, a magazine which reports on the info-tainment industries. <p>
The <a href="http://www.xe.net/currency/">Universal Currency Converter</a href> is an extremely easy-to-use site that permits you to do... guess what? Want to convert 20 Algerian Dinars into Finnish Markka? No problem: just key in the request and bingo!  (Twenty Algerian Dinar, by the way, will buy you some 1.65 Finnish Markka.)

					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
					</blockquote>
					</font>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

